idth: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Searching for questions</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'mapping1_training.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Objectives mapping</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'exclude and correct_training v2.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Excluding and Correcting questions</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"cursor: pointer;\" onclick=\"openTutorial(\'OSCE b.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Importing OSCE marks</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><strong>Advice on</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=195\" target=\"_top\">Selecting Question Types</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=196\" target=\"_top\">Teamworking</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=197\" target=\"_top\">Keywords</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=198\" target=\"_top\">Quality Assurance</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=199\" target=\"_top\">Security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=201\" target=\"_top\">Students with Special Needs</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=205\" target=\"_top\">Bloom\'s Taxonomy</a></li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><a href=\"index.php?id=209\" target=\"_top\">Preparing graphics for use in Rogo</a>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><a href=\"index.php?id=246\" target=\"_top\">Running Summative Exams</a>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>','\r\n\r\n\r\nRogoHelp and How to\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nGetting Started\r\n\r\nwith Formative Quizzes\r\nwith Summative Exams\r\n\r\nwith Surveys\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\nInteractive Tutorials&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCreating a Formative quiz\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSearching for questions\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nObjectives mapping\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nExcluding and Correcting questions\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nImporting OSCE marks\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\nAdvice on\r\n\r\nSelecting Question Types\r\nTeamworking\r\nKeywords\r\nQuality Assurance\r\nSecurity\r\nStudents with Special Needs\r\nBloom\'s Taxonomy\r\n\r\nPreparing graphics for use in Rogo&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\nRunning Summative Exams&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(3,'Surveys/About','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Questionnaires or surveys are a useful tool for improving quality and eliciting feedback. Conceptually, a survey is very similar to an assessment: both present questions to the user and record the candidate\'s selected answers. The only difference between the two comes at the end when the data is analysed. An assessment may be objectively marked and candidates compared to a threshold passmark. Surveys, on the other hand, can be quantitatively and qualitatively analysed depending on the question types used.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The screenshot below shows an example survey designed to elicit feedback regarding a module entitled \'GEM Neurosciences\'. Two question types are used here: likert scale and textbox.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/survey student view.png\" alt=\"survey student view.png\" width=\"756\" height=\"922\" /></div>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Likert Scale</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Likert scales can be used with a pre-defined scale or a custom scale that&nbsp;can be&nbsp;created with between 3 and 10 points. The labels at each end can be customised per question and an optional \'n/a\' column can be added for any situations where a question may not be applicable to all candidates.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Textbox</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The size of a textbox can be controlled in terms of the number of columns and rows to vary how large it is when displayed. Regardless of physical size each textbox can hold up to 65,535 characters of text.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Other Question Types</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Surveys can also use Dichotomous, MCQ, Multiple Response and Extended Matching, Matrix and Time/Date question types.</p>','Questionnaires or surveys are a useful tool for improving quality and eliciting feedback. Conceptually, a survey is very similar to an assessment: both present questions to the user and record the candidate\'s selected answers. The only difference between the two comes at the end when the data is analysed. An assessment may be objectively marked and candidates compared to a threshold passmark. Surveys, on the other hand, can be quantitatively and qualitatively analysed depending on the question types used. The screenshot below shows an example survey designed to elicit feedback regarding a module entitled \'GEM Neurosciences\'. Two question types are used here: likert scale and textbox. Likert Scale Likert scales can be used with a pre-defined scale or a custom scale that&nbsp;can be&nbsp;created with between 3 and 10 points. The labels at each end can be customised per question and an optional \'n/a\' column can be added for any situations where a question may not be applicable to all candidates. Textbox The size of a textbox can be controlled in terms of the number of columns and rows to vary how large it is when displayed. Regardless of physical size each textbox can hold up to 65,535 characters of text. Other Question Types Surveys can also use Dichotomous, MCQ, Multiple Response and Extended Matching, Matrix and Time/Date question types.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(46,'Papers/Types of Papers','<p>Rogo currently supports seven different types of assessment and survey papers:</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"8\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"../../artwork/formative.png\" alt=\"Formative Icon\" width=\"48\" height=\"48\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Formative Assessment</strong><br />Self-assessment quizzes, usually available for students to take throughout the semester. After completing all screens of a formative assessment, Rogo will display an \'answer\' screen showing the entire paper with ticks and crosses as appropriate indicating to the student which questions they got right and wrong together with any textual feedback entered by the question writer. Can be taken on mutiple occasions.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"../../artwork/progress.png\" alt=\"Progress Test Icon\" width=\"48\" height=\"48\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Progress Test</strong><br />A progress test can be multi-screen like a formative assessment but differs in that after completion the student will not be given feedback. Instead it is at the discression of the paper writer to release the marks by using the \'email class\' button at the bottom of the \'Class Totals\' report. A Progress Test can only be taken once but the paper owner may change the paper to a Formative paper which allow students to access it an see the results and feedback for each question. Students can be notified that the paper is available in Formative format by adding a news item to the VLE or by obtaining email addresses from student records system.</div>\r\n<div>(<a href=\"index.php?id=253\" target=\"_top\">Further details</a>)</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"../../artwork/summative.png\" alt=\"Summative Icon\" width=\"48\" height=\"48\" /></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Summative Assessment</strong><br />Summative assessments present in a similar way to progress tests with no answers screen at the end. However, whereas a progress test is used for monitoring progression throughout a semester or a year, a summative assessment contributes marks either in part or entirety towards a degree.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"../../artwork/survey.png\" alt=\"Survey Icon\" width=\"48\" height=\"48\" /></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Survey</strong><br />Surveys, or questionnaires, are used to create papers to elicit views and responses where there are no correct answers, for example, module evaluations. Typically, likert scales and open-ended textboxes are the most frequently used question type on a survey.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"../../artwork/osce.png\" alt=\"OSCE Icon\" width=\"48\" height=\"48\" /></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>OSCE Station</strong><br />Examiners can use Netbooks and other small format devices to record students demonstration of various skills. (<a href=\"index.php?id=174\" target=\"_top\">Further details</a>)</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/offline_shared.png\" alt=\"offline_shared.png\" width=\"48\" height=\"48\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div><strong>Offline Paper</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is an offline paper type supported by Rogo. The Offline Paper exam is administered and marked on paper and scores are then recorded in an Excel file, saved as a CSV file and&nbsp;imported into Rogo.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mapping allows&nbsp;personalised feedback to be made available to students.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/peer review paper icon.png\" alt=\"peer review paper icon.png\" width=\"48\" height=\"48\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div><strong>Peer Review</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This paper allows a peer review to be completed in&nbsp;Rogo. Students&nbsp;make selections from&nbsp;likert scale questions&nbsp;for selected peers.&nbsp;These can be completed as individual or group reviews.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','Rogo currently supports seven different types of assessment and survey papers:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFormative AssessmentSelf-assessment quizzes, usually available for students to take throughout the semester. After completing all screens of a formative assessment, Rogo will display an \'answer\' screen showing the entire paper with ticks and crosses as appropriate indicating to the student which questions they got right and wrong together with any textual feedback entered by the question writer. Can be taken on mutiple occasions.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nProgress TestA progress test can be multi-screen like a formative assessment but differs in that after completion the student will not be given feedback. Instead it is at the discression of the paper writer to release the marks by using the \'email class\' button at the bottom of the \'Class Totals\' report. A Progress Test can only be taken once but the paper owner may change the paper to a Formative paper which allow students to access it an see the results and feedback for each question. Students can be notified that the paper is available in Formative format by adding a news item to the VLE or by obtaining email addresses from student records system.\r\n(Further details)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSummative AssessmentSummative assessments present in a similar way to progress tests with no answers screen at the end. However, whereas a progress test is used for monitoring progression throughout a semester or a year, a summative assessment contributes marks either in part or entirety towards a degree.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSurveySurveys, or questionnaires, are used to create papers to elicit views and responses where there are no correct answers, for example, module evaluations. Typically, likert scales and open-ended textboxes are the most frequently used question type on a survey.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOSCE StationExaminers can use Netbooks and other small format devices to record students demonstration of various skills. (Further details)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOffline Paper\r\nThis is an offline paper type supported by Rogo. The Offline Paper exam is administered and marked on paper and scores are then recorded in an Excel file, saved as a CSV file and&nbsp;imported into Rogo.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mapping allows&nbsp;personalised feedback to be made available to students.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPeer Review\r\nThis paper allows a peer review to be completed in&nbsp;Rogo. Students&nbsp;make selections from&nbsp;likert scale questions&nbsp;for selected peers.&nbsp;These can be completed as individual or group reviews.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(86,'Clock','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A clock is available in the bottom status bar of each screen which shows the current tim (not the time remaining):</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/exam_clock.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"825\" height=\"235\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> The clock is created using JavaScript and as such takes its time from the client computer, not the server. Do not rely upon for split second accuracy.</p>','A clock is available in the bottom status bar of each screen which shows the current tim (not the time remaining): &nbsp; &nbsp; Note: The clock is created using JavaScript and as such takes its time from the client computer, not the server. Do not rely upon for split second accuracy.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(163,'Papers/Deleting','75',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(41,'Creating/New Papers','<h2>Creating a new Paper</h2>\r\n<div><strong>Interactive tutorial</strong></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'Formative paper creation v2.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Creating a formative quiz</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">A new blank paper can be created by selecting the \'Create New Paper\' (1.) link from the \'Paper Tasks\' task pane (see screenshot below).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/New_papers_1a.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"678\" height=\"408\" />&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">You then need to select the paper type (2.) and give it a unique name (3.) ideally in the following format: \'Module Code: Month (Session) e.g. A14ACE: March (2009/10)\'. Then you can move to the next step (4.).</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/New_papers_2.png\" alt=\"New_papers_2.png\" width=\"726\" height=\"252\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>You must then select which students can take the paper by selecting the correct module (5.) and the dates that it will be available from (6.) and two (7.). This is the final step (8.).</div>\r\n<div><strong></strong>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note: </strong>Take care when setting the availability date as the paper will be locked once the date has passed and will no longer be editable. The assessed papers (Summative, OSCE &amp; Offline Paper) are only available on the selected day so if this date is not known when the paper is being created an approximate date and time should be set and then changed when the details have been confirmed.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Formative papers are generally made available for a longer period of time such as 2 or 3 years.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/New_papers_3.png\" alt=\"New_papers_3.png\" width=\"708\" height=\"469\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Once the paper has been created you can select \'Edit Properties\' from the \'Paper Tasks\' task pane and select the required properties for your paper.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Select the relevant <strong>Team</strong> for your paper so that everyone on the team has access to the paper (a team for each module is created by Rogo).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The \'prologue\' text will be displayed at the top of the first screen of the paper and the \'postscript\' text will be displayed at the top of the marking screen after the paper has been completed. The remaining properties at the bottom control the cosmetic appearance of the paper in terms of foreground and background colours. Unless the paper creator has strong preferences the defaults should suffice for most situations. The Folder drop down field allows you to select one of your personal folders which will create a pointer to the paper. See <a href=\"display_page.php?id=43\">\'Creating New Folders\'</a>.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/New_papers_4.png\" alt=\"New_papers_4.png\" width=\"675\" height=\"200\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Assigning Questions to the Paper</h2>\r\n<p>For further details on how to assign questions from the question bank to specific papers see \'<a href=\"display_page.php?id=42\">Creating new Questions</a>\'.</p>','Creating a new Paper\r\nInteractive tutorial\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCreating a formative quiz\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nA new blank paper can be created by selecting the \'Create New Paper\' (1.) link from the \'Paper Tasks\' task pane (see screenshot below).\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nYou then need to select the paper type (2.) and give it a unique name (3.) ideally in the following format: \'Module Code: Month (Session) e.g. A14ACE: March (2009/10)\'. Then you can move to the next step (4.).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nYou must then select which students can take the paper by selecting the correct module (5.) and the dates that it will be available from (6.) and two (7.). This is the final step (8.).\r\n&nbsp;\r\nNote: Take care when setting the availability date as the paper will be locked once the date has passed and will no longer be editable. The assessed papers (Summative, OSCE &amp; Offline Paper) are only available on the selected day so if this date is not known when the paper is being created an approximate date and time should be set and then changed when the details have been confirmed.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nFormative papers are generally made available for a longer period of time such as 2 or 3 years.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nOnce the paper has been created you can select \'Edit Properties\' from the \'Paper Tasks\' task pane and select the required properties for your paper.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSelect the relevant Team for your paper so that everyone on the team has access to the paper (a team for each module is created by Rogo).\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe \'prologue\' text will be displayed at the top of the first screen of the paper and the \'postscript\' text will be displayed at the top of the marking screen after the paper has been completed. The remaining properties at the bottom control the cosmetic appearance of the paper in terms of foreground and background colours. Unless the paper creator has strong preferences the defaults should suffice for most situations. The Folder drop down field allows you to select one of your personal folders which will create a pointer to the paper. See \'Creating New Folders\'.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAssigning Questions to the Paper\r\nFor further details on how to assign questions from the question bank to specific papers see \'Creating new Questions\'.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(42,'Creating/New Questions','<h2>Types of Questions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo can handle a range of different types of questions including:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"line-height: 160%;\">\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=305\">Area</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=68\">Calculation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=13\">Dichotomous</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=14\">Extended Matching </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=16\">Fill-in-the-Blank</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=22\">Flash Interface</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=17\">Image Hotspot</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=62\">Likert Scale</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=18\">Multiple Choice</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=19\">Multiple Response</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=20\">Ranking</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=61\">Text Box</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=293\">True/False</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Creating a new Question</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To create a new question simply click on the \'Create new Question\' link in the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane. This will display a popup menu of all available question types (this requires Java).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/create question1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"516\" height=\"566\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A template form will next be displayed appropriate to the question type selected. Complete all the mandatory fields and as many optional pieces of information as required and select \'Add to Bank\'. Alternatively, if already in a paper you can click on the \'Add to Bank and Paper\' to assign the new question directly to the paper.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"assigning\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>Assigning Questions to Papers</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"assigning\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are a number of different ways to assign a question to a specific paper in Rogo, below are the main methods:</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Method 1 - Add new question to paper</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first method requires a paper to be created first (see <a href=\"../new_paper/new_paper.html\">Creating a new Paper</a>). Once the paper is made click on its icon to go into it. Next select the \'Create new Question\' from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane and select the type of question you wish to add. Complete all necessary fields in the question template form and then at the bottom of the screen select \'Add to Bank &amp; Paper\'. This will add this new question to the question bank and automatically assign it to the bottom of the current question paper. If the questions are added in order then the resulting question paper will automatically be in the correct order as well.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Method 2 - Add existing question to paper</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The second method, like the first, requires the user to locate a paper and to go into it. Check at this stage in the \'Edit Properties\' that the available time/dates are not active if not you will not be able to add any questions. Next select the \'Add Questions to Paper\' link from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. This will display a popup window similar to the one below:</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/assign qs to paper.png\" alt=\"assign qs to paper.png\" width=\"877\" height=\"505\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This dialog has three tabs showing questions created by the current user which are currently not assigned to any paper (unused), all the questions owned by the current user and a search tab. To add a question or questions just click the relevant checkboxes, check the screen number is correct and then click on the \'Add Questions\' button. Questions will be added in the order displayed. It is therefore often useful to click on the \'Created\' heading to order the questions. Adding multiple questions in this order will appear on the paper in the same order as originally entered.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Method 3 - Search and add to paper</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The third method involves selecting the \'Search\' link from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane. A search term should be entered or other appropriate ways of searching for a question&nbsp;(1.)&nbsp;and the \'Search\' button clicked (2.). Once a suitable question is found in the results set single click with the mouse (3.). Next select \'Link to Paper\' (4.) from the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane. A dialog box will be displayed showing all the papers owned by the current user (any paper with an active date will be displayed but greyed out). To add the currently selected question click on one of the radio buttons next to the required paper (5.) and click \'Add to Paper\' (6.). Alternatively, select the very last radio button and enter a new paper name. This will create a brand new paper and assign the chosen question.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/New_Questions1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1082\" height=\"476\" /></div>','Types of Questions Rogo can handle a range of different types of questions including: Area Calculation Dichotomous Extended Matching Fill-in-the-Blank Flash Interface Image Hotspot Likert Scale Multiple Choice Multiple Response Ranking Text Box True/False Creating a new Question To create a new question simply click on the \'Create new Question\' link in the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane. This will display a popup menu of all available question types (this requires Java). &nbsp; A template form will next be displayed appropriate to the question type selected. Complete all the mandatory fields and as many optional pieces of information as required and select \'Add to Bank\'. Alternatively, if already in a paper you can click on the \'Add to Bank and Paper\' to assign the new question directly to the paper. Assigning Questions to Papers There are a number of different ways to assign a question to a specific paper in Rogo, below are the main methods: Method 1 - Add new question to paper The first method requires a paper to be created first (see Creating a new Paper). Once the paper is made click on its icon to go into it. Next select the \'Create new Question\' from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane and select the type of question you wish to add. Complete all necessary fields in the question template form and then at the bottom of the screen select \'Add to Bank &amp; Paper\'. This will add this new question to the question bank and automatically assign it to the bottom of the current question paper. If the questions are added in order then the resulting question paper will automatically be in the correct order as well. Method 2 - Add existing question to paper The second method, like the first, requires the user to locate a paper and to go into it. Check at this stage in the \'Edit Properties\' that the available time/dates are not active if not you will not be able to add any questions. Next select the \'Add Questions to Paper\' link from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. This will display a popup window similar to the one below: &nbsp; &nbsp; This dialog has three tabs showing questions created by the current user which are currently not assigned to any paper (unused), all the questions owned by the current user and a search tab. To add a question or questions just click the relevant checkboxes, check the screen number is correct and then click on the \'Add Questions\' button. Questions will be added in the order displayed. It is therefore often useful to click on the \'Created\' heading to order the questions. Adding multiple questions in this order will appear on the paper in the same order as originally entered. Method 3 - Search and add to paper The third method involves selecting the \'Search\' link from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane. A search term should be entered or other appropriate ways of searching for a question&nbsp;(1.)&nbsp;and the \'Search\' button clicked (2.). Once a suitable question is found in the results set single click with the mouse (3.). Next select \'Link to Paper\' (4.) from the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane. A dialog box will be displayed showing all the papers owned by the current user (any paper with an active date will be displayed but greyed out). To add the currently selected question click on one of the radio buttons next to the required paper (5.) and click \'Add to Paper\' (6.). Alternatively, select the very last radio button and enter a new paper name. This will create a brand new paper and assign the chosen question. &nbsp;&nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(43,'Creating/New Folders','37',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(8,'Finding/Questions','<div><strong>Interactive Tutorial</strong></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'searching_training.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Searching for questions</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This question banks containing thousands of questions, locating a specific one can sometimes be problematic. The \'search\' facility is one solution to this problem, being able to locate any question in the bank that is assigned to the team(s) that you are part of. To start a new search select the \'Search\' link from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane.</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A special search pane will be displayed similar to the one shown below. Enter a word or phrase into the textbox and then click \'Search\'. If necessary you can limit the search to look for specific types of question and which section in the question to search. Dates when the question was modified and the Team or Owner can also be used in the search. The Blooms level and Keyword are also available to search on. Any matching question found in the bank will then be displayed in the main frame on the right hand side.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/search questions1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"742\" height=\"626\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Assuming some questions have been found with the search term, the user may then single click on the lead-in of the question and the options in the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane will become active:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/search question selected.png\" alt=\"search question selected.png\" width=\"825\" height=\"166\" /></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Edit Question</strong> - The current question can be opened and changes made unless a question has been used in an exam and is locked.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Information</strong> - Displays information (owner, creation date, modified date and papers used on) about the currently selected question.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Copy (create duplicate)</strong> - This will create a duplicate of the selected question in the question bank.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Link to Paper</strong> - This will display a dialog box allowing the user to link the currently selected question to an existing or new paper.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Delete Question</strong> - This will remove the currently selected question from the question bank. Deletions can only be performed by the question owner and only then if the question is not currently used on a paper.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','Interactive Tutorial\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSearching for questions\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThis question banks containing thousands of questions, locating a specific one can sometimes be problematic. The \'search\' facility is one solution to this problem, being able to locate any question in the bank that is assigned to the team(s) that you are part of. To start a new search select the \'Search\' link from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane.\r\nA special search pane will be displayed similar to the one shown below. Enter a word or phrase into the textbox and then click \'Search\'. If necessary you can limit the search to look for specific types of question and which section in the question to search. Dates when the question was modified and the Team or Owner can also be used in the search. The Blooms level and Keyword are also available to search on. Any matching question found in the bank will then be displayed in the main frame on the right hand side.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nAssuming some questions have been found with the search term, the user may then single click on the lead-in of the question and the options in the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane will become active:\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nEdit Question - The current question can be opened and changes made unless a question has been used in an exam and is locked.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nInformation - Displays information (owner, creation date, modified date and papers used on) about the currently selected question.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCopy (create duplicate) - This will create a duplicate of the selected question in the question bank.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nLink to Paper - This will display a dialog box allowing the user to link the currently selected question to an existing or new paper.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDelete Question - This will remove the currently selected question from the question bank. Deletions can only be performed by the question owner and only then if the question is not currently used on a paper.\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(260,'OSCE Station/Overview','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Results from OSCE stations can be recorded on paper, transferred to an Excel file and then imported into Rogo. Alternatively they can be recorded electronically using Netbooks and other small format devices. For both methods an OSCE paper is created in Rogo which holds the results and allows these to be viewed.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>See following pages for more details:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><a href=\"display_page.php?id=259\">Creating a Paper</a></span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><a href=\"display_page.php?id=257\">Electronic OSCE</a></span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><a href=\"display_page.php?id=258\">Offline OSCE</a></span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><a href=\"display_page.php?id=255\">Viewing Results</a></span></li>\r\n</ul>','Results from OSCE stations can be recorded on paper, transferred to an Excel file and then imported into Rogo. Alternatively they can be recorded electronically using Netbooks and other small format devices. For both methods an OSCE paper is created in Rogo which holds the results and allows these to be viewed. &nbsp; &nbsp; See following pages for more details: Creating a Paper Electronic OSCE Offline OSCE Viewing Results ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(261,'Media','<div>The following media can be used in&nbsp;questions:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Graphics in JPEG, GIF or PNG format</span></div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Audio in mp3 format</span></div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Video in FLV format, if you want to use video contact <span>$support_email</span></span></div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','The following media can be used in&nbsp;questions: &nbsp;  Graphics in JPEG, GIF or PNG format  Audio in mp3 format  Video in FLV format, if you want to use video contact $support_email ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(217,'Advice on/Moving Questions in a Paper','<h2>Question Order</h2>\r\n<div>To change the order of the questions you can select (click and hold)&nbsp;a question (1) and simply drag it&nbsp;up or down.</div>\r\n<h2>Screen Breaks</h2>\r\n<div>You can also \'Add screen break\' (2) which will result in \'moving\' the following question/questions to the next screen. The screen break can be moved and deleted.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Moving_questions.png\" alt=\"Moving_questions.png\" width=\"762\" height=\"456\" /></div>','Question Order To change the order of the questions you can select (click and hold)&nbsp;a question (1) and simply drag it&nbsp;up or down. Screen Breaks You can also \'Add screen break\' (2) which will result in \'moving\' the following question/questions to the next screen. The screen break can be moved and deleted. &nbsp; &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(97,'Standards Setting/Introduction','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Standards Setting is an optional feature and is made available&nbsp;for each module on an individual basis. If a module has been set to use Standards Setting, a \'Standards Setting\' option will be present on the Paper Tasks menu for each paper in the module (see graphic below). To enable a module for Standards Setting email&nbsp;$support_email stating the module that code.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/standards set highlight.png\" alt=\"standards set highlight.png\" width=\"523\" height=\"280\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Purpose of Standards Setting</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Standards setting is a process used to determine the required level of competence (pass mark) for an assessment. There are a number of different methods available to perform this process; two of the more frequently used include the Angoff method (used for GEM exams) and the Ebel method (most frequently used). Both processes employ a panel of subject matter experts (SMEs) to determine whether a borderline candidate would be expected to get the current question correct or not.</div>\r\n<h2>Advantages</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>They focus attention on item content</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>They are relatively easy to use</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>There is a considerable body of published work supporting their use</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>They are used frequently in high stakes testing</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Disadvantages</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>The concept of a \"borderline group\" is sometimes difficult to define</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Judges sometimes feel they are \"pulling numbers out of the air\"</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>The methods can be tedious</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Selection of panellists</h2>\r\n<p>The selection of panellists in standard setting is of the greatest importance. In summary, panellists should be:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Experts in the related field of examination</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Familiar with the examination methods</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Good problem solvers</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Familiar with level of candidates</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Interested in education</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>For high-stakes summative exams the panel should be made up of at least 6-8 experts.</p>\r\n<hr style=\"text-align: left; width: 40%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=98\">Angoff method</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=99\">Ebel method</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Standards Setting is an optional feature and is made available&nbsp;for each module on an individual basis. If a module has been set to use Standards Setting, a \'Standards Setting\' option will be present on the Paper Tasks menu for each paper in the module (see graphic below). To enable a module for Standards Setting email&nbsp;$support_email stating the module that code. &nbsp; &nbsp; Purpose of Standards Setting Standards setting is a process used to determine the required level of competence (pass mark) for an assessment. There are a number of different methods available to perform this process; two of the more frequently used include the Angoff method (used for GEM exams) and the Ebel method (most frequently used). Both processes employ a panel of subject matter experts (SMEs) to determine whether a borderline candidate would be expected to get the current question correct or not. Advantages  They focus attention on item content  They are relatively easy to use  There is a considerable body of published work supporting their use  They are used frequently in high stakes testing  Disadvantages  The concept of a \"borderline group\" is sometimes difficult to define  Judges sometimes feel they are \"pulling numbers out of the air\"  The methods can be tedious  Selection of panellists The selection of panellists in standard setting is of the greatest importance. In summary, panellists should be:  Experts in the related field of examination  Familiar with the examination methods  Good problem solvers  Familiar with level of candidates  Interested in education  For high-stakes summative exams the panel should be made up of at least 6-8 experts. See also: Angoff method Ebel method ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(98,'Standards Setting/Modified Angoff Method','<h2>Individual Review</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">To perform an individual review go into the paper and select \'Standards Setting\' from the sidebar menu. This will give you the options shown below and select the highlighted option. The screenshot below shows that a number of individual reviews have been completed.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/create new angoff.png\" alt=\"create new angoff.png\" width=\"822\" height=\"460\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When you create a new review you select the percentage of borderline&nbsp;candidates that you would expect to get the question correct for each question.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/angoff completing settings.png\" alt=\"angoff completing settings.png\" width=\"881\" height=\"369\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Group Review</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Before performing a group review two or more individual reviews must first have been completed for the current assessment. To start a group review select \'Standards Setting\' from the sidebar menu and then \'Modified Angoff\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/angoff group review1.png\" alt=\"angoff group review1.png\" width=\"756\" height=\"414\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A list of all the individual reviews will be displayed with checkboxes next to them. Uncheck any you do not wish to include&nbsp;and click on the \'Review\' button.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/angoff group select people.png\" alt=\"angoff group select people.png\" width=\"597\" height=\"304\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The assessment paper will now be displayed and beneath each question can be seen the ratings of each separate rather together with a mean percentage. Where the individual ratings are similar they will be displayed in black text. If, however, the range of ratings is greater than 10% then they will be displayed in red. Particular attention should be paid to items in red so that a consensus decision can be made by the group. Once decided enter the appropriate figure in the dropdown menu and click \'Save Ratings\' at the bottom of the screen.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/angoff_group_review3.png\" alt=\"angoff_group_review3.png\" width=\"826\" height=\"618\" /></div>\r\n<p>After clicking \'Save Ratings\' the main standards setting screen will appear&nbsp;and the new \'group review\' is shown with its own cut score.</p>','Individual Review To perform an individual review go into the paper and select \'Standards Setting\' from the sidebar menu. This will give you the options shown below and select the highlighted option. The screenshot below shows that a number of individual reviews have been completed. &nbsp; When you create a new review you select the percentage of borderline&nbsp;candidates that you would expect to get the question correct for each question. &nbsp; Group Review Before performing a group review two or more individual reviews must first have been completed for the current assessment. To start a group review select \'Standards Setting\' from the sidebar menu and then \'Modified Angoff\'. &nbsp; A list of all the individual reviews will be displayed with checkboxes next to them. Uncheck any you do not wish to include&nbsp;and click on the \'Review\' button. &nbsp; The assessment paper will now be displayed and beneath each question can be seen the ratings of each separate rather together with a mean percentage. Where the individual ratings are similar they will be displayed in black text. If, however, the range of ratings is greater than 10% then they will be displayed in red. Particular attention should be paid to items in red so that a consensus decision can be made by the group. Once decided enter the appropriate figure in the dropdown menu and click \'Save Ratings\' at the bottom of the screen. After clicking \'Save Ratings\' the main standards setting screen will appear&nbsp;and the new \'group review\' is shown with its own cut score.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(99,'Standards Setting/Ebel Method','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Standards Setting is an optional feature and is made available for each module on an individual basis. If a module has been set to use Standards Setting, a \'Standards Setting\' option will be present on the Paper Tasks menu for each paper in the module (see graphic below). To enable a module for Standards Setting email&nbsp;$support_email stating the module&nbsp;code.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/standards set highlight.png\" alt=\"standards set highlight.png\" width=\"523\" height=\"280\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Ebel method of standards setting has two distinct stages to it: 1) categorising questions, and 2) setting the number of borderline candidates expected to get each category correct.</p>\r\n<h2>Stage 1: Question Categorisation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the first step each question, or part of a question worth a mark, needs to be categorised on two orthogonal dimensions: 1) difficulty, and 2) importance. As the diagram below shows, the \'difficulty\' dimension has three categories: easy, medium and hard. The \'importance\' dimension has essential, important and nice to know categories. Each question can be plotted on this two dimensional space creating a 3 x 3 matrix:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/ebel_dimensions.png\" alt=\"ebel_dimensions.png\" width=\"392\" height=\"284\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">To actually start the categorisation process go into the paper to be standards set and then click on the \'Standards Setting\' menu option on the left. Next select \'Create new Ebel method\' and the screen will change to show the whole paper with blue dropdown lists next to each item requiring categorisation. The screenshot below shows question 4 which is a multiple response question requiring the student to select two features. Because it is possible to get one option correct without the other it is necessary to standards set both items. To do this dropdown the menu and select the relevant categorisation. For ease the two dimensions have been merged into one list of nine:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/ebel1.png\" alt=\"ebel1.png\" width=\"678\" height=\"345\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> On long papers with many questions it is prudent to save the settings at different points in case of computer crash. To do this scroll to the bottom of the screen and click on \'Save &amp; Continue\', alternatively press + C.</p>\r\n<h2>Stage 2: Setting Percentages</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">After categorising every question, the next stage is to work out the percentage of borderline candidates expected to get each category correct. Scroll down to the bottom of the screen and in the table shown below select the relevant percentages. The number of marks of questions is indicated within each cell. As a rule the percentages should decrease going from essential to nice to know and should also decrease going from easy to hard. So, for example, the number of borderline candidates expected to get a hard/nice to know should be much less than easy/essential.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/ebel2.png\" alt=\"ebel2.png\" width=\"871\" height=\"251\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> An optional second grid is included to set a higher threshold for Distinction candidates.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once again, at the end of the process click \'Save &amp; Exit\' which will take you back to a screen showing all the standards setting for the current paper. On this screen the calculated Pass Score (or cut score) is displayed; in this case 58%.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/standards set.png\" alt=\"standards set.png\" width=\"592\" height=\"178\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">To edit a standards set review at a later date go to the screen above and double-click on the standard setter\'s name.</div>','Standards Setting is an optional feature and is made available for each module on an individual basis. If a module has been set to use Standards Setting, a \'Standards Setting\' option will be present on the Paper Tasks menu for each paper in the module (see graphic below). To enable a module for Standards Setting email&nbsp;$support_email stating the module&nbsp;code. &nbsp; The Ebel method of standards setting has two distinct stages to it: 1) categorising questions, and 2) setting the number of borderline candidates expected to get each category correct. Stage 1: Question Categorisation In the first step each question, or part of a question worth a mark, needs to be categorised on two orthogonal dimensions: 1) difficulty, and 2) importance. As the diagram below shows, the \'difficulty\' dimension has three categories: easy, medium and hard. The \'importance\' dimension has essential, important and nice to know categories. Each question can be plotted on this two dimensional space creating a 3 x 3 matrix: To actually start the categorisation process go into the paper to be standards set and then click on the \'Standards Setting\' menu option on the left. Next select \'Create new Ebel method\' and the screen will change to show the whole paper with blue dropdown lists next to each item requiring categorisation. The screenshot below shows question 4 which is a multiple response question requiring the student to select two features. Because it is possible to get one option correct without the other it is necessary to standards set both items. To do this dropdown the menu and select the relevant categorisation. For ease the two dimensions have been merged into one list of nine: &nbsp; Note: On long papers with many questions it is prudent to save the settings at different points in case of computer crash. To do this scroll to the bottom of the screen and click on \'Save &amp; Continue\', alternatively press + C. Stage 2: Setting Percentages After categorising every question, the next stage is to work out the percentage of borderline candidates expected to get each category correct. Scroll down to the bottom of the screen and in the table shown below select the relevant percentages. The number of marks of questions is indicated within each cell. As a rule the percentages should decrease going from essential to nice to know and should also decrease going from easy to hard. So, for example, the number of borderline candidates expected to get a hard/nice to know should be much less than easy/essential. &nbsp; &nbsp; Note: An optional second grid is included to set a higher threshold for Distinction candidates. &nbsp; Once again, at the end of the process click \'Save &amp; Exit\' which will take you back to a screen showing all the standards setting for the current paper. On this screen the calculated Pass Score (or cut score) is displayed; in this case 58%. &nbsp; &nbsp; To edit a standards set review at a later date go to the screen above and double-click on the standard setter\'s name.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(100,'Student Help','<p>Students access their own online help system which is written specifically for their needs.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: black;\">goto <a href=\"../student/index.php\" target=\"_top\">Student Help</a></span></li>\r\n</ul>','Students access their own online help system which is written specifically for their needs. goto Student Help ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(102,'Exporting/Raw marks as CSV','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is a frequent requirement for lecturers and researchers to be able to export data from Rogo to perform further analysis in some external application. One of the most widely supported data formats is comma separated values (CSV) files. To export the results data for a cohort, go into a paper and then select the \'Reports\' from the \'Paper Tasks\' pane. At the menu below, check the dates you wish to report on and what degree is set and then select \'Export&nbsp;marks&nbsp;as CSV file\' (1).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/raw_marks_1a.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"540\" height=\"316\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After clicking on this link a \'File Download\' dialog box will be displayed similar to the one below. Click on triangle by the \'Save\' button and select \'Save as...\' (2).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/raw_marks_2.png\" alt=\"raw_marks_2.png\" width=\"533\" height=\"100\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The next step is to give the file a meaningful name (3) and decide where on your system to store it. Click on \'Save\' (4).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/raw_marks_3.png\" alt=\"raw_marks_3.png\" width=\"625\" height=\"447\" /></div>','It is a frequent requirement for lecturers and researchers to be able to export data from Rogo to perform further analysis in some external application. One of the most widely supported data formats is comma separated values (CSV) files. To export the results data for a cohort, go into a paper and then select the \'Reports\' from the \'Paper Tasks\' pane. At the menu below, check the dates you wish to report on and what degree is set and then select \'Export&nbsp;marks&nbsp;as CSV file\' (1). After clicking on this link a \'File Download\' dialog box will be displayed similar to the one below. Click on triangle by the \'Save\' button and select \'Save as...\' (2). The next step is to give the file a meaningful name (3) and decide where on your system to store it. Click on \'Save\' (4). ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(105,'Reports/Export Marks as CSV file','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is a frequent requirement for lecturers and researchers to be able to export data from Rogo to perform further analysis in some external application such as SPSS. One of the most widely supported data formats is comma separated values (CVS) files. To export the results data for a cohort, go into a paper and then select \'Reports\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. At the menu below, check the dates you wish to report on and what degree is set and then select \'Export marks as CSV file\' (1).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/raw_marks_1.png\" alt=\"raw_marks_1.png\" width=\"532\" height=\"308\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After clicking on this link a \'File Download\' dialog box will be displayed similar to the one below. Click on triangle by the \'Save\' button and select \'Save as...\' (2).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/raw_marks_2.png\" alt=\"raw_marks_2.png\" width=\"533\" height=\"100\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The next step is to give the file a meaningful name and decide where on your system to store it (3).&nbsp;Click on the \'Save\' button (4).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/raw_marks_3.png\" alt=\"raw_marks_3.png\" width=\"625\" height=\"447\" /></div>','It is a frequent requirement for lecturers and researchers to be able to export data from Rogo to perform further analysis in some external application such as SPSS. One of the most widely supported data formats is comma separated values (CVS) files. To export the results data for a cohort, go into a paper and then select \'Reports\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. At the menu below, check the dates you wish to report on and what degree is set and then select \'Export marks as CSV file\' (1). After clicking on this link a \'File Download\' dialog box will be displayed similar to the one below. Click on triangle by the \'Save\' button and select \'Save as...\' (2). The next step is to give the file a meaningful name and decide where on your system to store it (3).&nbsp;Click on the \'Save\' button (4). ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(12,'Accessibility','<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">Font size and Keyboard control</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">All question types, with the exception of Image Hotspots and Flash, output standard XHTML code to the browser. Proportional font sizes are used so that users can select different sized text within the browser to control how large the characters are (see below).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/text_sizes.png\" alt=\"Text Sizes\" width=\"635\" height=\"284\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>Answering mechanisms (radio buttons, check boxes, pull-down menus, etc) are all standard XHTML form elements and so can be controlled using the keyboard for those users who cannot operate a mouse.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Colour adjustment</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The foreground and background colours used on a paper can be altered specifically for individuals with special requirements without affecting the paper for the rest of a cohort. Specific changes at the individual level can include altering the foreground and background colours to make it easier for dyslexic candidates to read and increasing the font size for users with visual abnormalities. The paper below has been displayed within Internet Explorer at normal text size but uses Rogo to feed XHTML at 150% thus displaying it larger for candidates with visual problems.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/nle/about/touchstone/accessibility/dark_background.gif\" alt=\"Dark Background\" width=\"624\" height=\"317\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Adjustments to Examination Arrangements</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Additional time allowances can be given to students where required for students with disabilities. Students need to make an appointment with Academic Support who will then complete an Alternative Arrangements form and send it to the Examinations Office. The amount of extra time required can be set in Rogo as:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>10%</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>25%</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>33%</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>50%</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>100%</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This then needs to be taken into consideration when setting the availability time of the paper. All students have to be told when the exam has finished and they must stop answering questions. It is&nbsp;the role of the people running the exam to ensure that students&nbsp;that require extra time are allowed to continue after the other candidates have completed the exam until their extra time&nbsp;is used.</p>\r\n<h2>Setting Adjustments</h2>\r\n<p>Staff members with Rogo accounts can adjust the Accessibility settings within Rogo:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Use the Search facility to find the relevant student</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Click on the Accessibility tab and make the required selections</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/accessibility settings.png\" alt=\"accessibility settings.png\" width=\"647\" height=\"307\" /></p>','Font size and Keyboard control All question types, with the exception of Image Hotspots and Flash, output standard XHTML code to the browser. Proportional font sizes are used so that users can select different sized text within the browser to control how large the characters are (see below). &nbsp; &nbsp; Answering mechanisms (radio buttons, check boxes, pull-down menus, etc) are all standard XHTML form elements and so can be controlled using the keyboard for those users who cannot operate a mouse. &nbsp; Colour adjustment The foreground and background colours used on a paper can be altered specifically for individuals with special requirements without affecting the paper for the rest of a cohort. Specific changes at the individual level can include altering the foreground and background colours to make it easier for dyslexic candidates to read and increasing the font size for users with visual abnormalities. The paper below has been displayed within Internet Explorer at normal text size but uses Rogo to feed XHTML at 150% thus displaying it larger for candidates with visual problems. &nbsp; &nbsp; Adjustments to Examination Arrangements Additional time allowances can be given to students where required for students with disabilities. Students need to make an appointment with Academic Support who will then complete an Alternative Arrangements form and send it to the Examinations Office. The amount of extra time required can be set in Rogo as:  10%  25%  33%  50%  100%  This then needs to be taken into consideration when setting the availability time of the paper. All students have to be told when the exam has finished and they must stop answering questions. It is&nbsp;the role of the people running the exam to ensure that students&nbsp;that require extra time are allowed to continue after the other candidates have completed the exam until their extra time&nbsp;is used. Setting Adjustments Staff members with Rogo accounts can adjust the Accessibility settings within Rogo:  Use the Search facility to find the relevant student  Click on the Accessibility tab and make the required selections  ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(13,'Question - Types/Dichotomous','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Textual Dichotomous question</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dichotomous questions present a lead-in question (i.e. irritable bowel syndrome) together with a number of stems displayed below. The examinee must select either \'True\' or \'False\' for each stem, or \'Yes\' or \'No\' if these labels are used. An \'abstain\' column can be added&nbsp;to any dichotomous question with negative marking. This is not recommended, particularly if the paper is set to calculate a random mark.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/dichotomous_question.png\" alt=\"Dichotomous Question\" width=\"658\" height=\"298\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> If you have a True/False question with only one stem you should use the Multiple Choice (MCQ) question type</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><br /><strong><em>Graphical Dichotomous question</em></strong></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the example below graphics are used instead of textual stems. However, the principle is the same, each road symbol (stem) must be answered either \'True\' or \'False\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/dichotomous_question2.png\" alt=\"Dichotomous Question\" width=\"540\" height=\"552\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Marking Method can be set as Mark per Question or Mark per Option where the marks for correct and incorrect responses are set in the question. If the presentation has been set with an Abstain option, negative marks are not given for unanswered options.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/dicot marking.png\" alt=\"dicot marking.png\" width=\"571\" height=\"548\" /></div>','Presentation Textual Dichotomous question Dichotomous questions present a lead-in question (i.e. irritable bowel syndrome) together with a number of stems displayed below. The examinee must select either \'True\' or \'False\' for each stem, or \'Yes\' or \'No\' if these labels are used. An \'abstain\' column can be added&nbsp;to any dichotomous question with negative marking. This is not recommended, particularly if the paper is set to calculate a random mark. &nbsp; Note: If you have a True/False question with only one stem you should use the Multiple Choice (MCQ) question type &nbsp; Graphical Dichotomous question In the example below graphics are used instead of textual stems. However, the principle is the same, each road symbol (stem) must be answered either \'True\' or \'False\'. &nbsp; Marking The Marking Method can be set as Mark per Question or Mark per Option where the marks for correct and incorrect responses are set in the question. If the presentation has been set with an Abstain option, negative marks are not given for unanswered options. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(14,'Question - Types/Extended Matching','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Extended Matching questions are conceptually close to Multiple Response, but differ in that they present with multiple questions/scenarios based around a common theme. Each question has the same list of options (answers) to choose from. Often the number of options will be twice or three times the number of questions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the example below the theme is patients with blood in their urine. The same set of options is used throughout (i.e. \'Anticoagulant therapy\',\'Bladder cancer\',\'Catheter trauma\',\'Cystitis\',etc). The examinee should select (or match) one options per question using the dropdown lists.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/matching_question.png\" alt=\"Extended Matching Question\" width=\"728\" height=\"661\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">An&nbsp;extended matching question can be set with&nbsp;multiple answers which allows the question writer to test for multiple items, these could be diagnoses, tests, drugs, etc. Instead of a single answer to each scenario, the exam candidate has to select multiple correct options.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Extended matching questions are good for two primary reasons: a) a large number of options are presented so the likelihood of selecting the correct one by chance is low, and b) multiple scenarios are presented with differing ages, genders and chemical analyses thus creating a cognitively more demanding question than if just the first part was used as a multiple choice question.</div>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marks can be awarded by question where all stems are answered correctly or by option and can include negative marks for incorrect responses. As can be seen below the examinee has scored 4 out of the total possible 5 where marking is set to mark by option with 1 mark awarded for a correct response. Scenario 4 was wrong; the correct answer, shown in bold, should have been \'Renal cell carcinoma\'. Although not displayed here each scenario can have its own textual feedback.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/matching_answer.png\" alt=\"Extended Matching Marking\" width=\"715\" height=\"666\" /></div>','Presentation Extended Matching questions are conceptually close to Multiple Response, but differ in that they present with multiple questions/scenarios based around a common theme. Each question has the same list of options (answers) to choose from. Often the number of options will be twice or three times the number of questions. In the example below the theme is patients with blood in their urine. The same set of options is used throughout (i.e. \'Anticoagulant therapy\',\'Bladder cancer\',\'Catheter trauma\',\'Cystitis\',etc). The examinee should select (or match) one options per question using the dropdown lists. &nbsp; An&nbsp;extended matching question can be set with&nbsp;multiple answers which allows the question writer to test for multiple items, these could be diagnoses, tests, drugs, etc. Instead of a single answer to each scenario, the exam candidate has to select multiple correct options. Extended matching questions are good for two primary reasons: a) a large number of options are presented so the likelihood of selecting the correct one by chance is low, and b) multiple scenarios are presented with differing ages, genders and chemical analyses thus creating a cognitively more demanding question than if just the first part was used as a multiple choice question. Marking Marks can be awarded by question where all stems are answered correctly or by option and can include negative marks for incorrect responses. As can be seen below the examinee has scored 4 out of the total possible 5 where marking is set to mark by option with 1 mark awarded for a correct response. Scenario 4 was wrong; the correct answer, shown in bold, should have been \'Renal cell carcinoma\'. Although not displayed here each scenario can have its own textual feedback. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(203,'Teams/Editing','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Team Member list for a module can be modified by any member of the team. Click on \'Team Members\' to view a list of all Rogo users and select to add new users or deselect to remove users.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/team members1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"533\" height=\"382\" /></div>','The Team Member list for a module can be modified by any member of the team. Click on \'Team Members\' to view a list of all Rogo users and select to add new users or deselect to remove users. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(16,'Question - Types/Fill-in-the-Blank','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Fill-in-the-blank questions can in certain circumstances be a useful alternative to an open-ended short-essay question. They allow for the more objective testing of specific facts and pieces of knowledge. This question type can be used in two different modes, one with blank textboxes for students to complete and one with a dropdown list of options that students select from.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Blank Textboxes</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the example below it can be seen that 20 key terms have been removed from a paragraph of text. The exam candidate is require to type in their answer into each of the blank text boxes. Rogo can support any number of blanks within a piece of text and can even have two blanks next to each other.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span class=\"note\">To create a blank input box place [blank] and [/blank] tags around the options you wish to add in the \'Question\' field.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span class=\"note\">Where there are different spellings for words in UK and US English or acronyms the alternatives can be added as correct items. For example, both the full term and acronym shown here will be marked as correct, [blank]Irritable Bowel Syndrome,IBS[/blank].</span></div>\r\n<div><span class=\"note\">&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/blank_question2.png\" alt=\"Fill-in-the-Blank Question\" width=\"732\" height=\"500\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Dropdown Lists</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The disadvantage of a traditional fill-in-the-blank question, as shown above, is the problem of spelling. Dyslexic students and those who have made typing mistakes can be penalised by computer-based marking even though a human might see that they have got the correct answer. As an alternative to the spelling issue, Rogo can present each blank as a dropdown list with a number of pre-written distractors. In the screenshot below the same question as the first one is re-presented using these dropdown lists. Always put the correct answer as the <strong>first</strong> option, followed by the distractors (all options are randomised automatically).<br />e.g. for [blank]GDP,UDP,ADP,CDP[/blank] on the alpha-subunit of a G-protein which in turn activates enzyme</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/blank_question.png\" alt=\"Fill-in-the-Blank Question\" width=\"732\" height=\"453\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">The Marking Method can be set as either Mark per Question or by Option with the number of marks awarded for correct and incorrect responses (negative marks) set in the question.</div>','Fill-in-the-blank questions can in certain circumstances be a useful alternative to an open-ended short-essay question. They allow for the more objective testing of specific facts and pieces of knowledge. This question type can be used in two different modes, one with blank textboxes for students to complete and one with a dropdown list of options that students select from. &nbsp; Blank Textboxes In the example below it can be seen that 20 key terms have been removed from a paragraph of text. The exam candidate is require to type in their answer into each of the blank text boxes. Rogo can support any number of blanks within a piece of text and can even have two blanks next to each other. &nbsp; To create a blank input box place [blank] and [/blank] tags around the options you wish to add in the \'Question\' field. &nbsp; Where there are different spellings for words in UK and US English or acronyms the alternatives can be added as correct items. For example, both the full term and acronym shown here will be marked as correct, [blank]Irritable Bowel Syndrome,IBS[/blank]. &nbsp; &nbsp; Dropdown Lists The disadvantage of a traditional fill-in-the-blank question, as shown above, is the problem of spelling. Dyslexic students and those who have made typing mistakes can be penalised by computer-based marking even though a human might see that they have got the correct answer. As an alternative to the spelling issue, Rogo can present each blank as a dropdown list with a number of pre-written distractors. In the screenshot below the same question as the first one is re-presented using these dropdown lists. Always put the correct answer as the first option, followed by the distractors (all options are randomised automatically).e.g. for [blank]GDP,UDP,ADP,CDP[/blank] on the alpha-subunit of a G-protein which in turn activates enzyme &nbsp; &nbsp; Marking The Marking Method can be set as either Mark per Question or by Option with the number of marks awarded for correct and incorrect responses (negative marks) set in the question.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(17,'Question - Types/Image Hotspot','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Image Hotspot questions require a graphic that is no bigger than 900 x 800 pixels and in one of these 3 format: JPG, GIF or PNG.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the example shown below, the question requires the student to identify two parts of the ear.&nbsp;It&nbsp;is achieved by selecting one of the tabs to the left of the image and then clicking on the correct area of the graphic to the right. The number of different items a question can cover is from 1 to 10 where the example below is using 2. When the student selects a tab and then clicks on part of the image and flag with the corresponding colour is displayed to show their chosen location. The \'View all answers\' checkbox below the tabs allows the student to select whether they just want to see their selection for the current tab or all of the tabs.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/image hotspot.png\" alt=\"image hotspot.png\" width=\"1030\" height=\"755\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"background-color: #dedede; font-size: 90%; padding: 20px;\"><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp; Rogo can support elliptical, rectangular and multi-point irregular polygonal hotspot shapes. Multiple areas can also be highlighted as being correct for one tab.</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Marking and Feedback</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marks can be given for correctly selected requested area of the graphic either by question or option. Negative marks can also be given for incorrect responses. Depending on the feedback settings for the paper, ticks/crosses and correct areas on the graphic can be displayed for each tab.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/image hotspot feedback.png\" alt=\"image hotspot feedback.png\" width=\"1023\" height=\"746\" /></div>','Presentation Image Hotspot questions require a graphic that is no bigger than 900 x 800 pixels and in one of these 3 format: JPG, GIF or PNG. &nbsp; In the example shown below, the question requires the student to identify two parts of the ear.&nbsp;It&nbsp;is achieved by selecting one of the tabs to the left of the image and then clicking on the correct area of the graphic to the right. The number of different items a question can cover is from 1 to 10 where the example below is using 2. When the student selects a tab and then clicks on part of the image and flag with the corresponding colour is displayed to show their chosen location. The \'View all answers\' checkbox below the tabs allows the student to select whether they just want to see their selection for the current tab or all of the tabs. &nbsp; &nbsp; Note:&nbsp; Rogo can support elliptical, rectangular and multi-point irregular polygonal hotspot shapes. Multiple areas can also be highlighted as being correct for one tab. Marking and Feedback Marks can be given for correctly selected requested area of the graphic either by question or option. Negative marks can also be given for incorrect responses. Depending on the feedback settings for the paper, ticks/crosses and correct areas on the graphic can be displayed for each tab. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(18,'Question - Types/Multiple Choice (MCQ)','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo can support multiple choice questions (MCQs) with between 3 and 20 options. Radio buttons are used in the interface so that only one option can be selected. The display order of the options can be selected to show the options in the same order as entered in the editor, alphabetical or random.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mcq_question.png\" alt=\"Multiple Choice Question\" width=\"698\" height=\"288\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">One of the findings from evaluation surveys run about the usability of Rogo concerned some of the affordances provided by paper. For example, many people like to actually cross out on the exam paper distractors that they know to be wrong. This then leaves a smaller sub-set of possibilities to consider. While it is not possible to cross out options on the monitor, this type of action can be simulated&nbsp;by single clicking on the text of the option. Doing so will grey out the option clicked (see below). Clicking again over an already greyed out option will reinstate it in black.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mcq_question3.png\" alt=\"Multiple Choice Question\" width=\"698\" height=\"288\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The example below shows a question based on a Chime molecule which can be rotated by dragging the mouse. The options are also presented horizontally rather than the traditional vertical arrangement.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mcq_question2.png\" alt=\"Multiple Choice Question\" width=\"777\" height=\"849\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Use in Surveys</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The graphic below shows a Multiple Choice Question being used in a Survey paper. The \'Vertical Option Buttons (with \'other\' textbox)\' presentation mode has been selected. This gives the user the option of entering a response in a text field if the options in the question are not appropriate. This presentation mode is not used in exam papers as there is no correct answer.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mcq_other.png\" alt=\"mcq_other.png\" width=\"358\" height=\"240\" /></div>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The marking of MCQ questions is very simple because only one option is correct. If the user selects the correct option then the mark set for correct responses will be awarded. A negative mark can also be set for incorrect responses. A tick or a cross is placed next to the option selected by the user and the emboldened option indicates the correct answer.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mcq_answer.png\" alt=\"Multiple Choice Marking\" width=\"698\" height=\"244\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\">Feedback</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Specific feedback can be given for each option, the feedback for&nbsp;each option then&nbsp;appears regardless of which option is selected by the student. The learning advantage of&nbsp;using this feature is that you can give specific information about why the distractors are incorrect.</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/MCQ editor feedback.png\" alt=\"MCQ editor feedback.png\" width=\"805\" height=\"306\" />&nbsp;</div>','Presentation Rogo can support multiple choice questions (MCQs) with between 3 and 20 options. Radio buttons are used in the interface so that only one option can be selected. The display order of the options can be selected to show the options in the same order as entered in the editor, alphabetical or random.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; One of the findings from evaluation surveys run about the usability of Rogo concerned some of the affordances provided by paper. For example, many people like to actually cross out on the exam paper distractors that they know to be wrong. This then leaves a smaller sub-set of possibilities to consider. While it is not possible to cross out options on the monitor, this type of action can be simulated&nbsp;by single clicking on the text of the option. Doing so will grey out the option clicked (see below). Clicking again over an already greyed out option will reinstate it in black. &nbsp; The example below shows a question based on a Chime molecule which can be rotated by dragging the mouse. The options are also presented horizontally rather than the traditional vertical arrangement. &nbsp; Use in Surveys The graphic below shows a Multiple Choice Question being used in a Survey paper. The \'Vertical Option Buttons (with \'other\' textbox)\' presentation mode has been selected. This gives the user the option of entering a response in a text field if the options in the question are not appropriate. This presentation mode is not used in exam papers as there is no correct answer. &nbsp;  Marking The marking of MCQ questions is very simple because only one option is correct. If the user selects the correct option then the mark set for correct responses will be awarded. A negative mark can also be set for incorrect responses. A tick or a cross is placed next to the option selected by the user and the emboldened option indicates the correct answer. &nbsp; Feedback Specific feedback can be given for each option, the feedback for&nbsp;each option then&nbsp;appears regardless of which option is selected by the student. The learning advantage of&nbsp;using this feature is that you can give specific information about why the distractors are incorrect. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(19,'Question - Types/Multiple Response','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Multiple Response consist of questions which have multiple correct options. Unlike Multiple Choice Questions (MCQs), that can only have <em>one</em> of their options correct, Multiple Response allow each option to be selected or unselected. In the example below, 2 out of the&nbsp;5 options correctly match the question \"Which <strong>two</strong> cities are in Europe\".</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/multiple_response_1.png\" alt=\"multiple_response_1.png\" width=\"450\" height=\"203\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;If more than two options are selected a warning message will be displayed and after clicking \'OK\' the last option checked will be unchecked.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mltp_respn.png\" alt=\"mltp_respn.png\" width=\"356\" height=\"184\" /></div>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Multiple response questions can be marked by question or option where marks for correct and incorrect responses are set in the question. In the screenshot below the user has scored 1 out of 2. The user selected London and New York and so scored only 1 mark for London. London and Paris are highlighed in bold as these are the correct two answers.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/multiple_response_2.png\" alt=\"multiple_response_2.png\" width=\"450\" height=\"203\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Presentation Multiple Response consist of questions which have multiple correct options. Unlike Multiple Choice Questions (MCQs), that can only have one of their options correct, Multiple Response allow each option to be selected or unselected. In the example below, 2 out of the&nbsp;5 options correctly match the question \"Which two cities are in Europe\". &nbsp;If more than two options are selected a warning message will be displayed and after clicking \'OK\' the last option checked will be unchecked.  Marking Multiple response questions can be marked by question or option where marks for correct and incorrect responses are set in the question. In the screenshot below the user has scored 1 out of 2. The user selected London and New York and so scored only 1 mark for London. London and Paris are highlighed in bold as these are the correct two answers. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(20,'Question - Types/Ranking','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rather than selecting the correct option, as is the case with the other question types, the aim of a ranking question is to see if an exam candidate can put various options in the correct order.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/ranking_question.png\" alt=\"Ranking Question\" width=\"693\" height=\"267\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If the paper is formative then feedback, such as that shown below, will be displayed. This shows the order the student placed the options in and the correct order. In the example below the student has got the first 3 options correct but mixed up the fourth and fifth options.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/ranking_answer.png\" alt=\"ranking_answer.png\" width=\"703\" height=\"214\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The example shown above requires all options in the question to be ranked but you can use ranking questions to pick a specified number of options and rank these.&nbsp;The graphic&nbsp;below shows how this is set up in the question editor. In this example, one mark&nbsp;is awarded for correctly selected options with a bonus mark awarded for ranking these in the correct order.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/ranking bonus mark method.png\" alt=\"ranking bonus mark method.png\" width=\"907\" height=\"446\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<p>There are number of different ways of marking a ranking question:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left: 10px;\">\r\n<li class=\"subheading\">Mark per option\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;\">The correct&nbsp;mark set for the question is awarded for each item in the correct order. Zero marks (or the incorrect mark)&nbsp;awarded per item for any options in the wrong position.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li class=\"subheading\">Mark per question\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;\">All options in the list have to be correctly ranked to be awarded&nbsp;the Correct&nbsp;mark as set in the question. If any option is incorrectly ordered then zero (or the incorrect mark)&nbsp;is scored for the question.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li class=\"subheading\">Allow partial Marks\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;\">The&nbsp;mark set for correct answers&nbsp;is awarded for each item in the correct order.&nbsp;Partial marks are awarded for items that are only one number out. For example, if a user put 2nd or 4th as the position of&nbsp;an item that should be ranked 3rd&nbsp;then this would be awarded the partial mark set for the question. Any other answers are awarded zero or the mark set for incorrect answers.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li class=\"subheading\">Bonus Mark\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;\">One mark is awarded for each option that is applicable (i.e. should be included in the ranking) irrespective of position. A bonus mark will be added to this score if all the appropriate options are also in the correct order.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>','Presentation Rather than selecting the correct option, as is the case with the other question types, the aim of a ranking question is to see if an exam candidate can put various options in the correct order. &nbsp; If the paper is formative then feedback, such as that shown below, will be displayed. This shows the order the student placed the options in and the correct order. In the example below the student has got the first 3 options correct but mixed up the fourth and fifth options. &nbsp; The example shown above requires all options in the question to be ranked but you can use ranking questions to pick a specified number of options and rank these.&nbsp;The graphic&nbsp;below shows how this is set up in the question editor. In this example, one mark&nbsp;is awarded for correctly selected options with a bonus mark awarded for ranking these in the correct order. &nbsp; Marking There are number of different ways of marking a ranking question: Mark per option The correct&nbsp;mark set for the question is awarded for each item in the correct order. Zero marks (or the incorrect mark)&nbsp;awarded per item for any options in the wrong position. Mark per question All options in the list have to be correctly ranked to be awarded&nbsp;the Correct&nbsp;mark as set in the question. If any option is incorrectly ordered then zero (or the incorrect mark)&nbsp;is scored for the question. Allow partial Marks The&nbsp;mark set for correct answers&nbsp;is awarded for each item in the correct order.&nbsp;Partial marks are awarded for items that are only one number out. For example, if a user put 2nd or 4th as the position of&nbsp;an item that should be ranked 3rd&nbsp;then this would be awarded the partial mark set for the question. Any other answers are awarded zero or the mark set for incorrect answers. Bonus Mark One mark is awarded for each option that is applicable (i.e. should be included in the ranking) irrespective of position. A bonus mark will be added to this score if all the appropriate options are also in the correct order.  &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(21,'Question - Types/Matrix','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Matrix questions can be thought of as conceptually quite similar to extended matching. The most obvious difference is in visual appearance. The questions are presented in rows with possible answers as columns. Radio buttons are used as only one answer per row can be selected. In the example below the student must match the application to the file extension.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Options can be displayed in 3 different orders:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Display Order (as set in the question editor)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Alphabetic</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Random</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/matrix_question.png\" alt=\"Matrix question\" width=\"414\" height=\"289\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marks can be given for the question as a whole or for each option where each row is awarded the mark set for correct responses. Marks for incorrect responses can also be set.&nbsp; The cells with a light-green background signify the correct answers; the selected radio buttons show the student\'s original answers. Where the student answer matches the correct answer a tick is displayed, if not a cross.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/matrix_answer.png\" alt=\"Matrix answer\" width=\"561\" height=\"277\" /></div>','Presentation Matrix questions can be thought of as conceptually quite similar to extended matching. The most obvious difference is in visual appearance. The questions are presented in rows with possible answers as columns. Radio buttons are used as only one answer per row can be selected. In the example below the student must match the application to the file extension. &nbsp; Options can be displayed in 3 different orders:  Display Order (as set in the question editor)  Alphabetic  Random  &nbsp; Marking Marks can be given for the question as a whole or for each option where each row is awarded the mark set for correct responses. Marks for incorrect responses can also be set.&nbsp; The cells with a light-green background signify the correct answers; the selected radio buttons show the student\'s original answers. Where the student answer matches the correct answer a tick is displayed, if not a cross. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(22,'Question - Types/Flash','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo supports a wide number of different question types using in-built XHTML form elements such as radio buttons, check boxes and dropdown lists, but there are times when more interactive questions are required. A Macromedia Flash interface type of question has been added to allow this to be done. When such a question is added a question SWF and optional answer/feedback SWF file can be uploaded to the server. Parameters can be fed into the Flash movie so that it is properly configured. Marks from the movie are sent back to Rogo and recorded in the usual way. This allows for the combining of Flash with any of the other question types on the same paper.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The example below shows a Flash movie that requires the examinee to assemble the apparatus used for venepuncture. In this example the exam candidate is required to drag each parts into place in the correct order. One mark is awarded for each correctly assembled part but all marks are lost if a critical error is made.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/flash_question.png\" alt=\"Flash Interface Question\" width=\"729\" height=\"368\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The question SWF file on the questions screen records the mark that the student scored and sends it to the system database. This is stored in the Rogo log table and then subsequently retrieved and passed into the answer/feedback SWF. Obviously the feedback for each SWF movie differs depending on the content and nature of the movie and is totally customisable. An example of possible feedback is shown below, this is a still from an animation of the necessary equipment being assembled.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/flash_answer.png\" alt=\"Flash Interface Marking\" width=\"818\" height=\"373\" /></div>','Presentation Rogo supports a wide number of different question types using in-built XHTML form elements such as radio buttons, check boxes and dropdown lists, but there are times when more interactive questions are required. A Macromedia Flash interface type of question has been added to allow this to be done. When such a question is added a question SWF and optional answer/feedback SWF file can be uploaded to the server. Parameters can be fed into the Flash movie so that it is properly configured. Marks from the movie are sent back to Rogo and recorded in the usual way. This allows for the combining of Flash with any of the other question types on the same paper. The example below shows a Flash movie that requires the examinee to assemble the apparatus used for venepuncture. In this example the exam candidate is required to drag each parts into place in the correct order. One mark is awarded for each correctly assembled part but all marks are lost if a critical error is made. &nbsp; Marking The question SWF file on the questions screen records the mark that the student scored and sends it to the system database. This is stored in the Rogo log table and then subsequently retrieved and passed into the answer/feedback SWF. Obviously the feedback for each SWF movie differs depending on the content and nature of the movie and is totally customisable. An example of possible feedback is shown below, this is a still from an animation of the necessary equipment being assembled. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(23,'Assessments','<h2>Types of Assessments</h2>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Formative</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Formative assessments can be thought of as simple practice tests. They are useful in that they allow the user to determine: 1) their own understanding (including gaps) of a field, and 2) the difficulty and style of an end summative assessment. The marks generated from sitting formative assessments are never used to determine the final grading of a course or degree, they are practice only.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Progress Test</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Progress tests are used&nbsp;as a way of allowing students to monitor and reflect upon their progression through the year before they reach the final&nbsp;summative exam. Each progress test&nbsp;is setup to allow each student to log in during a specified&nbsp;period of time&nbsp;to take the exam. Each student may only take each progress test once and marks will <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">not</span> be given immediately afterwards as with formative assessments.&nbsp;After all students have completed the test, the marks can be sent by email and the paper can be changed to Formative to allow each student to go into the paper and&nbsp;view the marks and feedback for each question.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Summative</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Summative assessments are any exams or test where the marks are used to determine final course/module or degree grades.&nbsp;Rogo has supported a simultaneous start of over 360 students sitting the same exam. Please liaise with&nbsp;the learning team (email&nbsp;$support_email)&nbsp;if you are thinking about using Rogo for any summative exams.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">See also:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=63\">Online Summative Assessment Protocols &amp; Regulations</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=73\">External Examiners</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px;\" />\r\n<h2>Types of Questions</h2>\r\n<p>Click on any of the links below for more information and screen-shots demonstrating the question types supported by Rogo:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=305\">Area</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=68\">Calculation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=13\">Dichotomous</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=14\">Extended Matching</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=16\">Fill-in-the-Blank</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=22\">Flash Interface</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=17\">Image Hotspot</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=60\">Labelling</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=21\">Matrix</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=18\">Multiple Choice</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=19\">Multiple Response</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=20\">Ranking</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=252\">Script Concordance Test (SCT)</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=61\">Textbox</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=293\">True/False</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Types of Assessments Formative Formative assessments can be thought of as simple practice tests. They are useful in that they allow the user to determine: 1) their own understanding (including gaps) of a field, and 2) the difficulty and style of an end summative assessment. The marks generated from sitting formative assessments are never used to determine the final grading of a course or degree, they are practice only. Progress Test Progress tests are used&nbsp;as a way of allowing students to monitor and reflect upon their progression through the year before they reach the final&nbsp;summative exam. Each progress test&nbsp;is setup to allow each student to log in during a specified&nbsp;period of time&nbsp;to take the exam. Each student may only take each progress test once and marks will not be given immediately afterwards as with formative assessments.&nbsp;After all students have completed the test, the marks can be sent by email and the paper can be changed to Formative to allow each student to go into the paper and&nbsp;view the marks and feedback for each question. Summative Summative assessments are any exams or test where the marks are used to determine final course/module or degree grades.&nbsp;Rogo has supported a simultaneous start of over 360 students sitting the same exam. Please liaise with&nbsp;the learning team (email&nbsp;$support_email)&nbsp;if you are thinking about using Rogo for any summative exams. See also: Online Summative Assessment Protocols &amp; Regulations External Examiners  Types of Questions Click on any of the links below for more information and screen-shots demonstrating the question types supported by Rogo: Area Calculation Dichotomous Extended Matching Fill-in-the-Blank Flash Interface Image Hotspot Labelling Matrix Multiple Choice Multiple Response Ranking Script Concordance Test (SCT) Textbox True/False ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(129,'Summative Exams/Excluding Questions Post Exam','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Even after careful scrutiny from internal and external reviewers there are still occasions when some of the questions on an assessment may not perform as expected. In extreme cases where either the whole cohort got a question correct or very few got it correct it can be advisable to exclude this question or questions from the students\' marks.</p>\r\n<h2>Process of Exclusion</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">To determine which questions to exclude the Frequency/Facility Analysis report and Discrimination Analysis reports can be used. In the screenshot below a Frequency/Facility Analysis report has been run and this particular question has been answered particularly poorly. Only 12% of the cohort have got this Easy/Essential question correct:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/question_exclude1.png\" alt=\"question_exclude1.png\" width=\"453\" height=\"471\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>To exclude this question click on the <img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/question_exclude_icon.png\" alt=\"question_exclude_icon.png\" width=\"15\" height=\"11\" /> icon and the screen will change to:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/question_exclude2.png\" alt=\"question_exclude2.png\" width=\"453\" height=\"471\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Exclusions can be made&nbsp;from the Discrimination Analysis report. It is possible to exclude some questions on the basis of their Frequency/Facility values and then exclude further questions with poor Discrimination values. If a question is excluded erroneously simply click on the exclude icon again and it will return to black.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After analysing all the questions on a report and excluding poorly performing ones click on the \'Save\' button at the bottom of the screen to actually save the exclusions.</p>\r\n<h2>Results of Exclusion</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After clicking \'Save\' to store the exclusions you will be taken back to the screen listing all the questions on the paper. From here is it possible to go back into the \'Analysis Menu\' and run reports such as \'Class Totals\' and the \'Export Reports\'. Any questions excluded will not now be taken into account when running these reports.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> Calculate Random Mark is automatically adjusted (if used) after questions are excluded. Standards set cut scores are adjusted too automatically after question exclusion but the pass mark for a paper is not automatically altered. Please refer back to Standards Setting reports and if the pass mark has changed this must be altered in the \'Edit Properties\' dialog of the paper.</p>','Even after careful scrutiny from internal and external reviewers there are still occasions when some of the questions on an assessment may not perform as expected. In extreme cases where either the whole cohort got a question correct or very few got it correct it can be advisable to exclude this question or questions from the students\' marks. Process of Exclusion To determine which questions to exclude the Frequency/Facility Analysis report and Discrimination Analysis reports can be used. In the screenshot below a Frequency/Facility Analysis report has been run and this particular question has been answered particularly poorly. Only 12% of the cohort have got this Easy/Essential question correct: &nbsp; &nbsp; To exclude this question click on the icon and the screen will change to: &nbsp; Exclusions can be made&nbsp;from the Discrimination Analysis report. It is possible to exclude some questions on the basis of their Frequency/Facility values and then exclude further questions with poor Discrimination values. If a question is excluded erroneously simply click on the exclude icon again and it will return to black. After analysing all the questions on a report and excluding poorly performing ones click on the \'Save\' button at the bottom of the screen to actually save the exclusions. Results of Exclusion After clicking \'Save\' to store the exclusions you will be taken back to the screen listing all the questions on the paper. From here is it possible to go back into the \'Analysis Menu\' and run reports such as \'Class Totals\' and the \'Export Reports\'. Any questions excluded will not now be taken into account when running these reports. Note: Calculate Random Mark is automatically adjusted (if used) after questions are excluded. Standards set cut scores are adjusted too automatically after question exclusion but the pass mark for a paper is not automatically altered. Please refer back to Standards Setting reports and if the pass mark has changed this must be altered in the \'Edit Properties\' dialog of the paper.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(26,'Navigation/Bi-Directional','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In bidirectional mode the user is free to move around the paper one screen at a time forwards or backwards at the bottom of the screen (see buttons in screenshot below) or by clicking on the appropriate screen numbers in the top left of the screen. Answers are recorded in the database for the current screen whenever the user moves to a different one. No warning label is displayed neither is the warning dialog box which is used with the above unidirectional navigation. The only check that is made is when the user clicks on the \'Finish\' button on the final screen. Clicking \'OK\' on this final check will complete the paper and the user will no longer be able to navigate anymore.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Navigation_2.png\" alt=\"Navigation_2.png\" width=\"658\" height=\"145\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','In bidirectional mode the user is free to move around the paper one screen at a time forwards or backwards at the bottom of the screen (see buttons in screenshot below) or by clicking on the appropriate screen numbers in the top left of the screen. Answers are recorded in the database for the current screen whenever the user moves to a different one. No warning label is displayed neither is the warning dialog box which is used with the above unidirectional navigation. The only check that is made is when the user clicks on the \'Finish\' button on the final screen. Clicking \'OK\' on this final check will complete the paper and the user will no longer be able to navigate anymore. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(27,'Navigation/Uni-Directional','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In unidirectional mode all questions have to be completed on the current screen before submitting. There is no opportunity to complete previous questions once the user proceeds forwards.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The screenshot below was taken on screen 2 of an assessment paper. It only shows a single button to continue to screen 3.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Navigation_1.png\" alt=\"Navigation_1.png\" width=\"658\" height=\"159\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once the \'Screen 3 &gt;\' button is clicked a warning dialog box is display similar to the one below. If the user has completed all questions and is happy with their answers then they should click \'OK\'. Otherwise selecting \'Cancel\' will dismiss the dialog box and keep the user on the current screen.</p>\r\n<div align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/Navigation_3.png\" alt=\"Navigation_3.png\" width=\"490\" height=\"171\" /></div>\r\n<p>Unidirectional navigation is used on assessment papers which use questions which could result in <em><a href=\"index.php?id=28\" target=\"_top\">consequential error</a></em> or <em><a href=\"index.php?id=29\" target=\"_top\">consequential help</a></em>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','In unidirectional mode all questions have to be completed on the current screen before submitting. There is no opportunity to complete previous questions once the user proceeds forwards. The screenshot below was taken on screen 2 of an assessment paper. It only shows a single button to continue to screen 3.&nbsp; Once the \'Screen 3 &gt;\' button is clicked a warning dialog box is display similar to the one below. If the user has completed all questions and is happy with their answers then they should click \'OK\'. Otherwise selecting \'Cancel\' will dismiss the dialog box and keep the user on the current screen. Unidirectional navigation is used on assessment papers which use questions which could result in consequential error or consequential help. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(28,'Navigation/Consequential Error','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Consequential error can occur in situations where two or more questions are related to each other. Take the following as an example: in the first question the user is asked which is the largest company. Unfortunately they incorrectly answer \'Marks and Spencer\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/consequential_error1.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"308\" height=\"202\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In question 2 they are asked what this company\'s primary line of business is. Here they answer \'Retail\' which matches \'Marks and Spencer\'. However, they score zero for both questions since \'Microsoft\' is the biggest company and its line of business is \'Software\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/consequential_error2.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"318\" height=\"196\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Two avoid such situations the exam writer should place these two questions on different screens and set the whole assessment paper to <em>unidirectional</em> mode. The second question on the following screen should be amended to read \'Microsoft is the largest company. What is its primary business?\' thus setting any erroneous students back on track.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 40%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" align=\"left\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=27\">Uni-Directional</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=29\">Consequential Help</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Consequential error can occur in situations where two or more questions are related to each other. Take the following as an example: in the first question the user is asked which is the largest company. Unfortunately they incorrectly answer \'Marks and Spencer\'. &nbsp; In question 2 they are asked what this company\'s primary line of business is. Here they answer \'Retail\' which matches \'Marks and Spencer\'. However, they score zero for both questions since \'Microsoft\' is the biggest company and its line of business is \'Software\'. &nbsp; Two avoid such situations the exam writer should place these two questions on different screens and set the whole assessment paper to unidirectional mode. The second question on the following screen should be amended to read \'Microsoft is the largest company. What is its primary business?\' thus setting any erroneous students back on track. &nbsp; See also: Uni-Directional Consequential Help ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(29,'Navigation/Consequential Help','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Consequential help can occur in situations where two or more questions are related to each other. Take the following as an example: the user is asked what test to run for a woman who as fainted. This is a new sentence.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/consequential_help1.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"416\" height=\"190\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The user selects \'X-Ray\' as their answer. However, in question 2 they are told that Mrs Jones\' blood sugar level is low. This allows the user to scroll back up to question 1 and change their answer to \'Blood\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/consequential_help2.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"339\" height=\"186\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Two avoid such situations the exam writer should place these two questions on different screens and set the whole assessment paper to <em>unidirectional</em> mode.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 40%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" align=\"left\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=27\">Uni-Directional</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=28\">Consequential Error</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Consequential help can occur in situations where two or more questions are related to each other. Take the following as an example: the user is asked what test to run for a woman who as fainted. This is a new sentence. &nbsp; The user selects \'X-Ray\' as their answer. However, in question 2 they are told that Mrs Jones\' blood sugar level is low. This allows the user to scroll back up to question 1 and change their answer to \'Blood\'. &nbsp; Two avoid such situations the exam writer should place these two questions on different screens and set the whole assessment paper to unidirectional mode. &nbsp; See also: Uni-Directional Consequential Error &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(58,'Marking/No Adjustment','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">\'No Adjustment\' marking should be used on&nbsp;papers made up of True/False/Abstain where negative marking is already being applied at the question level.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For&nbsp;papers where the pass mark has been derived from a standards setting process there will be an option to select this as the marking method.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A paper can be set to \'no adjustment\' by clicking on the \'Edit Properties\' link from the sidebar menu. There is a setting, see below, on the \'General\' tab of the dialog box.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/no_adjustment_marking.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"882\" height=\"692\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">With \'no adjustment\' set each question in an assessment paper is positively marked. Incorrect answers score zero while correct answers are worth one or more marks.</p>','\'No Adjustment\' marking should be used on&nbsp;papers made up of True/False/Abstain where negative marking is already being applied at the question level. For&nbsp;papers where the pass mark has been derived from a standards setting process there will be an option to select this as the marking method. A paper can be set to \'no adjustment\' by clicking on the \'Edit Properties\' link from the sidebar menu. There is a setting, see below, on the \'General\' tab of the dialog box. With \'no adjustment\' set each question in an assessment paper is positively marked. Incorrect answers score zero while correct answers are worth one or more marks.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(115,'Image/Formatting','113',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(30,'Reports/Class Totals','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To generate a class listing of all examinees\' responses to an assessment (formative self-assessment or summative), locate the paper and enter it, then select the \'Reports\' link from the \'Paper Tasks\' pane. This will bring up a menu similar to the one below. Select the correct dates you are interested in (1) and click on the \'Class Totals\' link (2).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/class_totals_3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"540\" height=\"316\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The top of this report is filled with a table showing: examinee name, username, ID, degree course, raw mark, adjusted %, start date/time, duration and IP address. \'Student attempts only\' is checked by default - unchecking this option will allow&nbsp;staff attempts (if any)&nbsp;to be also presented in the report.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Class_totals3.png\" alt=\"Class_totals3.png\" width=\"1009\" height=\"204\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To view a students\' answers click on the icon to the left of the student name.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Below the table of user responses is a distribution bar chart plotting the frequency of each percentage score. The bars of any percentage below the pass mark are coloured red for fast identification. Below the distribution chart is a scatter plot of adjusted percentage marks against time.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note:</strong> Incomplete responses are not shown on this chart.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/class totals distribution chart and scatter.png\" alt=\"class totals distribution chart and scatter.png\" width=\"797\" height=\"702\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Additional Student Information</h2>\r\n<p>By clicking on the paper icon on the extreme left or the student name a popup menu will appear:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/reports class_totals student popup3.png\" alt=\"reports class_totals student popup3.png\" width=\"756\" height=\"309\" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Exam Script</strong><br />This will open a new window and display the exam script for the current student.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Feedback</strong><br />This will open a new window and display learning objective-based feedback in the same way as the student will be able to access through their own account in Insight.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Student Profile</strong><br />This will jump to the profile of the student which shows details such as student number, academic year and what Rogo papers have been taken.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>New Note...</strong><br />This will create a new note for the current student. Usually these are only used to keep track of any problems mid-exam.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Re-assign to User...</strong><br />This will be enabled when the submenu is called from a temporary guest account. It is the method of re-assigning marks from the temporary account to the real user account.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Late Submissions</strong><br />This option is used to either accept or reject late submissions for summative exams.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','To generate a class listing of all examinees\' responses to an assessment (formative self-assessment or summative), locate the paper and enter it, then select the \'Reports\' link from the \'Paper Tasks\' pane. This will bring up a menu similar to the one below. Select the correct dates you are interested in (1) and click on the \'Class Totals\' link (2). The top of this report is filled with a table showing: examinee name, username, ID, degree course, raw mark, adjusted %, start date/time, duration and IP address. \'Student attempts only\' is checked by default - unchecking this option will allow&nbsp;staff attempts (if any)&nbsp;to be also presented in the report. To view a students\' answers click on the icon to the left of the student name. Below the table of user responses is a distribution bar chart plotting the frequency of each percentage score. The bars of any percentage below the pass mark are coloured red for fast identification. Below the distribution chart is a scatter plot of adjusted percentage marks against time. &nbsp; Note: Incomplete responses are not shown on this chart. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Additional Student Information By clicking on the paper icon on the extreme left or the student name a popup menu will appear:  Exam ScriptThis will open a new window and display the exam script for the current student.  FeedbackThis will open a new window and display learning objective-based feedback in the same way as the student will be able to access through their own account in Insight.  Student ProfileThis will jump to the profile of the student which shows details such as student number, academic year and what Rogo papers have been taken.  New Note...This will create a new note for the current student. Usually these are only used to keep track of any problems mid-exam.  Re-assign to User...This will be enabled when the submenu is called from a temporary guest account. It is the method of re-assigning marks from the temporary account to the real user account.  Late SubmissionsThis option is used to either accept or reject late submissions for summative exams. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(229,'Blueprinting','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The process of planning assessment content against learning objectives is known as blueprinting.&nbsp;This is achieved in by mapping each question in Rogo to&nbsp;learning objectives. This is covered in the Mapping Objectives page.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px;\" />\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">See also:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=147\">Objectives</a></li>\r\n</ul>','The process of planning assessment content against learning objectives is known as blueprinting.&nbsp;This is achieved in by mapping each question in Rogo to&nbsp;learning objectives. This is covered in the Mapping Objectives page. &nbsp; See also: Objectives ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(32,'Reports/Class Totals as CSV file','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For those users without the latest copy of Office 2003, the class totals data can be exported as a CSV file for compatibility with older versions of Excel. To do this select the \'Reports\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane, set the correct dates you are interested in analysing and then click on the \'Class Totals (CSV file)\' link:</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/class_totals_csv1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"540\" height=\"316\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A pop-up box will appear asking the user whether to open or save the file. Usually, on a correctly configured system, open will successfully load the CSV file directly into Excel. If this fails, or you wish to load the data into some alternative software package, click on \'Save\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/class_totals_csv2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"654\" height=\"103\" /></div>\r\n<p>The resulting raw CSV file shown in a text editor:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/reports class totals tab deliminated.png\" alt=\"reports class totals tab deliminated.png\" width=\"784\" height=\"322\" /></p>','For those users without the latest copy of Office 2003, the class totals data can be exported as a CSV file for compatibility with older versions of Excel. To do this select the \'Reports\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane, set the correct dates you are interested in analysing and then click on the \'Class Totals (CSV file)\' link: &nbsp; A pop-up box will appear asking the user whether to open or save the file. Usually, on a correctly configured system, open will successfully load the CSV file directly into Excel. If this fails, or you wish to load the data into some alternative software package, click on \'Save\'. The resulting raw CSV file shown in a text editor: ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(33,'Reports/Quantitative Analysis','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Quantitative data is generated from likert scales which are mainly used in Surveys. To generate a report on quantitative data from a survey, select the survey paper and then the select \'Analysis Menu\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. This will bring up a menu similar to the one below:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<div><img src=\"images/reports_survey.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"542\" height=\"371\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Select the correct dates you are interested in and click on the format of the report that you require. Reports can be shown in XHTML or Word format and show the details of student responses to each of the questions.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/quantitative 1.PNG\" alt=\"quantitative 1.PNG\" width=\"759\" height=\"315\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"color: #c00000;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify; color: #c00000;\"><strong>Note:</strong><br />The \'Word 2003 format\' version of this report will not work properly with Word 2003 service pack 2. Please install Service Pack 3 from the Microsoft website for it to correctly work.</div>\r\n</div>','Quantitative data is generated from likert scales which are mainly used in Surveys. To generate a report on quantitative data from a survey, select the survey paper and then the select \'Analysis Menu\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. This will bring up a menu similar to the one below: &nbsp;  &nbsp; Select the correct dates you are interested in and click on the format of the report that you require. Reports can be shown in XHTML or Word format and show the details of student responses to each of the questions. &nbsp; &nbsp; Note:The \'Word 2003 format\' version of this report will not work properly with Word 2003 service pack 2. Please install Service Pack 3 from the Microsoft website for it to correctly work. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(34,'Reports/Qualitative Analysis','<div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Qualitative data is generated from Textbox questions which are mainly used in Surveys. To generate a report on qualitative data from a survey, select the survey paper and then the select \'Analysis Menu\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. This will bring up a menu similar to the one below:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/reports_survey.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"542\" height=\"371\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Select the correct dates you are interested in and click on the format of the report that you require. Reports can be shown in XHTML or Word format and show the details of student responses to each of the questions. Data resulting from open-ended textboxes is presented as a bulleted list - one bullet per candidate response.&nbsp;Automated processing of free-text comments is difficult for computers so Rogo does not attempt to do this. Instead it provides some basic tools for a researcher to look for patterns of responses and to summarise. The textbox in the top right hand corner of the screen can be used to enter keywords which can then be highlighted. In the screenshot below the user has entered the word \'good\' and all occurrences are displayed with a yellow background. This makes it easier to pull out all the sentences expressing similar views.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/qualitiative with highlightspng.png\" alt=\"qualitiative with highlightspng.png\" width=\"806\" height=\"336\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>',' Qualitative data is generated from Textbox questions which are mainly used in Surveys. To generate a report on qualitative data from a survey, select the survey paper and then the select \'Analysis Menu\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. This will bring up a menu similar to the one below: &nbsp;  &nbsp; Select the correct dates you are interested in and click on the format of the report that you require. Reports can be shown in XHTML or Word format and show the details of student responses to each of the questions. Data resulting from open-ended textboxes is presented as a bulleted list - one bullet per candidate response.&nbsp;Automated processing of free-text comments is difficult for computers so Rogo does not attempt to do this. Instead it provides some basic tools for a researcher to look for patterns of responses and to summarise. The textbox in the top right hand corner of the screen can be used to enter keywords which can then be highlighted. In the screenshot below the user has entered the word \'good\' and all occurrences are displayed with a yellow background. This makes it easier to pull out all the sentences expressing similar views. &nbsp; &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(37,'Folders/Creating new Folders','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When dealing with a large number of papers it is often useful to employ some sort of categorisation system based around folders. In addition to the set paper \'type\' folders that Rogo displays at the top of the homepage, it is also possible to create \'personal\' folders for your own use.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To create a new folder select the \'Make a new Folder\' (1)&nbsp;link from the \'General\' task pane on the homepage. A new folder will be displayed under the subheading of \'My Folders\' with a small textbox and a create button. Enter a suitable name for the new folder (2) and click on \'Create\' (3).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/New_folder2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"677\" height=\"408\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>','When dealing with a large number of papers it is often useful to employ some sort of categorisation system based around folders. In addition to the set paper \'type\' folders that Rogo displays at the top of the homepage, it is also possible to create \'personal\' folders for your own use. To create a new folder select the \'Make a new Folder\' (1)&nbsp;link from the \'General\' task pane on the homepage. A new folder will be displayed under the subheading of \'My Folders\' with a small textbox and a create button. Enter a suitable name for the new folder (2) and click on \'Create\' (3). &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(38,'Folders/Deleting','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When a folder is no longer required it may be deleted by first going into the folder and then selecting the \'Delete this folder\' link from the \'General\' pane. As personal folders only provide links to papers the papers shown in a folder&nbsp;are not deleted when&nbsp;the folder is deleted.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/delete folder1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"574\" height=\"383\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','When a folder is no longer required it may be deleted by first going into the folder and then selecting the \'Delete this folder\' link from the \'General\' pane. As personal folders only provide links to papers the papers shown in a folder&nbsp;are not deleted when&nbsp;the folder is deleted. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(39,'Folders/Assigning papers to','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Papers can be assigned (or put into) folders using the \'Create new Paper\' or \'Edit Properties\' functions. In the screenshot below the user has selected an existing paper and then clicked on \'Edit Properties\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. In the dialog box there is a \'folder\' field with a dropdown list showing all the folders owned by the current user. In this case&nbsp;\'AR personal folder\'&nbsp;has been selected. To confirm the selection, click on \'OK\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/assign paper to folder.png\" alt=\"assign paper to folder.png\" width=\"757\" height=\"646\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Papers can be assigned (or put into) folders using the \'Create new Paper\' or \'Edit Properties\' functions. In the screenshot below the user has selected an existing paper and then clicked on \'Edit Properties\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. In the dialog box there is a \'folder\' field with a dropdown list showing all the folders owned by the current user. In this case&nbsp;\'AR personal folder\'&nbsp;has been selected. To confirm the selection, click on \'OK\'. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(50,'User Functions/Search for Users','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To search for a user enter either their&nbsp;username into the relevant textboxes on the left hand side and then click \'Search\'. If you do not know their username you can enter their last name and to narrow down the search further the degree and academic year of study dropdown lists can be selected.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/search users.png\" alt=\"search users.png\" width=\"663\" height=\"302\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','To search for a user enter either their&nbsp;username into the relevant textboxes on the left hand side and then click \'Search\'. If you do not know their username you can enter their last name and to narrow down the search further the degree and academic year of study dropdown lists can be selected. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(51,'User Functions/View user file','<p style=\"text-align: justify; color: #c00000;\"><strong>Note:</strong> \'View user file\' can be used to find staff and external examiners in addition to students (click on \'Advanced\' for options).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To view the assessment and survey activities of a user first run a search for the person (1) you wish to view and click&nbsp;\'Search\' (2). The name is in the format of user (staff or student) last name and optional initials. For example, you could search for \'Smith\' for all the Smiths or \'Smith, J\' to search for John Smith.&nbsp;Find the user from the list of matching names and single click on the appropriate line (3). Next, click on the \'View user file\' link (4) from the \'Current User Tasks\' pane.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/user_file1.png\" alt=\"user_file1.png\" width=\"872\" height=\"485\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After clicking on the \'View user file\' information about the student (last name, initials, title, username) will be displayed together with a record of all assessments and surveys completed (see below).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/user_file2.png\" alt=\"user_file2.png\" width=\"674\" height=\"371\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Viewing Exam Papers</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To view the answers of a user to any type of assessment, locate the correct paper on the list and then click on the&nbsp;icon to the left of the paper name. This will popup in a new window with the question paper and examinee\'s answers.</p>','Note: \'View user file\' can be used to find staff and external examiners in addition to students (click on \'Advanced\' for options). To view the assessment and survey activities of a user first run a search for the person (1) you wish to view and click&nbsp;\'Search\' (2). The name is in the format of user (staff or student) last name and optional initials. For example, you could search for \'Smith\' for all the Smiths or \'Smith, J\' to search for John Smith.&nbsp;Find the user from the list of matching names and single click on the appropriate line (3). Next, click on the \'View user file\' link (4) from the \'Current User Tasks\' pane. After clicking on the \'View user file\' information about the student (last name, initials, title, username) will be displayed together with a record of all assessments and surveys completed (see below). Viewing Exam Papers To view the answers of a user to any type of assessment, locate the correct paper on the list and then click on the&nbsp;icon to the left of the paper name. This will popup in a new window with the question paper and examinee\'s answers.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(308,'Administrative Tools/Summative Exam Scheduling','<p>See also: <a href=\"display_page.php?id=307\">Summative Exams/Central Scheduling</a></p>\r\n<h2>SysAdmin Staff</h2>\r\n<p>When an academic member of staff creates a new summative exam, and central summative exam scheduling is switch on, a warning will be displayed on the \'Administrative Tools\' screen:</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_no_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/sysadmin_summ_sched_1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"195\" height=\"121\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The number in the red circle is the number of unscheduled summative papers which are pending. Only SysAdmin and Admin user roles can change time/dates on a summative paper when central summative exam scheduling is turned on. To perform scheduling click on the above \'Summative Exam Scheduling\' icon.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/sysadmin_summ_sched_2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"720\" height=\"180\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A list of unscheduled and scheduled papers should be shown. Either double-click on the paper name \'Advanced Astrophysics\' or single click on it and select \'View Details\' from the sidebar menu. In the screenshot below can be seen the details the academic filled out when they created the paper. From here we can select \'Edit Properties\' to bring up the paper dialog box where dates and labs can be set. After this the person performing the scheduling should select \'Email...\' from the sidebar menu and inform the academic of the selected time and date.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/sysadmin_summ_sched_3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"848\" height=\"364\" /></p>\r\n<p>After start time/date, end time/date and computer lab have been saved the unscheduled paper will now appear as scheduled and have a small calendar icon displayed. You can see a precise time/date is shown 06/05/2013 11:00 and the computer labs are rooms C20 and C19 on University Park. At this point the summative exam paper will also appear on the central exams calendar.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/sysadmin_summ_sched_4.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"720\" height=\"180\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Correcting Mistakes</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If an academic has created an assessment as a summative exam by mistake then a SysAdmin user can select \'Convert to Formative\' to change its type from summative to formative.</p>','See also: Summative Exams/Central Scheduling SysAdmin Staff When an academic member of staff creates a new summative exam, and central summative exam scheduling is switch on, a warning will be displayed on the \'Administrative Tools\' screen: The number in the red circle is the number of unscheduled summative papers which are pending. Only SysAdmin and Admin user roles can change time/dates on a summative paper when central summative exam scheduling is turned on. To perform scheduling click on the above \'Summative Exam Scheduling\' icon. A list of unscheduled and scheduled papers should be shown. Either double-click on the paper name \'Advanced Astrophysics\' or single click on it and select \'View Details\' from the sidebar menu. In the screenshot below can be seen the details the academic filled out when they created the paper. From here we can select \'Edit Properties\' to bring up the paper dialog box where dates and labs can be set. After this the person performing the scheduling should select \'Email...\' from the sidebar menu and inform the academic of the selected time and date. After start time/date, end time/date and computer lab have been saved the unscheduled paper will now appear as scheduled and have a small calendar icon displayed. You can see a precise time/date is shown 06/05/2013 11:00 and the computer labs are rooms C20 and C19 on University Park. At this point the summative exam paper will also appear on the central exams calendar. Correcting Mistakes If an academic has created an assessment as a summative exam by mistake then a SysAdmin user can select \'Convert to Formative\' to change its type from summative to formative.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(172,'Standards Setting/Scaling Marks','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Standards Setting reviews produce cut scores (pass marks) which are individual and differ from paper to paper. As a result it is difficult to compare between years of study or across modules. To overcome this it is possible in Rogo to scale back to a standard pass mark. To do this a paper must first be standard set using either Ebel or Modified Angoff techniques. After a review has been completed click on \'Paper Properties\' and select the \'Std Set\' option under marking method.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/scaling marking.png\" alt=\"scaling marking.png\" width=\"722\" height=\"279\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If there has been more than one review of the same paper, check which review cut score will be used to determine the pass mark. Next set the pass mark of the paper which is what all the marks will be adjusted back to.&nbsp;When happy with the settings click \'OK\'. At this point the cut score and distinction levels (if set) will be assigned to the current paper. Assigning the cut score to the paper <strong>must</strong> be done before the exam runs and the paper is locked.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">After the exam is sat, go into the \'Analysis Menu\' and normal and click \'Class Totals\'. The \'%\' column should now read \'Adjusted %\' to show that the marks are now being scaled back to the pass mark of, in the above example 50%, see Step 3. The adjusted percentage is calculated using a transformational model displayed below. Raw percentages are shown on the <em>x</em> axis together with the standard set cut score and distinction level. These are then mapped back to 50% and 70% respectively on the <em>x</em> axis to produce an adjusted percentage. Knowing the slope of the lines for failing, passing and distinction candidates allows any raw percentage on the x axis to be converted into an adjusted percentage on the <em>y</em> axis (see lilac line). Class totals with standard setting on will display these final <em>y</em> axis adjusted percentages.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/std_set_cranking2.png\" alt=\"std_set_cranking2.png\" width=\"323\" height=\"295\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">At the bottom of the \'Class Totals\' report there is a summary with key standard setting information. As the figure below shows \'SS\' represents the standard setting cut score or pass mark. \'SS Distinction\' is the upper threshold for the awarding of a distinction. If not set through the Ebel method it will automatically be calculated by taking the top 20% percentile. \'Pass Mark\' is the post-adjustment percentage used to determine pass/fails. In the example below it is reading 50%, this is the same 50% as set in the \'Paper Properties\' dialog, see Step 3 in the first figure above.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/std_set_cranking3.png\" alt=\"std_set_cranking3.png\" width=\"359\" height=\"447\" /></p>','Standards Setting reviews produce cut scores (pass marks) which are individual and differ from paper to paper. As a result it is difficult to compare between years of study or across modules. To overcome this it is possible in Rogo to scale back to a standard pass mark. To do this a paper must first be standard set using either Ebel or Modified Angoff techniques. After a review has been completed click on \'Paper Properties\' and select the \'Std Set\' option under marking method. &nbsp; &nbsp; If there has been more than one review of the same paper, check which review cut score will be used to determine the pass mark. Next set the pass mark of the paper which is what all the marks will be adjusted back to.&nbsp;When happy with the settings click \'OK\'. At this point the cut score and distinction levels (if set) will be assigned to the current paper. Assigning the cut score to the paper must be done before the exam runs and the paper is locked. &nbsp; After the exam is sat, go into the \'Analysis Menu\' and normal and click \'Class Totals\'. The \'%\' column should now read \'Adjusted %\' to show that the marks are now being scaled back to the pass mark of, in the above example 50%, see Step 3. The adjusted percentage is calculated using a transformational model displayed below. Raw percentages are shown on the x axis together with the standard set cut score and distinction level. These are then mapped back to 50% and 70% respectively on the x axis to produce an adjusted percentage. Knowing the slope of the lines for failing, passing and distinction candidates allows any raw percentage on the x axis to be converted into an adjusted percentage on the y axis (see lilac line). Class totals with standard setting on will display these final y axis adjusted percentages. &nbsp; &nbsp; At the bottom of the \'Class Totals\' report there is a summary with key standard setting information. As the figure below shows \'SS\' represents the standard setting cut score or pass mark. \'SS Distinction\' is the upper threshold for the awarding of a distinction. If not set through the Ebel method it will automatically be calculated by taking the top 20% percentile. \'Pass Mark\' is the post-adjustment percentage used to determine pass/fails. In the example below it is reading 50%, this is the same 50% as set in the \'Paper Properties\' dialog, see Step 3 in the first figure above. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(60,'Question - Types/Labelling','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Labelling questions require a graphic that is no bigger than 900 x 800 pixels and in one of these 3 format: JPG, GIF or PNG.</p>\r\n<h2>Student view</h2>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\"><img src=\"images/single_label_icon.png\" alt=\"icon\" width=\"23\" height=\"22\" /> Single use Labels</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the screenshot below, single use labels have been used where each label can only be used once.&nbsp;Students answering the question drag the correct label to the spaces shown over the graphic.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/labelling.png\" alt=\"labelling.png\" width=\"1004\" height=\"699\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\"><img src=\"images/dropdown_label_icon.png\" alt=\"icon\" width=\"23\" height=\"22\" /> Drop-down menus</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The drop-down menu label type is an interface alternative to the single label. Instead of dragging labels from the left over the image, dropdown menu boxes are displayed in situ over the image. To create a question using drop-down menus, create it using the single use label option initially change it to Drop-down.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/labelling drop down.png\" alt=\"labelling drop down.png\" width=\"677\" height=\"654\" /></p>\r\n<p>1 mark is given for each correctly positioned label.</p>\r\n<h2>Edit view</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The options for the labels are created individually and include some distractors.&nbsp;The labels that do require student selection need to be positioned over the relevant part of the graphic. The screenshot below shows that 4 labels have been created. The \'oxygen\' label has been positioned in the correct place and the \'water\' label is being dragged onto the graphic. The other 2 labels are distractors and do&nbsp;not need to be positioned over the graphic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/labelling edit.png\" alt=\"labelling edit.png\" width=\"934\" height=\"674\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\"><img src=\"images/multi_label_icon.png\" alt=\"icon\" width=\"23\" height=\"22\" /> Multi-use Labels</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Multi-use labels are useful for circumstances where there are more than one area requiring the same type of label. For example, in an anatomy example you would need two labels for \'lung\', \'foot\' or \'hand\'. To create a multi-use label select the <img src=\"images/multi_label_icon.png\" alt=\"icon\" width=\"23\" height=\"22\" /> icon from the toolbar. When a student drags a multi-use label onto the image, another label is replaced on the left to be dragged again to a different location.&nbsp; A mark is given for each correctly matched label.</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Graphic labels</strong></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As an alternative to text labels, graphics can be imported at the same time as the main graphic for use as labels. The image below shows 3 graphic labels waiting to be positioned and one (the spider) being dragged to the matching space. You can have a mixture of graphic and text labels in one question.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/labelling with graphic labels.png\" alt=\"labelling with graphic labels.png\" width=\"778\" height=\"507\" /></p>','Labelling questions require a graphic that is no bigger than 900 x 800 pixels and in one of these 3 format: JPG, GIF or PNG. Student view Single use Labels In the screenshot below, single use labels have been used where each label can only be used once.&nbsp;Students answering the question drag the correct label to the spaces shown over the graphic. &nbsp; Drop-down menus The drop-down menu label type is an interface alternative to the single label. Instead of dragging labels from the left over the image, dropdown menu boxes are displayed in situ over the image. To create a question using drop-down menus, create it using the single use label option initially change it to Drop-down. 1 mark is given for each correctly positioned label. Edit view The options for the labels are created individually and include some distractors.&nbsp;The labels that do require student selection need to be positioned over the relevant part of the graphic. The screenshot below shows that 4 labels have been created. The \'oxygen\' label has been positioned in the correct place and the \'water\' label is being dragged onto the graphic. The other 2 labels are distractors and do&nbsp;not need to be positioned over the graphic.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Multi-use Labels Multi-use labels are useful for circumstances where there are more than one area requiring the same type of label. For example, in an anatomy example you would need two labels for \'lung\', \'foot\' or \'hand\'. To create a multi-use label select the icon from the toolbar. When a student drags a multi-use label onto the image, another label is replaced on the left to be dragged again to a different location.&nbsp; A mark is given for each correctly matched label. Graphic labels As an alternative to text labels, graphics can be imported at the same time as the main graphic for use as labels. The image below shows 3 graphic labels waiting to be positioned and one (the spider) being dragged to the matching space. You can have a mixture of graphic and text labels in one question. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(61,'Question - Types/Textbox','<h2>Textboxes in Surveys</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The most common use of Textbox questions is probably for open-ended textual questions used for surveys. The part screenshot below shows one such example used to elicit student comments on how a module could be improved. The physical size of a textbox, in terms of rows and columns, can be altered by the member of staff writing the question. Textboxes have a maximum number of 65,535 characters which equates to over eight A4 pages.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/survey_textbox.png\" alt=\"Textbox used for survey\" width=\"702\" height=\"171\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Textboxes in Assessments</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The use of open-ended questions for assessment purposes is a challenge to computer-based assessment. Spelling mistakes, transpositional errors and various synonyms for many words all present problems when trying to mark free text responses. The number of marks that the question is worth is set and then the question is marked manually to judge how many marks each student response has achieved.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/assessment_textbox_response.png\" alt=\"Textbox used for assessment\" width=\"737\" height=\"265\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo does not attempt to mark free-text responses, instead it will highlight in yellow any keywords it finds in the student answer from its own internal list - as set by the question author. It will then present in dark red coloured text a pre-created model answer for the question, again written by the question author.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> These are optional features and are to aid the person who is marking the question but&nbsp;do not&nbsp;define the way that the response should be evaluated.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/assessment_textbox_feedback.png\" alt=\"Textbox used for assessment\" width=\"714\" height=\"325\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The textbox itself can also be set to WYSIWYG mode to allow formatting to be inserted. The example below shows the formatting toolbar and the same paragraph of text as above but with some bold and a ordered list inserted.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/wysiwyg.png\" alt=\"Textbox used for assessment\" width=\"714\" height=\"325\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Textboxes in Surveys The most common use of Textbox questions is probably for open-ended textual questions used for surveys. The part screenshot below shows one such example used to elicit student comments on how a module could be improved. The physical size of a textbox, in terms of rows and columns, can be altered by the member of staff writing the question. Textboxes have a maximum number of 65,535 characters which equates to over eight A4 pages. Textboxes in Assessments The use of open-ended questions for assessment purposes is a challenge to computer-based assessment. Spelling mistakes, transpositional errors and various synonyms for many words all present problems when trying to mark free text responses. The number of marks that the question is worth is set and then the question is marked manually to judge how many marks each student response has achieved. &nbsp; Rogo does not attempt to mark free-text responses, instead it will highlight in yellow any keywords it finds in the student answer from its own internal list - as set by the question author. It will then present in dark red coloured text a pre-created model answer for the question, again written by the question author. &nbsp; Note: These are optional features and are to aid the person who is marking the question but&nbsp;do not&nbsp;define the way that the response should be evaluated. &nbsp; &nbsp; The textbox itself can also be set to WYSIWYG mode to allow formatting to be inserted. The example below shows the formatting toolbar and the same paragraph of text as above but with some bold and a ordered list inserted. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(62,'Question - Types/Likert Scale','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo can support both Likert Scales and Semantic Differential questions together in the \'Likert Scale\' question type.</p>\r\n<h2>Likert Scales</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/likert_scale.png\" alt=\"Likert Scale\" width=\"612\" height=\"149\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Semantic Differential</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sematic differential question type was devised by Charles Osgood in 1957. This type of question, as can be seen below, uses bipolar dimensions are requires the respondent to indicate their preference in a certain dimension. The example, below uses the two poles \'low\' and \'high\' to elicit views on a module.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/semantic_differential.gif\" alt=\"Semantic Differential\" width=\"609\" height=\"372\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Rogo can support both Likert Scales and Semantic Differential questions together in the \'Likert Scale\' question type. Likert Scales &nbsp; Semantic Differential Sematic differential question type was devised by Charles Osgood in 1957. This type of question, as can be seen below, uses bipolar dimensions are requires the respondent to indicate their preference in a certain dimension. The example, below uses the two poles \'low\' and \'high\' to elicit views on a module. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(284,'Administrative Tools/SMS Import Summary','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Details of imports from&nbsp;Sutudent Management System (SMS)&nbsp;are shown in this screen. It shows the number of students added to Rogo (enroled) and also the number deleted. If a student has an account in Rogo for a given module but this is not present in the SMS system, the student will be removed from the module in Rogo. No user accounts will be deleted, simply they will be unenroled from the module(s).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Admin SMS import.png\" alt=\"Admin SMS import.png\" width=\"445\" height=\"346\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Details of imports from&nbsp;Sutudent Management System (SMS)&nbsp;are shown in this screen. It shows the number of students added to Rogo (enroled) and also the number deleted. If a student has an account in Rogo for a given module but this is not present in the SMS system, the student will be removed from the module in Rogo. No user accounts will be deleted, simply they will be unenroled from the module(s). &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(285,'Administrative Tools/Summative Exam Stats','<p>Details of all summative exams that have run over the year.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/admin exam stats2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"400\" height=\"307\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Details of all summative exams that have run over the year. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(65,'Papers/Copying','<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/Copying_paper2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"642\" height=\"332\" /></h2>\r\n<h2>Copying a Paper only</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Copying a paper allows you to create a paper with a new name that is an exact duplicate of the original. Because a paper is made up of \'pointers\' to questions, both the original and the new paper will link to the same questions. If any of the questions are edited, changes will be reflected in <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">both</span> papers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Copying a Paper and Questions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In situations where a copy of a paper is required but then the questions altered, this second copy type should be employed. Selecting \'Paper and Questions\' will copy all the questions in the bank and then form a duplicate paper from these new questions. Any alterations made to these new questions will <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">not</span> be reflected in the original paper as it refers back to an independent set of questions.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',' Copying a Paper only Copying a paper allows you to create a paper with a new name that is an exact duplicate of the original. Because a paper is made up of \'pointers\' to questions, both the original and the new paper will link to the same questions. If any of the questions are edited, changes will be reflected in both papers.&nbsp; &nbsp; Copying a Paper and Questions In situations where a copy of a paper is required but then the questions altered, this second copy type should be employed. Selecting \'Paper and Questions\' will copy all the questions in the bank and then form a duplicate paper from these new questions. Any alterations made to these new questions will not be reflected in the original paper as it refers back to an independent set of questions. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(66,'Security','<p>The whole of Rogo, staff and student screens,&nbsp;are setup to only allow connections through encrypted SSL connections.</p>\r\n<h2>IP Address Restrictions</h2>\r\n<p>In addition to the above it is also possible, for instance with summative exams, to limit student access to assessments down to a specific computer lab or labs. To do this select a paper, click on \'Edit Properties\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane and then click on the&nbsp;\'Security\'&nbsp;option on the left.&nbsp; In the screenshot below&nbsp;you can be seen that&nbsp;the assessment is limited to students on module&nbsp;B33E11 on&nbsp;May 24th 2011 and they can only access it from a computer in labs&nbsp;Coates C20 and QMC C77.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/paper security rogo.png\" alt=\"paper security rogo.png\" width=\"852\" height=\"606\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','The whole of Rogo, staff and student screens,&nbsp;are setup to only allow connections through encrypted SSL connections. IP Address Restrictions In addition to the above it is also possible, for instance with summative exams, to limit student access to assessments down to a specific computer lab or labs. To do this select a paper, click on \'Edit Properties\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane and then click on the&nbsp;\'Security\'&nbsp;option on the left.&nbsp; In the screenshot below&nbsp;you can be seen that&nbsp;the assessment is limited to students on module&nbsp;B33E11 on&nbsp;May 24th 2011 and they can only access it from a computer in labs&nbsp;Coates C20 and QMC C77. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(67,'Papers/Properties','<h2>\'General\' tab</h2>\r\n<h3>Paper Details</h3>\r\n<p><strong><em>Paper Name</em></strong></p>\r\n<div>The name of a paper must be completely unique in Rogo. Other limitations include it cannot be longer than 255 characters and must not include the following characters: &amp; ? @ ^ ~</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong><em>Paper Type</em></strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The type of paper is selected from the list below.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Formative Self-Assessment</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Progress Test</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Summative Exam</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Survey (Questionnaire)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>OSCE</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Offline Paper</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Folder</p>\r\n<p>This allows you to \'store\' a link to the current paper in one of your own \'my folders\' directories. You will only see your own folders and any folders belonging to any teams which you are a member.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Team</p>\r\n<div>Assigning a team to a paper allows any other member of the team to alter the properties of the paper. Note that sharing a paper with a team does not automatically share the constituate questions with the same team as the questions could be used across a number of different papers. Team sharing of questions can be performed by editing the individual questions.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"subheading\">Marking</h3>\r\n<div class=\"subheading\">Pass Mark</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Controls the percentage pass mark for assessments.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"subheading\">Distinction</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Controls the percentage distinction is set to for assessments. If distinction is not required then set to 100%.</div>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Method</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>No Adjustment - no adjustment made of student scores (with the exception of negative marking if set in a Dichotomous question)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Calculate Random Mark - Rogo will automatically calculate and scale the final marks or a student based on the statistical probability of getting the correct answer by chance.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Std Set - The \'cut score\' pass mark will be taken from a standards setting session and marks scaled from this to the pass mark.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 class=\"subheading\">Display Options</h3>\r\n<div class=\"subheading\">Display</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Full Screen - Display a paper in kiosk mode (Internet Explorer only)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Windowed - The paper will be displayed in a new window when sat</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Navigation</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Unidirectional (Linear) - Candidates will not be able to return to previous screens once submitted. Use for cases in which consequential error or consequential help are important issues.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Bidirectional - Candidates are free to go backwards or forwards between screens changing answers as many times as they wish before finally clicking \'Finish\'.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Background</p>\r\n<p>Background colour of the paper when presented to students (default is white). Either enter an HTML value in the textbox or click on the colour next to it to popup a colour selection chart.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Foreground</p>\r\n<p>Foreground colour of the paper when presented to students (default is black). Either enter an HTML value in the textbox or click on the colour next to it to popup a colour selection chart.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Theme</p>\r\n<p>Colour of headings/themes when the paper is presented. Either enter an HTML value in the textbox or click on the colour next to it to popup a colour selection chart.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Labels/Notes</p>\r\n<div>Colour of labels and notes when the paper is presented. Either enter an HTML value in the textbox or click on the colour next to it to popup a colour selection chart.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>C<strong><em>alculator</em></strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>This controls whether a software calculator is available to students during the exam.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>\'Prologue\' tab</h2>\r\n<div>The prologue is displayed once at the top of the first screen of an assessment or survey. It can be used to present background information or instructions pertinent to the current paper. It is totally optional.</div>\r\n<h2>\'Postscript\' tab</h2>\r\n<p>The postscript is displayed the top of the very last screen after the student has click on the \'Finish\' button. It can be used to include links to other websites, etc to do after the assessment or survey has been completed.</p>\r\n<h2>\'Security\' tab</h2>\r\n<p><strong><em>Module(s)</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>This controls which module/modules are permitted to access the assessment or survey.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Academic Year</p>\r\n<div>Academic year of study can be used to restrict a paper to a certain academic year (e.g. 2011/2012)</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Year of Study</p>\r\n<p>Year of study can be used to restrict a paper to certain years of study (e.g. Year 1)</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Available From</p>\r\n<p>Students may not take a paper before this date and time.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">To</p>\r\n<p>Students may not take a paper after this date and time.</p>\r\n<p class=\"subheading\">Restrict to Lab(s)</p>\r\n<p>The \'labs\' feature allows a paper, for example a summative exam, to be restricted to a particular computer lab. If no restrictions are needed then all labs should be unselected.</p>\r\n<h2>\'Exam Rubric\' tab</h2>\r\n<p>The exam rubric text is displayed on the initial \'blue\' screen that examinees log into before starting an exam (see below).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/exam_rubric.PNG\" alt=\"exam_rubric.PNG\" width=\"721\" height=\"455\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></div>\r\n<h2>\'Reviewers\' tab</h2>\r\n<p>Select the internal and external examiners who should be given access to the current paper. This facility is only important when dealing with summative exams.</p>\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=73\">External Examiners</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=158\">Internal Reviewers</a></li>\r\n</ul>','\'General\' tab\r\nPaper Details\r\nPaper Name\r\nThe name of a paper must be completely unique in Rogo. Other limitations include it cannot be longer than 255 characters and must not include the following characters: &amp; ? @ ^ ~\r\n&nbsp;\r\nPaper Type\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe type of paper is selected from the list below.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFormative Self-Assessment\r\n\r\n\r\nProgress Test\r\n\r\n\r\nSummative Exam\r\n\r\n\r\nSurvey (Questionnaire)\r\n\r\n\r\nOSCE\r\n\r\n\r\nOffline Paper\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFolder\r\nThis allows you to \'store\' a link to the current paper in one of your own \'my folders\' directories. You will only see your own folders and any folders belonging to any teams which you are a member.\r\nTeam\r\nAssigning a team to a paper allows any other member of the team to alter the properties of the paper. Note that sharing a paper with a team does not automatically share the constituate questions with the same team as the questions could be used across a number of different papers. Team sharing of questions can be performed by editing the individual questions.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nMarking\r\nPass Mark\r\n&nbsp;\r\nControls the percentage pass mark for assessments.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nDistinction\r\n&nbsp;\r\nControls the percentage distinction is set to for assessments. If distinction is not required then set to 100%.\r\nMethod\r\n\r\n\r\nNo Adjustment - no adjustment made of student scores (with the exception of negative marking if set in a Dichotomous question)\r\n\r\n\r\nCalculate Random Mark - Rogo will automatically calculate and scale the final marks or a student based on the statistical probability of getting the correct answer by chance.\r\n\r\n\r\nStd Set - The \'cut score\' pass mark will be taken from a standards setting session and marks scaled from this to the pass mark.\r\n\r\n\r\nDisplay Options\r\nDisplay\r\n\r\n\r\nFull Screen - Display a paper in kiosk mode (Internet Explorer only)\r\n\r\n\r\nWindowed - The paper will be displayed in a new window when sat\r\n\r\n\r\nNavigation\r\n\r\n\r\nUnidirectional (Linear) - Candidates will not be able to return to previous screens once submitted. Use for cases in which consequential error or consequential help are important issues.\r\n\r\n\r\nBidirectional - Candidates are free to go backwards or forwards between screens changing answers as many times as they wish before finally clicking \'Finish\'.\r\n\r\n\r\nBackground\r\nBackground colour of the paper when presented to students (default is white). Either enter an HTML value in the textbox or click on the colour next to it to popup a colour selection chart.\r\nForeground\r\nForeground colour of the paper when presented to students (default is black). Either enter an HTML value in the textbox or click on the colour next to it to popup a colour selection chart.\r\nTheme\r\nColour of headings/themes when the paper is presented. Either enter an HTML value in the textbox or click on the colour next to it to popup a colour selection chart.\r\nLabels/Notes\r\nColour of labels and notes when the paper is presented. Either enter an HTML value in the textbox or click on the colour next to it to popup a colour selection chart.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nCalculator\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThis controls whether a software calculator is available to students during the exam.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\'Prologue\' tab\r\nThe prologue is displayed once at the top of the first screen of an assessment or survey. It can be used to present background information or instructions pertinent to the current paper. It is totally optional.\r\n\'Postscript\' tab\r\nThe postscript is displayed the top of the very last screen after the student has click on the \'Finish\' button. It can be used to include links to other websites, etc to do after the assessment or survey has been completed.\r\n\'Security\' tab\r\nModule(s)\r\nThis controls which module/modules are permitted to access the assessment or survey.\r\nAcademic Year\r\nAcademic year of study can be used to restrict a paper to a certain academic year (e.g. 2011/2012)\r\n\r\nYear of Study\r\nYear of study can be used to restrict a paper to certain years of study (e.g. Year 1)\r\n\r\nAvailable From\r\nStudents may not take a paper before this date and time.\r\nTo\r\nStudents may not take a paper after this date and time.\r\nRestrict to Lab(s)\r\nThe \'labs\' feature allows a paper, for example a summative exam, to be restricted to a particular computer lab. If no restrictions are needed then all labs should be unselected.\r\n\'Exam Rubric\' tab\r\nThe exam rubric text is displayed on the initial \'blue\' screen that examinees log into before starting an exam (see below).\r\n\r\n\'Reviewers\' tab\r\nSelect the internal and external examiners who should be given access to the current paper. This facility is only important when dealing with summative exams.\r\nSee also:\r\n\r\nExternal Examiners\r\nInternal Reviewers\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(68,'Question - Types/Calculation','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Calculation questions use one or more variables (calculated random values) to present numeric questions which change each time the paper is attempted. In the example below, concerning questionnaire response rates, two variables are used: the first is a random number between 300 and 800 (incrementing in 100 values), and the second variable is a random integer between 10 and the calculated value of the first variable.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/calculation_question1.png\" alt=\"Calculation question presentation\" width=\"556\" height=\"145\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To be a bit more specific the question author has explicitly stated that the answer should be expressed to one decimal place. The author has also added a \'%\' character for the units; this is added at the end of the answer textbox.</p>\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">On the marking screen the user\'s answer is presented together with the correct answer displayed emboldened. If the user\'s answer is equal to the correct answer or within a predetermined tolerance a tick is displayed and marks awarded. The number of marks awarded for a question can be set within the editor (1 to 20), in the example below 1 mark is awarded for a correct answer. Partial marks can also be set for answers close to the correct answer. Like the marks for the correct answer, a tolerance and value is set for the partial mark.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/calculation_answer.png\" alt=\"Calculation question marking\" width=\"543\" height=\"192\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As can be seen in the example above the feedback, displayed in dark red, can also use the generated variables to really clarify how to calculate the answer.</p>\r\n<h2>Creating</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A calculation question consists of one or more variables used to construct a randomised question which changes each time attempted. To create the questionnaire response rate question displayed above, the following settings could be used. As shown below, two variables $A and $B are used. $A, the number of questionnaires sent out is set to be a random variable between 300 and 800. To make it more realistic the increment level is set to 100 so the only possible values that can be generated are 300, 400, 500, 600, 700 and 800. The number of responses, variable $B, is set to be between 10 and whatever value is generated for variable $A. In this case the increment level is set to 1.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The answer is checked against the value entered into the \'formula\' field. In the example below the basic calculation is divide $B by $A and then multiply by 100 to express as a percentage. This should be expressed using brackets to set the priority: ($B / $A) * 100. In some instances the generated values of $A and $B could result in an answer with a recurring number of decimal places. Also, the question stated that answers should be expressed to one decimal place. To do this the function \'round\' has been used (<a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"#functions\">see functions below</a>). A tolerance value can also be added, please note this is an absolute value. The number of marks that can be given for a correct answer may also be selected. Partial marks can be set if \'Tolerance for Partial Marks\' is set. Until Partial Marks are set the Allow partial Marks Marking Method is not available.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/calculation creation 2.png\" alt=\"calculation creation 2.png\" width=\"750\" height=\"517\" /></p>\r\n<div>.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>Student answers</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note for very small or large number answers:</strong> students should <strong>not</strong> use exponential indication (e.g. 1e-5 or 1x10<sup>-5</sup>) for large or small numbers since this format does not register and&nbsp;they will be awarded zero. The units of each answer, where required, should be stated next to the answer box.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2>Linked questions</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is possible to link two different calculation questions together by using the student\'s answer to the first question in the latter question. The question to link to is selected using the link icon next to the \'Min\' and \'Max\' fields. In the example shown below, variable $B is generated from the students answer to a previous question. Even if the student answered the initial question incorrectly they can still answer the linked question correctly as it is using the answer they gave in the earlier question. The same process can be used to use the same variables between questions on different screens.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note1:</strong> As student answers are stored as they move between screens, questions must be on different screens to allow a student\'s answer to be used in a following question. If a student has not answered the earlier question warnings will appear and the answer textbox disabled.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note2:</strong> If you copy linked questions to another paper the variable links will need to be reset</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/linked calculation editor.png\" alt=\"linked calculation editor.png\" width=\"700\" height=\"468\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Functions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Any of the following functions can be used in the answer formula. [x] and [y] represent variable parameters which the functions require. For example, to round a number to two decimal places the following can be written:</p>\r\n<blockquote>round($A,2)</blockquote>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Function</span></div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Description</span></div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>abs([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Absolute value</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>acos([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Arc cosine</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>acosh([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Inverse hyperbolic cosine</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>asin([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Arc sine</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>asinh([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Inverse hyperbolic sine</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>atan2([y],[x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Arc tangent of two variables</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>atan([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Arc tangent</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>atanh([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Inverse hyperbolic tangent</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>ceil([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Round fractions up</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>cos([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Cosine</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>cosh([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Hyperbolic cosine</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>deg2rad([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Converts the number in degrees to the radian equivalent</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>exp([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Calculates the exponent of e (the Neperian or Natural logarithm base)</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>expm1([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Returns exp(number) - 1, computed in a way that is accurate even when the value of number is close to zero</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>floor([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Round fractions down</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>fmod([x],[y])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Returns the floating point remainder (modulo) of the division of the arguments</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>log10([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Base-10 logarithm</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>log1p([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Returns log(1 + number), computed in a way that is accurate even when the value of number is close to zero</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>log([x],[base])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>logarithm (the [base] parameter is optional defaults to \'e\' and so to the natural logarithm if not provided)</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>max([x],[y],...)</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Find highest value</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>min([x],[y],...)</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Find lowest value</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>pi()</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Get value of pi</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>pow([x],[exp])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Exponential expression</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>round([x],[decimals])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Rounds a float to [decimals] number of places</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>sin([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Sine</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>sinh([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Hyperbolic sine</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>sqrt([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Square root</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>tan([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Tangent</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>tanh([x])</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div>Hyperbolic tangent</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','Presentation\r\nCalculation questions use one or more variables (calculated random values) to present numeric questions which change each time the paper is attempted. In the example below, concerning questionnaire response rates, two variables are used: the first is a random number between 300 and 800 (incrementing in 100 values), and the second variable is a random integer between 10 and the calculated value of the first variable.\r\n\r\nTo be a bit more specific the question author has explicitly stated that the answer should be expressed to one decimal place. The author has also added a \'%\' character for the units; this is added at the end of the answer textbox.\r\nMarking\r\nOn the marking screen the user\'s answer is presented together with the correct answer displayed emboldened. If the user\'s answer is equal to the correct answer or within a predetermined tolerance a tick is displayed and marks awarded. The number of marks awarded for a question can be set within the editor (1 to 20), in the example below 1 mark is awarded for a correct answer. Partial marks can also be set for answers close to the correct answer. Like the marks for the correct answer, a tolerance and value is set for the partial mark.\r\n\r\nAs can be seen in the example above the feedback, displayed in dark red, can also use the generated variables to really clarify how to calculate the answer.\r\nCreating\r\nA calculation question consists of one or more variables used to construct a randomised question which changes each time attempted. To create the questionnaire response rate question displayed above, the following settings could be used. As shown below, two variables $A and $B are used. $A, the number of questionnaires sent out is set to be a random variable between 300 and 800. To make it more realistic the increment level is set to 100 so the only possible values that can be generated are 300, 400, 500, 600, 700 and 800. The number of responses, variable $B, is set to be between 10 and whatever value is generated for variable $A. In this case the increment level is set to 1.\r\nThe answer is checked against the value entered into the \'formula\' field. In the example below the basic calculation is divide $B by $A and then multiply by 100 to express as a percentage. This should be expressed using brackets to set the priority: ($B / $A) * 100. In some instances the generated values of $A and $B could result in an answer with a recurring number of decimal places. Also, the question stated that answers should be expressed to one decimal place. To do this the function \'round\' has been used (see functions below). A tolerance value can also be added, please note this is an absolute value. The number of marks that can be given for a correct answer may also be selected. Partial marks can be set if \'Tolerance for Partial Marks\' is set. Until Partial Marks are set the Allow partial Marks Marking Method is not available.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n.\r\n\r\nStudent answers\r\nNote for very small or large number answers: students should not use exponential indication (e.g. 1e-5 or 1x10-5) for large or small numbers since this format does not register and&nbsp;they will be awarded zero. The units of each answer, where required, should be stated next to the answer box.\r\n\r\nLinked questions\r\nIt is possible to link two different calculation questions together by using the student\'s answer to the first question in the latter question. The question to link to is selected using the link icon next to the \'Min\' and \'Max\' fields. In the example shown below, variable $B is generated from the students answer to a previous question. Even if the student answered the initial question incorrectly they can still answer the linked question correctly as it is using the answer they gave in the earlier question. The same process can be used to use the same variables between questions on different screens.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nNote1: As student answers are stored as they move between screens, questions must be on different screens to allow a student\'s answer to be used in a following question. If a student has not answered the earlier question warnings will appear and the answer textbox disabled.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nNote2: If you copy linked questions to another paper the variable links will need to be reset\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFunctions\r\nAny of the following functions can be used in the answer formula. [x] and [y] represent variable parameters which the functions require. For example, to round a number to two decimal places the following can be written:\r\nround($A,2)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFunction\r\n\r\n\r\nDescription\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nabs([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nAbsolute value\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nacos([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nArc cosine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nacosh([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nInverse hyperbolic cosine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nasin([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nArc sine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nasinh([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nInverse hyperbolic sine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\natan2([y],[x])\r\n\r\n\r\nArc tangent of two variables\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\natan([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nArc tangent\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\natanh([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nInverse hyperbolic tangent\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nceil([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nRound fractions up\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\ncos([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nCosine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\ncosh([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nHyperbolic cosine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\ndeg2rad([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nConverts the number in degrees to the radian equivalent\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nexp([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nCalculates the exponent of e (the Neperian or Natural logarithm base)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nexpm1([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nReturns exp(number) - 1, computed in a way that is accurate even when the value of number is close to zero\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nfloor([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nRound fractions down\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nfmod([x],[y])\r\n\r\n\r\nReturns the floating point remainder (modulo) of the division of the arguments\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nlog10([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nBase-10 logarithm\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nlog1p([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nReturns log(1 + number), computed in a way that is accurate even when the value of number is close to zero\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nlog([x],[base])\r\n\r\n\r\nlogarithm (the [base] parameter is optional defaults to \'e\' and so to the natural logarithm if not provided)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nmax([x],[y],...)\r\n\r\n\r\nFind highest value\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nmin([x],[y],...)\r\n\r\n\r\nFind lowest value\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\npi()\r\n\r\n\r\nGet value of pi\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\npow([x],[exp])\r\n\r\n\r\nExponential expression\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nround([x],[decimals])\r\n\r\n\r\nRounds a float to [decimals] number of places\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nsin([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nSine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nsinh([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nHyperbolic sine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nsqrt([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nSquare root\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\ntan([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nTangent\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\ntanh([x])\r\n\r\n\r\nHyperbolic tangent\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(69,'Fire Exits','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There is only one Fire Exit icon&nbsp;in a bottom left&nbsp;corner of the screen that will only be displayed for <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">summative</span> papers.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/Fire_exit.png\" alt=\"Fire_exit.png\" width=\"548\" height=\"114\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the event of a real fire evacuation invigilators will instruct all examinees to scroll to the bottom of the screen and&nbsp;click on the&nbsp;fire exit icon. This will do two things:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Examinees answers will be sent back to the server for recording. This allows a record of attempted questions in the event that there is a real fire and some of the client computers are destroyed.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #484848;\">The second thing which will happen is the screen will be blanked with the following notice (see below). This is to stop examinees being able to look at peers\' answers while evacuating the room.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/fire_exit2.png\" alt=\"Fire Exit\" width=\"566\" height=\"90\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','There is only one Fire Exit icon&nbsp;in a bottom left&nbsp;corner of the screen that will only be displayed for summative papers. &nbsp; &nbsp; In the event of a real fire evacuation invigilators will instruct all examinees to scroll to the bottom of the screen and&nbsp;click on the&nbsp;fire exit icon. This will do two things: Examinees answers will be sent back to the server for recording. This allows a record of attempted questions in the event that there is a real fire and some of the client computers are destroyed. The second thing which will happen is the screen will be blanked with the following notice (see below). This is to stop examinees being able to look at peers\' answers while evacuating the room.  &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(70,'Calculator','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Certain papers may have a software calculator included for performing mathematical calculations. This facility is provided at the discretion of the exam writer. If a calculator is provided, a small icon to launch it will be displayed just below each question number.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/calc_icon_on_paper.png\" alt=\"calc_icon_on_paper.png\" width=\"852\" height=\"229\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Clicking on this icon will popup in a new window a JavaScript calculator. It goes without saying that JavaScript must be enabled in your browser for this calculator to work. The default mode of the calculator can be seen below:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/calc_ui.png\" alt=\"calc_ui.png\" width=\"270\" height=\"433\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Including on Papers</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The calculator can be included on a paper by going into the paper properties dialog box and checking the \'Calculator\' option on the \'General\' tab:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/calculator paper properties.jpg\" alt=\"calculator paper properties.jpg\" width=\"629\" height=\"149\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Certain papers may have a software calculator included for performing mathematical calculations. This facility is provided at the discretion of the exam writer. If a calculator is provided, a small icon to launch it will be displayed just below each question number. Clicking on this icon will popup in a new window a JavaScript calculator. It goes without saying that JavaScript must be enabled in your browser for this calculator to work. The default mode of the calculator can be seen below: &nbsp; Including on Papers The calculator can be included on a paper by going into the paper properties dialog box and checking the \'Calculator\' option on the \'General\' tab: &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(71,'HTML Tags & Special Characters','<h2>Formatting Tags</h2>\r\n<p>XHTML tags (shown in red) can be included in any of the non-WYSIWYG fields in Rogo to provide various styles of formatting. The table below shows some of the most frequently used tags:</p>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"width: 550px;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Function</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Tags</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Example</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Bold</td>\r\n<td>This is aboldword.</td>\r\n<td>This is a <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">bold</span> word.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Carriage Return</td>\r\n<td>Carriage <span style=\"color: #c00000;\"><br /></span>Return</td>\r\n<td>Carriage<br />Return</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Italic</td>\r\n<td>This is anitalicizedword.</td>\r\n<td>This is a <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">italicized</span> word.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Subscript</td>\r\n<td>H2O</td>\r\n<td>H<sub><small>2</small></sub>O</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Superscript</td>\r\n<td>E = MC2</td>\r\n<td>E = MC<sup><small>2</small></sup></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Special Characters</h2>\r\n<p>To use special characters in any of the non-WYSIWYG fields in Rogo enter their code from the middle column. These codes will be replaced automatically when the paper is viewed by students.</p>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"width: 550px;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Character</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Code</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Example</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Alpha</td>\r\n<td>&alpha;</td>\r\n<td>&alpha;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Beta</td>\r\n<td>&beta;</td>\r\n<td>&beta;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Gamma</td>\r\n<td>&gamma;</td>\r\n<td>&gamma;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Micro</td>\r\n<td>&micro;</td>\r\n<td>&micro;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>less-than or equal to</td>\r\n<td>&le;</td>\r\n<td>&le;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>greater-than or equal to</td>\r\n<td>&ge;</td>\r\n<td>&ge;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Special characters can be inserted in the WYSIWYG fields by using the Special Character button on the toolbar [&Omega;]. Click on the desired character and click Close (not all Greek characters are supported).</div>','Formatting Tags\r\nXHTML tags (shown in red) can be included in any of the non-WYSIWYG fields in Rogo to provide various styles of formatting. The table below shows some of the most frequently used tags:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFunction\r\nTags\r\nExample\r\n\r\n\r\nBold\r\nThis is aboldword.\r\nThis is a bold word.\r\n\r\n\r\nCarriage Return\r\nCarriage Return\r\nCarriageReturn\r\n\r\n\r\nItalic\r\nThis is anitalicizedword.\r\nThis is a italicized word.\r\n\r\n\r\nSubscript\r\nH2O\r\nH2O\r\n\r\n\r\nSuperscript\r\nE = MC2\r\nE = MC2\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSpecial Characters\r\nTo use special characters in any of the non-WYSIWYG fields in Rogo enter their code from the middle column. These codes will be replaced automatically when the paper is viewed by students.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCharacter\r\nCode\r\nExample\r\n\r\n\r\nAlpha\r\n&alpha;\r\n&alpha;\r\n\r\n\r\nBeta\r\n&beta;\r\n&beta;\r\n\r\n\r\nGamma\r\n&gamma;\r\n&gamma;\r\n\r\n\r\nMicro\r\n&micro;\r\n&micro;\r\n\r\n\r\nless-than or equal to\r\n&le;\r\n&le;\r\n\r\n\r\ngreater-than or equal to\r\n&ge;\r\n&ge;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSpecial characters can be inserted in the WYSIWYG fields by using the Special Character button on the toolbar [&Omega;]. Click on the desired character and click Close (not all Greek characters are supported).','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(162,'Formatting/Text','71',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(113,'Formatting/Images','<h2>Diagrams</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If an image only uses a few primary colours such as a diagram it is best to save it in a lossless format such as CompuServe Graphics Interchange (GIF) format or Portable Network Graphics (PNG) format. GIF images are limited to a maximum of 256 colours whereas PNG can handle 24bit colour images (16.7 million colours).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/png_example.png\" alt=\"PNG Example\" width=\"538\" height=\"404\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Figure 1:</strong> Image saved in PNG format (size 7.8Kb)</div>\r\n<p><br /> </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Because the chart in Figure 1 does not contain many colours it has been saved as a PNG image and only takes up 7.8Kb of space. The same image saved in JPEG format requires 31.9Kb, roughly 4 times larger. If 300 students took an exam with this image in then 7,230Kb of extra network traffic have been generated. Also, if you look closely at Figure 2 you will see how the format is lossy. Where the colour should be the same shade it appears blotchy when magnified.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/jpeg_problem.png\" alt=\"JPEG Example\" width=\"541\" height=\"599\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Figure 2:</strong> Image saved in JPEG format (size 31.9Kb)</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Photographs/X-Rays</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">GIF images are not suitable for colour photographs because the image only supports 256 colours. To reproduce a colour photograph acurately requires at least 16.7 million colours. Although a PNG image could handle this the file size would be very large. Instead the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) format is much better for photographs (including radiographs).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The image in Figure 3 has been saved in JPEG format with compression level set to 30 in Paint Shop Pro. This a good compromise between visual quality and file size.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/flag_jpeg_compressed.jpg\" alt=\"JPEG Example\" width=\"512\" height=\"384\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Figure 3:</strong> Image saved in JPEG format (size 36.7Kb)</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The image in Figure 4 has been saved as a PNG and so although the image quality is going to be perfect as PNG is a lossless format, to the human eye it is difficult to appreciate the differences between Figure 3 and Figure 4. However, the file size of this PNG image is nearly 10 times bigger than the JPEG.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/flag_png.png\" alt=\"PNG Example\" width=\"512\" height=\"384\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Figure 4:</strong> Image saved in PNG format (size 327.0Kb)</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>JPEG Compression</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">JPEG uses a compression algorithm which is lossey, you don\'t get back 100% of the information that was in the original image. But this algorithm can be controlled in most art packages to find the best balance between visual quality and file size. The screen shot below shows a dialog box from Paint Shop Pro which controls the quality of a JPEG image.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/jpeg_compression.gif\" alt=\"JPEG Compression\" width=\"428\" height=\"334\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Diagrams If an image only uses a few primary colours such as a diagram it is best to save it in a lossless format such as CompuServe Graphics Interchange (GIF) format or Portable Network Graphics (PNG) format. GIF images are limited to a maximum of 256 colours whereas PNG can handle 24bit colour images (16.7 million colours). Figure 1: Image saved in PNG format (size 7.8Kb)  Because the chart in Figure 1 does not contain many colours it has been saved as a PNG image and only takes up 7.8Kb of space. The same image saved in JPEG format requires 31.9Kb, roughly 4 times larger. If 300 students took an exam with this image in then 7,230Kb of extra network traffic have been generated. Also, if you look closely at Figure 2 you will see how the format is lossy. Where the colour should be the same shade it appears blotchy when magnified. Figure 2: Image saved in JPEG format (size 31.9Kb) &nbsp; Photographs/X-Rays GIF images are not suitable for colour photographs because the image only supports 256 colours. To reproduce a colour photograph acurately requires at least 16.7 million colours. Although a PNG image could handle this the file size would be very large. Instead the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) format is much better for photographs (including radiographs). The image in Figure 3 has been saved in JPEG format with compression level set to 30 in Paint Shop Pro. This a good compromise between visual quality and file size. Figure 3: Image saved in JPEG format (size 36.7Kb) &nbsp; The image in Figure 4 has been saved as a PNG and so although the image quality is going to be perfect as PNG is a lossless format, to the human eye it is difficult to appreciate the differences between Figure 3 and Figure 4. However, the file size of this PNG image is nearly 10 times bigger than the JPEG. Figure 4: Image saved in PNG format (size 327.0Kb) &nbsp; JPEG Compression JPEG uses a compression algorithm which is lossey, you don\'t get back 100% of the information that was in the original image. But this algorithm can be controlled in most art packages to find the best balance between visual quality and file size. The screen shot below shows a dialog box from Paint Shop Pro which controls the quality of a JPEG image. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(73,'External Examiners','<h2>1. Creating Accounts</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Each external examiner <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">must</span> have their own authentication account when reviewing papers in Rogo. New accounts may be created by emailing $support_email. External examiners will automatically be sent an email with their log in details when their accounts are first created.</p>\r\n<h2>2. Assigning Examiners to Papers</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">External examiners are assigned to papers by means of the \'Edit Properties\' dialog box. Click on the \'Reviewers\' tab on the left hand side and select all the examiners who are required to review the current paper. Importantly, <strong>remember</strong> to set a deadline by which time all externals should have completed their review. This deadline should typically be a couple of weeks before the intended exam date to allow time for any changes to be made to the assessment. External examiners will lose access to papers automatically on expiry of the deadline.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/External_Examiners1.png\" alt=\"External_Examiners1.png\" width=\"882\" height=\"329\" /></div>\r\n<h2>3. Contacting Externals</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is the role of the module convenor to contact any external examiners connected with an examination. The URL that should be emailed to these externals is:<br /><br /><tt><span style=\"color: #c00000; font-weight: bold;\"><a style=\"color: #0066dc;\" href=\"$local_server\">$local_server</a></span></tt></p>\r\n<h2>4. Examiners Logging In</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When Rogo detects an external logging into <span style=\"color: #c00000; font-weight: bold;\"><a style=\"color: #0066dc;\" href=\"$local_server\">$local_server</a></span> it will redirect the user to a special screen which displays only those papers that require attention from the current external. The screenshot below shows a fictitious example of a resit papers that have been set for review by Dr McCartney. Only papers with <strong>future availability </strong>dates are shown, past dates are assumed to have been sat by examinees and so no longer need reviewing.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/ext examiner.png\" alt=\"ext examiner.png\" width=\"839\" height=\"380\" /></p>\r\n<h2>5. Examiner writes Comments Online</h2>\r\n<p>All external examiner comments for summative exams scheduled for delivery using Rogo should be provided online using Rogo. To do this the external can type textual comments into the textboxes beneath each question as the paper is reviewed.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/external_comments.png\" alt=\"External Examiner review page\" width=\"882\" height=\"302\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>6. UoN Academics Review Comments</h2>\r\n<p>After the deadline passes where by all externals should have commented on an exam, it is possible for the paper owner (or anyone else on the team) to select \'Reports\' from the sidebar and then select \'External Examiners\'. This will display all questions on the paper together with comments from each external under each question. The screenshot below shows Q1 with two externals comments. Dr RK Grencis thinks the paper is OK and made no comment, while Dr J Lunec raised a \'minor\' problem with associated comment. If changes are required to a question then the&nbsp;<img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/review Q change icon.png\" alt=\"review Q change icon.png\" width=\"22\" height=\"22\" /> icon can be used to edit the question.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/ext review report.png\" alt=\"ext review report.png\" width=\"781\" height=\"599\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>7. Uon Academics Respond to Comments/Amend Questions</h2>\r\n<p>If you click on the Comments tab you can add details of any action taken for each point raised during the review..</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/External_Examiners2.png\" alt=\"External_Examiners2.png\" width=\"826\" height=\"311\" /></div>\r\n<h2>8. \'Closing the Loop\' with the External</h2>\r\n<div>After the review period has ended, External Examiners have access to a paper up to one week after the exam has been taken. This should provide enough time for the examiner to go back into the paper and read what actions and responses the exam author wishes to take. The first screenshot below shows the internal response added below the externals comments with a green \'Read - actioned\' status.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/read_agree.png\" alt=\"read_agree.png\" width=\"907\" height=\"151\" /></div>\r\n<p>The screenshot below shows an internal response with red \'Read- disagree\' status.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/read_disagree.png\" alt=\"read_disagree.png\" width=\"907\" height=\"149\" /></div>\r\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Externals can no longer change their comments after the review deadline for the paper, but they may still read&nbsp;responses to their comments for up to one week after the exam was taken.</p>','1. Creating Accounts Each external examiner must have their own authentication account when reviewing papers in Rogo. New accounts may be created by emailing $support_email. External examiners will automatically be sent an email with their log in details when their accounts are first created. 2. Assigning Examiners to Papers External examiners are assigned to papers by means of the \'Edit Properties\' dialog box. Click on the \'Reviewers\' tab on the left hand side and select all the examiners who are required to review the current paper. Importantly, remember to set a deadline by which time all externals should have completed their review. This deadline should typically be a couple of weeks before the intended exam date to allow time for any changes to be made to the assessment. External examiners will lose access to papers automatically on expiry of the deadline. 3. Contacting Externals It is the role of the module convenor to contact any external examiners connected with an examination. The URL that should be emailed to these externals is:$local_server 4. Examiners Logging In When Rogo detects an external logging into $local_server it will redirect the user to a special screen which displays only those papers that require attention from the current external. The screenshot below shows a fictitious example of a resit papers that have been set for review by Dr McCartney. Only papers with future availability dates are shown, past dates are assumed to have been sat by examinees and so no longer need reviewing. &nbsp; 5. Examiner writes Comments Online All external examiner comments for summative exams scheduled for delivery using Rogo should be provided online using Rogo. To do this the external can type textual comments into the textboxes beneath each question as the paper is reviewed. &nbsp; 6. UoN Academics Review Comments After the deadline passes where by all externals should have commented on an exam, it is possible for the paper owner (or anyone else on the team) to select \'Reports\' from the sidebar and then select \'External Examiners\'. This will display all questions on the paper together with comments from each external under each question. The screenshot below shows Q1 with two externals comments. Dr RK Grencis thinks the paper is OK and made no comment, while Dr J Lunec raised a \'minor\' problem with associated comment. If changes are required to a question then the&nbsp; icon can be used to edit the question. &nbsp; 7. Uon Academics Respond to Comments/Amend Questions If you click on the Comments tab you can add details of any action taken for each point raised during the review.. 8. \'Closing the Loop\' with the External After the review period has ended, External Examiners have access to a paper up to one week after the exam has been taken. This should provide enough time for the examiner to go back into the paper and read what actions and responses the exam author wishes to take. The first screenshot below shows the internal response added below the externals comments with a green \'Read - actioned\' status. The screenshot below shows an internal response with red \'Read- disagree\' status. Note: Externals can no longer change their comments after the review deadline for the paper, but they may still read&nbsp;responses to their comments for up to one week after the exam was taken.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(74,'Deleting/Questions from Papers','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Go into a paper and then single click on the lead-in of the question you wish to delete (1). Next select \'Remove from Paper\' from the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane (2)&nbsp;and select \'Delete Pointer\' in the safety check dialog box (3).</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/questions_from_paper.png\" alt=\"questions_from_paper.png\" width=\"770\" height=\"571\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Go into a paper and then single click on the lead-in of the question you wish to delete (1). Next select \'Remove from Paper\' from the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane (2)&nbsp;and select \'Delete Pointer\' in the safety check dialog box (3). &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(75,'Deleting/Papers','\r\n\r\n<div>Click on the paper you wish to delete to go into it. Next select \'Delete Paper\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Note 1:</strong> Only the owner of a paper (or team member, if on team) may delete it.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Note 2:</strong> Deleting a paper will not delete the questions it contains; these still remain in the question bank.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>',' Click on the paper you wish to delete to go into it. Next select \'Delete Paper\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. &nbsp; Note 1: Only the owner of a paper (or team member, if on team) may delete it. &nbsp; Note 2: Deleting a paper will not delete the questions it contains; these still remain in the question bank. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(76,'Deleting/Questions from Bank','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are two methods of locating a question that needs to be deleted:</p>\r\n<h2>Method 1</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first method involves clicking on one of the first 3 links in the Question Bank Tasks shown below. \'Questions by Type\' has been selected in the example shown below and a popup menu is displayed to allow the user to select the question type of the question that needs to be deleted.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/question_by_type1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"421\" height=\"451\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Next single click on the lead-in of the question you wish to delete (this will activate the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane) and then click \'Delete Question\' from the sidebar menu.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/question for deleting1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"769\" height=\"358\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If a question is used on one or more papers a warning dialog box will be displayed similar to the one below. This will display the name of the paper(s) the question is used on. This is a safety feature to ensure that papers do not get ruined by accidentally deleting questions. To proceed with deleting the question it must first be deleted from the paper(s) concerned.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/delete question warning1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"520\" height=\"194\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once the current question has been removed from all papers the following dialog will be displayed to double check that the user does wish to delete it. Simply click \'Delete\' to proceed.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/confirm question deletion1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"520\" height=\"175\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Method 2</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The second method involves performing a search for a question you wish to delete. Click on \'Search\' from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane and then select \'Questions\' from the popup menu. Enter a search term in the textbox and click \'Search\'. When the desired question has been located single click on it and then click on \'Delete Question\' from the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/search and delete.png\" alt=\"search and delete.png\" width=\"770\" height=\"561\" /></div>','There are two methods of locating a question that needs to be deleted: Method 1 The first method involves clicking on one of the first 3 links in the Question Bank Tasks shown below. \'Questions by Type\' has been selected in the example shown below and a popup menu is displayed to allow the user to select the question type of the question that needs to be deleted. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Next single click on the lead-in of the question you wish to delete (this will activate the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane) and then click \'Delete Question\' from the sidebar menu. &nbsp; If a question is used on one or more papers a warning dialog box will be displayed similar to the one below. This will display the name of the paper(s) the question is used on. This is a safety feature to ensure that papers do not get ruined by accidentally deleting questions. To proceed with deleting the question it must first be deleted from the paper(s) concerned. &nbsp; Once the current question has been removed from all papers the following dialog will be displayed to double check that the user does wish to delete it. Simply click \'Delete\' to proceed. Method 2 The second method involves performing a search for a question you wish to delete. Click on \'Search\' from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane and then select \'Questions\' from the popup menu. Enter a search term in the textbox and click \'Search\'. When the desired question has been located single click on it and then click on \'Delete Question\' from the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(146,'Deleting/Folders','38',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(81,'Teams/About','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Each module has a module team where all members of the team can access and edit the papers and questions created by a member of the team. All users of Rogo need to be on a team to create and access papers. When you create a new paper you must select a module for the paper and this paper then becomes available to all members of the team for that module. If you create a question in a paper, the relevant module team will automatically be selected.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Question</strong><br />Allows anyone in the team to edit and save changes to the question.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Paper</strong><br />Allows any team member to make changes to the properties of a paper.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Folder</strong><br />Allows for the sharing of \'personal folders\' within a team. Any personal folder assigned to a team will automatically show up in the \'My Folders\' section of all team members.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','Each module has a module team where all members of the team can access and edit the papers and questions created by a member of the team. All users of Rogo need to be on a team to create and access papers. When you create a new paper you must select a module for the paper and this paper then becomes available to all members of the team for that module. If you create a question in a paper, the relevant module team will automatically be selected.  QuestionAllows anyone in the team to edit and save changes to the question.   PaperAllows any team member to make changes to the properties of a paper.&nbsp;&nbsp;   FolderAllows for the sharing of \'personal folders\' within a team. Any personal folder assigned to a team will automatically show up in the \'My Folders\' section of all team members.&nbsp;&nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(87,'Copying/Papers','65',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(88,'Copying/Questions','<h2>Copying Questions</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are 2 ways of copying a question:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Method 1</strong> - Go to a paper which already uses the question and single click to highlight it. Next go to the sidebar menu and select \'Copy onto Paper X...\' from the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane. A new window will open listing the papers that you have access to and a paper can be selected from the list. This adds a copy of the question to the selected paper and as there are now 2 versions of the question changes made to one of these does not affect the other.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Method 2 </strong>- Select a question from the Question Bank by using the relevant search option then single clicking on the required question. You then have the option of \'Copy onto Paper X ...\' which&nbsp;works in the same way as described in Method 1.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When a question is copied the ownership of the copy is always set to the person performing the copy action regardless of the person owning the original.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Linking to Questions&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you don\'t want to make any changes to&nbsp;a question you can just select a paper that you want to link&nbsp;the question to. This is done by following the process in Method 2 but selecting \'Link to paper\' rather than the copy option. This would mean that any changes to the question would appear in both papers that are linked to it.</div>','Copying Questions There are 2 ways of copying a question: &nbsp; Method 1 - Go to a paper which already uses the question and single click to highlight it. Next go to the sidebar menu and select \'Copy onto Paper X...\' from the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane. A new window will open listing the papers that you have access to and a paper can be selected from the list. This adds a copy of the question to the selected paper and as there are now 2 versions of the question changes made to one of these does not affect the other. &nbsp; Method 2 - Select a question from the Question Bank by using the relevant search option then single clicking on the required question. You then have the option of \'Copy onto Paper X ...\' which&nbsp;works in the same way as described in Method 1. &nbsp; When a question is copied the ownership of the copy is always set to the person performing the copy action regardless of the person owning the original. &nbsp; Linking to Questions&nbsp; If you don\'t want to make any changes to&nbsp;a question you can just select a paper that you want to link&nbsp;the question to. This is done by following the process in Method 2 but selecting \'Link to paper\' rather than the copy option. This would mean that any changes to the question would appear in both papers that are linked to it.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(91,'Searching/for Papers','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">To search for a paper select the \'Search\' option from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane and then \'Papers\' from the popup menu.</div>\r\n<div><strong></strong>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> The search facility will only look for papers for the team(s) that you are part of.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/search papers1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"516\" height=\"419\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are different types of information that you can enter to find the paper that you are looking for. You can enter the name (or partial name) of a paper under \'Word and or phrase\' and select the type of paper(s). You can also select when and to who the paper is accessible using the options under \'Accessibility\' (Please note that \'Lab\' is only appropriate to Summative exams). \'Ownership\' allows you to select the Team or Individual that owns the paper. When you have entered the information you have for the paper you want to find, click on \'Search\'. In the example below all paper types and the paper owner has been selected to find&nbsp;relevant papers.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/search papers list1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"531\" height=\"417\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','To search for a paper select the \'Search\' option from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane and then \'Papers\' from the popup menu. &nbsp; Note: The search facility will only look for papers for the team(s) that you are part of. &nbsp; &nbsp; There are different types of information that you can enter to find the paper that you are looking for. You can enter the name (or partial name) of a paper under \'Word and or phrase\' and select the type of paper(s). You can also select when and to who the paper is accessible using the options under \'Accessibility\' (Please note that \'Lab\' is only appropriate to Summative exams). \'Ownership\' allows you to select the Team or Individual that owns the paper. When you have entered the information you have for the paper you want to find, click on \'Search\'. In the example below all paper types and the paper owner has been selected to find&nbsp;relevant papers. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(92,'Searching/for People','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To search for a user enter either their last name or their username into the relevant textboxes on the left hand side and then click \'Search\'. To narrow down the search further the degree and academic year of study dropdown lists can be used. You can also Search for all students on a selected module.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/search students.png\" alt=\"search students.png\" width=\"849\" height=\"480\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','To search for a user enter either their last name or their username into the relevant textboxes on the left hand side and then click \'Search\'. To narrow down the search further the degree and academic year of study dropdown lists can be used. You can also Search for all students on a selected module. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(93,'Creating/Sub-Folders','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To create a sub-folder within a \'parent\' folder, first go into the parent folder and then select \'Make a new sub-folder\' from the \'Folder Tasks\' pane in the sidebar menu.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/sub_folder.png\" alt=\"sub_folder.png\" width=\"591\" height=\"129\" /></p>','To create a sub-folder within a \'parent\' folder, first go into the parent folder and then select \'Make a new sub-folder\' from the \'Folder Tasks\' pane in the sidebar menu. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(94,'User Functions/User Types','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The system has a number of different types of users each of which is assigned various access rights and privilages:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>External Examiner</strong><br />Academic staff from external institutions who review summative exam papers before use as part of the quality assurance process.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Graduate</strong><br />A student who has already graduated. Graduates are not allocated any privilages but remain on the system so that past reports continue to function properly.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Invigilator</strong><br />Staff in charge of overseeing the conduct of an exam room. This role provides access to specific invigilator screens only. <a href=\"index.php?id=215\" target=\"_top\">See also...</a></div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Staff</strong><br />University and NHS members of staff who have&nbsp;standard accounts. Staff can view and edit questions&nbsp;and papers that are assigned to&nbsp;a team that they are a member of.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Staff (Admin)</strong><br />University staff with admin rights for a selected school.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Student</strong><br />A student from any degree who is registered to take either assessments or surveys. The only parts of the system they are authorised to access is the initial blue screen with the \'Sit Paper\' button on and the actual assessment paper window itself. Students also have access to their own online help system (separate to the staff one).</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>SysAdmin</strong><br />IT members of staff who oversee the technical operation of the system. They have access to an additional \'Administrative Tools\' section and can edit or override any part of the system.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','The system has a number of different types of users each of which is assigned various access rights and privilages:  External ExaminerAcademic staff from external institutions who review summative exam papers before use as part of the quality assurance process.   GraduateA student who has already graduated. Graduates are not allocated any privilages but remain on the system so that past reports continue to function properly.   InvigilatorStaff in charge of overseeing the conduct of an exam room. This role provides access to specific invigilator screens only. See also...   StaffUniversity and NHS members of staff who have&nbsp;standard accounts. Staff can view and edit questions&nbsp;and papers that are assigned to&nbsp;a team that they are a member of.   Staff (Admin)University staff with admin rights for a selected school.   StudentA student from any degree who is registered to take either assessments or surveys. The only parts of the system they are authorised to access is the initial blue screen with the \'Sit Paper\' button on and the actual assessment paper window itself. Students also have access to their own online help system (separate to the staff one).   SysAdminIT members of staff who oversee the technical operation of the system. They have access to an additional \'Administrative Tools\' section and can edit or override any part of the system. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(300,'Questions - About/Adding to a Paper','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To add a question directly into a paper, select the question that you want to add and then select \'Link to paper\'.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The graphic below shows this process. A question search has been performed and a&nbsp;question selected (1). Clicking on \'Link to paper\' (2) results in a&nbsp;new window&nbsp;being opened. This shows a list of papers owned by the user and one paper has been selected (3). Clicking an&nbsp;\'Add to Paper\' button (4)&nbsp;in this window&nbsp;adds the question to the paper.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Locked and Active papes are shown in the list but are greyed out with a warning icon to show that they cannot be altered.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Link_to_paper.png\" alt=\"Link_to_paper.png\" width=\"826\" height=\"463\" /></p>','To add a question directly into a paper, select the question that you want to add and then select \'Link to paper\'. The graphic below shows this process. A question search has been performed and a&nbsp;question selected (1). Clicking on \'Link to paper\' (2) results in a&nbsp;new window&nbsp;being opened. This shows a list of papers owned by the user and one paper has been selected (3). Clicking an&nbsp;\'Add to Paper\' button (4)&nbsp;in this window&nbsp;adds the question to the paper. Locked and Active papes are shown in the list but are greyed out with a warning icon to show that they cannot be altered. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(95,'Papers/Assigning to Folders','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Papers can be assigned (or put into) folders using the \'Create new Paper\' or \'Edit Properties\' functions. In the screenshot below the user has selected an existing paper and then clicked on \'Edit Properties\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. In the dialog box there is a \'folder\' field with a dropdown list showing all the folders owned by the current user. In this case the&nbsp;\'AR personal folder\' has been selected.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img src=\"images/assign_folder.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"883\" height=\"692\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Papers can be assigned (or put into) folders using the \'Create new Paper\' or \'Edit Properties\' functions. In the screenshot below the user has selected an existing paper and then clicked on \'Edit Properties\' from the \'Current Paper Tasks\' pane. In the dialog box there is a \'folder\' field with a dropdown list showing all the folders owned by the current user. In this case the&nbsp;\'AR personal folder\' has been selected. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(164,'Finding/Papers','91',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(109,'Finding/People','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To find a user (staff, student, external examiner), select \'Search/People\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Click the down arrow button next to \'Advanced\' to view the categories of Rogo users and select the one relevant to your search.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/search1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"775\" height=\"428\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The various options can be used individually or in combination. For example, a general search for students may only select a degree and a year. A more specific search could be by entering a particular last name or student ID if known.</p>','To find a user (staff, student, external examiner), select \'Search/People\'. Click the down arrow button next to \'Advanced\' to view the categories of Rogo users and select the one relevant to your search. &nbsp; &nbsp; The various options can be used individually or in combination. For example, a general search for students may only select a degree and a year. A more specific search could be by entering a particular last name or student ID if known.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(110,'Recycle Bin','<div style=\"text-align: left;\">Deleted papers and questions are moved into the Recycle Bin.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/recycle_bin1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"776\" height=\"419\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">If you need to restore a deleted paper or question, select it from the list and then select \'Restore this item\' from the Recycle Bin Tasks panel.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/recycle_bin2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"776\" height=\"230\" /></div>','Deleted papers and questions are moved into the Recycle Bin. &nbsp; &nbsp; If you need to restore a deleted paper or question, select it from the list and then select \'Restore this item\' from the Recycle Bin Tasks panel. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(158,'Reviewing Papers/Internal Peer Review','<h2>1. Assigning Internal examiners to papers</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Internal examiners are assigned to papers by means of the \'Edit Properties\' dialog box. Click on the \'Reviewers\' tab on the left hand side and select all the examiners who are required to review the current paper. Importantly, remember to set a deadline by which time all internal reviewers should have completed their review.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/Reviewer1.png\" alt=\"Reviewer1.png\" width=\"882\" height=\"410\" /></p>\r\n<h2>2. Review alerts</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When an internal reviewer accesses Rogo they will be alerted to any papers that require their attention. Papers with past dates are assumed to have been sat and therefore not requiring a review.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Reviewer2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"583\" height=\"420\" /></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2>3. Examiner comments</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When a paper is selected the reviewer sees a copy of each question with an area underneath to make comments.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/peer review 3.PNG\" alt=\"peer review 3.PNG\" width=\"956\" height=\"374\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>4. Reviewing comments</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Comments from the internal examiners can be viewed by selecting \'Analysis Menu\' from the side bar and then \'Internal Peer Review\'. Comments are shown under each question with an area for adding a response and whether any actions have taken place.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/peer review 4.PNG\" alt=\"peer review 4.PNG\" width=\"803\" height=\"255\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>5. Reviewer writes Comments Online</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Reviewers can type textual comments into the textboxes beneath each question as the paper is reviewed.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/external_comments.png\" alt=\"External Examiner review page\" width=\"882\" height=\"302\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>6. Review of Comments</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After the deadline passes where by all reviewers should have commented on an exam, it is possible for the paper owner (or anyone else on the team) to select \'Analysis Menu\' from the sidebar and then select \'Internal Peer Review\'. This will display all questions on the paper together with comments from each reviewer under each question. The screenshot below shows Q1 with two externals comments. Dr RK Grencis thinks the paper is OK and made no comment, while Dr J Lunec raised a \'minor\' problem with associated comment. If changes are required to a question then the <img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"../../artwork/edit_icon_16.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" /> icon can be used to edit the question.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/internal peer review.png\" alt=\"internal peer review.png\" width=\"795\" height=\"504\" /></p>\r\n<h2>7. Uon Academics Respond to Comments/Amend Questions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Click on the edit <img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"../../artwork/edit_icon_16.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" /> icon to go into a question in edit mode.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/edit q changes tab.png\" alt=\"edit q changes tab.png\" width=\"823\" height=\"280\" /></div>','1. Assigning Internal examiners to papers Internal examiners are assigned to papers by means of the \'Edit Properties\' dialog box. Click on the \'Reviewers\' tab on the left hand side and select all the examiners who are required to review the current paper. Importantly, remember to set a deadline by which time all internal reviewers should have completed their review.&nbsp; 2. Review alerts When an internal reviewer accesses Rogo they will be alerted to any papers that require their attention. Papers with past dates are assumed to have been sat and therefore not requiring a review.  3. Examiner comments When a paper is selected the reviewer sees a copy of each question with an area underneath to make comments. &nbsp; &nbsp; 4. Reviewing comments Comments from the internal examiners can be viewed by selecting \'Analysis Menu\' from the side bar and then \'Internal Peer Review\'. Comments are shown under each question with an area for adding a response and whether any actions have taken place. &nbsp; &nbsp; 5. Reviewer writes Comments Online Reviewers can type textual comments into the textboxes beneath each question as the paper is reviewed. &nbsp; 6. Review of Comments After the deadline passes where by all reviewers should have commented on an exam, it is possible for the paper owner (or anyone else on the team) to select \'Analysis Menu\' from the sidebar and then select \'Internal Peer Review\'. This will display all questions on the paper together with comments from each reviewer under each question. The screenshot below shows Q1 with two externals comments. Dr RK Grencis thinks the paper is OK and made no comment, while Dr J Lunec raised a \'minor\' problem with associated comment. If changes are required to a question then the icon can be used to edit the question. 7. Uon Academics Respond to Comments/Amend Questions Click on the edit icon to go into a question in edit mode. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(159,'Reviewing Papers/External Examiners','73',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(161,'Summative Exams/Question Locking','<p>Once a summative exam has run, the paper and all questions that it links to are locked and cannot be amended. This ensures that the questions in the bank accurately match the results of the exam.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/question_locking.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"691\" height=\"215\" /></p>','Once a summative exam has run, the paper and all questions that it links to are locked and cannot be amended. This ensures that the questions in the bank accurately match the results of the exam. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(127,'Health and Safety','<h2>VDUs</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">VDUs have been blamed, usually wrongly, for a wide range of health problems. In fact, most problems occur because of the way the equipment is set up and used, rather than the equipment itself. A few simple guidelines can help to keep you comfortable when taking an online exam.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Sitting position</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Perform the following checks and make adjustments where necessary as soon as you are seated at a workstation. If you believe the setup of your workstation may adversely affect your performance please inform an invigilator before the exam begins.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Try to adjust the chair so that as you type and use the mouse your forearms are horizontal and your eyes are the same height as the top of the screen.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Place your feet flat on the floor and keep your legs uncrossed.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Position the mouse within easy reach and sit upright and close to the desk so that your mouse arm is not stretched. Support it on the desk so that it is relaxed.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Don\'t grip the mouse too tightly and rest your fingers lightly on the buttons.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Move the keyboard out of the way if it is not being used.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Adjust the brightness/contrast of the screen if necessary.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Characters on the screen should be in focus and not flickering or moving. If you have a problem with your monitor, inform an invigilator - there are always spare screens.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/vdu_position.jpg\" alt=\"vdu seating position\" width=\"351\" height=\"345\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Can work with a VDU affect my eyesight?</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Extensive research has found no evidence that VDUs can cause disease or permanent damage to the eyes. However, long spells of VDU work can lead to tired eyes and discomfort. To reduce this:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Try to look away from the screen occasionally so that your eyes can change their focus.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Remember to bring glasses if you need them.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Get your eyes tested at least every two years.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr style=\"text-align: left; width: 40%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href=\"images/indg36.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/pdf.gif\" alt=\"pdf.gif\" width=\"32\" height=\"32\" /></a></td>\r\n<td><a href=\"images/indg36.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Working with VDUs</a><br /> by the Health and Safety Executive</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','VDUs\r\nVDUs have been blamed, usually wrongly, for a wide range of health problems. In fact, most problems occur because of the way the equipment is set up and used, rather than the equipment itself. A few simple guidelines can help to keep you comfortable when taking an online exam.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSitting position\r\nPerform the following checks and make adjustments where necessary as soon as you are seated at a workstation. If you believe the setup of your workstation may adversely affect your performance please inform an invigilator before the exam begins.\r\n\r\n\r\nTry to adjust the chair so that as you type and use the mouse your forearms are horizontal and your eyes are the same height as the top of the screen.\r\n\r\n\r\nPlace your feet flat on the floor and keep your legs uncrossed.\r\n\r\n\r\nPosition the mouse within easy reach and sit upright and close to the desk so that your mouse arm is not stretched. Support it on the desk so that it is relaxed.\r\n\r\n\r\nDon\'t grip the mouse too tightly and rest your fingers lightly on the buttons.\r\n\r\n\r\nMove the keyboard out of the way if it is not being used.\r\n\r\n\r\nAdjust the brightness/contrast of the screen if necessary.\r\n\r\n\r\nCharacters on the screen should be in focus and not flickering or moving. If you have a problem with your monitor, inform an invigilator - there are always spare screens.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCan work with a VDU affect my eyesight?\r\nExtensive research has found no evidence that VDUs can cause disease or permanent damage to the eyes. However, long spells of VDU work can lead to tired eyes and discomfort. To reduce this:\r\n\r\n\r\nTry to look away from the screen occasionally so that your eyes can change their focus.\r\n\r\n\r\nRemember to bring glasses if you need them.\r\n\r\n\r\nGet your eyes tested at least every two years.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSee also:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWorking with VDUs by the Health and Safety Executive\r\n\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(120,'Marking/Calculate Random Mark','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">One of the problems of most objective tests is that the correct answer is always presented on-screen to the user. Therefore, even if the candidate knows nothing of the subject matter in question, there is always the possibility that they will select the correct answer by chance. For example, the likelihood of selecting the correct answer to a True/False dichotomous question is 50/50. Likewise the probability of selecting the correct answer in a five option MCQ question is 1 in 5 or 20%. Rogo can be configured so that it automatically calculates the mark which would be expected if a candidate answered all questions at random. This mark is then subtracted from a real candidate\'s performance, it is subtracted from the total possible marks for the paper, and then the new candidate mark is expressed as a percentage out of the new paper mark.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To calculate the random mark there is a setting, see below, in the paper properties dialog box:</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/marking random.png\" alt=\"marking random.png\" width=\"674\" height=\"529\" /></div>\r\n<div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div>\r\n<div><strong></strong>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note 1:</strong> An alternative Marking method is to standards set the paper. If a module has been set to include Standards Setting, this will appear as another option on the screen above.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note 2:</strong> Calculate random mark is also known as correction for guessing or CFG.</div>','One of the problems of most objective tests is that the correct answer is always presented on-screen to the user. Therefore, even if the candidate knows nothing of the subject matter in question, there is always the possibility that they will select the correct answer by chance. For example, the likelihood of selecting the correct answer to a True/False dichotomous question is 50/50. Likewise the probability of selecting the correct answer in a five option MCQ question is 1 in 5 or 20%. Rogo can be configured so that it automatically calculates the mark which would be expected if a candidate answered all questions at random. This mark is then subtracted from a real candidate\'s performance, it is subtracted from the total possible marks for the paper, and then the new candidate mark is expressed as a percentage out of the new paper mark. To calculate the random mark there is a setting, see below, in the paper properties dialog box: &nbsp; &nbsp; Note 1: An alternative Marking method is to standards set the paper. If a module has been set to include Standards Setting, this will appear as another option on the screen above. Note 2: Calculate random mark is also known as correction for guessing or CFG.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(121,'Marking/Correcting Mistakes','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">After a summative exam has been run the \'Frequency/Facility Analysis\' report should be run from the \'Analysis Menu\'. If any questions are found to have a very high number of students getting the question wrong then a check should be made to see if the correct option was set properly in Rogo. In the example below \'Sydney\' has erroneously been entered as the correct answer. Only 2% of candidates selected this as their answer, whereas 83% selected \'London\'.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<table style=\"width: 300px; border-collapse: collapse;\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"3\">1. What is the capital of England?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"3\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 50px;\" align=\"right\">10</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 50px; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;(8%)</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 200px; text-align: left;\">New York</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"right\">99</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;(83%)</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">London</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"right\">8</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;(7%)</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">Paris</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"right\"><strong>2</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>&nbsp;(2%)</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Sydney</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"right\">1</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;(1%)</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">Tokyo</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">To correct this mistake the member of staff responsible for the assessment should go into the question to edit it. Although the question will say that it is locked, it is still possible to change what is set as the correct answer(s). As shown below, select the answer which should be correct:</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/correct_question.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"609\" height=\"442\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;At the bottom of the screen the \'Save\' button will be disabled as the question is locked, but instead click \'Correct\'. This will 1) set the correct answer in the question bank, and 2) remark all student attempts to this question with the new answer. If the \'Class Totals\' report is brought up it will now display correct marks.</p>','After a summative exam has been run the \'Frequency/Facility Analysis\' report should be run from the \'Analysis Menu\'. If any questions are found to have a very high number of students getting the question wrong then a check should be made to see if the correct option was set properly in Rogo. In the example below \'Sydney\' has erroneously been entered as the correct answer. Only 2% of candidates selected this as their answer, whereas 83% selected \'London\'. &nbsp;   1. What is the capital of England?  &nbsp;  10 &nbsp;(8%) New York  99 &nbsp;(83%) London  8 &nbsp;(7%) Paris  2 &nbsp;(2%) Sydney  1 &nbsp;(1%) Tokyo   &nbsp; To correct this mistake the member of staff responsible for the assessment should go into the question to edit it. Although the question will say that it is locked, it is still possible to change what is set as the correct answer(s). As shown below, select the answer which should be correct: &nbsp; &nbsp;At the bottom of the screen the \'Save\' button will be disabled as the question is locked, but instead click \'Correct\'. This will 1) set the correct answer in the question bank, and 2) remark all student attempts to this question with the new answer. If the \'Class Totals\' report is brought up it will now display correct marks.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(248,'Objectives/Creating Objectives in Rogo','<div>If you are not linking to objectives held externally you can create objectives <em>within</em> Rogo.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>The first step is to select \'Manage Objectives\' from the screen that you see when you go into the module (1). If this is greyed out, objectives mapping may not have been set for your module. Contact Learning-Team-Support if your module needs to be set for objectives mapping.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/manage_objectives_highlight.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"358\" height=\"166\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>The screen shown below is accessed when you have selected \'Manage Objectives\' from the initial module screen. You can select the details for a session and then enter the objectives that will be covered in the session. The session may be an individual lecture or can be a topic area. The URL field is optional but can be used if you have a webpage that holds student resources that you want to refer to as part of the student assessment feedback.</div>\r\n&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/objectives_new_session1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"744\" height=\"335\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Once an objective has been created, you can edit the text if required. Although there is not a delete option, if you delete all the text for an objective it will be empty and if you select \'Save\' the Objective will be removed.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note: </strong>If you change the text for an objective that has been mapped to a question the link will be maintained.</div>','If you are not linking to objectives held externally you can create objectives within Rogo. The first step is to select \'Manage Objectives\' from the screen that you see when you go into the module (1). If this is greyed out, objectives mapping may not have been set for your module. Contact Learning-Team-Support if your module needs to be set for objectives mapping. &nbsp; &nbsp; The screen shown below is accessed when you have selected \'Manage Objectives\' from the initial module screen. You can select the details for a session and then enter the objectives that will be covered in the session. The session may be an individual lecture or can be a topic area. The URL field is optional but can be used if you have a webpage that holds student resources that you want to refer to as part of the student assessment feedback. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Once an objective has been created, you can edit the text if required. Although there is not a delete option, if you delete all the text for an objective it will be empty and if you select \'Save\' the Objective will be removed. &nbsp; Note: If you change the text for an objective that has been mapped to a question the link will be maintained.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(128,'Initial Screen','<p>When a student logs into a paper, they see an \'initial screen\' which provides&nbsp;information about the assessment or survey:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img src=\"images/initial_screen2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"601\" height=\"309\" /></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">The name of the examination/survey paper is shown at the top of the screen.</li>\r\n<li>The <strong>Rubric </strong>shows the rules of the exam.</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Candidates</strong> shows who is allowed to complete the paper, this is set by module&nbsp;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The number of separate <strong>Screens</strong> used in the paper is shown where each screen will contain at least one question, usually several.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Navigation </strong>will display either: a) unidirectional or b) bidirectional. In unidirectional mode the user will not be permitted to return to previous screens. All questions on the current screen should be attempted before clicking on the submit button. In bidirectional mode this does not matter as the user can move freely backwards and forwards between screens.</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Marks</strong> shows the total available marks for the paper. If the paper is scaled, as in the example above, then the marks will also include in brackets the calculated random mark.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Current User</strong> shows the name of the currently logged in user.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Duration</strong> shows the candidate how long they have to complete the exam.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Help</strong> launches the online help system in a new window.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>\'Start &gt;&gt;\'</strong> button starts the exam or survey in a new window.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Previous&nbsp;Completions</strong> are listed below the blue line at the bottom of the screen. This is useful for formative assessment where users wish to monitor their improvement across a year or semester.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','When a student logs into a paper, they see an \'initial screen\' which provides&nbsp;information about the assessment or survey: &nbsp; The name of the examination/survey paper is shown at the top of the screen. The Rubric shows the rules of the exam. Candidates shows who is allowed to complete the paper, this is set by module&nbsp;  The number of separate Screens used in the paper is shown where each screen will contain at least one question, usually several. Navigation will display either: a) unidirectional or b) bidirectional. In unidirectional mode the user will not be permitted to return to previous screens. All questions on the current screen should be attempted before clicking on the submit button. In bidirectional mode this does not matter as the user can move freely backwards and forwards between screens. Marks shows the total available marks for the paper. If the paper is scaled, as in the example above, then the marks will also include in brackets the calculated random mark.  Current User shows the name of the currently logged in user.  Duration shows the candidate how long they have to complete the exam. Help launches the online help system in a new window. \'Start &gt;&gt;\' button starts the exam or survey in a new window. Previous&nbsp;Completions are listed below the blue line at the bottom of the screen. This is useful for formative assessment where users wish to monitor their improvement across a year or semester. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(130,'Marking/Excluding Questions Post Exam','129',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(137,'Objectives/Mapping','<p><strong>Interactive tutorial</strong></p>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'mapping1_training.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Objectives mapping</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2>Purpose</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mapping questions in Rogo to learning objectives set for the learning sessions achieves two main aims:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">When Objectives mapping has been completed, the \'Mapped Objectives\' report shows the objective <strong>sampling</strong> of a paper. Sampling is an important educational concept to see which parts of the curriculum are being assessed each year by various papers.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once mapped, personalised <strong>feedback</strong> can be provided to students to assist them in their studies/development (see <a href=\"display_page.php?id=145\">Student Feedback</a>).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Objectives in Rogo</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Before you start mapping objectives, the relevant objectives need to be available to Rogo. This could be through a link to a VLE or by <a href=\"display_page.php?id=248\">creating them in Rogo</a>.</p>\r\n<h2>Method</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo supports the mapping (linking) of learning objectives set for the sessions to individual questions on an assessment. There are three ways in which to create these mappings:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>When Adding a question</li>\r\n<li>When Editing a question</li>\r\n<li>Through the \'Mapped objectives\' report</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> Before a question can be mapped it must first be included on a paper and that paper must be associated with at least 1 module in a particular academic year. The reason for this is that Rogo needs to know what module and session to use when obtaining the objectives.</p>\r\n<h2>1. When Adding a question</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The process of mapping objectives while Adding a question is very similar to Editing (please see Editing process below).</p>\r\n<h2>2. When Editing a question</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Double click on the question to be mapped to go into the edit screen and click on \'Mapping\'. A list of all the \'session\' level learning objectives for the module associated with the paper is displayed, organised by session. Scan down the sessions/topic areas and any that are relevant to the current question may be expanded out by clicking on the plus icon. Selecting the plus icon will show all the individual learning objectives for that particular session. Use the checkboxes to then associate (link) as many as appropriate to the current question.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/question_mapping.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"916\" height=\"386\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To save the mappings click back on the Editor tab, scroll to the bottom of the screen and click \'Save\'.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This process should be repeated for all the questions on the assessment.</p>\r\n<h2>3. Through the \'Mapped objectives\' report</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once a summative exam runs all the questions are locked and cannot be modified. Once this happens for a particular question the mapping process as described above, through question editing, can no longer be used. In these circumstances, objectives can still be mapped by selecting the \'Mapped objectives\' from the sidebar menu. All the questions on the paper will be listed in screen order. Click on the mapping icon (see highlight) to launch the objective mapping dialog box.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/objectives mapping.png\" alt=\"objectives mapping.png\" width=\"855\" height=\"369\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">A new dialog window will appear with all the session learning objectives for the module that the current paper is associated with. Click on any of the sessions/topic areas&nbsp;which related to the current question. When the plus is expanded individual objectives will be shown. Check the boxes of any that relate to the current question.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/mapping_objectives2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"843\" height=\"682\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>When happy with all mappings click the \'Save\' button.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note: </strong>You can change mappings through the \'Mapped Objectives\' report including removing links for objectives by deselecting the objective.</div>','Interactive tutorial\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nObjectives mapping\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPurpose\r\nMapping questions in Rogo to learning objectives set for the learning sessions achieves two main aims:\r\n\r\nWhen Objectives mapping has been completed, the \'Mapped Objectives\' report shows the objective sampling of a paper. Sampling is an important educational concept to see which parts of the curriculum are being assessed each year by various papers.\r\nOnce mapped, personalised feedback can be provided to students to assist them in their studies/development (see Student Feedback).\r\n\r\nObjectives in Rogo\r\nBefore you start mapping objectives, the relevant objectives need to be available to Rogo. This could be through a link to a VLE or by creating them in Rogo.\r\nMethod\r\nRogo supports the mapping (linking) of learning objectives set for the sessions to individual questions on an assessment. There are three ways in which to create these mappings:\r\n\r\nWhen Adding a question\r\nWhen Editing a question\r\nThrough the \'Mapped objectives\' report\r\n\r\nNote: Before a question can be mapped it must first be included on a paper and that paper must be associated with at least 1 module in a particular academic year. The reason for this is that Rogo needs to know what module and session to use when obtaining the objectives.\r\n1. When Adding a question\r\nThe process of mapping objectives while Adding a question is very similar to Editing (please see Editing process below).\r\n2. When Editing a question\r\nDouble click on the question to be mapped to go into the edit screen and click on \'Mapping\'. A list of all the \'session\' level learning objectives for the module associated with the paper is displayed, organised by session. Scan down the sessions/topic areas and any that are relevant to the current question may be expanded out by clicking on the plus icon. Selecting the plus icon will show all the individual learning objectives for that particular session. Use the checkboxes to then associate (link) as many as appropriate to the current question.\r\n\r\nTo save the mappings click back on the Editor tab, scroll to the bottom of the screen and click \'Save\'.\r\nThis process should be repeated for all the questions on the assessment.\r\n3. Through the \'Mapped objectives\' report\r\nOnce a summative exam runs all the questions are locked and cannot be modified. Once this happens for a particular question the mapping process as described above, through question editing, can no longer be used. In these circumstances, objectives can still be mapped by selecting the \'Mapped objectives\' from the sidebar menu. All the questions on the paper will be listed in screen order. Click on the mapping icon (see highlight) to launch the objective mapping dialog box.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nA new dialog window will appear with all the session learning objectives for the module that the current paper is associated with. Click on any of the sessions/topic areas&nbsp;which related to the current question. When the plus is expanded individual objectives will be shown. Check the boxes of any that relate to the current question.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nWhen happy with all mappings click the \'Save\' button.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nNote: You can change mappings through the \'Mapped Objectives\' report including removing links for objectives by deselecting the objective.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(138,'Objectives/Reports','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After all the questions on a paper have been mapped there are a number of reports which can visualise the resulting relationships between the questions in Rogo and the objectives that have been set for the module. The first two (\'by Session\' and \'by Question\') are useful to see what questions an assessment is sampling as an exam is being prepared. In some cases the decision to write additional questions may be taken to ensure adequate sampling from the whole module. The other report, \'Learning Objective Analysis\' is then used once the assessment has taken place and can show how well the cohort as a whole achieved each objective.</p>\r\n<h2>by Session</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The \'by session\' report (see below) shows all the session-level learning objectives for a particular module. Where an objective is covered by a question on the current assessment it will be displayed in black and have the question number appended in orange.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the example below, the objective \'Define the terms aetiology, pathogenesis, natural history and prognosis\' has been mapped to question number 14. This report is particularly useful in seeing at a glance how a module\'s objectives are <em>sampled</em> by the current assessment.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/objectives by session.png\" alt=\"objectives by session.png\" width=\"646\" height=\"361\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note for Medical School users:</strong> It is possible to click on the session title in blue (or the shortcut icon) and bring up that particular session of the NLE in a new window.</p>\r\n<h2>by Question</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The \'by Question\' report complements \'by Session\' but this time is displayed in question order. This report is good for seeing which sessions contribute to which questions. For example, Question 5 below assesses objectives from both CLS/L1/08 and CLS/l1/11. <strong>Note for Medical School users: </strong>Click on these hyperlinks to bring the required session in the NLE up in a new window.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/objectives by question.png\" alt=\"objectives by question.png\" width=\"745\" height=\"412\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Learning Objective Analysis</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This report can be found from the \'Analysis Menu\'. It shows in ranked order of best performance how well the cohort as a whole achieved each objective. The percentage score next to the icon is the percentage of the cohort getting questions mapped to the objective correct.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This report, particularly the least well answered objectives at the bottom, can be used to improve teaching and tackle areas of weakness.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/mapping7.png\" alt=\"mapping7.png\" width=\"921\" height=\"470\" /></div>','Introduction After all the questions on a paper have been mapped there are a number of reports which can visualise the resulting relationships between the questions in Rogo and the objectives that have been set for the module. The first two (\'by Session\' and \'by Question\') are useful to see what questions an assessment is sampling as an exam is being prepared. In some cases the decision to write additional questions may be taken to ensure adequate sampling from the whole module. The other report, \'Learning Objective Analysis\' is then used once the assessment has taken place and can show how well the cohort as a whole achieved each objective. by Session The \'by session\' report (see below) shows all the session-level learning objectives for a particular module. Where an objective is covered by a question on the current assessment it will be displayed in black and have the question number appended in orange. In the example below, the objective \'Define the terms aetiology, pathogenesis, natural history and prognosis\' has been mapped to question number 14. This report is particularly useful in seeing at a glance how a module\'s objectives are sampled by the current assessment. Note for Medical School users: It is possible to click on the session title in blue (or the shortcut icon) and bring up that particular session of the NLE in a new window. by Question The \'by Question\' report complements \'by Session\' but this time is displayed in question order. This report is good for seeing which sessions contribute to which questions. For example, Question 5 below assesses objectives from both CLS/L1/08 and CLS/l1/11. Note for Medical School users: Click on these hyperlinks to bring the required session in the NLE up in a new window. &nbsp; Learning Objective Analysis This report can be found from the \'Analysis Menu\'. It shows in ranked order of best performance how well the cohort as a whole achieved each objective. The percentage score next to the icon is the percentage of the cohort getting questions mapped to the objective correct. &nbsp; This report, particularly the least well answered objectives at the bottom, can be used to improve teaching and tackle areas of weakness. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(147,'Mapping/Objectives','137',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(145,'Objectives/Student Feedback','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In addition to being able to clearly see how an assessment samples the objectives of a module, another huge benefit is the personalised feedback that can be given to students. In the past all a student would be given is a percentage mark with a pass/fail classification. Now it is possible for students to see a report that is personalised to their specific performance on a particular exam. This report is accessed through a URL generated by Rogo.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The screenshot below shows an example of a student who has taken the A14ONG exam from 2008/09. As you can see, no questions are shown to the student so some or all may be re-used in future exams. Instead, the student is shown a rank ordered list of objectives by percent acquisition. A traffic light icon system is used, green all/mostly acquired, amber partially acquired and red little/not acquired. Rogo assumes that a student gets the answer to a question correct then they have achieved the learning objective that is linked to this question. Partial acquisition can occur where multiple questions all test the same objective. A student could, for example, get one question right and one wrong, this would give an average of 50% acquisition and therefore be displayed as the amber icon. The key below gives further details.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Icons</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Green=wholly/mainly achieved, Amber=partially achieved, and Red=mainly not achieved.</div>\r\n<div><strong>Your Mark</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Shows the number of marks of questions linked to each objective together with the number of marks you actually scored on these questions.</div>\r\n<div><strong>Relative</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Show the average number of marks relative to the whole cohort. So, for example, a score of +0.1 means you scored 0.1 more marks than students in the cohort did on average for this learning objective.</div>\r\n<div><strong>Q no</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The number of questions linked to a particular learning objective.</div>\r\n<div><strong>Objective</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The text of the learning objective itself.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/exam_feedback.png\" alt=\"exam_feedback.png\" width=\"960\" height=\"730\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">At the bottom of the above report (not shown on graphic) is a distribution bar chart which shows the range of performance of the whole cohort and then plots the individual student\'s performance against this. This allows the student to see how well they are doing in comparison with their peers.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you want to provide objectives feedback for students the \'Objectives Report\' checkbox is selected to provide the URL for the feedback which can then be sent to students (or a link provided in the VLE).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/paper feedback report options.png\" alt=\"paper feedback report options.png\" width=\"676\" height=\"163\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=210\">Objectives/Overview</a></li>\r\n</ul>','In addition to being able to clearly see how an assessment samples the objectives of a module, another huge benefit is the personalised feedback that can be given to students. In the past all a student would be given is a percentage mark with a pass/fail classification. Now it is possible for students to see a report that is personalised to their specific performance on a particular exam. This report is accessed through a URL generated by Rogo. The screenshot below shows an example of a student who has taken the A14ONG exam from 2008/09. As you can see, no questions are shown to the student so some or all may be re-used in future exams. Instead, the student is shown a rank ordered list of objectives by percent acquisition. A traffic light icon system is used, green all/mostly acquired, amber partially acquired and red little/not acquired. Rogo assumes that a student gets the answer to a question correct then they have achieved the learning objective that is linked to this question. Partial acquisition can occur where multiple questions all test the same objective. A student could, for example, get one question right and one wrong, this would give an average of 50% acquisition and therefore be displayed as the amber icon. The key below gives further details. &nbsp; Icons Green=wholly/mainly achieved, Amber=partially achieved, and Red=mainly not achieved. Your Mark Shows the number of marks of questions linked to each objective together with the number of marks you actually scored on these questions. Relative Show the average number of marks relative to the whole cohort. So, for example, a score of +0.1 means you scored 0.1 more marks than students in the cohort did on average for this learning objective. Q no The number of questions linked to a particular learning objective. Objective The text of the learning objective itself. &nbsp; &nbsp; At the bottom of the above report (not shown on graphic) is a distribution bar chart which shows the range of performance of the whole cohort and then plots the individual student\'s performance against this. This allows the student to see how well they are doing in comparison with their peers. &nbsp; If you want to provide objectives feedback for students the \'Objectives Report\' checkbox is selected to provide the URL for the feedback which can then be sent to students (or a link provided in the VLE). &nbsp; &nbsp; See also: Objectives/Overview ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(289,'Marking/Variable Marks','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The number of marks awarded for correct answers can be set individually for each question. This allows a paper writer to set the marks that are appropriate for the question. Marks for incorrect answers can also be selected for modules that have been set up to allow negative marking. These marks are then used for the marking method that has been selected.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Please note:</strong> If a Multiple Response question has \'Marks if incorrect\' set to a value, negative marks will be given for unanswered questions. If the field is set to 0 as shown below, students will be able to leave a question unanswered without receiving negative marks.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/marking method.png\" alt=\"marking method.png\" width=\"686\" height=\"101\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','The number of marks awarded for correct answers can be set individually for each question. This allows a paper writer to set the marks that are appropriate for the question. Marks for incorrect answers can also be selected for modules that have been set up to allow negative marking. These marks are then used for the marking method that has been selected. Please note: If a Multiple Response question has \'Marks if incorrect\' set to a value, negative marks will be given for unanswered questions. If the field is set to 0 as shown below, students will be able to leave a question unanswered without receiving negative marks. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(219,'Feedback/Formative feedback','<h2>About Feedback</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\" align=\"justify\">Feedback is a crucial aspect of effective learning in HE. Feedback can be included in Formative exams not only to tell the students whether they answered questions correctly but also to give details about the correct answer.</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Good feedback can have a motivating effect on the user</span></div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div align=\"justify\">Should provide constructive information that aids learning</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div align=\"justify\">Has been shown to improve performance in summative assessment</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div align=\"justify\">Quality feedback is timely and specific</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Setting Feedback levels in Paper</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\" align=\"justify\">The graphic below shows the paper properties in the \'General\' tab with&nbsp;the first&nbsp;4 feedback options selected. If the 5th option&nbsp;is selected, students will only see feedback&nbsp;for questions they have answered.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/formative feedback settings.png\" alt=\"formative feedback settings.png\" width=\"689\" height=\"220\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Correct Answers/Text Feedback</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The text feedback on the graphic below gives specific feedback for the options selected and shows&nbsp;the correct option that was missed by the student.</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/student formative feedback2.png\" alt=\"student formative feedback2.png\" width=\"634\" height=\"352\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Learning Objectives</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" align=\"justify\">If a paper has been mapped to learning objectives then these will appear beneath the question. They remind the student the board topic area and can link back to the VLE for further learning resources.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/feedback_objectives.png\" alt=\"feedback_objectives.png\" width=\"700\" height=\"329\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Standards Setting</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\" align=\"justify\">For assessments in Medicine and allied health sciences it is possible to standards set the questions in a paper and then to display this information to students on the feedback screen. The abreviations are explained below, for example EE is Easy/Essential. Providing standards setting feedback in addition to the standard correct answer can provide an extra level of detail for students. For example most students should be getting Easy/Essential correct, but it is less important if some Hard/Nice to Know questions are answered incorrectly. Vice versa a student answering Hard/Nice to Know correctly may be on track for an honours degree award.</p>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/std_set_feedback.png\" alt=\"std_set_feedback.png\" width=\"728\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Standards Setting ratings</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; width: 600px; border-collapse: collapse;\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EE</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Easy-Essential</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">ME</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Medium-Essential</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HE</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Hard-Essential</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Easy-Important</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">MI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Medium-Important</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Hard-Important</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Easy-Nice to know</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">MN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Medium-Nice to know</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Hard--Nice to know</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','About Feedback Feedback is a crucial aspect of effective learning in HE. Feedback can be included in Formative exams not only to tell the students whether they answered questions correctly but also to give details about the correct answer.  Good feedback can have a motivating effect on the user  Should provide constructive information that aids learning  Has been shown to improve performance in summative assessment  Quality feedback is timely and specific  Setting Feedback levels in Paper The graphic below shows the paper properties in the \'General\' tab with&nbsp;the first&nbsp;4 feedback options selected. If the 5th option&nbsp;is selected, students will only see feedback&nbsp;for questions they have answered.&nbsp;&nbsp; Correct Answers/Text Feedback The text feedback on the graphic below gives specific feedback for the options selected and shows&nbsp;the correct option that was missed by the student. Learning Objectives If a paper has been mapped to learning objectives then these will appear beneath the question. They remind the student the board topic area and can link back to the VLE for further learning resources. Standards Setting For assessments in Medicine and allied health sciences it is possible to standards set the questions in a paper and then to display this information to students on the feedback screen. The abreviations are explained below, for example EE is Easy/Essential. Providing standards setting feedback in addition to the standard correct answer can provide an extra level of detail for students. For example most students should be getting Easy/Essential correct, but it is less important if some Hard/Nice to Know questions are answered incorrectly. Vice versa a student answering Hard/Nice to Know correctly may be on track for an honours degree award. &nbsp; Standards Setting ratings &nbsp;   EE Easy-Essential ME Medium-Essential HE Hard-Essential  EI Easy-Important MI Medium-Important HI Hard-Important  EN Easy-Nice to know MN Medium-Nice to know HN Hard--Nice to know   &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(150,'Surveys/Quantitative Report','33',NULL,'pointer','2010-02-01 14:27:27',1217,'Staff',NULL),(152,'Summative Exams/Summative Assessment Lifecycle','<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<table style=\"text-align: center;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 150px;\" rowspan=\"12\"><span style=\"color: #365f91; font-size: 140%; font-weight: bold;\">Pre-Exam</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Create Assessment</strong><br />1) Book Computer Lab, 2) Inform Exams Office, and 3) Inform <br />$support_email</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=170\" target=\"_top\">Enter Questions</a></strong><br />Click above link for development life-cycle</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=137\" target=\"_top\">Map Objectives</a></strong><br />Edit/create questions if important objectives are not being assessed</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Peer Review Paper</strong><br />Edit Questions where necessary</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=73\" target=\"_top\">External Examiner Review</a></strong><br />Edit Questions where necessary</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=97\" target=\"_top\">Standards Setting</a></strong><br />Used in the Faculty of Medicine and Health Sciences</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 150px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><span style=\"color: #e36c0a; font-size: 140%; font-weight: bold;\">Mid-Exam</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_orange.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Run the Exam</strong><br /><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=161\" target=\"_top\">Questions Lock automatically</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_orange.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 150px;\" rowspan=\"7\"><span style=\"color: #4f6228; font-size: 140%; font-weight: bold;\">Post-Exam</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_green.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Analysis of Performance</strong><br /><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=30\" target=\"_top\">Class Totals</a>, <a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=154\" target=\"_top\">Frequency &amp; Discrimination Analysis</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_green.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_green.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=121\" target=\"_top\">Fix any Incorrect Answers</a></strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_green.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_green.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=129\" target=\"_top\">Exclusion of poor Question</a></strong><br />see Frequency &amp; Discrimination (U-L) Analysis</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_green.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_green.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Marks ratification at Exam Board</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>','\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPre-Exam\r\nCreate Assessment1) Book Computer Lab, 2) Inform Exams Office, and 3) Inform $support_email\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nEnter QuestionsClick above link for development life-cycle\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMap ObjectivesEdit/create questions if important objectives are not being assessed\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPeer Review PaperEdit Questions where necessary\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nExternal Examiner ReviewEdit Questions where necessary\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nStandards SettingUsed in the Faculty of Medicine and Health Sciences\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMid-Exam\r\nRun the ExamQuestions Lock automatically\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPost-Exam\r\nAnalysis of PerformanceClass Totals, Frequency &amp; Discrimination Analysis\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFix any Incorrect Answers\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nExclusion of poor Questionsee Frequency &amp; Discrimination (U-L) Analysis\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMarks ratification at Exam Board\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(154,'Reports/Frequency & Discrimination Analysis','<div><strong>Interactive Tutorial</strong></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'exclude and correct_training v2.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Excluding and Correcting questions</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Frequency &amp; Discrimination Analysis&nbsp;is accessed through \'Reports\' and is used to look at the number of students that have selected each option in a question and how well it discriminates between the upper and lower 27% of students.&nbsp; These values help to identify how well the question is working.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The item difficulty of each question, ranges from 0.0 to 1.0, and is calculated as the average score for the question divided by the maximum achievable score. An item difficulty of 0.0 indicates a very hard question (no-one got it right), while a value of 1.0 shows a very easy question (no-one got it wrong). Questions that have item difficulties of more than 0.75 or less than 0.25 are less effective in differentiating users. An ideal value is 0.5.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/freq and discrim.png\" alt=\"freq and discrim.png\" width=\"885\" height=\"554\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If the number of students getting the answer correct is under 50% (t &lt; 50%) then double-check that the correct answer has been properly set when editing the question. If this is not the case then the correct answer can be set see: <a href=\"index.php?id=121\" target=\"_top\">Correcting Mistakes</a>.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;\"><span style=\"line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; color: #484848; font-size: 10.5pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">Discrimination ranges from -1.0 to +1.0, and is a Pearson product-moment correlation between the item and the total test score. A correlation close to +1.0 means that the question is measuring the same thing as the test. A low correlation shows that getting the question right is not related to a good test score. A negative correlation means that getting the question right associates with a low-test score. Users who answer correctly questions with a discrimination of less than 0.25 up to -1 do not necessarily do well in the test as a whole.</span></div>\r\n<div class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: 150%; margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt;\"><span style=\"line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; color: #484848; font-size: 10.5pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; color: #484848; font-size: 10.5pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n<div class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: 150%; margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;\"><span style=\"line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\'; color: #484848; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">The report (see above) shows the number of students in each group (u=upper group, l=lower group) that correctly answered each option in each question and the corresponding discrimination value (d). Questions that discriminate well have a value of above 0.2 although a low value may be acceptable for core knowledge. </span></p>\r\n</div>','Interactive Tutorial\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nExcluding and Correcting questions\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe Frequency &amp; Discrimination Analysis&nbsp;is accessed through \'Reports\' and is used to look at the number of students that have selected each option in a question and how well it discriminates between the upper and lower 27% of students.&nbsp; These values help to identify how well the question is working.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe item difficulty of each question, ranges from 0.0 to 1.0, and is calculated as the average score for the question divided by the maximum achievable score. An item difficulty of 0.0 indicates a very hard question (no-one got it right), while a value of 1.0 shows a very easy question (no-one got it wrong). Questions that have item difficulties of more than 0.75 or less than 0.25 are less effective in differentiating users. An ideal value is 0.5.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIf the number of students getting the answer correct is under 50% (t &lt; 50%) then double-check that the correct answer has been properly set when editing the question. If this is not the case then the correct answer can be set see: Correcting Mistakes.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nDiscrimination ranges from -1.0 to +1.0, and is a Pearson product-moment correlation between the item and the total test score. A correlation close to +1.0 means that the question is measuring the same thing as the test. A low correlation shows that getting the question right is not related to a good test score. A negative correlation means that getting the question right associates with a low-test score. Users who answer correctly questions with a discrimination of less than 0.25 up to -1 do not necessarily do well in the test as a whole.\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe report (see above) shows the number of students in each group (u=upper group, l=lower group) that correctly answered each option in each question and the corresponding discrimination value (d). Questions that discriminate well have a value of above 0.2 although a low value may be acceptable for core knowledge. \r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(168,'Searching/for Questions','8',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(170,'Questions - About/Development Life-cycle','<p>The advice listed here applies to questions used in assessments (formative, progress tests and summative exams). Questions used for surveys may want to follow a shorter development life-cycle.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<table style=\"text-align: center;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 180px;\" rowspan=\"4\"><span style=\"color: #365f91; font-size: 140%; font-weight: bold;\">Conceptual Stage</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Review Objectives</strong><br /> Review aim of module and session-level objectives</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Abstract Purpose</strong><br /> What do you want students to be able to demonstrate?</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 180px;\" rowspan=\"10\"><span style=\"color: #e36c0a; font-size: 140%; font-weight: bold;\">Writing Stage</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_orange.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Possible Question Type(s)</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_orange.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_orange.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Lead-in</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_orange.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_orange.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Scenario</strong><br /> Background information to help answer the lead-in</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_orange.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_orange.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Options</strong><br /> Correct answer, then distractors</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_orange.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_orange.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Formatting</strong><br /> Visual formatting, bold, italics, etc.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_orange.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left; width: 180px;\" rowspan=\"10\"><span style=\"color: #4f6228; font-size: 140%; font-weight: bold;\">Checking Stage</span></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_green.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong>Testing</strong><br /> Question added to paper and tested</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_green.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_green.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=147\" target=\"_top\">Mapping Objectives</a></strong><br /> Blueprinting</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_green.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_green.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\"><strong><a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"index.php?id=158\" target=\"_top\">Peer Review</a></strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>','The advice listed here applies to questions used in assessments (formative, progress tests and summative exams). Questions used for surveys may want to follow a shorter development life-cycle.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nConceptual Stage\r\nReview Objectives Review aim of module and session-level objectives\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAbstract Purpose What do you want students to be able to demonstrate?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWriting Stage\r\nPossible Question Type(s)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nLead-in\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nScenario Background information to help answer the lead-in\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOptions Correct answer, then distractors\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFormatting Visual formatting, bold, italics, etc.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nChecking Stage\r\nTesting Question added to paper and tested\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMapping Objectives Blueprinting\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPeer Review\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(176,'Summative Exams/Summative Roles','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The table below lists the generic roles that have to be fulfilled for a successful online summative exam from two different perspectives: 1) chronologically: pre-exam, mid-exam and post-exam, and 2) by the type of staff: academic, administrative or IT support. Multiple roles will sometimes be covered by the same person. It is your duty, if you suspect that a role isn\'t being covered, to raise this point with the examinations officer so that cover can be sought.</p>\r\n<table style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center; background-color: #484848; width: 10%; color: white;\"><strong>Phase</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center; background-color: #484848; width: 30%; color: white;\"><strong>Academic</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center; background-color: #484848; width: 30%; color: white;\"><strong>Administrative</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center; background-color: #484848; width: 30%; color: white;\"><strong>IT</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center; background-color: #a7c0de;\"><strong>Pre-Exam</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e0e8f2; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Module Convenor</em></strong><br />Selects appropriate format for assessment</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Question writer(s)</em></strong><br />Questions are written by academics, could include module convenor and others</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Question inputter</em></strong><br />Questions require entry into e-assessment system. Sometimes this is cut and paste from Word, sometimes questions are written directly into e-assessment system. Best practice is that the academic question writer should input questions but in some cases this may be delegated.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Objectives mapping</em></strong><br />Questions should be mapped to learning objectives if used.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Internal question reviewers</em></strong><br />Questions should be reviewed by experts in the subject matter for any problems.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Standards Setting team</em></strong><br />For subjects using standard setting techniques, a team meeting must be arranged to facilitate this process.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>External question reviewers</em></strong><br />Access to the completed paper needs to be given to an external examiner, so that comments can be recorded online using Rogo.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e0e8f2; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Exam scheduling</em></strong><br />A timetable of exams is created for each module.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Room Booking</em></strong><br />In conjunction with the exam timetabling must be the booking of computer labs with sufficient numbers of computers.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Accessibility Unit</em></strong><br />Examinees with special needs, such as dyslexia, must be identified and appropriate adjustments made so that they are not unfairly disadvantaged at exam time.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e0e8f2; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Server support/security</em></strong><br />The server on which the e-assessment system resides requires regular maintenance and security updating. This must be performed with knowledge of the exam timetable.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Networking</em></strong><br />Teams responsible for the local area network must be notified of exam times so that maintenance to routers/switches, etc can be planned.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Desktop Support</em></strong><br />All the PCs should be working and configured correctly</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Trainers for Staff</em></strong><br />Staff must be trained in: a) the capabilities of the e-assessment system, and b) how to create questions/papers in the system well in advance of the scheduled exam date.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Trainers for Students</em></strong><br />The students must be informed that they should expect some of their exams to be online and how the software works for each question type.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center; background-color: #facaa2;\"><strong>Mid-Exam</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #fdede1; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Academic source for mid-exam problems</em></strong><br />As with paper exams, an academic should be on hand in case of any content problems.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #fdede1; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Invigilators</em></strong><br />As with paper-based exams invigilators are required to be vigilant for plagiarism.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #fdede1; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Software support</em></strong><br />Staff knowledgeable in the e-assessment system in use must be on call during exam time in case of any crashes or other problems.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center; background-color: #ccdcac;\"><strong>Post-Exam</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #edf2e2; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Module Convenor</em></strong><br />After the exam is complete the performance of the exam cohort should be examined and any poorly performing questions removed.</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Exam Board</em></strong><br />Final moderated marks should be sent to a formal exam board.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #edf2e2; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Marks Upload</em></strong><br />Staff dealing with the loading of final marks into student records systems.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #edf2e2; vertical-align: top;\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Software support</em></strong><br />Support for staff running reports after an exam.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','The table below lists the generic roles that have to be fulfilled for a successful online summative exam from two different perspectives: 1) chronologically: pre-exam, mid-exam and post-exam, and 2) by the type of staff: academic, administrative or IT support. Multiple roles will sometimes be covered by the same person. It is your duty, if you suspect that a role isn\'t being covered, to raise this point with the examinations officer so that cover can be sought.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPhase\r\nAcademic\r\nAdministrative\r\nIT\r\n\r\n\r\nPre-Exam\r\n\r\nModule ConvenorSelects appropriate format for assessment\r\nQuestion writer(s)Questions are written by academics, could include module convenor and others\r\nQuestion inputterQuestions require entry into e-assessment system. Sometimes this is cut and paste from Word, sometimes questions are written directly into e-assessment system. Best practice is that the academic question writer should input questions but in some cases this may be delegated.\r\nObjectives mappingQuestions should be mapped to learning objectives if used.\r\nInternal question reviewersQuestions should be reviewed by experts in the subject matter for any problems.\r\nStandards Setting teamFor subjects using standard setting techniques, a team meeting must be arranged to facilitate this process.\r\nExternal question reviewersAccess to the completed paper needs to be given to an external examiner, so that comments can be recorded online using Rogo.\r\n\r\n\r\nExam schedulingA timetable of exams is created for each module.\r\nRoom BookingIn conjunction with the exam timetabling must be the booking of computer labs with sufficient numbers of computers.\r\nAccessibility UnitExaminees with special needs, such as dyslexia, must be identified and appropriate adjustments made so that they are not unfairly disadvantaged at exam time.\r\n\r\n\r\nServer support/securityThe server on which the e-assessment system resides requires regular maintenance and security updating. This must be performed with knowledge of the exam timetable.\r\nNetworkingTeams responsible for the local area network must be notified of exam times so that maintenance to routers/switches, etc can be planned.\r\nDesktop SupportAll the PCs should be working and configured correctly\r\nTrainers for StaffStaff must be trained in: a) the capabilities of the e-assessment system, and b) how to create questions/papers in the system well in advance of the scheduled exam date.\r\nTrainers for StudentsThe students must be informed that they should expect some of their exams to be online and how the software works for each question type.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMid-Exam\r\n\r\nAcademic source for mid-exam problemsAs with paper exams, an academic should be on hand in case of any content problems.\r\n\r\n\r\nInvigilatorsAs with paper-based exams invigilators are required to be vigilant for plagiarism.\r\n\r\n\r\nSoftware supportStaff knowledgeable in the e-assessment system in use must be on call during exam time in case of any crashes or other problems.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPost-Exam\r\n\r\nModule ConvenorAfter the exam is complete the performance of the exam cohort should be examined and any poorly performing questions removed.\r\nExam BoardFinal moderated marks should be sent to a formal exam board.\r\n\r\n\r\nMarks UploadStaff dealing with the loading of final marks into student records systems.\r\n\r\n\r\nSoftware supportSupport for staff running reports after an exam.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','page','2012-09-20 14:14:20',1217,'Staff',NULL),(178,'Questions - About/Hints for creating and editing','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you are copying text for a question from a document, e.g a Word document, you may experience problems if you paste directly into the text field for the question. To avoid problems select \'Paste text\' as shown in the graphic below and paste your text into the new window.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/paste from word.png\" alt=\"paste from word.png\" width=\"839\" height=\"222\" /></div>','If you are copying text for a question from a document, e.g a Word document, you may experience problems if you paste directly into the text field for the question. To avoid problems select \'Paste text\' as shown in the graphic below and paste your text into the new window. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(181,'Feedback/Summative feedback','145',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(183,'Summative Exams/Starting','<h2>Starting Exams</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Students should be brought into a computer lab 15 minutes before the scheduled start time of the exam to allow enough time to leave bags in appropriate places and to log in.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ideally log in instruction slips (see example below) will be laid out at each workstation by the invigilators. Where this has not happened, for whatever reason, verbally announce that at the first prompt (logging into Novell) the student should all use the username <strong>gtzexam1</strong> and the password <strong>3xamuser1</strong>. This log in will start what is called the \'Exam Desktop\' which is designed to stop cheating by preventing different applications&nbsp;from running&nbsp;and access to the Internet.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In some situations the username <strong>gtzexam1</strong> may not work, if this&nbsp;is the case,&nbsp;instruct the cohort to log into Novell with their usual university username/password, start Internet Explorer and then go to the following URL: <a style=\"color: blue;\" href=\"$local_server\">$local_server</a>.&nbsp;In very rare situations the <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">user account may be automatically locked. This will only occur if an incorrect password is used <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">5 times in succession on the same computer</span>. Should this happen then call the IT helpline on x16677 and they will be able to unlock the account immediately.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/log_in_instructions.png\" alt=\"log_in_instructions.png\" width=\"606\" height=\"424\" /></p>\r\n<p><br /><a href=\"images/gtzexam1.doc\">MS Word version of Instructions</a> to print instruction slips.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">After logging into the \'Exam Desktop\' with the username <strong>gtzexam1</strong>, the system will then ask the student for their own university username and password. At this point Rogo will automatically work out what exam papers are scheduled to run currently and what module the current student is registered on. See \'Potential Problems\' below if the expected exam paper does not appear for any users.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/exam_rubric.PNG\" alt=\"exam_rubric.PNG\" width=\"721\" height=\"455\" /></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Verbally re-iterate to the cohort that students should stop when they get to the \'blue screen\' (see screenshot above). When it looks like all users have logged in successfully verbally ask \"please raise your hand if you are <strong>not</strong> logged in\". Delay the start time of the exam if there are students who have yet to get to the \'blue screen\'. Note: This does not include students arriving at exams late.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Announce: \"You have xxx minutes starting now, please click \'Start &gt;&gt;\'\"</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol><hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Ending Exams</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> The software <strong>does not </strong>automatically end an exam. The reason for this is that the exam may have started late and needs to end late too or additional time may be required to offset for a temporary loss of network time, etc.</p>\r\n<p>At the end of the exam make the following announcements:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>\"You must stop answering questions now.\"</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>\"Navigate to the last screen.\"</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>\"Click on the &lsquo;Finish&rsquo; button in the bottom right corner of the last screen.\"</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>\"Press &lsquo;CTRL&rsquo;, &lsquo;ALT&rsquo; and &lsquo;DELETE&rsquo; to log out of your workstation.\"</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol><hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<h2>Potential Problems</h2>\r\n<p>In some situations either a single student or the whole of a class may get a screen similar to the one below stating that no exams can be found:</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/starting2.png\" alt=\"starting2.png\" width=\"618\" height=\"431\" /></div>\r\n<p>The information provided on this screen is to assist in solving what the problem might be. Data provided includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>IP Address</strong> - This is the IP address of the current computer. If Rogo recognises it in its database then the computer lab it belongs in will be displayed in brackets. In the example above the lab is \'Coates C20\'. Check that this lab has been assigned to the assessment paper.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Time/Date</strong> - This is the current server time/date when the current paper was requested. Has the assessment paper been set for the right time/date? Check the year is correct - this can often be set into the far future.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Academic Year</strong> - This is the academic year of the currently logged in student.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Modules</strong> - A list of modules (by academic session) is listed for the currently logged in student. Is the assessment paper on the correct module? Is the current student registered on the correct module?</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Roles</strong> - This is the role of the currently logged in user. A normal exam candidate should have the role \'Student\'.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The most frequent problems encountered with papers can usually be sorted by going into \'Edit Properties\' dialog box of the paper. Check the correct start/end dates have been set, has the correct computer lab been checked, has the correct module been set and in the right academic year?</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If making any changes in the \'Edit Properties\' dialog remember to click \'Save\' and then inform the student(s) to hit F5 on the keyboard to refresh the screen and hopefully bring up the required paper.</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=185\">Temporary Accounts</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Starting Exams  Students should be brought into a computer lab 15 minutes before the scheduled start time of the exam to allow enough time to leave bags in appropriate places and to log in.  Ideally log in instruction slips (see example below) will be laid out at each workstation by the invigilators. Where this has not happened, for whatever reason, verbally announce that at the first prompt (logging into Novell) the student should all use the username gtzexam1 and the password 3xamuser1. This log in will start what is called the \'Exam Desktop\' which is designed to stop cheating by preventing different applications&nbsp;from running&nbsp;and access to the Internet.  In some situations the username gtzexam1 may not work, if this&nbsp;is the case,&nbsp;instruct the cohort to log into Novell with their usual university username/password, start Internet Explorer and then go to the following URL: $local_server.&nbsp;In very rare situations the user account may be automatically locked. This will only occur if an incorrect password is used 5 times in succession on the same computer. Should this happen then call the IT helpline on x16677 and they will be able to unlock the account immediately. &nbsp; MS Word version of Instructions to print instruction slips. &nbsp; After logging into the \'Exam Desktop\' with the username gtzexam1, the system will then ask the student for their own university username and password. At this point Rogo will automatically work out what exam papers are scheduled to run currently and what module the current student is registered on. See \'Potential Problems\' below if the expected exam paper does not appear for any users.  Verbally re-iterate to the cohort that students should stop when they get to the \'blue screen\' (see screenshot above). When it looks like all users have logged in successfully verbally ask \"please raise your hand if you are not logged in\". Delay the start time of the exam if there are students who have yet to get to the \'blue screen\'. Note: This does not include students arriving at exams late.  Announce: \"You have xxx minutes starting now, please click \'Start &gt;&gt;\'\"  Ending Exams Note: The software does not automatically end an exam. The reason for this is that the exam may have started late and needs to end late too or additional time may be required to offset for a temporary loss of network time, etc. At the end of the exam make the following announcements:  \"You must stop answering questions now.\"  \"Navigate to the last screen.\"  \"Click on the &lsquo;Finish&rsquo; button in the bottom right corner of the last screen.\"  \"Press &lsquo;CTRL&rsquo;, &lsquo;ALT&rsquo; and &lsquo;DELETE&rsquo; to log out of your workstation.\"  Potential Problems In some situations either a single student or the whole of a class may get a screen similar to the one below stating that no exams can be found: The information provided on this screen is to assist in solving what the problem might be. Data provided includes:  IP Address - This is the IP address of the current computer. If Rogo recognises it in its database then the computer lab it belongs in will be displayed in brackets. In the example above the lab is \'Coates C20\'. Check that this lab has been assigned to the assessment paper.  Time/Date - This is the current server time/date when the current paper was requested. Has the assessment paper been set for the right time/date? Check the year is correct - this can often be set into the far future.  Academic Year - This is the academic year of the currently logged in student.  Modules - A list of modules (by academic session) is listed for the currently logged in student. Is the assessment paper on the correct module? Is the current student registered on the correct module?  Roles - This is the role of the currently logged in user. A normal exam candidate should have the role \'Student\'.  The most frequent problems encountered with papers can usually be sorted by going into \'Edit Properties\' dialog box of the paper. Check the correct start/end dates have been set, has the correct computer lab been checked, has the correct module been set and in the right academic year? If making any changes in the \'Edit Properties\' dialog remember to click \'Save\' and then inform the student(s) to hit F5 on the keyboard to refresh the screen and hopefully bring up the required paper. See also: Temporary Accounts ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(185,'Summative Exams/Temporary Accounts','<h2>Overview</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Temporary accounts are only used during summative exams if a student is unable to access the exam paper. This may be if they are not yet registered on the module or if they have forgotten their username or password. This is a 2 step process as detailed below where the first step occurs during the exam and the second after the exam has finished.</p>\r\n<h2>1. Assigning Temporary Accounts - During exam</h2>\r\n<div>A&nbsp;Temporary&nbsp;account can be assigned to the student at the start of the exam. At the log in dialog box click \'Cancel\' and the following screen will appear:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/access1.png\" alt=\"access1.png\" width=\"536\" height=\"254\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Click on \'Temporary Account\' (1) and then the student should enter their title, surname and first name and student ID if known (2) and then click \'OK\' (3). If the student ID is not known the field should be left blank so that Rogo then looks at the name fields.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/access2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"451\" height=\"224\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">After clicking \'OK\' the system will do a search to see which user accounts are not in use. As the screenshot below shows, \'user1\' account must be in use by another student, so \'user2\' has been selected. Passwords are changed on each account every time one is allocated. The idea is that these are very much temporary accounts that should only be used for a single exam.</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/access3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"450\" height=\"204\" /></p>\r\n<h2>2. Re-assign marks to Student - Post Exam</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If&nbsp;a Temporary Account has been used,&nbsp;when the exam has finished it is necessary to transfer the exam script plus marks over to the real account of the student. To do this go into the \'Analysis Menu\' from the paper and select \'Class Totals\'. Next scroll down to surnames beginning with \'U\' and highlighted in yellow should be any temporary accounts used. Clicking on the name will&nbsp;show a popup menu, select \'Re-assign to User...\'.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/access4.png\" alt=\"access4.png\" width=\"757\" height=\"254\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo will look at the details the student entered against the temporary account and look the student up. The example below shows details of the student that has been associated with the \'user1\' guest account. Clicking&nbsp;on the user\'s image/name&nbsp;will transfer the exam script and marks over to the student\'s records.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/access5.png\" alt=\"access5.png\" width=\"620\" height=\"340\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Overview Temporary accounts are only used during summative exams if a student is unable to access the exam paper. This may be if they are not yet registered on the module or if they have forgotten their username or password. This is a 2 step process as detailed below where the first step occurs during the exam and the second after the exam has finished. 1. Assigning Temporary Accounts - During exam A&nbsp;Temporary&nbsp;account can be assigned to the student at the start of the exam. At the log in dialog box click \'Cancel\' and the following screen will appear: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Click on \'Temporary Account\' (1) and then the student should enter their title, surname and first name and student ID if known (2) and then click \'OK\' (3). If the student ID is not known the field should be left blank so that Rogo then looks at the name fields.&nbsp; After clicking \'OK\' the system will do a search to see which user accounts are not in use. As the screenshot below shows, \'user1\' account must be in use by another student, so \'user2\' has been selected. Passwords are changed on each account every time one is allocated. The idea is that these are very much temporary accounts that should only be used for a single exam. 2. Re-assign marks to Student - Post Exam If&nbsp;a Temporary Account has been used,&nbsp;when the exam has finished it is necessary to transfer the exam script plus marks over to the real account of the student. To do this go into the \'Analysis Menu\' from the paper and select \'Class Totals\'. Next scroll down to surnames beginning with \'U\' and highlighted in yellow should be any temporary accounts used. Clicking on the name will&nbsp;show a popup menu, select \'Re-assign to User...\'. &nbsp; &nbsp; Rogo will look at the details the student entered against the temporary account and look the student up. The example below shows details of the student that has been associated with the \'user1\' guest account. Clicking&nbsp;on the user\'s image/name&nbsp;will transfer the exam script and marks over to the student\'s records. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(189,'Papers/Locking','<div><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/paper locked.png\" alt=\"paper locked.png\" width=\"707\" height=\"325\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Summative assessment papers lock immediately after the start time/date of the exam. This is a quality assurance mechanism which 1) stops accidental alteration of the paper mid-exam, and 2) preserves the paper exactly how the student saw it for the future. This second point is very important for tasks such as GMC inspections so that it is possible to go back to papers years in the past and be assured that what is being viewed currently is what the students saw.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When a paper locks it locks all questions used on that paper so they cannot be edited. Papers cannot be unlocked. If you wish to use roughly the same paper again in the future but alter a few of the questions then it is possible to make a copy of the paper and copy the questions too. It is then possible to edit these copied questions while the originals remain locked.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=65\" target=\"_top\">Copying Papers</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=161\" target=\"_top\">Question Locking</a></li>\r\n</ul>',' &nbsp; Summative assessment papers lock immediately after the start time/date of the exam. This is a quality assurance mechanism which 1) stops accidental alteration of the paper mid-exam, and 2) preserves the paper exactly how the student saw it for the future. This second point is very important for tasks such as GMC inspections so that it is possible to go back to papers years in the past and be assured that what is being viewed currently is what the students saw. &nbsp; When a paper locks it locks all questions used on that paper so they cannot be edited. Papers cannot be unlocked. If you wish to use roughly the same paper again in the future but alter a few of the questions then it is possible to make a copy of the paper and copy the questions too. It is then possible to edit these copied questions while the originals remain locked. &nbsp; See also: Copying Papers Question Locking ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(191,'Getting Started/with Formative Quizzes','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">A formative quiz is a self assessment quiz that students can use to assess their knowledge. For new students in particular, it also allows them to become familiar with the different question types that Rogo supports. Formative quizzes are of most use to students when both the question types and level of difficulty match the summative paper. The use of effective feedback enables Formative papers to contribute to student learning.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Details of how to make a new paper are on the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=41\">\'Making a new Paper\' </a>page. Help pages giving details of each of the different question types supported by Rogo can be found under questions. The paper Properties as seen in the screenshot below include the URL for the paper. Students are given this URL to run the self assessment quiz.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> If you want the paper to be available over a number of years, set the Session to N/A (under the Security options).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/formative quiz.png\" alt=\"formative quiz.png\" width=\"751\" height=\"560\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">You can access details of student use of a Formative quiz using the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=30\">Class Totals</a> report.</div>','A formative quiz is a self assessment quiz that students can use to assess their knowledge. For new students in particular, it also allows them to become familiar with the different question types that Rogo supports. Formative quizzes are of most use to students when both the question types and level of difficulty match the summative paper. The use of effective feedback enables Formative papers to contribute to student learning. &nbsp; Details of how to make a new paper are on the \'Making a new Paper\' page. Help pages giving details of each of the different question types supported by Rogo can be found under questions. The paper Properties as seen in the screenshot below include the URL for the paper. Students are given this URL to run the self assessment quiz. &nbsp; Note: If you want the paper to be available over a number of years, set the Session to N/A (under the Security options). &nbsp; &nbsp; You can access details of student use of a Formative quiz using the Class Totals report.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(192,'Getting Started/with Summative Exams','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Summative assessments are any exams or test where the marks are used to determine final course/module or degree grades.&nbsp;&nbsp;They can only be taken by students during the time allocated to that exam and the papers are not accessible to students at any other time.&nbsp;To increase security, papers&nbsp;are also&nbsp;assigned to the relevant module and&nbsp;restricted to the&nbsp;labs booked for the exam.&nbsp;Once a summative&nbsp;exam&nbsp;has run,&nbsp;the paper and&nbsp;all questions that it links to are locked and cannot be amended.&nbsp; This ensures that the questions in the bank accurately match the results of the exam.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Details of the full process of creating and running summative exams can be found in the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=152\">\'Summative Assessment Lifecycle\' </a>help page.&nbsp;&nbsp; There are also details of the different roles&nbsp;involved in the running of exams on the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=176\">\'Summative Role\'</a> help page.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Summative papers in the initial stages are&nbsp;created in the same way as Formative quizzes, details of how to make a new paper are on the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=41\">\'Making a new Paper\' </a>page.&nbsp;Help pages giving details of each of the different question types supported by Rogo can be found under questions.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Summative assessments are any exams or test where the marks are used to determine final course/module or degree grades.&nbsp;&nbsp;They can only be taken by students during the time allocated to that exam and the papers are not accessible to students at any other time.&nbsp;To increase security, papers&nbsp;are also&nbsp;assigned to the relevant module and&nbsp;restricted to the&nbsp;labs booked for the exam.&nbsp;Once a summative&nbsp;exam&nbsp;has run,&nbsp;the paper and&nbsp;all questions that it links to are locked and cannot be amended.&nbsp; This ensures that the questions in the bank accurately match the results of the exam. &nbsp; Details of the full process of creating and running summative exams can be found in the \'Summative Assessment Lifecycle\' help page.&nbsp;&nbsp; There are also details of the different roles&nbsp;involved in the running of exams on the \'Summative Role\' help page. &nbsp; Summative papers in the initial stages are&nbsp;created in the same way as Formative quizzes, details of how to make a new paper are on the \'Making a new Paper\' page.&nbsp;Help pages giving details of each of the different question types supported by Rogo can be found under questions. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(193,'Getting Started/with Surveys','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Surveys are frequently created to obtain student feedback after completion of a module.&nbsp;Quantitative and Qualitative data can be captured and then analysed using Rogo. For more information see the following links:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=3\">About Surveys</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=150\">Quantitative reports</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=34\">Qualitative reports</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Surveys are frequently created to obtain student feedback after completion of a module.&nbsp;Quantitative and Qualitative data can be captured and then analysed using Rogo. For more information see the following links: &nbsp; About Surveys Quantitative reports Qualitative reports ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(195,'Advice on/Selecting Question Types','<script type=\"text/javascript\">// <![CDATA[\r\nfunction callExamplePaper() {\r\nparent.opener.parent.location.href=\'https://rogo.nottingham.ac.uk/paper/details.php?paperID=2181\';\r\nparent.close();\r\n}\r\n// ]]></script>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The table below shows the different question types that can be used in Rogo. You can see how these questions were created by looking at the \'<a onclick=\"callExamplePaper()\" href=\"#\">Question type example paper</a>\'.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px currentColor; border-collapse: collapse;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Area question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The area question type is used when the student is required to trace around a particular part of an image.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=305\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Area\'</span></a>&nbsp;help page.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">&nbsp;<img src=\"images/area_help_3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"364\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Calculation question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The calculation question type is used when the student is required to give a numerical answer that requires the use of a formula. The question will randomly generate figures for variables that you have set.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=68\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Calculation\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/calculation.jpg\" alt=\"calculation.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"132\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Dichotomous question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The Dichotomous question type is used when a lead in question is followed by a number of stems. There is a choice of giving the stems \'Yes/No\' or \'True/False\' options. Questions with only one Yes/No or True/False stem should be created using the \'Multiple Choice\' question type.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=13\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Dichotomous\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/dichotomous.jpg\" alt=\"dichotomous.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"241\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Extended Matching question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>This question type can be used to cover different patients that present with the same problem but under investigation show differences which lead to a different diagnosis. There is one set of available options that can be selected from for each stem of the question.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note:</strong> There can be more than one correct answer for each stem.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=14\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Extended Matching\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/extended matching.jpg\" alt=\"extended matching.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"422\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Fill-in-the-Blank question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>This question type shows a piece of text with blanks that the students must complete. Questions can either be set to ask students to type the correct answer or select from a drop down list. Selecting from a drop down list avoids the possibility of students introducing spelling mistakes but does act as a prompt as the correct answer is being selected from a list.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>If students are being asked to type the correct answer you can set the question to accept acronyms and US spellings where appropriate.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=16\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Fill-in-the-Blank\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/fill in the blank.jpg\" alt=\"fill in the blank.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"408\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Flash question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>If you want to create a custom question type you can create a suitable SWF Flash file and then use the Flash question type to include it in Rogo.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=22\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Flash\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/flash.jpg\" alt=\"flash.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"334\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Image Hotspot question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The Image Hotpot question type is used where the student\'s ability to identify features on an image is required.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=17\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Image Hotspot\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/image hotspot.jpg\" alt=\"image hotspot.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"255\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Labelling question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>This is used when you want students to name highlighted areas of a graphic. Spaces for labels identify areas of interest but require the student to drag the correct label into the spaces.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=60\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Labelling\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/labelling.jpg\" alt=\"labelling.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"291\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Likert Scale question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>These are often used in surveys but as students need to select from a scale the data obtained from this question type allows Rogo to complete <a href=\"display_page.php?id=33\">Quantitative data analysis</a>.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=62\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Likert Scale\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/likert.jpg\" alt=\"likert.jpg\" width=\"250\" /></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Matrix question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The Matrix question is used when there are a number of items that can be matched as shown in this example.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=21\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Matrix\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/matrix.jpg\" alt=\"matrix.jpg\" width=\"277\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Multiple Choice question</strong></div>\r\n<p>The \'Multiple Choice\' question type is used when there is only 1 correct answer and between 2 and 20 options. It can be used for True/False questions where there are 2 options (True and False). If you have a question with more than 1 correct answer you should use the \'Multiple Response\' question type.</p>\r\n<p>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=18\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Multiple Choice (MCQ)\'</span></a>help page.</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/MCQ example3.jpg\" alt=\"MCQ example3.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"211\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Multiple Response question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>This question type is used when the user needs to select more than one correct option.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=19\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Multiple Response\'</span></a>help page.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/Multiple response.jpg\" alt=\"Multiple response.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"519\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Ranking question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>This question type is used when there are items that can be put in an order such as the frequency of occurance as shown in the example opposite.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=20\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Ranking\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/ranking.jpg\" alt=\"ranking.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"180\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Textbox question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Textbox questions are mainly used in Surveys but can be used in exam papers. Rogo is not able to mark Textbox questions but does store the data captured which can then be manually marked.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=61\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Textbox\'</span></a> help page.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/textbox.jpg\" alt=\"textbox.jpg\" width=\"450\" height=\"121\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>True/False question</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>This question type is used when the user needs to select either True or False.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>For more information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=19\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\">\'Multiple Response\'</span></a>help page.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center; border: #6b6f7a 1px solid;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/true false for Question types page.png\" alt=\"true false for Question types page.png\" width=\"246\" height=\"95\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','// The table below shows the different question types that can be used in Rogo. You can see how these questions were created by looking at the \'Question type example paper\'.&nbsp;   Area question &nbsp; The area question type is used when the student is required to trace around a particular part of an image. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Area\'&nbsp;help page.  &nbsp;  Calculation question &nbsp; The calculation question type is used when the student is required to give a numerical answer that requires the use of a formula. The question will randomly generate figures for variables that you have set. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Calculation\' help page.    Dichotomous question &nbsp; The Dichotomous question type is used when a lead in question is followed by a number of stems. There is a choice of giving the stems \'Yes/No\' or \'True/False\' options. Questions with only one Yes/No or True/False stem should be created using the \'Multiple Choice\' question type. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Dichotomous\' help page.   Extended Matching question &nbsp; This question type can be used to cover different patients that present with the same problem but under investigation show differences which lead to a different diagnosis. There is one set of available options that can be selected from for each stem of the question. &nbsp; Note: There can be more than one correct answer for each stem. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Extended Matching\' help page.    Fill-in-the-Blank question &nbsp; This question type shows a piece of text with blanks that the students must complete. Questions can either be set to ask students to type the correct answer or select from a drop down list. Selecting from a drop down list avoids the possibility of students introducing spelling mistakes but does act as a prompt as the correct answer is being selected from a list. &nbsp; If students are being asked to type the correct answer you can set the question to accept acronyms and US spellings where appropriate. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Fill-in-the-Blank\' help page.    Flash question &nbsp; If you want to create a custom question type you can create a suitable SWF Flash file and then use the Flash question type to include it in Rogo. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Flash\' help page.    Image Hotspot question &nbsp; The Image Hotpot question type is used where the student\'s ability to identify features on an image is required. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Image Hotspot\' help page.   Labelling question &nbsp; This is used when you want students to name highlighted areas of a graphic. Spaces for labels identify areas of interest but require the student to drag the correct label into the spaces. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Labelling\' help page.    Likert Scale question &nbsp; These are often used in surveys but as students need to select from a scale the data obtained from this question type allows Rogo to complete Quantitative data analysis. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Likert Scale\' help page.     Matrix question &nbsp; The Matrix question is used when there are a number of items that can be matched as shown in this example. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Matrix\' help page.    Multiple Choice question The \'Multiple Choice\' question type is used when there is only 1 correct answer and between 2 and 20 options. It can be used for True/False questions where there are 2 options (True and False). If you have a question with more than 1 correct answer you should use the \'Multiple Response\' question type. For more information see the \'Multiple Choice (MCQ)\'help page. &nbsp;   Multiple Response question &nbsp; This question type is used when the user needs to select more than one correct option. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Multiple Response\'help page. &nbsp;   Ranking question &nbsp; This question type is used when there are items that can be put in an order such as the frequency of occurance as shown in the example opposite. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Ranking\' help page.   Textbox question &nbsp; Textbox questions are mainly used in Surveys but can be used in exam papers. Rogo is not able to mark Textbox questions but does store the data captured which can then be manually marked. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Textbox\' help page.   True/False question &nbsp; This question type is used when the user needs to select either True or False. &nbsp; For more information see the \'Multiple Response\'help page. &nbsp;   ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(303,'Administrative Tools/LTI Keys','<h2>Initial Configuration</h2>\r\n<p>LTI Keys are used as a mechanism for establishing trust between LTI compatible systems. Often the terms tool consumer and tool provider are used. The common scenario would be for the consumer to be a VLE like Moodle or Sakai and the tool provider would be Rogo.</p>\r\n<p>For the two systems to communicate a <strong>key</strong> and a <strong>secret</strong> must be set up at both ends. This initial setup should only need to be done once. For details on how to set up LTI in your tool consumer please refer to the online help as appropriate for the system you are integrating. The launch URL to be entered in the tool consumer is: <strong>$local_server/LTI/</strong></p>\r\n<p>On the Rogo side of things select \'Administrative Tools\' from the homepage (as SysAdmin) and then select \'LTI Keys\'. Now click \'Add new LTI Key\' and enter a descriptive name for the LTI key and then enter a key and secret. This must match the key and secret entered into the LTI tool consumer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/lti_key_secret.png\" alt=\"lti_key_secret.png\" width=\"630\" height=\"198\" /></p>','Initial Configuration LTI Keys are used as a mechanism for establishing trust between LTI compatible systems. Often the terms tool consumer and tool provider are used. The common scenario would be for the consumer to be a VLE like Moodle or Sakai and the tool provider would be Rogo. For the two systems to communicate a key and a secret must be set up at both ends. This initial setup should only need to be done once. For details on how to set up LTI in your tool consumer please refer to the online help as appropriate for the system you are integrating. The launch URL to be entered in the tool consumer is: $local_server/LTI/ On the Rogo side of things select \'Administrative Tools\' from the homepage (as SysAdmin) and then select \'LTI Keys\'. Now click \'Add new LTI Key\' and enter a descriptive name for the LTI key and then enter a key and secret. This must match the key and secret entered into the LTI tool consumer. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Admin',NULL),(292,'Papers/Peer Review','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A Peer Review paper allows students to complete reviews of their peers contributions to group work. Papers consist of a number of Likert Scale questions, typically&nbsp;with custom scales. The image&nbsp;below shows a completed&nbsp;review by&nbsp;two students&nbsp;for Mr Testerc.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/review form.png\" alt=\"review form.png\" width=\"762\" height=\"471\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A Review Summary report can be selected to show the overall marks&nbsp;as a mean or percentage, see example below:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/mean report.png\" alt=\"mean report.png\" width=\"871\" height=\"199\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','A Peer Review paper allows students to complete reviews of their peers contributions to group work. Papers consist of a number of Likert Scale questions, typically&nbsp;with custom scales. The image&nbsp;below shows a completed&nbsp;review by&nbsp;two students&nbsp;for Mr Testerc.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A Review Summary report can be selected to show the overall marks&nbsp;as a mean or percentage, see example below: &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(196,'Advice on/Teamworking','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Assigning papers and Questions to Teams allows each member of the team to edit them as required. This avoids relying on one person to make changes and problems encountered when a paper or question owner is unavailable.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Any team member can add new members to the team. The screenshot below shows that there are&nbsp;5 current team members for the selected module (1.). If one of these members clicks on the \'Edit\' link above the members list, a new window listing all staff users will be displayed and a new member/members can then be selected (2.). Clicking \'OK\' button&nbsp; (3.) confirms the choice.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Teamwork3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"579\" height=\"370\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>For more information about working in teams see the following help pages:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=81\">About Teams</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Assigning papers and Questions to Teams allows each member of the team to edit them as required. This avoids relying on one person to make changes and problems encountered when a paper or question owner is unavailable. &nbsp; Any team member can add new members to the team. The screenshot below shows that there are&nbsp;5 current team members for the selected module (1.). If one of these members clicks on the \'Edit\' link above the members list, a new window listing all staff users will be displayed and a new member/members can then be selected (2.). Clicking \'OK\' button&nbsp; (3.) confirms the choice. &nbsp; &nbsp; For more information about working in teams see the following help pages: About Teams ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(197,'Advice on/Keywords','<h2>Personal Keywords</h2>\r\n<div>Each user can create their own list of keywords which can be assigned to questions. Personal Keywords are managed from the homepage under \'My Personal Keywords\'.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Team Keywords</h2>\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Team keywords can be created so that all members of the module team can use the same keywords. Team (module)&nbsp;keywords are managed from the relevant module folder.</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Using keywords when creating questions can help with finding questions at a later date. The screenshot below shows a Team Keyword and three Personal Keywords. This list of keywords appears for every question that a user creates and can be added to or updated.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/keywords in question.png\" alt=\"keywords in question.png\" width=\"917\" height=\"557\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Importing and Exporting</h2>\r\n<div>You can import and export personal and team&nbsp;(module)&nbsp;keyword lists allowing the same keywords to be used in different modules or by different people in their personal keyword list.</div>','Personal Keywords Each user can create their own list of keywords which can be assigned to questions. Personal Keywords are managed from the homepage under \'My Personal Keywords\'. &nbsp; Team Keywords Team keywords can be created so that all members of the module team can use the same keywords. Team (module)&nbsp;keywords are managed from the relevant module folder. &nbsp; Using keywords when creating questions can help with finding questions at a later date. The screenshot below shows a Team Keyword and three Personal Keywords. This list of keywords appears for every question that a user creates and can be added to or updated. &nbsp; &nbsp; Importing and Exporting You can import and export personal and team&nbsp;(module)&nbsp;keyword lists allowing the same keywords to be used in different modules or by different people in their personal keyword list.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(198,'Advice on/Quality Assurance','<h2>Peer Review</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When a summative paper has been created, questions are reviewed by peers to identify basic errors and also to check that it fits the curriculum. See the following help page for information on how this works: <a href=\"display_page.php?id=158\">Internal Peer review</a></div>\r\n<h2>External Examiners</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once the Peer Review has taken place, external examiners are asked to review the questions in a paper. The external examiners are from other institutions and have a wider view of the subject covered in a given question. See the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=159\">\'External Examiners\' </a>help page for further details.</div>\r\n<h2>Track Changes</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Details of changes made to a question after the Peer and External Examiner reviews are recorded by Rogo and can be viewed from the question editor. The screenshot below shows the details that are recorded.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/quality assurance changes.png\" alt=\"quality assurance changes.png\" width=\"1068\" height=\"369\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Paper/Question Locking</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once a summative exam has run, the paper and all questions that it links to are locked and cannot be amended. This ensures that the questions in the bank accurately match the results of the exam.</div>\r\n<h2>Question Correction</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When analysing the results of an exam you may find that an unexpected number of students have been marked as incorrectly answering a particular question. Although questions are locked after a summative exam has run, if the correct answer for a question has been set incorrectly it is possible to change this post exam. The answer for the question can be changed in the question editor, clicking the \'Correct\' button then allows Rogo to recalculate the student marks. Please note: it is <strong>not</strong> possible to change any other parts of the question and it is also not possible to correct \'Labelling\' and \'Fill-in-the-Blank\' questions. For further information see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=121\">\'Correcting Mistakes\' </a>help page.</p>\r\n<h2>Question Exclusion</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If after analysing the results of an exam it is decided that a question has not effectively assessed student knowledge it is possible to exclude it from the results. For further details look at the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=129\">\'Excluding Questions Post Exam\' </a>help page.</p>','Peer Review When a summative paper has been created, questions are reviewed by peers to identify basic errors and also to check that it fits the curriculum. See the following help page for information on how this works: Internal Peer review External Examiners Once the Peer Review has taken place, external examiners are asked to review the questions in a paper. The external examiners are from other institutions and have a wider view of the subject covered in a given question. See the \'External Examiners\' help page for further details. Track Changes Details of changes made to a question after the Peer and External Examiner reviews are recorded by Rogo and can be viewed from the question editor. The screenshot below shows the details that are recorded. &nbsp; Paper/Question Locking Once a summative exam has run, the paper and all questions that it links to are locked and cannot be amended. This ensures that the questions in the bank accurately match the results of the exam. Question Correction When analysing the results of an exam you may find that an unexpected number of students have been marked as incorrectly answering a particular question. Although questions are locked after a summative exam has run, if the correct answer for a question has been set incorrectly it is possible to change this post exam. The answer for the question can be changed in the question editor, clicking the \'Correct\' button then allows Rogo to recalculate the student marks. Please note: it is not possible to change any other parts of the question and it is also not possible to correct \'Labelling\' and \'Fill-in-the-Blank\' questions. For further information see the \'Correcting Mistakes\' help page. Question Exclusion If after analysing the results of an exam it is decided that a question has not effectively assessed student knowledge it is possible to exclude it from the results. For further details look at the \'Excluding Questions Post Exam\' help page.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(199,'Advice on/Security','<h2>Importance</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo holds large quantities of highly important data which must be kept safe at all times. Data includes student usernames/passwords and importantly answers and marks to high-stakes summative exams. Results from such exams determine the awarding of degrees and other qualifications which have important career ramifications.</p>\r\n<h2>Staff Regulations</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Staff passwords must <strong>not</strong> be shared. Additional staff accounts can be created&nbsp;if required.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The results of one student must <strong>never</strong> be discussed with another student.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Where possible as much work should be done within Rogo For example, analysis, question exclusion, etc rather than export to Excel. It is very easy to lose data exported from the Rogo server if a laptop or pen drive is stolen.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Data Protection Breaches</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Information Commissioner\'s Office (ICO) announced in a 12 January 2010 release that new powers designed to fine organizations responsible for security breaches are likely to come into effect on 6 April 2010. From that date forward, fines of up to <strong>&pound;500,000</strong> can be imposed on organizations for what are considered serious breaches of the UK\'s Data Protection Act 1998.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For the fine to be levied, \"the Information Commissioner must be satisfied that there has been a serious breach that was likely to cause damage or distress and it was either deliberate or negligent and the organisation failed to take reasonable steps to prevent it.\"</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><a href=\"display_page.php?id=200\">Data Protection</a> - details what personal data is held by Rogo.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','Importance Rogo holds large quantities of highly important data which must be kept safe at all times. Data includes student usernames/passwords and importantly answers and marks to high-stakes summative exams. Results from such exams determine the awarding of degrees and other qualifications which have important career ramifications. Staff Regulations  Staff passwords must not be shared. Additional staff accounts can be created&nbsp;if required.  The results of one student must never be discussed with another student.  Where possible as much work should be done within Rogo For example, analysis, question exclusion, etc rather than export to Excel. It is very easy to lose data exported from the Rogo server if a laptop or pen drive is stolen.  Data Protection Breaches The Information Commissioner\'s Office (ICO) announced in a 12 January 2010 release that new powers designed to fine organizations responsible for security breaches are likely to come into effect on 6 April 2010. From that date forward, fines of up to &pound;500,000 can be imposed on organizations for what are considered serious breaches of the UK\'s Data Protection Act 1998. For the fine to be levied, \"the Information Commissioner must be satisfied that there has been a serious breach that was likely to cause damage or distress and it was either deliberate or negligent and the organisation failed to take reasonable steps to prevent it.\" See also:  Data Protection - details what personal data is held by Rogo. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(282,'Administrative Tools/Schools','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Selecting \'Schools\' from the \'Administrative Tools\'&nbsp;screen gives you an option <span style=\"color: #000000;\">of creating, editing or deleting a school</span>. A list of schools is shown below with additional information on the Faculty it is part of and number of modules set up. If there are no modules for a school it displays&nbsp;in grey.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Admin schools v2.png\" alt=\"Admin schools v2.png\" width=\"690\" height=\"233\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Selecting \'Schools\' from the \'Administrative Tools\'&nbsp;screen gives you an option of creating, editing or deleting a school. A list of schools is shown below with additional information on the Faculty it is part of and number of modules set up. If there are no modules for a school it displays&nbsp;in grey. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(200,'Data Protection','<h2>Right of Subject Access</h2>\r\n<p>The Data Protection Act provides that upon making a request in writing (which includes transmission by electronic means) and upon paying the appropriate fee to the University, an individual is entitled to be told by the University whether they, or someone else on the University\'s behalf, is processing that individuals\' personal data, and if so, to be given a description of:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>the personal data;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>the purposes for which they are being processed; and</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>those to whom they are or may be disclosed.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The University will not comply with a request where it has already complied with an identical or similar request by the same individual unless a reasonable interval has elapsed between compliance with the previous request and the making of the current request</p>\r\n<h2>Under the terms of the Act, you have to provide the University with the following before the subject access request can be processed:</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Your request in writing (which includes transmission by electronic means)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>The information you require (which has to be sufficient to enable the University to locate the data which are sought).</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>A&nbsp;fee of &pound;10 is payable to cover administration costs.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>You should note that, by the terms of the Act, the University has to consider its duty of confidentiality to any other individual involved. This may involve obtaining the consent of other individuals to disclose the data. You will be informed if consent has not been given. You are also required to provide proof of your identity sufficient to satisfy the University before it will release any data. You will receive a response to your request within 40 days of receipt of a completed subject access request form, accompanying fee and proof of identification.</p>\r\n<h2>Rogo data</h2>\r\n<p>The table below shows the database table structure for information recorded for each user sitting an assessment or survey in Rogo. One database record is written per user per question so a single user may have as many as 150 records stored for a single examination paper. Data is recorded and stored for all paper types: formative, progress tests, summative exams and surveys.</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">id</td>\r\n<td>System administration only.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">username</td>\r\n<td>Username of the currently log in user. This can be cross referenced with the personal data (see below) to establish title, last name and email address of the user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">started</td>\r\n<td>The date/time when an assessment or survey was started by the current user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">q_paper</td>\r\n<td>The ID of the assessment/survey.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">q_id</td>\r\n<td>The numeric ID of the current question.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">mark</td>\r\n<td>The mark awarded to the user for the current question (not applicable to surveys).</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">totalpos</td>\r\n<td>The total possible marks available for the current question (not applicable to surveys).</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">user answer</td>\r\n<td>The answer provided by the user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">duration</td>\r\n<td>The duration, measured in seconds, that the user spent on the current screen.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">screen</td>\r\n<td>The number of the screen.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">ip address</td>\r\n<td>The IP address of the computer at which the assessment/survey was sat.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Personal data</h2>\r\n<p>The table below shows the database table structure for information stored for each user regarding authentication details. This data is used to verify that the user (staff or student) has a right to access Rogo and once given access which particular functions they are allowed to use within the system.</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">username</td>\r\n<td>The username of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">password</td>\r\n<td>The password of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">title</td>\r\n<td>The title (Mr, Mrs, Ms, etc) of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">initials</td>\r\n<td>The initials of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">forenames</td>\r\n<td>The forenames of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">last name</td>\r\n<td>The last name (family name) of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">degree programme</td>\r\n<td>The degree program (A100, A101, A300, etc) a user is registered for.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">year</td>\r\n<td>The year of study a user is registered for.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">roles</td>\r\n<td>The roles assigned to a user (usually \'Staff\' or \'Student\').</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">email address</td>\r\n<td>The email address of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">modules</td>\r\n<td>A list of all the modules the user is registered on.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Right of Subject Access\r\nThe Data Protection Act provides that upon making a request in writing (which includes transmission by electronic means) and upon paying the appropriate fee to the University, an individual is entitled to be told by the University whether they, or someone else on the University\'s behalf, is processing that individuals\' personal data, and if so, to be given a description of:\r\n\r\n\r\nthe personal data;\r\n\r\n\r\nthe purposes for which they are being processed; and\r\n\r\n\r\nthose to whom they are or may be disclosed.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe University will not comply with a request where it has already complied with an identical or similar request by the same individual unless a reasonable interval has elapsed between compliance with the previous request and the making of the current request\r\nUnder the terms of the Act, you have to provide the University with the following before the subject access request can be processed:\r\n\r\n\r\nYour request in writing (which includes transmission by electronic means)\r\n\r\n\r\nThe information you require (which has to be sufficient to enable the University to locate the data which are sought).\r\n\r\n\r\nA&nbsp;fee of &pound;10 is payable to cover administration costs.\r\n\r\n\r\nYou should note that, by the terms of the Act, the University has to consider its duty of confidentiality to any other individual involved. This may involve obtaining the consent of other individuals to disclose the data. You will be informed if consent has not been given. You are also required to provide proof of your identity sufficient to satisfy the University before it will release any data. You will receive a response to your request within 40 days of receipt of a completed subject access request form, accompanying fee and proof of identification.\r\nRogo data\r\nThe table below shows the database table structure for information recorded for each user sitting an assessment or survey in Rogo. One database record is written per user per question so a single user may have as many as 150 records stored for a single examination paper. Data is recorded and stored for all paper types: formative, progress tests, summative exams and surveys.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nid\r\nSystem administration only.\r\n\r\n\r\nusername\r\nUsername of the currently log in user. This can be cross referenced with the personal data (see below) to establish title, last name and email address of the user.\r\n\r\n\r\nstarted\r\nThe date/time when an assessment or survey was started by the current user.\r\n\r\n\r\nq_paper\r\nThe ID of the assessment/survey.\r\n\r\n\r\nq_id\r\nThe numeric ID of the current question.\r\n\r\n\r\nmark\r\nThe mark awarded to the user for the current question (not applicable to surveys).\r\n\r\n\r\ntotalpos\r\nThe total possible marks available for the current question (not applicable to surveys).\r\n\r\n\r\nuser answer\r\nThe answer provided by the user.\r\n\r\n\r\nduration\r\nThe duration, measured in seconds, that the user spent on the current screen.\r\n\r\n\r\nscreen\r\nThe number of the screen.\r\n\r\n\r\nip address\r\nThe IP address of the computer at which the assessment/survey was sat.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nPersonal data\r\nThe table below shows the database table structure for information stored for each user regarding authentication details. This data is used to verify that the user (staff or student) has a right to access Rogo and once given access which particular functions they are allowed to use within the system.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nusername\r\nThe username of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\npassword\r\nThe password of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\ntitle\r\nThe title (Mr, Mrs, Ms, etc) of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\ninitials\r\nThe initials of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\nforenames\r\nThe forenames of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\nlast name\r\nThe last name (family name) of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\ndegree programme\r\nThe degree program (A100, A101, A300, etc) a user is registered for.\r\n\r\n\r\nyear\r\nThe year of study a user is registered for.\r\n\r\n\r\nroles\r\nThe roles assigned to a user (usually \'Staff\' or \'Student\').\r\n\r\n\r\nemail address\r\nThe email address of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\nmodules\r\nA list of all the modules the user is registered on.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(249,'Summative Exams/Setup','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are a number of things that must be setup for an online Rogo Summative exam to run smoothly:</div>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Book a room(s) with sufficient time to setup, run and clear away after the exam. Booking the room 1 hour before the exam and 1 hour after is ideal but 30 minutes either side is the minimum. The time of the exam needs to include time for students requiring extra time and an additional 15 minutes in case of technical problems.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Set the Duration field to show how long the exam is.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ensure that Date and Time are set correctly in the paper properties. Again consider the time that the paper is available needs to include the extra time as noted above.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Select the Lab(s) that the exam will run in to ensure that the exam can be run in that Lab(s). Exams cannot be run outside of the booked room(s).</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Book invigilator support for the exam.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div><strong>Additional Note:</strong> If a lack of lab availability means that you have to run the exam across 2 sessions, ensure that the paper availability time covers both sessions.</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/problem.png\" alt=\"problem.png\" width=\"866\" height=\"614\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>See also <a href=\"display_page.php?id=152\">Summative Assessment Lifecycle</a></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','There are a number of things that must be setup for an online Rogo Summative exam to run smoothly:  Book a room(s) with sufficient time to setup, run and clear away after the exam. Booking the room 1 hour before the exam and 1 hour after is ideal but 30 minutes either side is the minimum. The time of the exam needs to include time for students requiring extra time and an additional 15 minutes in case of technical problems.  Set the Duration field to show how long the exam is.  Ensure that Date and Time are set correctly in the paper properties. Again consider the time that the paper is available needs to include the extra time as noted above.  Select the Lab(s) that the exam will run in to ensure that the exam can be run in that Lab(s). Exams cannot be run outside of the booked room(s).  Book invigilator support for the exam.  Additional Note: If a lack of lab availability means that you have to run the exam across 2 sessions, ensure that the paper availability time covers both sessions. &nbsp; See also Summative Assessment Lifecycle &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(201,'Advice on/Students with Special Needs','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is possible to make certain accommodations within Rogo to assist students with dyslexia and other conditions. Accommodations that can be made include changes to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Font typeface</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Font size</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Foreground text colour</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Background colour</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Awarding additional exam time</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Any changes much first be approved by the Disability Policy Advisory Unit (DPAU). Standard procedure is that the DPAU would then contact the Exams Office and suggest a number of changes which would assist the student concerned. School Examination Officers are then given details of the requirements.&nbsp;&nbsp;Changes are made to the student profile and the student is asked to check any visual changes by accessing any formative quiz in Rogo.</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=12\">Accessibility</a></li>\r\n</ul>','It is possible to make certain accommodations within Rogo to assist students with dyslexia and other conditions. Accommodations that can be made include changes to:  Font typeface  Font size  Foreground text colour  Background colour  Awarding additional exam time  Any changes much first be approved by the Disability Policy Advisory Unit (DPAU). Standard procedure is that the DPAU would then contact the Exams Office and suggest a number of changes which would assist the student concerned. School Examination Officers are then given details of the requirements.&nbsp;&nbsp;Changes are made to the student profile and the student is asked to check any visual changes by accessing any formative quiz in Rogo. See also: Accessibility ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(204,'Read Only Mode','<div>Read only mode is activated when you try and&nbsp;open a question which&nbsp;is already being edited by another member of staff - this is a safety feature.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/read_only1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"482\" height=\"171\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>You will be able to view the question (read only) but the \'Save Changes\' button at the bottom will be disabled.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/read_only2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"748\" height=\"442\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Read only mode is activated when you try and&nbsp;open a question which&nbsp;is already being edited by another member of staff - this is a safety feature. &nbsp; &nbsp; You will be able to view the question (read only) but the \'Save Changes\' button at the bottom will be disabled.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(205,'Advice on/Bloom\'s Taxonomy','<div>Bloom\'s Taxonomy is a classification of learning objectives (Bloom, <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span>1956) involving knowledge and development of technical skills. There are 6 categories which can be thought of as levels of difficulty where one must be mastered before moving to the next one. Considering how a question in Rogo relates to Bloom\'s taxonomy can help with assessing the level of difficulty of a question and the cognitive processes that a student must complete to answer the question. The table below gives details of each of the 6 categories which are ordered in level of difficulty with the simplest behaviour first.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>There is an option to select the Bloom\'s Taxonomy level in the question editor and questions can be searched for by level.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/table_header_background.gif\'); border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: white; font-weight: bold;\">Category and Key Words</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/table_header_background.gif\'); border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: white; font-weight: bold;\">Example question</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-top: 10px; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><strong style=\"color: #f27000;\">Knowledge:</strong> Recall data or information.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Key Words:</strong> defines, describes, identifies, knows, labels, lists, matches, names, outlines, recalls, recognizes, reproduces, selects, states.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/knowledge example v2.png\" alt=\"knowledge example v2.png\" width=\"450\" height=\"207\" /></div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-top: 10px; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><strong><span style=\"color: #f27000;\">Comprehension</span>:</strong> Understand the meaning, translation, interpolation, and interpretation of instructions and problems. State a problem in one\'s own words.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Key Words:</strong> comprehends, converts, defends, distinguishes, estimates, explains, extends, generalizes, gives Examples, infers, interprets, paraphrases, predicts, rewrites, summarizes, translates.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/comprehension example.png\" alt=\"comprehension example.png\" width=\"450\" height=\"814\" /></div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-top: 10px; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div>\r\n<div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div>\r\n<div><strong><span style=\"color: #f27000;\">Application</span>:</strong> Use a concept in a new situation or unprompted use of an abstraction. Applies what was learned in the classroom into novel situations in the work place.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Key Words:</strong> applies, changes, computes, constructs, demonstrates, discovers, manipulates, modifies, operates, predicts, prepares, produces, relates, shows, solves, uses.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/application example.png\" alt=\"application example.png\" width=\"450\" height=\"137\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-top: 10px; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Analysis:</strong> </span>Separates material or concepts into component parts so that its organizational structure may be understood. Distinguishes between facts and inferences.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Key Words:</strong> analyzes, breaks down, compares, contrasts,diagrams, deconstructs, differentiates, discriminates, distinguishes, identifies, illustrates, infers, outlines, relates, selects, separates.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/analysis.png\" alt=\"analysis.png\" width=\"450\" height=\"287\" /></div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"padding-top: 10px; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #f27000;\"><strong>Synthesis:</strong> </span>Builds a structure or pattern from diverse elements. Put parts together to form a whole, with emphasis on creating a new meaning or structure.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Key Words:</strong> categorizes, combines, compiles, composes, creates, devises, designs, explains, generates, modifies, organizes, plans, rearranges, reconstructs, relates, reorganizes, revises, rewrites, summarizes, tells, writes.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div>No examples in Rogo?</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-top: 10px; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><strong><span style=\"color: #f27000;\">Evaluation:</span></strong> Make judgments about the value of ideas or materials.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Key Words:</strong> appraises, compares, concludes, contrasts, criticizes, critiques, defends, describes, discriminates, evaluates, explains, interprets, justifies, relates, summarizes, supports.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/evaluation example.png\" alt=\"evaluation example.png\" width=\"450\" height=\"465\" /></div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>Bloom, B. S. Engelhart, M. D. Furst, E. J. Hill W. H. and Krathwohl, D. R. (1956) <em>Taxonomy of Educational Objectives, The Classification of Educational Goals. Handbook 1: Cognitive Domain, </em>New York, Longmans</p>\r\n</div>','Bloom\'s Taxonomy is a classification of learning objectives (Bloom, &nbsp;1956) involving knowledge and development of technical skills. There are 6 categories which can be thought of as levels of difficulty where one must be mastered before moving to the next one. Considering how a question in Rogo relates to Bloom\'s taxonomy can help with assessing the level of difficulty of a question and the cognitive processes that a student must complete to answer the question. The table below gives details of each of the 6 categories which are ordered in level of difficulty with the simplest behaviour first. &nbsp; There is an option to select the Bloom\'s Taxonomy level in the question editor and questions can be searched for by level. &nbsp;   Category and Key Words  Example question   Knowledge: Recall data or information. &nbsp; Key Words: defines, describes, identifies, knows, labels, lists, matches, names, outlines, recalls, recognizes, reproduces, selects, states. &nbsp; &nbsp;    Comprehension: Understand the meaning, translation, interpolation, and interpretation of instructions and problems. State a problem in one\'s own words. &nbsp; Key Words: comprehends, converts, defends, distinguishes, estimates, explains, extends, generalizes, gives Examples, infers, interprets, paraphrases, predicts, rewrites, summarizes, translates.    &nbsp; &nbsp; Application: Use a concept in a new situation or unprompted use of an abstraction. Applies what was learned in the classroom into novel situations in the work place. &nbsp; Key Words: applies, changes, computes, constructs, demonstrates, discovers, manipulates, modifies, operates, predicts, prepares, produces, relates, shows, solves, uses. &nbsp;  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;   Analysis: Separates material or concepts into component parts so that its organizational structure may be understood. Distinguishes between facts and inferences. &nbsp; Key Words: analyzes, breaks down, compares, contrasts,diagrams, deconstructs, differentiates, discriminates, distinguishes, identifies, illustrates, infers, outlines, relates, selects, separates.    Synthesis: Builds a structure or pattern from diverse elements. Put parts together to form a whole, with emphasis on creating a new meaning or structure. &nbsp; Key Words: categorizes, combines, compiles, composes, creates, devises, designs, explains, generates, modifies, organizes, plans, rearranges, reconstructs, relates, reorganizes, revises, rewrites, summarizes, tells, writes. &nbsp;  No examples in Rogo?   Evaluation: Make judgments about the value of ideas or materials. &nbsp; Key Words: appraises, compares, concludes, contrasts, criticizes, critiques, defends, describes, discriminates, evaluates, explains, interprets, justifies, relates, summarizes, supports.     &nbsp; Bloom, B. S. Engelhart, M. D. Furst, E. J. Hill W. H. and Krathwohl, D. R. (1956) Taxonomy of Educational Objectives, The Classification of Educational Goals. Handbook 1: Cognitive Domain, New York, Longmans ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(288,'Marking/Marking Method','<h1>General marking features</h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Where questions have a number of parts that can be marked independently the Marking Method can be set to mark either by question or by option. The question types that is relevant to are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Dichotomous</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Extended Matching</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Fill-in-the-Blank</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Image Hotspot</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Labelling</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Matrix</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Multiple Response</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Ranking</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/marking method.png\" alt=\"marking method.png\" width=\"686\" height=\"101\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Question specific Marking Methods</h1>\r\n<h2>Ranking</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Ranking question type has two additional Marking Methods:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Allow partial Marks</strong> - Partial marks are awarded where options have been selected one&nbsp;place away from the correct place, e.g. 2nd rather than 3rd</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Bonus Mark</strong> - A bonus mark is awarded when every option is in the correct place.</p>\r\n<h2>Calculation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The \'Allow partial Marks\' marking method allows the question writer to set the number of marks given for answers that are within a selected tolerance of the correct answer. This marking method is applied to all questions but if no tolerance is set for partial marks then these&nbsp;will not be&nbsp;allocated.</p>','General marking features Where questions have a number of parts that can be marked independently the Marking Method can be set to mark either by question or by option. The question types that is relevant to are: Dichotomous Extended Matching Fill-in-the-Blank Image Hotspot Labelling Matrix Multiple Response Ranking &nbsp; &nbsp; Question specific Marking Methods Ranking The Ranking question type has two additional Marking Methods: Allow partial Marks - Partial marks are awarded where options have been selected one&nbsp;place away from the correct place, e.g. 2nd rather than 3rd Bonus Mark - A bonus mark is awarded when every option is in the correct place. Calculation The \'Allow partial Marks\' marking method allows the question writer to set the number of marks given for answers that are within a selected tolerance of the correct answer. This marking method is applied to all questions but if no tolerance is set for partial marks then these&nbsp;will not be&nbsp;allocated.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(206,'Mapping/Longitudinal Objectives','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\" align=\"justify\">It is not possible to cover all objectives in one paper but over a few years it should be possible for all objectives to have been covered at least once. A report on Mapped objectives can be viewed over&nbsp;the years that the paper has been run&nbsp;to allow you to quickly see when objectives have been assessed.</div>\r\n<div align=\"justify\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\" align=\"justify\">To view this report, open a summative exam and select \'Mapped Objectives\' from the \'Paper Tasks\' pane. Selecting \'Longitudinal\' will display a screen as shown below:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/longitudinal objectives.png\" alt=\"longitudinal objectives.png\" width=\"800\" height=\"536\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\" align=\"justify\">Filled areas with a question number show that they have been mapped to the question(s) noted. Clicking on a question number will launch a preview of the question. If there is no fill or a question number for an objective it means that the objective has not been mapped for the selected paper. Where there is a hash fill, the objective did not exist for that year (see the 2007/08 column).</div>','It is not possible to cover all objectives in one paper but over a few years it should be possible for all objectives to have been covered at least once. A report on Mapped objectives can be viewed over&nbsp;the years that the paper has been run&nbsp;to allow you to quickly see when objectives have been assessed. &nbsp; To view this report, open a summative exam and select \'Mapped Objectives\' from the \'Paper Tasks\' pane. Selecting \'Longitudinal\' will display a screen as shown below: &nbsp; &nbsp; Filled areas with a question number show that they have been mapped to the question(s) noted. Clicking on a question number will launch a preview of the question. If there is no fill or a question number for an objective it means that the objective has not been mapped for the selected paper. Where there is a hash fill, the objective did not exist for that year (see the 2007/08 column).','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(207,'Copyright','<div>[ <a href=\"#introduction\">Introduction</a> | <a href=\"#is_copyrighted\">What is Copyrighted?</a> | <a href=\"#isnt_copyrighted\">What isn&rsquo;t Copyrighted?</a> | <a href=\"#assessments\">Assessments</a> | <a href=\"#assessments\">Common Fallacies</a> | <a href=\"#links\">Links</a> ]<br /><br /></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"width: 100%; text-align: left;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p>Copyright is a collection of rights which are applied to any piece of original work. There is no need to apply to any regulatory body, protection is automatic. Copyright provides protection from unauthorised third party copying by a set of &lsquo;restricted acts&rsquo;. The main acts include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>copying the work</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>issuing copies of the work to the public</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>renting or lending the work to the public</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>performing, showing or playing the work to the public</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>broadcasting the work</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>including the work in a cable programme service</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>adapting or amending the work</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Areas where this is most likely to occur include lecture presentations and student handouts where book sections/chapters or diagrams and img_borders have been copied. Although it is legal to photocopy sections of a book for a class, the same material cannot be scanned or typed into a computer and made available online.</p>\r\n<h2>What is Copyrighted?</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Literary Work</strong><br />Any form of original written work is included in this literary category. Literary merit is not important but the length of the work can be. Very short phrases and words cannot be copyrighted. Although freely available to look at on the Internet it is generally acknowledged with web pages are protected by copyright. Any computer form of literature, for example, databases, emails or hypermedia systems, are protected by copyright law just as paper-based documents are.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Dramatic Work</strong><br />Works of this type include plays, dance and mime. Dramatic work is distinguished from literary work by having spoken words or described actions to perform.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Musical Work</strong><br />Musical scores (including annotations) are classified as musical work, but lyrics are covered as literary works.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Artistic Work</strong><br />Graphic works, photographs, sculptures and collages are protected regardless of artistic merit. However, works of architecture are only protected if there is artistic quality.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Sound Recording</strong><br />Every type of sound recording on any type of medium capable of reproducing the sound.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Film</strong><br />Any medium from which moving images may be reproduced. Initially this was from film strips, but now includes video cassette, CD-ROM movies and DVD disks.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Broadcasts</strong><br />Material transmitted by wireless communication (including satellite) and is lawfully receivable by members of the general public.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Cable Programmes</strong><br />Transmissions carried by way of cable.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Published Editions</strong><br />There is copyright in the typography and layout of literary, dramatic and musical works.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>If a particular work would be a valuable addition to the NLE but it is protected by copyright law, the person wishing to include the material should seek permission from the copyright holder. The copyright holder could be a single individual or it could be the publishers of a book or musical work.</p>\r\n<h2>What isn&rsquo;t Copyrighted?</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Lifespan of the Copyright</strong><br />Copyright only protects works for a limited period of time. Different types of work have different copyright lifespans:</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td bgcolor=\"#808080\">\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Anonymous</td>\r\n<td width=\"300\">70 years from first publication</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Artistic</td>\r\n<td width=\"300\">the creator&rsquo;s life plus 70 years after their death</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Computer-generated</td>\r\n<td width=\"300\">50 years from first creation</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Dramatic</td>\r\n<td width=\"300\">the creator&rsquo;s life plus 70 years after their death</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Film</td>\r\n<td width=\"300\">70 years from the death of the last to survive of: the principal director; the author of the screenplay; the author of the dialogue; or the composer of the music specially created for the film</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Literary</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"3\" width=\"200\">the creator&rsquo;s life plus 70 years after their death</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Musical</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Photographic</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr bgcolor=\"white\">\r\n<td>Sound recording</td>\r\n<td width=\"300\">50 years from first publication</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Works outwith the above time periods may be freely copied.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Your own Work</strong><br />Any original work which you create has automatic copyright protection. However, it should be noted that often the copyright of work completed by an individual as part of paid employment becomes the copyright material of the company or institution.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Individual Facts</strong><br />Individual facts such as URLs, email and physical addresses, and citations are free from copyright. However, collections of such entities as a whole can be copyrightable. For example, the copying of a whole database of email addresses would constitute a copyright infringement.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Implications for Assessments</h2>\r\n<div>S.32(3) of the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1998 states that copyright is not infringed by anything done for the purpose of setting or answering questions in an examination. Please note that this does not apply to assessment instruments that are made available online as a learning resource. As Rogo is used to create both summative and formative quiz papers materials from a source external to the University must not be included in formative quiz papers unless permission for use has been granted by the copyright owner.</div>\r\n<h2>Common Fallacies</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Copyright isn\'t serious</strong><br />Copyright is a law in many countries around the law. Breaking it can result in fines and imprisonment. In the United Kingdom the most recent version of this law is Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988 and came into force on 1 August 1989.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>There is no Copyright Statement</strong><br />Copyright is an automatic right given to the original creator of the work. It does not have to be applied for or registered in any way. The absence of any copyright notice does not negate the right.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>It is digital already</strong><br />Being digital already does not matter, if you copy it without permission you are breaking the law.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>I found it on Google</strong><br />Google is an Internet search engine which provides pointers to images, music and websites held on remote servers. Because it is providing pointers to the original materials it operates within the law. However, people copying materials from Google and using it in their own resources will be breaking copyright law if permission is not sought.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Free for use in Teaching</strong><br />Some materials, such as slide resources, state \'\'\'\'free for use in teaching\'\'\'\'. This is often assumed means that the slides can be scanned in and uploaded onto an educational Virtual Learning Environment. This is wrong, copyright for use on the Internet, whether public access or password secured, is often restricted even when the label \'\'\'\'free for use in teaching\'\'\'\' is used.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>The journal article is PDF already</strong><br />Increasing numbers of academic journals are providing their text electronically via the Internet. Many assume that because their university subscribes to the journal then they have the right to copy it and put it in their materials or on a Virtual Learning Environment. You may include a web link from the VLE to an electronic journal but copying a PDF and uploading the file into the VLE certainly breaks copyright without permission being sought.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>I asked for permission and got no rejection</strong><br />The absence of permission does not give the right to copy the material. Explicit copyright agreement must be obtained before materials are copied. It is within the rights of the copyright holder to change for the copying of materials they hold.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Links</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Download: <a href=\"http://www.ukoln.ac.uk/services/elib/papers/other/jisc-tltp/jisc.pdf\" target=\"_new\">JISC/TLTP Copyright Guidelines (.pdf)</a></div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','[ Introduction | What is Copyrighted? | What isn&rsquo;t Copyrighted? | Assessments | Common Fallacies | Links ]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIntroduction\r\nCopyright is a collection of rights which are applied to any piece of original work. There is no need to apply to any regulatory body, protection is automatic. Copyright provides protection from unauthorised third party copying by a set of &lsquo;restricted acts&rsquo;. The main acts include:\r\n\r\n\r\ncopying the work\r\n\r\n\r\nissuing copies of the work to the public\r\n\r\n\r\nrenting or lending the work to the public\r\n\r\n\r\nperforming, showing or playing the work to the public\r\n\r\n\r\nbroadcasting the work\r\n\r\n\r\nincluding the work in a cable programme service\r\n\r\n\r\nadapting or amending the work\r\n\r\n\r\nAreas where this is most likely to occur include lecture presentations and student handouts where book sections/chapters or diagrams and img_borders have been copied. Although it is legal to photocopy sections of a book for a class, the same material cannot be scanned or typed into a computer and made available online.\r\nWhat is Copyrighted?\r\n\r\n\r\nLiterary WorkAny form of original written work is included in this literary category. Literary merit is not important but the length of the work can be. Very short phrases and words cannot be copyrighted. Although freely available to look at on the Internet it is generally acknowledged with web pages are protected by copyright. Any computer form of literature, for example, databases, emails or hypermedia systems, are protected by copyright law just as paper-based documents are.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDramatic WorkWorks of this type include plays, dance and mime. Dramatic work is distinguished from literary work by having spoken words or described actions to perform.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMusical WorkMusical scores (including annotations) are classified as musical work, but lyrics are covered as literary works.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nArtistic WorkGraphic works, photographs, sculptures and collages are protected regardless of artistic merit. However, works of architecture are only protected if there is artistic quality.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSound RecordingEvery type of sound recording on any type of medium capable of reproducing the sound.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFilmAny medium from which moving images may be reproduced. Initially this was from film strips, but now includes video cassette, CD-ROM movies and DVD disks.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBroadcastsMaterial transmitted by wireless communication (including satellite) and is lawfully receivable by members of the general public.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCable ProgrammesTransmissions carried by way of cable.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPublished EditionsThere is copyright in the typography and layout of literary, dramatic and musical works.\r\n\r\n\r\nIf a particular work would be a valuable addition to the NLE but it is protected by copyright law, the person wishing to include the material should seek permission from the copyright holder. The copyright holder could be a single individual or it could be the publishers of a book or musical work.\r\nWhat isn&rsquo;t Copyrighted?\r\n\r\n\r\nLifespan of the CopyrightCopyright only protects works for a limited period of time. Different types of work have different copyright lifespans:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAnonymous\r\n70 years from first publication\r\n\r\n\r\nArtistic\r\nthe creator&rsquo;s life plus 70 years after their death\r\n\r\n\r\nComputer-generated\r\n50 years from first creation\r\n\r\n\r\nDramatic\r\nthe creator&rsquo;s life plus 70 years after their death\r\n\r\n\r\nFilm\r\n70 years from the death of the last to survive of: the principal director; the author of the screenplay; the author of the dialogue; or the composer of the music specially created for the film\r\n\r\n\r\nLiterary\r\nthe creator&rsquo;s life plus 70 years after their death\r\n\r\n\r\nMusical\r\n\r\n\r\nPhotographic\r\n\r\n\r\nSound recording\r\n50 years from first publication\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWorks outwith the above time periods may be freely copied.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nYour own WorkAny original work which you create has automatic copyright protection. However, it should be noted that often the copyright of work completed by an individual as part of paid employment becomes the copyright material of the company or institution.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIndividual FactsIndividual facts such as URLs, email and physical addresses, and citations are free from copyright. However, collections of such entities as a whole can be copyrightable. For example, the copying of a whole database of email addresses would constitute a copyright infringement.\r\n\r\n\r\nImplications for Assessments\r\nS.32(3) of the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1998 states that copyright is not infringed by anything done for the purpose of setting or answering questions in an examination. Please note that this does not apply to assessment instruments that are made available online as a learning resource. As Rogo is used to create both summative and formative quiz papers materials from a source external to the University must not be included in formative quiz papers unless permission for use has been granted by the copyright owner.\r\nCommon Fallacies\r\n\r\n\r\nCopyright isn\'t seriousCopyright is a law in many countries around the law. Breaking it can result in fines and imprisonment. In the United Kingdom the most recent version of this law is Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988 and came into force on 1 August 1989.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThere is no Copyright StatementCopyright is an automatic right given to the original creator of the work. It does not have to be applied for or registered in any way. The absence of any copyright notice does not negate the right.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIt is digital alreadyBeing digital already does not matter, if you copy it without permission you are breaking the law.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI found it on GoogleGoogle is an Internet search engine which provides pointers to images, music and websites held on remote servers. Because it is providing pointers to the original materials it operates within the law. However, people copying materials from Google and using it in their own resources will be breaking copyright law if permission is not sought.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFree for use in TeachingSome materials, such as slide resources, state \'\'\'\'free for use in teaching\'\'\'\'. This is often assumed means that the slides can be scanned in and uploaded onto an educational Virtual Learning Environment. This is wrong, copyright for use on the Internet, whether public access or password secured, is often restricted even when the label \'\'\'\'free for use in teaching\'\'\'\' is used.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe journal article is PDF alreadyIncreasing numbers of academic journals are providing their text electronically via the Internet. Many assume that because their university subscribes to the journal then they have the right to copy it and put it in their materials or on a Virtual Learning Environment. You may include a web link from the VLE to an electronic journal but copying a PDF and uploading the file into the VLE certainly breaks copyright without permission being sought.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI asked for permission and got no rejectionThe absence of permission does not give the right to copy the material. Explicit copyright agreement must be obtained before materials are copied. It is within the rights of the copyright holder to change for the copying of materials they hold.\r\n\r\n\r\nLinks\r\n\r\n\r\nDownload: JISC/TLTP Copyright Guidelines (.pdf)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(209,'Advice on/Preparing graphics','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">You can easily format graphics for use in Rogo without any specialised graphic knowledge or software. For example if you have a graphic that you want to use in a Rogo question you are likely to need to resize it and save it in a suitable file format. Both of these can easily be achieved using the standard windows graphics package, Paint.&nbsp; You can find out what size a graphic is by selecting \'Image\' then \'Attributes\'.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The graphic size can be adjusted by selecting \'Image\' then \'Stretch/Skew\' and then enter a value for the Horizontal and Vertical stretch. Please note that the percentage Stretch should be the same for both and by entering less than 100 in these boxes you can make the graphic smaller.&nbsp; In the graphic below, 60% has been entered for both the Horizontal and Vertical sizes.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/graphics%20in%20paint%202.jpg\" alt=\"graphics in paint 2.jpg\" width=\"719\" height=\"454\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The graphic can then be saved in a suitable format such as JPEG or PNG for use in Rogo,&nbsp; For more information about graphics see the <a href=\"display_page.php?id=113\">\'Formatting Images\'</a> help page.</div>','You can easily format graphics for use in Rogo without any specialised graphic knowledge or software. For example if you have a graphic that you want to use in a Rogo question you are likely to need to resize it and save it in a suitable file format. Both of these can easily be achieved using the standard windows graphics package, Paint.&nbsp; You can find out what size a graphic is by selecting \'Image\' then \'Attributes\'. &nbsp; The graphic size can be adjusted by selecting \'Image\' then \'Stretch/Skew\' and then enter a value for the Horizontal and Vertical stretch. Please note that the percentage Stretch should be the same for both and by entering less than 100 in these boxes you can make the graphic smaller.&nbsp; In the graphic below, 60% has been entered for both the Horizontal and Vertical sizes. &nbsp; &nbsp; The graphic can then be saved in a suitable format such as JPEG or PNG for use in Rogo,&nbsp; For more information about graphics see the \'Formatting Images\' help page.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(210,'Objectives/Overview','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Objectives are the \'desired outcomes\' of student learning and are set in the Medical School VLE (NLE) for the medical school or in Rogo for other schools. Assessments in Rogo are mapped to session objectives and this then allows individualised student feedback to be given post exam. You can see below that for the Medical School objectives are first set in the NLE at Module and then Session level. The session level objectives are then mapped to questions in Rogo and ultimately students are given feedback on objectives acquisition.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Alignment between the desired outcome, how we teach and how we assess is likely to achieve more effective learning.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<table style=\"text-align: center;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Medical School</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td><strong>Generic</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\">\r\n<div><br /><strong>Module Objectives </strong></div>\r\n<div>set in SATURN and copied into NLE</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" /></td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\">\r\n<div><br /><strong>Session Objectives </strong></div>\r\n<div>set in the NLE</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\">\r\n<div><br /><strong>Session Objectives </strong></div>\r\n<div>set in Rogo</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" /></td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\">\r\n<div><br /><strong>Question Mapping</strong></div>\r\n<div>set in Rogo</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\">\r\n<div><br /><strong>Question Mapping</strong></div>\r\n<div>set in Rogo</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" /></td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/life_cycle_down_arrow_blue.png\" alt=\"arrow\" width=\"9\" height=\"38\" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\">\r\n<div><br /><strong>Exam Feedback</strong></div>\r\n<div>available to students via Insight</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/life_cycle_background_blue.png\'); width: 281px; height: 84px;\">\r\n<div><br /><strong>Exam Feedback</strong></div>\r\n<div>available to students via web browser</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=181\">Feedback</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Objectives are the \'desired outcomes\' of student learning and are set in the Medical School VLE (NLE) for the medical school or in Rogo for other schools. Assessments in Rogo are mapped to session objectives and this then allows individualised student feedback to be given post exam. You can see below that for the Medical School objectives are first set in the NLE at Module and then Session level. The session level objectives are then mapped to questions in Rogo and ultimately students are given feedback on objectives acquisition.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nAlignment between the desired outcome, how we teach and how we assess is likely to achieve more effective learning.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMedical School\r\n&nbsp;\r\nGeneric\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nModule Objectives \r\nset in SATURN and copied into NLE\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSession Objectives \r\nset in the NLE\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSession Objectives \r\nset in Rogo\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nQuestion Mapping\r\nset in Rogo\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nQuestion Mapping\r\nset in Rogo\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nExam Feedback\r\navailable to students via Insight\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nExam Feedback\r\navailable to students via web browser\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSee also:\r\n\r\nFeedback\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(211,'Papers/Creating','41',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(212,'Surveys/Qualitative Reports','34',NULL,'pointer',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(213,'Patient Consent for medical images','<h2>Requirement for Consent</h2>\r\n<p>Explicit consent must be given for all resources involving patients: images, videos, etc. The only exceptions to this rule are the following categories which do not require consent:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Images taken from pathology slides</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>X-rays</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Laparoscopic images</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Images of internal organs</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Ultrasound images</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Common Fallacies</h2>\r\n<h3>Blacking out Eyes</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Many people hold the widespread misconception that if they black out the eyes of a patient it will make the image anonymous and therefore bypass the need for explicit consent. This is wrong for two reasons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Blacking out the eyes does not make images anonymous as the example below shows.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Even if the image was completely anonymous, for example a photo of a finger, it would still require explicit consent as it still does not come under any of the categories listed above for which consent is not required.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/bush.jpg\" alt=\"bush.jpg\" width=\"227\" height=\"300\" /></div>\r\n<h3>Consent for Life</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A second fallacy is once consent is given by the patient the materials can be used for ever. This is wrong! Any patient has the right, at any time, to withdraw previously given consent. In such situations the person using the material must: 1) ensure that all current material being used is withdrawn wherever it may be (Internet, logbooks, PowerPoint, etc), and 2) ensure that the material is not used again in the future. The easiest way to ensure this second point is to securely delete the material in question.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.gmc-uk.org/guidance/current/library/making_audiovisual.asp\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/url_small.gif\" alt=\"URL\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" /></a> <a href=\"http://www.gmc-uk.org/guidance/current/library/making_audiovisual.asp\">Further information from the GMC</a></p>','Requirement for Consent Explicit consent must be given for all resources involving patients: images, videos, etc. The only exceptions to this rule are the following categories which do not require consent:  Images taken from pathology slides  X-rays  Laparoscopic images  Images of internal organs  Ultrasound images  Common Fallacies Blacking out Eyes Many people hold the widespread misconception that if they black out the eyes of a patient it will make the image anonymous and therefore bypass the need for explicit consent. This is wrong for two reasons:  Blacking out the eyes does not make images anonymous as the example below shows.  Even if the image was completely anonymous, for example a photo of a finger, it would still require explicit consent as it still does not come under any of the categories listed above for which consent is not required.  Consent for Life A second fallacy is once consent is given by the patient the materials can be used for ever. This is wrong! Any patient has the right, at any time, to withdraw previously given consent. In such situations the person using the material must: 1) ensure that all current material being used is withdrawn wherever it may be (Internet, logbooks, PowerPoint, etc), and 2) ensure that the material is not used again in the future. The easiest way to ensure this second point is to securely delete the material in question. Further information from the GMC','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(286,'Administrative Tools/Courses','<p>A list of courses that are set in Rogo are shown through this option.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Courses_list.png\" alt=\"Courses_list.png\" width=\"689\" height=\"210\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','A list of courses that are set in Rogo are shown through this option. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(214,'Marking/Textbox marking','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When a Textbox question is included in a Summative exam it is necessary for the questions to be marked using the following process:</div>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Primary Marking - The paper for each student is marked individually </span></div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Secondary Marking - This is an <strong>optional</strong> stage where a proportion of students are selected for their papers to be given a secondary mark</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Finalise Marks - This final stage is used to either confirm&nbsp;the Primary marks or decide on the final mark if some students have been secondary marked</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The options for Textbox Marking can be found in the&nbsp;Reports Menu.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/textbox_marking1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"547\" height=\"432\" /></div>\r\n<div><strong>Primary Marking</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Each question is displayed with the student answer and a drop down box is used to select the mark for that question.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/primary mark.png\" alt=\"primary mark.png\" width=\"846\" height=\"244\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you need to identify responses that have not been marked you can select \'Hide already marked\' which is displayed in the top right corner of the screen.</div>\r\n<div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div>\r\n<div><strong>Secondary Marking</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is completed in 2 stages, the first being the selection of students papers that will be second marked (\'Select Papers for Remarking\' in the Analysis Menu). Once the students have been selected, \'Second Mark by Question\' is selected from the Analysis Menu.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Finalise Marks</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>* </strong><em>This stage has to be completed even when secondary marking is not required. </em></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once the primary and secondary (if required) marking has been completed, \'Finalise Marks\' is selected from the Analysis Menu and then each question must be selected and finalised individually. If there is a discrepancy greater than 1.0 between the 1st and 2nd marks, Rogo will highlight these as requiring a final mark to be selected (see Override column in the screenshot below).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/textmarking3.png\" alt=\"textmarking3.png\" width=\"813\" height=\"294\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','When a Textbox question is included in a Summative exam it is necessary for the questions to be marked using the following process:  Primary Marking - The paper for each student is marked individually  Secondary Marking - This is an optional stage where a proportion of students are selected for their papers to be given a secondary mark  Finalise Marks - This final stage is used to either confirm&nbsp;the Primary marks or decide on the final mark if some students have been secondary marked  The options for Textbox Marking can be found in the&nbsp;Reports Menu. &nbsp; Primary Marking Each question is displayed with the student answer and a drop down box is used to select the mark for that question. &nbsp; &nbsp; If you need to identify responses that have not been marked you can select \'Hide already marked\' which is displayed in the top right corner of the screen. &nbsp; Secondary Marking This is completed in 2 stages, the first being the selection of students papers that will be second marked (\'Select Papers for Remarking\' in the Analysis Menu). Once the students have been selected, \'Second Mark by Question\' is selected from the Analysis Menu. &nbsp; Finalise Marks * This stage has to be completed even when secondary marking is not required. &nbsp; Once the primary and secondary (if required) marking has been completed, \'Finalise Marks\' is selected from the Analysis Menu and then each question must be selected and finalised individually. If there is a discrepancy greater than 1.0 between the 1st and 2nd marks, Rogo will highlight these as requiring a final mark to be selected (see Override column in the screenshot below). &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(215,'Invigilators','<h2>Invigilator Screens</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Since many invigilators used are postgraduate students, a special area of Rogo has been created for these invigilators to log into. No access is given to the main Rogo staff screens, just some additional support they may require on the day.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To log in, the invigilator should start a web browser (i.e. Internet Explorer) and go to: <span style=\"color: blue; font-weight: bold;\">$local_server</span>. The log in details are: username - <strong>invigilator1</strong> and the password - <strong>blue56</strong>. All invigilators can log in with the same username and password. Once the invigilator has logged in, Rogo will look for a paper set for the current lab.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>No Paper Found</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first problem that an invigilator may encounter is no paper found for the current lab. This could be caused by the wrong lab being selected or the dates incorrectly set. The invigilator&nbsp;cannot change the properties of the paper&nbsp;but should try one of the emergency&nbsp;telephone numbers that is listed on the screen notifying the problem.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Exam Screen</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Assuming a paper has been correctly set for the right computer lab and time, a screen similar to the one below will be displayed. It contains four main types of information:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The top header bar has the name of the computer lab the current machine is in and the current time (top right). It is important that exams are not started before their scheduled start time.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">On the left hand side is the name of the exam paper scheduled for this lab together with a list of students permitted to take it. Importantly, just below the paper name, in this case \'A11CLS:May (2009/10\' is the scheduled start time.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">On the right hand side of the screen is a tasklist which the invigilator should follow before, during and after the exam.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Finally, in the bottom right corner is emergency mobile telephone numbers which can be used for serious problems where the whole student cohort is affected.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/invigilator1.png\" alt=\"invigilator1.png\" width=\"825\" height=\"644\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Recording Notes about Student Problems</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If there is an IT problem, or even a subject matter content problem, it is possible to make a record of this in the student notes. This information can then be used in exam boards where appropriate. An example use of this would be if a student\'s computer locks up and they have to be moved to another machine. The invigilator, after they have helped the student move, should go back to the workstation they are logged into and scroll down the list of candidates to find the relevant student name. Single click on the name will bring up a yellow notes window. Enter the note and then click \'Save\'. A small yellow notes icon will then be displayed next to the students name.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Clicking on \'Paper Note\' allows a note to be added for the paper which effects all students such as delay in the start of the exam. These notes are viewable by staff after the exam has been completed.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/invigilator2.png\" alt=\"invigilator2.png\" width=\"670\" height=\"234\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Solving Student Log in Problems</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If an exam candidate has problems either logging in or is not registered on the correct module then a guest account can be used. At the log in dialog box click \'Cancel\' and the following screen will appear:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/access1.png\" alt=\"access1.png\" width=\"536\" height=\"254\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Click on \'Temporary Account\' (1)&nbsp;and then the student should enter their title, surname and first name and student ID if known (2) and then click \'OK\' (3).</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/access2.png\" alt=\"access2.png\" width=\"450\" height=\"233\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">After clicking \'OK\' the system will do a search to see which user accounts are not in use. As the screenshot below shows, \'user1\' account must be in use by another student, so \'user2\' has been selected. Passwords are changed on each account every time one is allocated.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The&nbsp;temporary accounts can only be used for a single exam and the marks are re-assigned to the student by the paper owner after the exam has been completed.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/access3.png\" alt=\"access3.png\" width=\"451\" height=\"189\" /></div>','Invigilator Screens Since many invigilators used are postgraduate students, a special area of Rogo has been created for these invigilators to log into. No access is given to the main Rogo staff screens, just some additional support they may require on the day. To log in, the invigilator should start a web browser (i.e. Internet Explorer) and go to: $local_server. The log in details are: username - invigilator1 and the password - blue56. All invigilators can log in with the same username and password. Once the invigilator has logged in, Rogo will look for a paper set for the current lab. &nbsp; No Paper Found The first problem that an invigilator may encounter is no paper found for the current lab. This could be caused by the wrong lab being selected or the dates incorrectly set. The invigilator&nbsp;cannot change the properties of the paper&nbsp;but should try one of the emergency&nbsp;telephone numbers that is listed on the screen notifying the problem. &nbsp; Exam Screen Assuming a paper has been correctly set for the right computer lab and time, a screen similar to the one below will be displayed. It contains four main types of information:  The top header bar has the name of the computer lab the current machine is in and the current time (top right). It is important that exams are not started before their scheduled start time.  On the left hand side is the name of the exam paper scheduled for this lab together with a list of students permitted to take it. Importantly, just below the paper name, in this case \'A11CLS:May (2009/10\' is the scheduled start time.  On the right hand side of the screen is a tasklist which the invigilator should follow before, during and after the exam.  Finally, in the bottom right corner is emergency mobile telephone numbers which can be used for serious problems where the whole student cohort is affected.  Recording Notes about Student Problems If there is an IT problem, or even a subject matter content problem, it is possible to make a record of this in the student notes. This information can then be used in exam boards where appropriate. An example use of this would be if a student\'s computer locks up and they have to be moved to another machine. The invigilator, after they have helped the student move, should go back to the workstation they are logged into and scroll down the list of candidates to find the relevant student name. Single click on the name will bring up a yellow notes window. Enter the note and then click \'Save\'. A small yellow notes icon will then be displayed next to the students name. &nbsp; Clicking on \'Paper Note\' allows a note to be added for the paper which effects all students such as delay in the start of the exam. These notes are viewable by staff after the exam has been completed. &nbsp; Solving Student Log in Problems If an exam candidate has problems either logging in or is not registered on the correct module then a guest account can be used. At the log in dialog box click \'Cancel\' and the following screen will appear: &nbsp; &nbsp; Click on \'Temporary Account\' (1)&nbsp;and then the student should enter their title, surname and first name and student ID if known (2) and then click \'OK\' (3). After clicking \'OK\' the system will do a search to see which user accounts are not in use. As the screenshot below shows, \'user1\' account must be in use by another student, so \'user2\' has been selected. Passwords are changed on each account every time one is allocated. &nbsp; The&nbsp;temporary accounts can only be used for a single exam and the marks are re-assigned to the student by the paper owner after the exam has been completed. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(216,'Question - Types/Random Question Block','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Random question blocks can be added to accompany standard questions in a paper. The benefit of this to the student is that they can test their knowledge over a greater variety of questions. This is only available in Formative self assessment papers <strong>not</strong> Summative exam papers. Question blocks are created by selecting existing questions and then&nbsp;the Add Question(s) button as shown in the graphic below. The 3 questions shown in the&nbsp;graphic will be selected randomly when the paper runs.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/random q block select qs.png\" alt=\"random q block select qs.png\" width=\"873\" height=\"552\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Questions selected can be of different types but if they have different numbers of marks they are not included in the Frequency &amp; Discrimination (U-L) Analysis report.</div>','Random question blocks can be added to accompany standard questions in a paper. The benefit of this to the student is that they can test their knowledge over a greater variety of questions. This is only available in Formative self assessment papers not Summative exam papers. Question blocks are created by selecting existing questions and then&nbsp;the Add Question(s) button as shown in the graphic below. The 3 questions shown in the&nbsp;graphic will be selected randomly when the paper runs. &nbsp; &nbsp; Questions selected can be of different types but if they have different numbers of marks they are not included in the Frequency &amp; Discrimination (U-L) Analysis report.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(221,'Summative Exams/Late Submissions','<div><strong>Note:</strong> Late Submissions are not occasions where&nbsp;a student arrives late for an exam.&nbsp; In these situations the student would be required to end the exam&nbsp;at the same time as&nbsp;the other students.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">It might be necessary to note a late submission if the exam time set in the paper has not taken account for&nbsp;students requiring extra time. Exam invigilators take a note of any students that complete an exam later than the scheduled period by adding a note against the students details in Rogo. After the exam has been completed, students who completed the exam late are shown when a \'Class Total\' analysis is run. Clicking on the student name in the class total screen displays a \'Late Submissions\' option in the popup menu.</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/late_submissions_1.png\" alt=\"late_submissions_1.png\" width=\"929\" height=\"287\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">A new window will appear detailing which questions were submitted late and on what screens.&nbsp;The module convenor should decide whether they are going to accept or reject the late submissions and state their reasons accordingly in the \'Reason\' textbox. Clicking \'Accept\'&nbsp;will move the late answers and marks over to the appropriate log file and refresh the \'Class Totals\' report behind. \'Reject\' will simply clear the late submissions. \'Cancel\' can be used to postpone making a decision.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note</strong>: It is not possible to partially&nbsp;accept or reject late submissions. Either the circumstances surrounding late submission are acceptable or not.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/late_submissions_2.png\" alt=\"late_submissions_2.png\" width=\"620\" height=\"442\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>','Note: Late Submissions are not occasions where&nbsp;a student arrives late for an exam.&nbsp; In these situations the student would be required to end the exam&nbsp;at the same time as&nbsp;the other students. &nbsp; It might be necessary to note a late submission if the exam time set in the paper has not taken account for&nbsp;students requiring extra time. Exam invigilators take a note of any students that complete an exam later than the scheduled period by adding a note against the students details in Rogo. After the exam has been completed, students who completed the exam late are shown when a \'Class Total\' analysis is run. Clicking on the student name in the class total screen displays a \'Late Submissions\' option in the popup menu. A new window will appear detailing which questions were submitted late and on what screens.&nbsp;The module convenor should decide whether they are going to accept or reject the late submissions and state their reasons accordingly in the \'Reason\' textbox. Clicking \'Accept\'&nbsp;will move the late answers and marks over to the appropriate log file and refresh the \'Class Totals\' report behind. \'Reject\' will simply clear the late submissions. \'Cancel\' can be used to postpone making a decision. &nbsp; Note: It is not possible to partially&nbsp;accept or reject late submissions. Either the circumstances surrounding late submission are acceptable or not.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(223,'QTI/About','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\" align=\"justify\">QTI is an acronym for Question &amp; Test Interoperability and is a standard produced by the IMS Global Learning Consortium. QTI was inspired by the need for interoperability in question design, and to avoid people losing or having to re-type questions when technology changes. Developing and validating good questions is time consuming, and it\'s desirable to be able to create them in a platform and technology neutral format.</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 40%; text-align: left; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/question/\" target=\"_blank\">www.imsglobal.org/question/</a></li>\r\n</ul>','QTI is an acronym for Question &amp; Test Interoperability and is a standard produced by the IMS Global Learning Consortium. QTI was inspired by the need for interoperability in question design, and to avoid people losing or having to re-type questions when technology changes. Developing and validating good questions is time consuming, and it\'s desirable to be able to create them in a platform and technology neutral format. &nbsp; See also: www.imsglobal.org/question/ ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(224,'QTI/Import','<div>Rogo can import questions from other e-assessment systems by importing files saved in QTI format.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>This is done from inside a paper by following the process below:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Select \'QTI Import/Export from the Paper Tasks menu</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Select \'Import\'</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Click on the \'Browse...\' button and then select either a ZIP file containing the QTI XML file, graphics and other media, or a single QTI XML file</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Click on \'Import File\'</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/QTI_import.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"751\" height=\"365\" /></p>','Rogo can import questions from other e-assessment systems by importing files saved in QTI format. &nbsp; This is done from inside a paper by following the process below:  Select \'QTI Import/Export from the Paper Tasks menu  Select \'Import\'  Click on the \'Browse...\' button and then select either a ZIP file containing the QTI XML file, graphics and other media, or a single QTI XML file  Click on \'Import File\'  &nbsp;','page','2012-09-12 11:45:00',23024,'Staff',NULL),(225,'QTI/Export','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Questions from a Rogo paper can be exported for use in other assessment tools. QTI Import/Export in&nbsp;Paper Tasks contains an Export option. Selecting this from within a paper creates a zip file containing question data including graphics used within the questions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/QTI_export.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"751\" height=\"365\" /></p>','Questions from a Rogo paper can be exported for use in other assessment tools. QTI Import/Export in&nbsp;Paper Tasks contains an Export option. Selecting this from within a paper creates a zip file containing question data including graphics used within the questions.&nbsp; &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(226,'Objectives/How to Write','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"#what\">What are Learning Objectives?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#difference\">What are the difference between Aims and Objectives?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#categories\">What are the main categories of learning objectives?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#write\">How do you write aims and learning objectives?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#examples\">Examples of learning objectives verbs</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#demanding\">How can I modify learning objectives to make them more demanding?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#why\">Why do we have to use learning objectives?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#advantages\">What are the advantages of using learning objectives</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#readaround\">I want my students to \'read around the subject\'. Don\'t learning objectives narrow the range of student learning?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#individual\">We have module objectives, why do we need objectives for individual teaching sessions?</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><a name=\"what\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>What are Learning Objectives?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"what\"></a></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Learning Objectives are statements that describe what a learner will be able to do as a result of learning. They are sometimes called learning outcomes. Learning Objectives are also statements that describe what a learner will be able to do as a result of teaching. Some definitions stress that a learning objective is a sort of contract that teachers make with learners that describes what they will be able to do after learning that they could not do before, the \'added value\' of teaching. However the connection between teaching and learning is not a simple one. Just because knowledge or skills are taught does not mean that particular knowledge or skills are learned. Many factors can interfere with the achievement of objectives: the existing knowledge of the learner, the relevance or usefulness of the material presented, the skills of the teacher.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Objectives are the \'desired outcomes\' of student learning and need to be set for the course both at the module and session levels. Assessments then need to be referenced to these objectives to allow them to report on the results of the teaching. Alignment between the desired outcome, how we teach and how we assess is likely to achieve more effective teaching.</div>\r\n<p><a name=\"difference\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>What are the difference between Aims and Objectives?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"difference\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Aims are general statements concerning the overall goals, ends or intentions of teaching. Objectives are the individual stages that learners must achieve on the way in order to reach these goals. For example a teacher might have an aim that a student should be able to take blood pressure using a sphygmomanometer. However to achieve this aim a series of objectives must be met. eg to explain procedure to patient, to position cuff correctly, to inflate to correct pressure etc, etc.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A lecturer might have as an overall aim that students should understand the relationship between protein structure and function. To achieve this aim the following objectives might have to be met: describe amino acid structure, list common categories of amino acid, explain how peptide bonds are formed, describe how covalent, ionic and hydrophobic interactions create secondary and tertiary structures, etc, etc.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Aims are general, objectives are specific.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>There are more objectives than aims.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Aims are like strategy, objective are like tactics.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Aims and objectives can form hierarchical structures so that in complex curricula aims at one level might be seen as objectives at another.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"categories\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>What are the main categories of learning objectives?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"categories\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Learning objectives are aimed at the three domains of learning: knowledge, skills and attitudes. These are also termed the cognitive, psychomotor and affective domains of learning.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"write\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>How do you write aims and learning objectives?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"write\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As a teacher you will need to decide what you want your learners to be able to DO after they have learned something that you have taught. Many things can be potentially learned during a teaching episode but you will use your judgement to focus on the most important outcomes for your learners at that stage of their course. For instance if you want them to be able to take blood pressure using a sphygmomanometer after you have demonstrated the procedure that would constitute your aim. But to achieve that they will have to have attained a series of objectives on the way. Some of these objectives might include the basic knowledge behind cardiovascular physiology such as the sequence of the cardiac cycle, systole, diastole, cardiac output, stroke volume etc. etc. Further skill objectives might include communicating with patients, explaining procedures etc. Finally the skills of the procedure itself broken down into suitable steps. So the aims and objectives for one possible teaching sequence might look like the following:</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; width: 85%; background-color: #ffffee;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"6\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Aims:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The student should be able to measure blood pressure on a colleague/patient using a sphygmomanometer and a stethoscope (to an accuracy of +/- 10mm Hg).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Objectives:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">Can describe the cardiac cycle and explain the terms systole, diastole, cardiac output, stroke volume.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>Can effectively communicate instructions to patient concerning the procedure.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>Fits and inflates cuff to appropriate pressure.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>Releases pressure carefully and uses stethoscope to listen to brachial artery and Korotkow sounds.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>Deflates cuff.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">Records systolic and diastolic pressure correctly.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the case of more knowledge orientated aims and objectives imagine you are going to give a lecture with the aim of ensuring that students understand the relationship between protein structure and function and the various factors that influence enzyme reactions. Here you need to break the knowledge down into smaller components that logically build towards the final goal.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; width: 85%; background-color: #ffffee;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"6\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Aims:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">To understand the relationship between protein structure and function and the factors that influence enzyme reactions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Objectives:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">State the different categories of amino acid.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>Explain what a peptide bond is and how polypeptides are formed.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>State the four levels of protein structure and explain how the sequence of amino acids leads to the final three dimensional configuration of the protein.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>Explain how variations in pH, ion concentration and temperature influence the three dimensional configuration of a protein.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>State that an enzyme is a protein designed to catalyse a specific chemical reaction.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>State that an enzyme speeds up the rate of a chemical reaction by lowering the activation energy of the transition complex and that it does not influence the equilibrium or overall energy change of a reaction.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<div>Explain how variations in pH, ion concentration and temperature influence catalytic activity.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">Describe how enzyme activity can be regulated by other molecules.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Note that objectives do not include the word \'know\' or \'understand\'. They do include active verbs such as \'state\', \'explain\', \'outline\', \'list\' or \'describe\'. Know and understand do not specify any overt \'doing\' and although knowing and understanding underpin learning, objectives are always written using active doing verbs. They are statements of what you want your learners to do. At the end of the day being a doctor, nurse or dentist is about doing things not just knowing things.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"examples\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>Examples of learning objectives verbs</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"examples\"></a></p>\r\n<p>The following lists contains examples of verbs which describe the sorts of things you want your students to be able to do and may help you to write useful learning objectives.</p>\r\n<h3>Knowledge</h3>\r\n<table style=\"width: 600px;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>analyse</td>\r\n<td>arrange</td>\r\n<td>calculate</td>\r\n<td>circle</td>\r\n<td>cite</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>classify</td>\r\n<td>compare</td>\r\n<td>contrast</td>\r\n<td>compare</td>\r\n<td>define</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>describe</td>\r\n<td>diagram</td>\r\n<td>differentiate</td>\r\n<td>group</td>\r\n<td>identify</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>interpret</td>\r\n<td>itemize</td>\r\n<td>label</td>\r\n<td>list</td>\r\n<td>match</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>name</td>\r\n<td>outline</td>\r\n<td>plan</td>\r\n<td>record</td>\r\n<td>revise</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>select</td>\r\n<td>solve</td>\r\n<td>state</td>\r\n<td>tabulate</td>\r\n<td>give examples</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>evaluate</td>\r\n<td>recognise</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3>Skills</h3>\r\n<table style=\"width: 600px;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>adjust</td>\r\n<td>assemble</td>\r\n<td>chart</td>\r\n<td>collect</td>\r\n<td>use</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>draw</td>\r\n<td>employ</td>\r\n<td>establish</td>\r\n<td>illustrate</td>\r\n<td>imitate</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>interact</td>\r\n<td>locate</td>\r\n<td>maintain</td>\r\n<td>measure</td>\r\n<td>modify</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>operate</td>\r\n<td>organise</td>\r\n<td>rearrange</td>\r\n<td>return</td>\r\n<td>set up</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>practice</td>\r\n<td>manipulate</td>\r\n<td>master</td>\r\n<td>fit</td>\r\n<td>perform</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>demonstrate</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3>Attitudes</h3>\r\n<table style=\"width: 600px;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>accept</td>\r\n<td>adopt</td>\r\n<td>advocate</td>\r\n<td>approve</td>\r\n<td>assess</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>challenge</td>\r\n<td>characterise</td>\r\n<td>choose</td>\r\n<td>criticise</td>\r\n<td>defend</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>evaluate</td>\r\n<td>formulate</td>\r\n<td>judge</td>\r\n<td>justify</td>\r\n<td>manage</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>model</td>\r\n<td>persuade</td>\r\n<td>recommend</td>\r\n<td>resolve</td>\r\n<td>select</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>specify</td>\r\n<td>value</td>\r\n<td>re-assure</td>\r\n<td>empathise</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><a name=\"demanding\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>How can I modify learning objectives to make them more demanding?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"demanding\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Learning objectives can be made more difficult or demanding depending on the degree of understanding or levels of experience of learners. You can change the active verb to a more complex one or you can add specific conditions or limits.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For example simple objectives might be to list or state facts, formulae or definitions, essentially recalling information from memory and reproducing it. More complex objectives might ask learners to apply or use knowledge in a particular context that might not have been met before. This is more cognitively demanding and really tests whether learners have deeply understood concepts. Finally the highest levels of objectives ask learners to solve complex problems by, for example evaluating or analysing evidence or synthesizing information. To critically evaluate the causes of something involves not only a deep understanding of detailed factual information but also an ability to make complex judgments about the validity of evidence.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Conditions that could be added to objectives might include modifications to the circumstances in which they are carried out. \'Given a diagram of the inner ear correctly labels X, Y and Z\' is easier than having to draw a diagram from scratch. Similarly \'describe quantitatively\' is more demanding than just \'describe\' and \'describe quantitatively using data from published studies\' implies a familiarity with the primary literature that only the advanced student might have.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Certain objectives can be modified by the degree to which they need to be completed. Explain in detail is more complex than in outline. Measure to 95% accuracy is harder than simply measuring without any degree of accuracy given.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"why\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>Why do we have to use learning objectives?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"why\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are a number of ways of thinking about this question. The quickest answer is that all teachers in higher education have to use learning objectives. The Quality Assurance Agency (the quality control branch of the Higher Education Funding Council) specify that all taught sessions must have learning objectives. QAA observers, when conducting a subject review, use an observation protocol that includes monitoring the learning objectives of the teacher. QAA observers have the right to watch any teacher teach and can ask them what their learning objectives are.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A related view revolves around questions of quality and audit. If you don\'t know what you\'re trying to produce how can you be sure your teaching methods and techniques are working? If you have no objective standards how can you monitor your teaching effectiveness and how can you improve? Since all teachers must evaluate their teaching they must know what their output is.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From a curriculum perspective the learning objectives from each taught session should fit together coherently building towards the overall aims of each module and the whole curriculum. If learning objectives are not know for each session then it is impossible to see how the whole curriculum fits together. It becomes impossible for teachers in different phases of the curriculum to see what students have learned in other areas making managing and auditing the curriculum more difficult. In the case of the medical curriculum having many sessions without pre-defined learning objectives leads to a \'hidden\' curriculum rather than the goal of an integrated curriculum.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"advantages\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>What are the advantages of using learning objectives?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"advantages\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From an educational perspective learning objectives define learning outcomes and focus teaching. They help to clarify, organize and prioritize learning. They help students evaluate their own progress and encourage them to take responsibility for their learning.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"readaround\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>I want my students to \'read around the subject\'. Don\'t learning objectives narrow the range of student learning?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"readaround\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Medicine is such an enormous subject that some boundaries have to be placed on the learning required to become a pre-registration house officer. The General Medical Council in Tomorrow\'s Doctors specifically recommended a reduction in factual knowledge. Specific aims and learning objectives are therefore essential in defining core knowledge, skills and attitudes. Students are free to learn more if they so wish but learning objectives should define the \'bottom line\'. Individual teachers may wish that students learn more about their own favourite areas but this has to be seen in the context of the overall curriculum and has to be argued with the appropriate course co-ordinator or curriculum committee. On the other hand if it is decided that \'reading around the subject\' is a fundamental requirement of some components of the course then appropriate learning objectives can be defined for this outcome.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"individual\"></a></p>\r\n<h2>We have module objectives, why do we need objectives for individual teaching sessions?</h2>\r\n<p><a name=\"individual\"></a></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">From a curriculum perspective the learning objectives from each taught session should fit together coherently, building towards the overall aims of each module and the whole curriculum. If learning objectives are not known for each session then it is impossible to see how the whole curriculum fits together. It becomes impossible for teachers in different phases of the curriculum to see what students have learned in other areas making managing and auditing the curriculum more difficult. In the case of the medical curriculum having many sessions without pre-defined learning objectives leads to a \'hidden\' curriculum rather than the goal of an integrated curriculum.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Session objectives are mapped to assessment questions in Rogo meaning that the exams results can provide a report on the effectiveness of teaching of the objectives.</div>','\r\nWhat are Learning Objectives?\r\nWhat are the difference between Aims and Objectives?\r\nWhat are the main categories of learning objectives?\r\nHow do you write aims and learning objectives?\r\nExamples of learning objectives verbs\r\nHow can I modify learning objectives to make them more demanding?\r\nWhy do we have to use learning objectives?\r\nWhat are the advantages of using learning objectives\r\nI want my students to \'read around the subject\'. Don\'t learning objectives narrow the range of student learning?\r\nWe have module objectives, why do we need objectives for individual teaching sessions?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat are Learning Objectives?\r\n\r\nLearning Objectives are statements that describe what a learner will be able to do as a result of learning. They are sometimes called learning outcomes. Learning Objectives are also statements that describe what a learner will be able to do as a result of teaching. Some definitions stress that a learning objective is a sort of contract that teachers make with learners that describes what they will be able to do after learning that they could not do before, the \'added value\' of teaching. However the connection between teaching and learning is not a simple one. Just because knowledge or skills are taught does not mean that particular knowledge or skills are learned. Many factors can interfere with the achievement of objectives: the existing knowledge of the learner, the relevance or usefulness of the material presented, the skills of the teacher.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nObjectives are the \'desired outcomes\' of student learning and need to be set for the course both at the module and session levels. Assessments then need to be referenced to these objectives to allow them to report on the results of the teaching. Alignment between the desired outcome, how we teach and how we assess is likely to achieve more effective teaching.\r\n\r\nWhat are the difference between Aims and Objectives?\r\n\r\nAims are general statements concerning the overall goals, ends or intentions of teaching. Objectives are the individual stages that learners must achieve on the way in order to reach these goals. For example a teacher might have an aim that a student should be able to take blood pressure using a sphygmomanometer. However to achieve this aim a series of objectives must be met. eg to explain procedure to patient, to position cuff correctly, to inflate to correct pressure etc, etc.\r\nA lecturer might have as an overall aim that students should understand the relationship between protein structure and function. To achieve this aim the following objectives might have to be met: describe amino acid structure, list common categories of amino acid, explain how peptide bonds are formed, describe how covalent, ionic and hydrophobic interactions create secondary and tertiary structures, etc, etc.\r\n\r\n\r\nAims are general, objectives are specific.\r\n\r\n\r\nThere are more objectives than aims.\r\n\r\n\r\nAims are like strategy, objective are like tactics.\r\n\r\n\r\nAims and objectives can form hierarchical structures so that in complex curricula aims at one level might be seen as objectives at another.\r\n\r\nWhat are the main categories of learning objectives?\r\n\r\nLearning objectives are aimed at the three domains of learning: knowledge, skills and attitudes. These are also termed the cognitive, psychomotor and affective domains of learning.\r\n\r\nHow do you write aims and learning objectives?\r\n\r\nAs a teacher you will need to decide what you want your learners to be able to DO after they have learned something that you have taught. Many things can be potentially learned during a teaching episode but you will use your judgement to focus on the most important outcomes for your learners at that stage of their course. For instance if you want them to be able to take blood pressure using a sphygmomanometer after you have demonstrated the procedure that would constitute your aim. But to achieve that they will have to have attained a series of objectives on the way. Some of these objectives might include the basic knowledge behind cardiovascular physiology such as the sequence of the cardiac cycle, systole, diastole, cardiac output, stroke volume etc. etc. Further skill objectives might include communicating with patients, explaining procedures etc. Finally the skills of the procedure itself broken down into suitable steps. So the aims and objectives for one possible teaching sequence might look like the following:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAims:\r\nThe student should be able to measure blood pressure on a colleague/patient using a sphygmomanometer and a stethoscope (to an accuracy of +/- 10mm Hg).\r\nObjectives:\r\n\r\n\r\nCan describe the cardiac cycle and explain the terms systole, diastole, cardiac output, stroke volume.\r\n\r\n\r\nCan effectively communicate instructions to patient concerning the procedure.\r\n\r\n\r\nFits and inflates cuff to appropriate pressure.\r\n\r\n\r\nReleases pressure carefully and uses stethoscope to listen to brachial artery and Korotkow sounds.\r\n\r\n\r\nDeflates cuff.\r\n\r\n\r\nRecords systolic and diastolic pressure correctly.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn the case of more knowledge orientated aims and objectives imagine you are going to give a lecture with the aim of ensuring that students understand the relationship between protein structure and function and the various factors that influence enzyme reactions. Here you need to break the knowledge down into smaller components that logically build towards the final goal.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAims:\r\nTo understand the relationship between protein structure and function and the factors that influence enzyme reactions.\r\nObjectives:\r\n\r\n\r\nState the different categories of amino acid.\r\n\r\n\r\nExplain what a peptide bond is and how polypeptides are formed.\r\n\r\n\r\nState the four levels of protein structure and explain how the sequence of amino acids leads to the final three dimensional configuration of the protein.\r\n\r\n\r\nExplain how variations in pH, ion concentration and temperature influence the three dimensional configuration of a protein.\r\n\r\n\r\nState that an enzyme is a protein designed to catalyse a specific chemical reaction.\r\n\r\n\r\nState that an enzyme speeds up the rate of a chemical reaction by lowering the activation energy of the transition complex and that it does not influence the equilibrium or overall energy change of a reaction.\r\n\r\n\r\nExplain how variations in pH, ion concentration and temperature influence catalytic activity.\r\n\r\n\r\nDescribe how enzyme activity can be regulated by other molecules.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNote that objectives do not include the word \'know\' or \'understand\'. They do include active verbs such as \'state\', \'explain\', \'outline\', \'list\' or \'describe\'. Know and understand do not specify any overt \'doing\' and although knowing and understanding underpin learning, objectives are always written using active doing verbs. They are statements of what you want your learners to do. At the end of the day being a doctor, nurse or dentist is about doing things not just knowing things.\r\n\r\nExamples of learning objectives verbs\r\n\r\nThe following lists contains examples of verbs which describe the sorts of things you want your students to be able to do and may help you to write useful learning objectives.\r\nKnowledge\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nanalyse\r\narrange\r\ncalculate\r\ncircle\r\ncite\r\n\r\n\r\nclassify\r\ncompare\r\ncontrast\r\ncompare\r\ndefine\r\n\r\n\r\ndescribe\r\ndiagram\r\ndifferentiate\r\ngroup\r\nidentify\r\n\r\n\r\ninterpret\r\nitemize\r\nlabel\r\nlist\r\nmatch\r\n\r\n\r\nname\r\noutline\r\nplan\r\nrecord\r\nrevise\r\n\r\n\r\nselect\r\nsolve\r\nstate\r\ntabulate\r\ngive examples\r\n\r\n\r\nevaluate\r\nrecognise\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSkills\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nadjust\r\nassemble\r\nchart\r\ncollect\r\nuse\r\n\r\n\r\ndraw\r\nemploy\r\nestablish\r\nillustrate\r\nimitate\r\n\r\n\r\ninteract\r\nlocate\r\nmaintain\r\nmeasure\r\nmodify\r\n\r\n\r\noperate\r\norganise\r\nrearrange\r\nreturn\r\nset up\r\n\r\n\r\npractice\r\nmanipulate\r\nmaster\r\nfit\r\nperform\r\n\r\n\r\ndemonstrate\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAttitudes\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\naccept\r\nadopt\r\nadvocate\r\napprove\r\nassess\r\n\r\n\r\nchallenge\r\ncharacterise\r\nchoose\r\ncriticise\r\ndefend\r\n\r\n\r\nevaluate\r\nformulate\r\njudge\r\njustify\r\nmanage\r\n\r\n\r\nmodel\r\npersuade\r\nrecommend\r\nresolve\r\nselect\r\n\r\n\r\nspecify\r\nvalue\r\nre-assure\r\nempathise\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nHow can I modify learning objectives to make them more demanding?\r\n\r\nLearning objectives can be made more difficult or demanding depending on the degree of understanding or levels of experience of learners. You can change the active verb to a more complex one or you can add specific conditions or limits.\r\nFor example simple objectives might be to list or state facts, formulae or definitions, essentially recalling information from memory and reproducing it. More complex objectives might ask learners to apply or use knowledge in a particular context that might not have been met before. This is more cognitively demanding and really tests whether learners have deeply understood concepts. Finally the highest levels of objectives ask learners to solve complex problems by, for example evaluating or analysing evidence or synthesizing information. To critically evaluate the causes of something involves not only a deep understanding of detailed factual information but also an ability to make complex judgments about the validity of evidence.\r\nConditions that could be added to objectives might include modifications to the circumstances in which they are carried out. \'Given a diagram of the inner ear correctly labels X, Y and Z\' is easier than having to draw a diagram from scratch. Similarly \'describe quantitatively\' is more demanding than just \'describe\' and \'describe quantitatively using data from published studies\' implies a familiarity with the primary literature that only the advanced student might have.\r\nCertain objectives can be modified by the degree to which they need to be completed. Explain in detail is more complex than in outline. Measure to 95% accuracy is harder than simply measuring without any degree of accuracy given.\r\n\r\nWhy do we have to use learning objectives?\r\n\r\nThere are a number of ways of thinking about this question. The quickest answer is that all teachers in higher education have to use learning objectives. The Quality Assurance Agency (the quality control branch of the Higher Education Funding Council) specify that all taught sessions must have learning objectives. QAA observers, when conducting a subject review, use an observation protocol that includes monitoring the learning objectives of the teacher. QAA observers have the right to watch any teacher teach and can ask them what their learning objectives are.\r\nA related view revolves around questions of quality and audit. If you don\'t know what you\'re trying to produce how can you be sure your teaching methods and techniques are working? If you have no objective standards how can you monitor your teaching effectiveness and how can you improve? Since all teachers must evaluate their teaching they must know what their output is.\r\nFrom a curriculum perspective the learning objectives from each taught session should fit together coherently building towards the overall aims of each module and the whole curriculum. If learning objectives are not know for each session then it is impossible to see how the whole curriculum fits together. It becomes impossible for teachers in different phases of the curriculum to see what students have learned in other areas making managing and auditing the curriculum more difficult. In the case of the medical curriculum having many sessions without pre-defined learning objectives leads to a \'hidden\' curriculum rather than the goal of an integrated curriculum.\r\n\r\nWhat are the advantages of using learning objectives?\r\n\r\nFrom an educational perspective learning objectives define learning outcomes and focus teaching. They help to clarify, organize and prioritize learning. They help students evaluate their own progress and encourage them to take responsibility for their learning.\r\n\r\nI want my students to \'read around the subject\'. Don\'t learning objectives narrow the range of student learning?\r\n\r\nMedicine is such an enormous subject that some boundaries have to be placed on the learning required to become a pre-registration house officer. The General Medical Council in Tomorrow\'s Doctors specifically recommended a reduction in factual knowledge. Specific aims and learning objectives are therefore essential in defining core knowledge, skills and attitudes. Students are free to learn more if they so wish but learning objectives should define the \'bottom line\'. Individual teachers may wish that students learn more about their own favourite areas but this has to be seen in the context of the overall curriculum and has to be argued with the appropriate course co-ordinator or curriculum committee. On the other hand if it is decided that \'reading around the subject\' is a fundamental requirement of some components of the course then appropriate learning objectives can be defined for this outcome.\r\n\r\nWe have module objectives, why do we need objectives for individual teaching sessions?\r\n\r\nFrom a curriculum perspective the learning objectives from each taught session should fit together coherently, building towards the overall aims of each module and the whole curriculum. If learning objectives are not known for each session then it is impossible to see how the whole curriculum fits together. It becomes impossible for teachers in different phases of the curriculum to see what students have learned in other areas making managing and auditing the curriculum more difficult. In the case of the medical curriculum having many sessions without pre-defined learning objectives leads to a \'hidden\' curriculum rather than the goal of an integrated curriculum.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSession objectives are mapped to assessment questions in Rogo meaning that the exams results can provide a report on the effectiveness of teaching of the objectives.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(287,'Equation Editor','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Equations Editor is used to&nbsp;include equations within text fields when creating questions. It is accessed from the icon above a formatted text field (1). The equations are built by selecting required symbols, operators etc in a separate Equations Editor window (2) .</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/equation.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"767\" height=\"324\" /></p>','The Equations Editor is used to&nbsp;include equations within text fields when creating questions. It is accessed from the icon above a formatted text field (1). The equations are built by selecting required symbols, operators etc in a separate Equations Editor window (2) . ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(227,'Standards Setting/Save ratings','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When you have Standards Set a question you can save the ratings into the question bank. This means that if the question is used in a different paper, that Standards Setting will have been maintained. This includes Formative papers where the standards setting is shown as part of the student feedback</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/SS save ratings to question bank.png\" alt=\"SS save ratings to question bank.png\" width=\"700\" height=\"263\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>If you want to save the ratings, select the save ratings option before clicking on one of the save options (see graphic above).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=219\">Student Feedback.</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>','When you have Standards Set a question you can save the ratings into the question bank. This means that if the question is used in a different paper, that Standards Setting will have been maintained. This includes Formative papers where the standards setting is shown as part of the student feedback &nbsp; &nbsp; If you want to save the ratings, select the save ratings option before clicking on one of the save options (see graphic above). &nbsp; See also: Student Feedback. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(228,'Marking/Setting a Pass Mark','<p>The method used to set a pass mark has to be:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Defensible</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Credible</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Supported by body of evidence in the literature</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Feasible</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Acceptable to all stakeholders</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In terms of determining whether a score has reached the desired pass mark, Rogo supports three main methods:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>No Adjustment</li>\r\n<li>Calculate Random Mark</li>\r\n<li>Standards Setting Scaling</li>\r\n</ol>','The method used to set a pass mark has to be:  Defensible  Credible  Supported by body of evidence in the literature  Feasible  Acceptable to all stakeholders  In terms of determining whether a score has reached the desired pass mark, Rogo supports three main methods: No Adjustment Calculate Random Mark Standards Setting Scaling ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(231,'Administrative Tools/Computer Labs','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\'Computer Labs\' provide a way of securing access to papers in specific locations. They allow system administrators to build up effectively \'lists\' of IP addresses and use these as easily managed entities. This then permits academic staff to easily and conveniently select recognisable computer lab names without having to worry about the technicalities of IP addresses and such like.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Admin computer lab.png\" alt=\"Admin computer lab\" width=\"657\" height=\"205\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Once \'Computer Labs\' has been selected from the \'Administrative Tools\' screen you have 3 options to select from:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><a href=\"index.php?id=232\" target=\"_parent\"><strong>Create new lab</strong></a> - A new lab can be set in Rogo to allow summative papers to be set to run in that lab.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>View/Edit Details</strong> - A typical change is if IP addresses change in the lab</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Delete Lab</strong> - If a lab is no longer used to run summative Rogo exams it can be removed from the list of Computer Labs.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','\'Computer Labs\' provide a way of securing access to papers in specific locations. They allow system administrators to build up effectively \'lists\' of IP addresses and use these as easily managed entities. This then permits academic staff to easily and conveniently select recognisable computer lab names without having to worry about the technicalities of IP addresses and such like. &nbsp; Once \'Computer Labs\' has been selected from the \'Administrative Tools\' screen you have 3 options to select from:  Create new lab - A new lab can be set in Rogo to allow summative papers to be set to run in that lab.  View/Edit Details - A typical change is if IP addresses change in the lab  Delete Lab - If a lab is no longer used to run summative Rogo exams it can be removed from the list of Computer Labs. ','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(232,'Administrative Tools/Create new lab','<div>To create a new lab you need to add information about the lab. An example is shown below.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/admin lab.png\" alt=\"admin lab.png\" width=\"810\" height=\"391\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>IP Addresses</strong></div>\r\n<div>This is a list of the IP addess for each PC in the lab where each entry is separated with a carriage return. This can be obtained from IT support. It is very important that these are correct otherwise summative exams will not run on the PCs in the room.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Campus</strong></div>\r\n<div>Selected from a drop down list</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Building and Room Number</strong></div>\r\n<div>Manually entered</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Timetabling</strong></div>\r\n<div>Centrally timetabled (as above) or if the lab is not centrally timetabled enter name of individual that completes the timetable</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>IT Support</strong></div>\r\n<div>Consult the IT helpline if the person providing support for the lab is not known.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Plagarism</strong></div>\r\n<div>Note the method(s) used in the room to minimise plagarism. Two examples are shown in the graphic above but some labs may use physical barriers.</div>','To create a new lab you need to add information about the lab. An example is shown below. &nbsp; &nbsp; IP Addresses This is a list of the IP addess for each PC in the lab where each entry is separated with a carriage return. This can be obtained from IT support. It is very important that these are correct otherwise summative exams will not run on the PCs in the room. &nbsp; Campus Selected from a drop down list &nbsp; Building and Room Number Manually entered &nbsp; Timetabling Centrally timetabled (as above) or if the lab is not centrally timetabled enter name of individual that completes the timetable &nbsp; IT Support Consult the IT helpline if the person providing support for the lab is not known. &nbsp; Plagarism Note the method(s) used in the room to minimise plagarism. Two examples are shown in the graphic above but some labs may use physical barriers.','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(233,'Administrative Tools/Creating new Modules','<div>New modules can be set up using the following procedure:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Select \'Modules\' from the \'Administrative Tools\'&nbsp;screen then Select \'Create new Module\' from the Module Tasks menu (see graphic below).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/create module.png\" alt=\"create module.png\" width=\"853\" height=\"350\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Complete the fields shown in the graphic above with the details for the new module. <br />The Objectives API field can be left blank if objectives are not used in assessments in the school selected.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>You have now set up a new module on Rogo but as Rogo requires members of staff to be on the module team before they can access or create questions and papers for the module, you must add at least one person to the new module team. That person will then be able to add other members to the Team.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note: </strong>The&nbsp;\'Allow Self-enroll\'&nbsp;is an option to allow self enrolment&nbsp;for non module based assessments.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Once the module has been created students need to be added.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>You can then export the data by selecting \'Further Details\' and clicking on Go (see the top of the graphic above). The student list is then made available for you to open or save as a .txt file. Select \'Save Target As\' and save the .txt file. You now need to import the student list into Rogo. Return to the Administrative Tools menu and select \'User Management\'. The image below shows the screen after \'Import Students\' has been selected.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/import ARC.png\" alt=\"import ARC.png\" width=\"950\" height=\"496\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>You can now select the .txt file that you have just create containing the list of students. Although this list contains a full list of students taking the module, Rogo requires some additional information.&nbsp;Follow the same procedure as when creating the student list to create a .txt file containing the list of modules for the selected school. You can then import the module list into Rogo by selecting \'Import Modules (CSV)\' as shown in the image above.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Note:</span> If you are creating more than 1 module from the same school, create the modules, first, add students to each module and then import the Module data once as this is relevant to each of the new modules.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','New modules can be set up using the following procedure: &nbsp; Select \'Modules\' from the \'Administrative Tools\'&nbsp;screen then Select \'Create new Module\' from the Module Tasks menu (see graphic below). &nbsp; &nbsp; Complete the fields shown in the graphic above with the details for the new module. The Objectives API field can be left blank if objectives are not used in assessments in the school selected. &nbsp; You have now set up a new module on Rogo but as Rogo requires members of staff to be on the module team before they can access or create questions and papers for the module, you must add at least one person to the new module team. That person will then be able to add other members to the Team. &nbsp; Note: The&nbsp;\'Allow Self-enroll\'&nbsp;is an option to allow self enrolment&nbsp;for non module based assessments. &nbsp; Once the module has been created students need to be added. &nbsp; You can then export the data by selecting \'Further Details\' and clicking on Go (see the top of the graphic above). The student list is then made available for you to open or save as a .txt file. Select \'Save Target As\' and save the .txt file. You now need to import the student list into Rogo. Return to the Administrative Tools menu and select \'User Management\'. The image below shows the screen after \'Import Students\' has been selected. &nbsp; &nbsp; You can now select the .txt file that you have just create containing the list of students. Although this list contains a full list of students taking the module, Rogo requires some additional information.&nbsp;Follow the same procedure as when creating the student list to create a .txt file containing the list of modules for the selected school. You can then import the module list into Rogo by selecting \'Import Modules (CSV)\' as shown in the image above. &nbsp; Note: If you are creating more than 1 module from the same school, create the modules, first, add students to each module and then import the Module data once as this is relevant to each of the new modules. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(234,'Summative Exams/Problem Checklist','<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/problem.png\" alt=\"problem.png\" width=\"866\" height=\"614\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If a large number of students can all not enter a summative exam then it is likely that one or more security properties are incorrectly set. First thing to do is go into the paper and then select \'Edit properties\' (see screenshot above). Check the following settings:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Dates/Times</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Modules</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Computer Labs</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Timezone (normally \'London\') - differences are from <span class=\"st\">Coordinated Universal Time (</span>UTC), not Greenwich Mean Time.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Session (e.g. 2010/11)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Type (e.g. summative)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>',' If a large number of students can all not enter a summative exam then it is likely that one or more security properties are incorrectly set. First thing to do is go into the paper and then select \'Edit properties\' (see screenshot above). Check the following settings:  Dates/Times  Modules  Computer Labs  Timezone (normally \'London\') - differences are from Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), not Greenwich Mean Time.  Session (e.g. 2010/11)  Type (e.g. summative) ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(235,'Administrative Tools/Optimize Tables','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Optimize Table function runs the MySQL Optimize Table command to reclaim unused space and defragment the data files in the database. This speeds up the performance of Rogo and is generally used before the main exam periods (beginning of January and May). All tables in the database are selected by default but can be deselected if necessary.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/admin_optimize_tables.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"469\" height=\"267\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','The Optimize Table function runs the MySQL Optimize Table command to reclaim unused space and defragment the data files in the database. This speeds up the performance of Rogo and is generally used before the main exam periods (beginning of January and May). All tables in the database are selected by default but can be deselected if necessary. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(236,'Administrative Tools/Clear Orphan Media','<div>This is used to remove any media files such as images or sound files that are no longer used.&nbsp;&nbsp;This&nbsp;occurs&nbsp;when the&nbsp;files&nbsp; have been removed from a question or the question has been deleted.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note:</strong> Files that are very new are not deleted as they may be part of a question that is currently being created.</div>','This is used to remove any media files such as images or sound files that are no longer used.&nbsp;&nbsp;This&nbsp;occurs&nbsp;when the&nbsp;files&nbsp; have been removed from a question or the question has been deleted.&nbsp; &nbsp; Note: Files that are very new are not deleted as they may be part of a question that is currently being created.','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(237,'Administrative Tools/Create new Course','<div><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Courses (qualification such as Degrees, Diplomas, etc) act as organisational units for collections of modules. Selecting \'courses\' from the \'Administrative Tools\'&nbsp;screen gives you an option of creating, editing or deleting a course. The screenshot below shows the details of the create&nbsp;new&nbsp;course&nbsp;form. The person requesting the inclusion of the&nbsp;course&nbsp;will need to provide this information to a system administrator user.</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/create course.png\" alt=\"create course.png\" width=\"750\" height=\"199\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Courses (qualification such as Degrees, Diplomas, etc) act as organisational units for collections of modules. Selecting \'courses\' from the \'Administrative Tools\'&nbsp;screen gives you an option of creating, editing or deleting a course. The screenshot below shows the details of the create&nbsp;new&nbsp;course&nbsp;form. The person requesting the inclusion of the&nbsp;course&nbsp;will need to provide this information to a system administrator user. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(239,'Administrative Tools/Clear Old Logs','<p>This removes logs for Formative papers and Progress&nbsp;tests for students with \'graduated\' or \'left\' status. Passwords are cleared and these students will no longer have access to Rogo.</p>','This removes logs for Formative papers and Progress&nbsp;tests for students with \'graduated\' or \'left\' status. Passwords are cleared and these students will no longer have access to Rogo.','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(240,'Administrative Tools/System Information','<div>This shows details of:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>the database tables</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>the MySQL status</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>server information</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>client computer</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>server partitions</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Things to note</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Details of the client computer is useful as it includes the IP address. This is needed if you need to set up an individual PC as a Lab. This may be required if a student needs to sit an exam on a PC that is not located in one of the labs that are set for use during exams.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>When looking at the Partitions, the first one in the list is the root and is the most important as this is where Rogo is located.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/System_information2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"836\" height=\"672\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','This shows details of:  the database tables  the MySQL status  server information  client computer  server partitions  &nbsp; Things to note Details of the client computer is useful as it includes the IP address. This is needed if you need to set up an individual PC as a Lab. This may be required if a student needs to sit an exam on a PC that is not located in one of the labs that are set for use during exams. &nbsp; When looking at the Partitions, the first one in the list is the root and is the most important as this is where Rogo is located. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(242,'Administrative Tools/Calendar','<div>The calendar shows details of all summative exams and OSCE stations running through Rogo. It does not show formative quizes, progress test and surveys. Each exam shown on the calendar has a link to the paper and links to the computer labs that have been selected to run the exam.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/calendar.jpg\" alt=\"calendar.jpg\" width=\"881\" height=\"432\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','The calendar shows details of all summative exams and OSCE stations running through Rogo. It does not show formative quizes, progress test and surveys. Each exam shown on the calendar has a link to the paper and links to the computer labs that have been selected to run the exam. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(243,'Administrative Tools/Clear Guest Users','<div>Students who are unable to access an summative exam paper can be set up as a Guest User with a Guest Account. After the exam has taken place the student results are matched to their official account and the Guest Account is cleared (see <a href=\"display_page.php?id=185\">Temporary Accounts</a>). If a Guest Account has been set up outside of an exam, the Clear Guest Users function can be used to clear all details and the guest account made available for future use.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"images/clear_guest_users.png\" alt=\"clear_guest_users.png\" width=\"719\" height=\"225\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Students who are unable to access an summative exam paper can be set up as a Guest User with a Guest Account. After the exam has taken place the student results are matched to their official account and the Guest Account is cleared (see Temporary Accounts). If a Guest Account has been set up outside of an exam, the Clear Guest Users function can be used to clear all details and the guest account made available for future use. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(245,'Administrative Tools/User Management','<div>User Management allows you to search for existing&nbsp;users and to create new user accounts. You can see from the graphic below that there are different categories of users including External Examiners and Invigilators. The option for \'Inactive Staff\' is typically used for people that have an account but may not use if for a period of time such as 1 year. Inactive staff can be set as Active when required.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>New User Accounts can also be created and the Type/Course drop down field allows you to select the job type e.g. Academic Lecturer, External Examiner etc. or if a student account is being created their course is selected. LDAP details can be retrieved by entering the username or surname of the person that requires an account.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Note:</strong> Rogo automatically generates a password but people with an LDAP account can access Rogo using their LDAP Password. Although there is an option to send an email to welcome the user, this is rarely used.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/admin create user.png\" alt=\"admin create user.png\" width=\"753\" height=\"705\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','User Management allows you to search for existing&nbsp;users and to create new user accounts. You can see from the graphic below that there are different categories of users including External Examiners and Invigilators. The option for \'Inactive Staff\' is typically used for people that have an account but may not use if for a period of time such as 1 year. Inactive staff can be set as Active when required. &nbsp; New User Accounts can also be created and the Type/Course drop down field allows you to select the job type e.g. Academic Lecturer, External Examiner etc. or if a student account is being created their course is selected. LDAP details can be retrieved by entering the username or surname of the person that requires an account. &nbsp; Note: Rogo automatically generates a password but people with an LDAP account can access Rogo using their LDAP Password. Although there is an option to send an email to welcome the user, this is rarely used. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'SysAdmin',NULL),(246,'Advice on/Running Summative Exams','<h2>Room booking and set up</h2>\r\n<div>Suitable room(s) to be booked ideally with an additional 2 hours before and 1 hour after the time that the exam is due to run.&nbsp; This allows the following:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Set up of the room to ensure that login instruction slips, blank paper for rough working and physical barriers or polarised filters are in place for each workstation</span></div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Candidate entry to the room 15 minutes before the scheduled exam start time to&nbsp;ensure that they are able&nbsp;to login to&nbsp;a suitable&nbsp;workstation</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>The room is available for candidates requiring extra time</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>The room is available if the exam period is extended due to technical problems</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>For exams that will run <strong>during</strong> the centrally scheduled examination periods, the Academic Services Division should be consulted and they will book rooms suitable for e-assessment. For exams taking place <strong>outside</strong> of these periods the school/academic member of staff will need to book the rooms.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Running the exam</h2>\r\n<div>Candidates are not allowed to leave exam in the following circumstances:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #484848;\">When the exam lasts 1 hour or less</span></div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>When there are 2 sessions of the exam when all candidates cannot complete the exam at the same time due to lack of room availability (corralling)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #b6b6b6; color: #b6b6b6; height: 1px; border: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px;\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><a href=\"display_page.php?id=183\">Summative Exams/Starting</a></div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','Room booking and set up Suitable room(s) to be booked ideally with an additional 2 hours before and 1 hour after the time that the exam is due to run.&nbsp; This allows the following:  Set up of the room to ensure that login instruction slips, blank paper for rough working and physical barriers or polarised filters are in place for each workstation  Candidate entry to the room 15 minutes before the scheduled exam start time to&nbsp;ensure that they are able&nbsp;to login to&nbsp;a suitable&nbsp;workstation  The room is available for candidates requiring extra time  The room is available if the exam period is extended due to technical problems  For exams that will run during the centrally scheduled examination periods, the Academic Services Division should be consulted and they will book rooms suitable for e-assessment. For exams taking place outside of these periods the school/academic member of staff will need to book the rooms.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; Running the exam Candidates are not allowed to leave exam in the following circumstances:  When the exam lasts 1 hour or less  When there are 2 sessions of the exam when all candidates cannot complete the exam at the same time due to lack of room availability (corralling)  See also:  Summative Exams/Starting ','page','2012-09-20 11:48:39',1217,'Staff',NULL),(247,'Reports/Learning Objective Analysis','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This report shows the percentage acquisition of each objective assessed within a paper for the full cohort.&nbsp; This shows if there are any objectives that a large proportion of students failed to acquire.&nbsp; Individual <a href=\"index.php?id=145\" target=\"_top\">student feedback </a>is also available to each student.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/Learn_obj_analysis.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"707\" height=\"545\" /></div>','This report shows the percentage acquisition of each objective assessed within a paper for the full cohort.&nbsp; This shows if there are any objectives that a large proportion of students failed to acquire.&nbsp; Individual student feedback is also available to each student. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(250,'Mathematical formulas using LaTex','<div>See also <a href=\"display_page.php?id=287\">Equation Editor</a></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Mathematical formulas can be displayed in questions and options using LaTeX, a document markup language. An example is shown in the graphic below.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/LaTeX example.png\" alt=\"LaTeX example.png\" width=\"432\" height=\"297\" /></div>\r\n<div>You can see how the first option in the above question was set up in Rogo in the graphic below:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/formula.png\" alt=\"formula.png\" width=\"727\" height=\"239\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;[tex]......[/tex] is used to show that the content between the brackets is using the LaTeX language.</div>','See also Equation Editor\r\n&nbsp;\r\nMathematical formulas can be displayed in questions and options using LaTeX, a document markup language. An example is shown in the graphic below.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou can see how the first option in the above question was set up in Rogo in the graphic below:\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;[tex]......[/tex] is used to show that the content between the brackets is using the LaTeX language.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(252,'Question - Types/Script Concordance Test (SCT)','<h2>Background</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Script Concordance Test (SCT) question type assesses reasoning skills in clinical situations, specifically those with uncertain scenarios. The table below shows how this question type differs from the Multiple Choice type.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; width: 720px; border-collapse: collapse;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/table_header_background.gif\'); border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: white; font-weight: bold;\">Multiple Choice</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"background-image: url(\'images/table_header_background.gif\'); border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div style=\"color: white; font-weight: bold;\">Script Concordance</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-top: 10px; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The clinical vignette provides well defined and accurate data to select a solution.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div>The clinical vignette is ambiguous, provides vague data aimed at decision making in an uncertainty context. There is more than 1 acceptable answer.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-top: 10px; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Assesses the level of knowledge.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<div>Assesses medical reasoning and <strong>cannot</strong> be answered by memorising pieces of knowledge.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Use in Rogo</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">An example of this type of question as used in Rogo is shown below. The Vignette shows some unclear data and an initial hypothesis is shown below. This is then followed by the New more detailed information. The question then asks whether the new information supports the hypothesis.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/script con student view.png\" alt=\"script con student view.png\" width=\"842\" height=\"362\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The graphic below shows that each of the 5 options has an \'Experts\' field. This is used to show how many experts would select that option. As noted before, there is no correct answer so experts may select a different option. The number of experts that should be asked for their opinion is between 10-20.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Recording experts opinion</h2>\r\n<div>Expert&nbsp;opinions for&nbsp;SCT questions are recorded by following this procedure:</div>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>URL shown at the top of the Reviewers tab is copied into a web browser</li>\r\n<li>All Experts use the following logon: <strong>Username</strong> = sctreviewer, <strong>Password</strong> = password set on the security tab of the paper</li>\r\n<li>After logon the Expert is asked to enter their details</li>\r\n<li>Expert gives their answer to each SCT question</li>\r\n<li>Once all Experts have made their selections, you can view a report by selecting Reports, SCT Responses/Reasons (under Reviews)</li>\r\n<li>Click on Save Results to Question Bank</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Once this has been completed the number of experts that have selected each option,&nbsp;display in the question as shown below.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/script con edit window.png\" alt=\"script con edit window.png\" width=\"940\" height=\"937\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The option that has been selected by the largest number of experts will give 1 mark when selected by a student. The other options give a lower mark depending on the number of experts that have selected it. For example if there are 17 experts and&nbsp;8 select option&nbsp;4 this will be worth 1 mark, if&nbsp;1 expert selects an option, it will be worth 1/8 (0.13) and so on. The graphic below shows 3 possible marks for the question.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/script con marking.png\" alt=\"script con marking.png\" width=\"820\" height=\"198\" />&nbsp;</div>','Background The Script Concordance Test (SCT) question type assesses reasoning skills in clinical situations, specifically those with uncertain scenarios. The table below shows how this question type differs from the Multiple Choice type. &nbsp;   Multiple Choice  Script Concordance   &nbsp; The clinical vignette provides well defined and accurate data to select a solution. &nbsp; &nbsp;  The clinical vignette is ambiguous, provides vague data aimed at decision making in an uncertainty context. There is more than 1 acceptable answer.   &nbsp; Assesses the level of knowledge. &nbsp;  Assesses medical reasoning and cannot be answered by memorising pieces of knowledge.   &nbsp; Use in Rogo An example of this type of question as used in Rogo is shown below. The Vignette shows some unclear data and an initial hypothesis is shown below. This is then followed by the New more detailed information. The question then asks whether the new information supports the hypothesis. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The graphic below shows that each of the 5 options has an \'Experts\' field. This is used to show how many experts would select that option. As noted before, there is no correct answer so experts may select a different option. The number of experts that should be asked for their opinion is between 10-20. &nbsp; Recording experts opinion Expert&nbsp;opinions for&nbsp;SCT questions are recorded by following this procedure: URL shown at the top of the Reviewers tab is copied into a web browser All Experts use the following logon: Username = sctreviewer, Password = password set on the security tab of the paper After logon the Expert is asked to enter their details Expert gives their answer to each SCT question Once all Experts have made their selections, you can view a report by selecting Reports, SCT Responses/Reasons (under Reviews) Click on Save Results to Question Bank &nbsp; Once this has been completed the number of experts that have selected each option,&nbsp;display in the question as shown below. &nbsp; &nbsp; Marking The option that has been selected by the largest number of experts will give 1 mark when selected by a student. The other options give a lower mark depending on the number of experts that have selected it. For example if there are 17 experts and&nbsp;8 select option&nbsp;4 this will be worth 1 mark, if&nbsp;1 expert selects an option, it will be worth 1/8 (0.13) and so on. The graphic below shows 3 possible marks for the question. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(253,'Papers/Progress Tests','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Only one set of student&nbsp; results are stored for a progress test but access is available for the same test&nbsp;if they&nbsp;are unable to complete it&nbsp;on the first attempt. A further access will let them complete the paper but will only be classed as one attempt.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When all students have completed a progress test, the marks can be emailed to them. This is done by selecting \'Class Totals\' from the \'Analysis Menu\'.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/progress_test_email_marks_rogo.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"819\" height=\"509\" /></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Clicking on the \'Email Class Marks\' button allows you to send an email to the class with a suitable message. The \'Tag\' drop down list allows you to add variables to the message as shown in the graphic above. As this only gives students the marks, the paper can be changed from \'Progress Test\' to \'Formative\'. This will allow students to go back into the paper and view marks and feedback for each question.</div>','Only one set of student&nbsp; results are stored for a progress test but access is available for the same test&nbsp;if they&nbsp;are unable to complete it&nbsp;on the first attempt. A further access will let them complete the paper but will only be classed as one attempt. &nbsp; When all students have completed a progress test, the marks can be emailed to them. This is done by selecting \'Class Totals\' from the \'Analysis Menu\'. &nbsp; Clicking on the \'Email Class Marks\' button allows you to send an email to the class with a suitable message. The \'Tag\' drop down list allows you to add variables to the message as shown in the graphic above. As this only gives students the marks, the paper can be changed from \'Progress Test\' to \'Formative\'. This will allow students to go back into the paper and view marks and feedback for each question.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(254,'Administrative Tools/Clear Training','<div>The \'Training\' module has been created to give a place for participants on Rogo training workshops to work during the workshop. They are added to the \'Train\' module team and the access remains until the \'Clear Training\' tool (1. in screenshot below)&nbsp;is used which removes all papers and team members from the module. The module is then ready to be used in the next workshop.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/Clear_Training.PNG\" alt=\"Clear_Training.PNG\" width=\"757\" height=\"421\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','The \'Training\' module has been created to give a place for participants on Rogo training workshops to work during the workshop. They are added to the \'Train\' module team and the access remains until the \'Clear Training\' tool (1. in screenshot below)&nbsp;is used which removes all papers and team members from the module. The module is then ready to be used in the next workshop.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(255,'OSCE Station/Viewing results','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">As with other paper types, results can be viewed through \'Class Totals\' in the \'Analysis Menu\'. The marks are shown for each student with the corresponding classification (see below).</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/OSCE1.png\" alt=\"OSCE1.png\" width=\"891\" height=\"370\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">You can also view the details of the results by clicking once on a student name then selecting \'OSCE Mark Sheet\' (see example below).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/OSCE2.png\" alt=\"OSCE2.png\" width=\"734\" height=\"530\" /></div>','As with other paper types, results can be viewed through \'Class Totals\' in the \'Analysis Menu\'. The marks are shown for each student with the corresponding classification (see below). &nbsp; &nbsp; You can also view the details of the results by clicking once on a student name then selecting \'OSCE Mark Sheet\' (see example below). &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(257,'OSCE Station/Electronic OSCE','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo supports the use of Netbooks and other small format devices to electronically record marks while a student is performing an examination within an OSCE. To do this an OSCE paper must first have been created and a number of likert questions added (either \'0, 1, 2\' or \'fail, borderling, pass\'). The paper should be scheduled for the correct day using the date settings in the \'Edit Properties\' option from the sidebar menu.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">On the day of the assessment each exminer should go to <strong><a href=\"../../osce/\">$local_server/osce/</a></strong>. This will bring up a list of all the students in the module that the OSCE station has been assigned to, as shown below. Initially all names will be displayed in bold, like Outlook this is to signify that these student have been unmarked (or unread).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/osce1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"891\" height=\"370\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">When a student arrives at the OSCE station the examiner should ask for their name and locate them on the alphabetic list. Clicking on their name will bring up a fresh marking sheet with their photo on (see below).</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/osce4.png\" alt=\"osce4.png\" width=\"862\" height=\"854\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the above example a 0, 1, 2 type likert scale has been used for each question. The first few questions have already been answered and the colour coding can been seen for each option: 0 is red, 1 is amber and 2 is green. On non-touchscreen devices it may be easier to use the keyboard rather than the small trackerpads provided. To do this use the up and down arrow keys to move a beige highlight up and down over the questions. Once on the required question use the left and right arrow keys to move the highlight between 0, 1 and 2. If most of the skills that the student is demonstrating is satisfactory it should be possible to press the left arrow key to select 2 and then select the down arrow key to move to the next question and so on.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">At the bottom some OSCE stations will have an overall score that the marker will need to indicate and there is space to type free-text comments. When happy with the correct recording of all the answers the examiner should click the \'Save\' button at the bottom. At this point the data will be sent back to Rogo and the original class list brought up ready for the next student.&nbsp;When data has been&nbsp;entered for a student it is no longer&nbsp;displayed in bold showing that Rogo is now holding his recorded OSCE sheet. Multiple examiners can divide up the marking load of a single station. At the end of the assessment the lead examiner for the station should log into Rogo normally (i.e. <a href=\"../../\">$local_server</a>)&nbsp;and go to the OSCE station paper. Next from the \'Analysis Menu\' the \'Class Totals\' report can be used to display all the marks of the whole cohort.</div>','Rogo supports the use of Netbooks and other small format devices to electronically record marks while a student is performing an examination within an OSCE. To do this an OSCE paper must first have been created and a number of likert questions added (either \'0, 1, 2\' or \'fail, borderling, pass\'). The paper should be scheduled for the correct day using the date settings in the \'Edit Properties\' option from the sidebar menu. &nbsp; On the day of the assessment each exminer should go to $local_server/osce/. This will bring up a list of all the students in the module that the OSCE station has been assigned to, as shown below. Initially all names will be displayed in bold, like Outlook this is to signify that these student have been unmarked (or unread). &nbsp; When a student arrives at the OSCE station the examiner should ask for their name and locate them on the alphabetic list. Clicking on their name will bring up a fresh marking sheet with their photo on (see below). &nbsp; In the above example a 0, 1, 2 type likert scale has been used for each question. The first few questions have already been answered and the colour coding can been seen for each option: 0 is red, 1 is amber and 2 is green. On non-touchscreen devices it may be easier to use the keyboard rather than the small trackerpads provided. To do this use the up and down arrow keys to move a beige highlight up and down over the questions. Once on the required question use the left and right arrow keys to move the highlight between 0, 1 and 2. If most of the skills that the student is demonstrating is satisfactory it should be possible to press the left arrow key to select 2 and then select the down arrow key to move to the next question and so on. &nbsp; At the bottom some OSCE stations will have an overall score that the marker will need to indicate and there is space to type free-text comments. When happy with the correct recording of all the answers the examiner should click the \'Save\' button at the bottom. At this point the data will be sent back to Rogo and the original class list brought up ready for the next student.&nbsp;When data has been&nbsp;entered for a student it is no longer&nbsp;displayed in bold showing that Rogo is now holding his recorded OSCE sheet. Multiple examiners can divide up the marking load of a single station. At the end of the assessment the lead examiner for the station should log into Rogo normally (i.e. $local_server)&nbsp;and go to the OSCE station paper. Next from the \'Analysis Menu\' the \'Class Totals\' report can be used to display all the marks of the whole cohort.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(267,'Offline Paper','<h2>Creating a Paper</h2>\r\n<p>Offline Papers are created when students are marked manually (e.g.&nbsp;paper based exam)&nbsp;but their scores are stored in Rogo. The paper is created with a number of Text Box questions where the following are set for each question:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The question - Useful if this is the question that the students answered</li>\r\n<li>Marks - number of marks that the question is worth</li>\r\n<li>Mapping - each question can be mapped to objectives</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Importing Marks</h2>\r\n<p>Marks are imported from a CSV file. The CSV file hold the Student ID number and the mark for each question. It is important that the number of questions in the paper and CSV file match. An example CSV file is shown below.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/offline csv.png\" alt=\"offline csv.png\" width=\"475\" height=\"265\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>When you have created a CSV file you need to import into Rogo. When the marks have been loaded you can use Class Totals to view the marks in the same way as other paper types.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/offline_import_marks.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"859\" height=\"288\" /></p>','Creating a Paper Offline Papers are created when students are marked manually (e.g.&nbsp;paper based exam)&nbsp;but their scores are stored in Rogo. The paper is created with a number of Text Box questions where the following are set for each question: The question - Useful if this is the question that the students answered Marks - number of marks that the question is worth Mapping - each question can be mapped to objectives &nbsp; Importing Marks Marks are imported from a CSV file. The CSV file hold the Student ID number and the mark for each question. It is important that the number of questions in the paper and CSV file match. An example CSV file is shown below. &nbsp; When you have created a CSV file you need to import into Rogo. When the marks have been loaded you can use Class Totals to view the marks in the same way as other paper types.&nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(258,'OSCE Station/Offline OSCE','<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"cursor: pointer;\" onclick=\"openTutorial(\'OSCE b.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Importing OSCE marks</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Offline OSCEs are those in which standard paper-based mark sheets are used by staff. These are then gathered together at the end of the process and scanned into a computer using Optical Mark Recognition (OMR) software. The marks should be exported into Excel and then formatted into the following order for loading into Rogo:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/osce_marks1.png\" alt=\"osce_marks1.png\" width=\"729\" height=\"321\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The first column holds the ID of the student, the next few columns run from Question 1 to how ever many questions are used on that particular OSCE station, in the example above 9 questions. The username of the examiner, overall classification and free text feedback (if required) complete the data in the Excel file.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The file in Excel should be exported as a Comma-Separated Values (CSV) file. This CSV file can be loaded into Rogo by going into the OSCE station paper and selecting \'Import OSCE Marks\' from the \'Paper Tasks\' section of the sidebar menu. Click the \'Browse...\' button and select the CSV file, then click \'Load Marks\'. To check that marks have been correctly imported select the \'Analysis Menu\' and then \'Class Totals\'.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/OSCE_save_to_CSV.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"686\" height=\"445\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #f2f2f2; padding: 5px;\"><strong>Note:</strong>It is important to check two things before importing OSCE marks:<ol>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">The number of Likert Scale questions matches exactly the number used on the paper form and is in the same order. </span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">The \'Overall Classification\' scheme is correctly set in the \'Paper Properties\' dialog box. </span></li>\r\n</ol></div>','\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nImporting OSCE marks\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nOffline OSCEs are those in which standard paper-based mark sheets are used by staff. These are then gathered together at the end of the process and scanned into a computer using Optical Mark Recognition (OMR) software. The marks should be exported into Excel and then formatted into the following order for loading into Rogo:\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe first column holds the ID of the student, the next few columns run from Question 1 to how ever many questions are used on that particular OSCE station, in the example above 9 questions. The username of the examiner, overall classification and free text feedback (if required) complete the data in the Excel file.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe file in Excel should be exported as a Comma-Separated Values (CSV) file. This CSV file can be loaded into Rogo by going into the OSCE station paper and selecting \'Import OSCE Marks\' from the \'Paper Tasks\' section of the sidebar menu. Click the \'Browse...\' button and select the CSV file, then click \'Load Marks\'. To check that marks have been correctly imported select the \'Analysis Menu\' and then \'Class Totals\'.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nNote:It is important to check two things before importing OSCE marks:\r\nThe number of Likert Scale questions matches exactly the number used on the paper form and is in the same order. \r\nThe \'Overall Classification\' scheme is correctly set in the \'Paper Properties\' dialog box. \r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(259,'OSCE Station/Creating a Paper','<div>For both Offline and Electronic OSCEs an OSCE paper needs to be created to hold the results. The paper consists of a number of Likert Scale questions.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/OSCE questions.png\" alt=\"OSCE questions.png\" width=\"764\" height=\"253\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>There&nbsp;are three different OSCE Station Scales&nbsp;that can be selected&nbsp;for&nbsp;your likert scale questions as seen in the graphic below.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/OSCE scale.png\" alt=\"OSCE scale.png\" width=\"716\" height=\"484\" />&nbsp;</div>','For both Offline and Electronic OSCEs an OSCE paper needs to be created to hold the results. The paper consists of a number of Likert Scale questions. &nbsp; &nbsp; There&nbsp;are three different OSCE Station Scales&nbsp;that can be selected&nbsp;for&nbsp;your likert scale questions as seen in the graphic below.&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(262,'Summative Exams/Running multiple papers','<div>More than one summative paper can run at the same time for the same students in the same labs. When this is done the following will happen:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><span style=\"color: #484848;\">Students login and are given a choice of papers</span></div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>A switch button becomes available to allow students to switch between papers</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/multiple_papers.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"386\" height=\"245\" /></div>','More than one summative paper can run at the same time for the same students in the same labs. When this is done the following will happen:  Students login and are given a choice of papers  A switch button becomes available to allow students to switch between papers  &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(264,'Questions - About/Status','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are 5 status options for questions. These can be used for your own categorisation but there are also some functionality differences.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Experimental</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Questions given this status can be included in assessment papers but are not included in the marks but answers can be viewed from frequency analysis. Questions of this type may be used if you want to see how students answer the question before including it as a marked question.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Retired</strong></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If a question is given this status it is not deleted but is not included in search results.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/status.png\" alt=\"status.png\" width=\"647\" height=\"167\" />&nbsp;</div>','There are 5 status options for questions. These can be used for your own categorisation but there are also some functionality differences. &nbsp; Experimental Questions given this status can be included in assessment papers but are not included in the marks but answers can be viewed from frequency analysis. Questions of this type may be used if you want to see how students answer the question before including it as a marked question. &nbsp; Retired If a question is given this status it is not deleted but is not included in search results. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(269,'Student access','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Students with a Rogo account can access all papers that they have been assigned to including those available in previous years of their study. Access is through the following URL: <a href=\"$local_server\">$local_server/students/</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Please note:</strong> This <strong>does not </strong>include summative exam papers which can only be accessed on the scheduled exam day.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/students.png\" alt=\"students.png\" width=\"781\" height=\"412\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The graphic above shows a typical screen that a student sees when they logon to Rogo. Each module they have been registered for is displayed&nbsp;with a link to each paper in that module. A tab for each year of study is shown at the top of the screen so a student can revisit papers that they&nbsp;had access to in previous years.</p>','Students with a Rogo account can access all papers that they have been assigned to including those available in previous years of their study. Access is through the following URL: $local_server/students/ Please note: This does not include summative exam papers which can only be accessed on the scheduled exam day. The graphic above shows a typical screen that a student sees when they logon to Rogo. Each module they have been registered for is displayed&nbsp;with a link to each paper in that module. A tab for each year of study is shown at the top of the screen so a student can revisit papers that they&nbsp;had access to in previous years.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(270,'Experts for SCT questions','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In script concordance questions the values for the number of experts that agree with each option are recorded and stored in Rogo. This is achieved using the following process:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Experts logon&nbsp;using the URL shown in the \'Reviewers\' tab in the paper properties where&nbsp;all experts use the same logon to access the paper:</p>\r\n<p>Username =&nbsp;sctreviewer</p>\r\n<p>Password = password set in the Password field of the Security tab of the paper properties.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/experts screen.png\" alt=\"experts screen.png\" width=\"981\" height=\"479\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When the expert has logged in they are asked to enter their name and email address. They then review each script concordance question in the paper selecting the option that they agree with and add a comment to explain their selection. Experts can logon again to review their response and change if necessary.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The paper owner&nbsp;selects \'SCT Responses/Reasons\'&nbsp;from Reports to view the Experts responses. A button at the bottom the screen allows the results to be saved to the Question Bank. This means that if the questions included in the paper are used in a different assessment the&nbsp;experts information&nbsp;will&nbsp;still be in the question.&nbsp;The reasons why the experts selected an option can be useful for writing option specific feedback.</p>','In script concordance questions the values for the number of experts that agree with each option are recorded and stored in Rogo. This is achieved using the following process: Experts logon&nbsp;using the URL shown in the \'Reviewers\' tab in the paper properties where&nbsp;all experts use the same logon to access the paper: Username =&nbsp;sctreviewer Password = password set in the Password field of the Security tab of the paper properties. &nbsp; When the expert has logged in they are asked to enter their name and email address. They then review each script concordance question in the paper selecting the option that they agree with and add a comment to explain their selection. Experts can logon again to review their response and change if necessary. The paper owner&nbsp;selects \'SCT Responses/Reasons\'&nbsp;from Reports to view the Experts responses. A button at the bottom the screen allows the results to be saved to the Question Bank. This means that if the questions included in the paper are used in a different assessment the&nbsp;experts information&nbsp;will&nbsp;still be in the question.&nbsp;The reasons why the experts selected an option can be useful for writing option specific feedback.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(271,'Retiring Papers and Questions','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A Paper with or without its questions can be retired giving the option to view retired papers in the module folders. This can make it easier to find relevant papers in the module window if the view does not include retired papers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you want to retire a paper, go into the paper and then select \'Retire Paper\'. You are then given the option to just retire the paper or retire the paper and questions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Retired papers are only displayed when \'Show retired\' is selected in the module window (1). These are then displayed in grey (2).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/retired_paper.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"787\" height=\"434\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Retired questions are only displayed for searches when Status is set as \'(any status)\' or \'Retired\'.</p>','A Paper with or without its questions can be retired giving the option to view retired papers in the module folders. This can make it easier to find relevant papers in the module window if the view does not include retired papers. If you want to retire a paper, go into the paper and then select \'Retire Paper\'. You are then given the option to just retire the paper or retire the paper and questions. Retired papers are only displayed when \'Show retired\' is selected in the module window (1). These are then displayed in grey (2). Retired questions are only displayed for searches when Status is set as \'(any status)\' or \'Retired\'.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(272,'Self enrol module','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo can support assessments that are not linked to an academic module. As Rogo is module-based, self enrolment modules need to be created. To set up a new self-enrol module please supply details to $support_email</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/self enrol.png\" alt=\"self enrol.png\" width=\"563\" height=\"184\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When entering the self enrol module a URL will be display at the top of the screen (see above). This URL can be emailed to students or included as a link in Moodle for self enroling. To actually enrol, students&nbsp;follow the URL and log in with their university username/password. The next screen confirms the name and school of the module to which the student confirms their intention to self-enrol. Once they have successfully enrolled they will see a confirmation screen that includes a link to a page showing all papers they can access, sorted by module.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/self enrol confirmation.png\" alt=\"self enrol confirmation.png\" width=\"515\" height=\"307\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Rogo can support assessments that are not linked to an academic module. As Rogo is module-based, self enrolment modules need to be created. To set up a new self-enrol module please supply details to $support_email &nbsp; &nbsp; When entering the self enrol module a URL will be display at the top of the screen (see above). This URL can be emailed to students or included as a link in Moodle for self enroling. To actually enrol, students&nbsp;follow the URL and log in with their university username/password. The next screen confirms the name and school of the module to which the student confirms their intention to self-enrol. Once they have successfully enrolled they will see a confirmation screen that includes a link to a page showing all papers they can access, sorted by module. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(273,'Temporary Accounts - Re-assign marks','<h2>Re-assigning marks to Student</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If a Temporary Account has been used, when the exam has finished it is necessary to transfer the exam script&nbsp;and marks over to the real account of the student. To do this go into the \'Reports\' menu from the paper and select \'Class Totals\'.&nbsp;Temporary accounts are highlighted in yellow and named \'Temporary Account No.10\' etc. Clicking on the name will&nbsp;show a popup menu, select \'Re-assign to User...\'.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/class totals temp account.png\" alt=\"class totals temp account.png\" width=\"695\" height=\"241\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo will look at the details the student entered against the temporary account and look the student up. The example below shows details of the student that has been associated with \'Temporary Account 10\'. Clicking \'OK\' will transfer the exam script and marks over to the student\'s records. This will also release the Temporary account&nbsp; and allow&nbsp;it to be used in a new exam.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/access5.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"620\" height=\"340\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Re-assigning marks to Student If a Temporary Account has been used, when the exam has finished it is necessary to transfer the exam script&nbsp;and marks over to the real account of the student. To do this go into the \'Reports\' menu from the paper and select \'Class Totals\'.&nbsp;Temporary accounts are highlighted in yellow and named \'Temporary Account No.10\' etc. Clicking on the name will&nbsp;show a popup menu, select \'Re-assign to User...\'. &nbsp; &nbsp; Rogo will look at the details the student entered against the temporary account and look the student up. The example below shows details of the student that has been associated with \'Temporary Account 10\'. Clicking \'OK\' will transfer the exam script and marks over to the student\'s records. This will also release the Temporary account&nbsp; and allow&nbsp;it to be used in a new exam. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(274,'Administrative Tools/Trac (issue tracking)','<p><img src=\"images/trac.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"137\" height=\"134\" align=\"Right\" /></p>\r\n<p>\'Trac\' is used to track issues (bugs)&nbsp;raised and feature requests in Rogo. The Trac system can be accessed from the \'Administrative Tools\' screen.</p>\r\n<p>The following details are vital to help the Rogo developers assess work required related to the ticket:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Reporter </strong>- This field should show the identity of the person that created the ticket so they can be contacted if further detail is required.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Description</strong> - Enough detail to fully describe the problem/request.</p>',' \'Trac\' is used to track issues (bugs)&nbsp;raised and feature requests in Rogo. The Trac system can be accessed from the \'Administrative Tools\' screen. The following details are vital to help the Rogo developers assess work required related to the ticket: Reporter - This field should show the identity of the person that created the ticket so they can be contacted if further detail is required. Description - Enough detail to fully describe the problem/request.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(276,'Student Metadata','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Where it is necessary to recognise different groups of students within a module, student metadata can be imported. The screenshot below shows the display after \'Import Student metadata\' (1) has been selected from within the relevant module. To conclude the import the year must be chosen (2) and appropriate file browsed by clicking the \'Browse\' button (3), and, finaly, the \'Import\' button clicked (4).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A CSV file needs to be created with student usernames&nbsp;in the first column then the required metadata in the following columns (can be one or more types). You can&nbsp;carry&nbsp;out a further import with new metadata columns and the new information will be added to what is already there.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The metadata&nbsp;is displayed as part of the&nbsp;Class Totals report that can be run post exam. Columns for the&nbsp;new data are displayed allowing the results to be ordered by that column. You can also select a Metadata option when you run the report to restrict the report according to the Metadata selected.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/metadata.png\" alt=\"metadata.png\" width=\"960\" height=\"453\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Where it is necessary to recognise different groups of students within a module, student metadata can be imported. The screenshot below shows the display after \'Import Student metadata\' (1) has been selected from within the relevant module. To conclude the import the year must be chosen (2) and appropriate file browsed by clicking the \'Browse\' button (3), and, finaly, the \'Import\' button clicked (4). A CSV file needs to be created with student usernames&nbsp;in the first column then the required metadata in the following columns (can be one or more types). You can&nbsp;carry&nbsp;out a further import with new metadata columns and the new information will be added to what is already there. The metadata&nbsp;is displayed as part of the&nbsp;Class Totals report that can be run post exam. Columns for the&nbsp;new data are displayed allowing the results to be ordered by that column. You can also select a Metadata option when you run the report to restrict the report according to the Metadata selected. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(278,'Administrative Tools/Staff profile','<div>There are two Admin staff profiles in addition to the normal staff profile:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>SysAdmin - Access to all parts of Rogo</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Admin (1) - Additional functionality for selected schools (2)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/Staff_profile.png\" alt=\"Staff_profile.png\" width=\"818\" height=\"362\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></div>\r\n<p>If a user is set as Admin, one or more Schools need to be selected. This gives the following additional rights:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Access to all modules in the selected school(s)</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Import of Students Metadata</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Manage Team keywords</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Setting the Admin profile</h2>\r\n<div>When an Admin profile is required the following steps are followed:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Rogo account created if not already set</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Enter user account and select check the Admin box</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Save the changes to the profile</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Re enter the account and click on the Admin tab then select the school that the user requires Admin functionality for</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','There are two Admin staff profiles in addition to the normal staff profile:\r\n\r\n\r\nSysAdmin - Access to all parts of Rogo\r\n\r\n\r\nAdmin (1) - Additional functionality for selected schools (2)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIf a user is set as Admin, one or more Schools need to be selected. This gives the following additional rights:\r\n\r\n\r\nAccess to all modules in the selected school(s)\r\n\r\n\r\nImport of Students Metadata\r\n\r\n\r\nManage Team keywords\r\n\r\n\r\nSetting the Admin profile\r\nWhen an Admin profile is required the following steps are followed:\r\n\r\n\r\nRogo account created if not already set\r\n\r\n\r\nEnter user account and select check the Admin box\r\n\r\n\r\nSave the changes to the profile\r\n\r\n\r\nRe enter the account and click on the Admin tab then select the school that the user requires Admin functionality for\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(307,'Summative Exams/Central Scheduling','<p><strong>Note:</strong> \'Summative Scheduling\' only applies to summative exam paper types.</p>\r\n<h2>Purpose</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is critical that the properties of summative exams are correctly set, after all students may depend on these exams to get through their modules. It is possible to centralise the administration of setting time/dates and computer labs for summativ exams. The details below apply to institutions running Rogo with this central summative exam scheduling switched on.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Academic staff are free to create new papers and to add/edit questions, but responsibility for setting a time/date and computer lab location is handled by a central exams office.</p>\r\n<h2>Paper Creation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To create a new paper with summative exams scheduling turned on an academic can select \'Create&nbsp;new Paper\' from the sidebar menu of the homepage. A dialog box similar to the one below will appear. Select \'Summative Exam\' as the paper type (1) and then enter an appropriate name&nbsp;for the exam (i.e. \'Advanced Astrophysics (2012/13)\' (2)) and click \'Next &gt;\' (3).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_no_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/summ_scheduling_1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"770\" height=\"565\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">On the second page of the wizard is a basic form to collect details about what is required for the exam. Here an academic will specify which calendar month they require the exam for, in this case May. \'Barriers Needed\' tells the exams office whether physical barriers are needed between computers to stop plagarism. For first sit exams select \'\', or for resits specify the nearest range for the number of students needing to retake the exam. Notes is used to convey any specific information about the scheduling to the exams office. Finally, at the bottom select the module(s) the paper is intended for. In this example \'HG0FCA - Foundation calculus\' has been selected.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_no_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/summ_scheduling_2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"770\" height=\"565\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Scheduling</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When the summative exam is first created it will have no start or end dates and will not appear in the exam calendar. The exams office will read the information submitted as part of page 2 of the wizard and will set an appropriate time/date and computer lab for the cohort. They will then email the academic who at that point can let the students know the time of the exam. At this point the exam will also appear in the exam calendar.</p>','Note: \'Summative Scheduling\' only applies to summative exam paper types. Purpose It is critical that the properties of summative exams are correctly set, after all students may depend on these exams to get through their modules. It is possible to centralise the administration of setting time/dates and computer labs for summativ exams. The details below apply to institutions running Rogo with this central summative exam scheduling switched on. Academic staff are free to create new papers and to add/edit questions, but responsibility for setting a time/date and computer lab location is handled by a central exams office. Paper Creation To create a new paper with summative exams scheduling turned on an academic can select \'Create&nbsp;new Paper\' from the sidebar menu of the homepage. A dialog box similar to the one below will appear. Select \'Summative Exam\' as the paper type (1) and then enter an appropriate name&nbsp;for the exam (i.e. \'Advanced Astrophysics (2012/13)\' (2)) and click \'Next &gt;\' (3).&nbsp; On the second page of the wizard is a basic form to collect details about what is required for the exam. Here an academic will specify which calendar month they require the exam for, in this case May. \'Barriers Needed\' tells the exams office whether physical barriers are needed between computers to stop plagarism. For first sit exams select \'\', or for resits specify the nearest range for the number of students needing to retake the exam. Notes is used to convey any specific information about the scheduling to the exams office. Finally, at the bottom select the module(s) the paper is intended for. In this example \'HG0FCA - Foundation calculus\' has been selected. Scheduling When the summative exam is first created it will have no start or end dates and will not appear in the exam calendar. The exams office will read the information submitted as part of page 2 of the wizard and will set an appropriate time/date and computer lab for the cohort. They will then email the academic who at that point can let the students know the time of the exam. At this point the exam will also appear in the exam calendar.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(290,'Marking/Important Points','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marking in Rogo is flexible where different marking methods and&nbsp;marks per question/option can be selected. There are some important points to remember:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">If a negative mark is set for incorrect responses to Multiple Response questions, students will receive the negative mark if the question is not answered.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Consider the chance of a student guessing the correct answer and how many marks a correct answer is awarded. Where questions can easily be answered correctly by guessing, you may not want to award a large number of marks in comparison to other questions in the paper.</li>\r\n</ol>','Marking in Rogo is flexible where different marking methods and&nbsp;marks per question/option can be selected. There are some important points to remember: If a negative mark is set for incorrect responses to Multiple Response questions, students will receive the negative mark if the question is not answered. Consider the chance of a student guessing the correct answer and how many marks a correct answer is awarded. Where questions can easily be answered correctly by guessing, you may not want to award a large number of marks in comparison to other questions in the paper. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(291,'Student view','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you want to see how a paper will appear to a student, select \'Test &amp; Preview\' from&nbsp;the \'Paper Tasks\' options. This is exactly the same as what a student will see including the marks and feedback after the paper has been completed. As you are a member of staff, your results will not be stored but for testing your questions \'Test &amp; Preview\' is the method that should be used.</p>','If you want to see how a paper will appear to a student, select \'Test &amp; Preview\' from&nbsp;the \'Paper Tasks\' options. This is exactly the same as what a student will see including the marks and feedback after the paper has been completed. As you are a member of staff, your results will not be stored but for testing your questions \'Test &amp; Preview\' is the method that should be used.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(293,'Question - Types/TrueFalse','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p>A statement is displayed with an option to select either True or False.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/true false presentation.png\" alt=\"true false presentation.png\" width=\"367\" height=\"136\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Creating/Editing</h2>\r\n<p>The statement is set in the Lead-in field and the answer is set as either True or False. If your module uses negative marking, negative marks for incorrect answers can be set as well as marks for correct answers.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/true false edit.png\" alt=\"true false edit.png\" width=\"909\" height=\"304\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Presentation A statement is displayed with an option to select either True or False. &nbsp; Creating/Editing The statement is set in the Lead-in field and the answer is set as either True or False. If your module uses negative marking, negative marks for incorrect answers can be set as well as marks for correct answers. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(294,'Administrative Tools/Bulk Course Import','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Selecting \'Courses\' from the \'Administrative Tools\' screen gives you an option of \'Bulk Course Import\'. Multiple courses can be imported by using a CSV file. The screenshot below shows the required format of the CSV file. Only one course is shown here but for bulk import, additional rows can be included in the file.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/Bulk_course.PNG\" alt=\"Bulk_course.PNG\" width=\"650\" height=\"314\" /></p>','Selecting \'Courses\' from the \'Administrative Tools\' screen gives you an option of \'Bulk Course Import\'. Multiple courses can be imported by using a CSV file. The screenshot below shows the required format of the CSV file. Only one course is shown here but for bulk import, additional rows can be included in the file. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(295,'Administrative Tools/Bulk Module Import','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Selecting \'Modules\' from the \'Administrative Tools\'&nbsp;screen gives you an option of \'Bulk Module Import\'. Multiple modules can be imported in bulk by using a&nbsp;CSV file in the format shown below. The options shown in columns F to L are&nbsp;options that can be set for a module. Once modules have been imported, they can be edited if any of the settings need to be changed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/Bulk_module.PNG\" alt=\"Bulk_module.PNG\" width=\"903\" height=\"345\" /></p>','Selecting \'Modules\' from the \'Administrative Tools\'&nbsp;screen gives you an option of \'Bulk Module Import\'. Multiple modules can be imported in bulk by using a&nbsp;CSV file in the format shown below. The options shown in columns F to L are&nbsp;options that can be set for a module. Once modules have been imported, they can be edited if any of the settings need to be changed.&nbsp; &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(296,'Reference Material','<h2>About</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For certain assessments academics may wish to provide various reference materials to assist with question answering. This could be drug lists for use in Medicine or Pharmacy, or formulae for Maths and Engineering. Providing reference material inside the assessment system avoids the need for photocopying and handing out sheet of paper at each workstation.</p>\r\n<h2>Creating</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To create a new reference material navigate into a module and then click \'Reference Material\' from the sidebar menu. The screenshot below shows a simple example of Highway Code material copied from Wikipedia. A name is given to the reference material, a width (400px in this case) and at least one module should be selected. Click \'Save\' at the bottom when happy with the material.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/ref_create.png\" alt=\"ref_create.png\" width=\"1145\" height=\"673\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Using in Papers</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To associate, or link, the reference material with an actual paper, navigate firstly to a paper. Next, select \'Edit Properties\' from the sidebar menu. In the dialog box that appears (see below) click on the \'Reference Material\' tab. Here a list of reference materials that belong to the modules that the paper is on will appear. In this case there is only one but multiple reference materials can be used simultaneously on a paper. Select the checkbox next to \'Highway Code\' and click \'OK\' to save the settings.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/ref_dialog.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"882\" height=\"296\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Now when \'Test &amp; Preview\' is selected the reference material will be displayed in a sidebar on the right hand side of the screen. The assessment questions part of the screen and the reference material part will scroll independently if there is too much text for the screen.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/ref_assessment.png\" alt=\"ref_assessment.png\" width=\"1059\" height=\"641\" /></p>','About For certain assessments academics may wish to provide various reference materials to assist with question answering. This could be drug lists for use in Medicine or Pharmacy, or formulae for Maths and Engineering. Providing reference material inside the assessment system avoids the need for photocopying and handing out sheet of paper at each workstation. Creating To create a new reference material navigate into a module and then click \'Reference Material\' from the sidebar menu. The screenshot below shows a simple example of Highway Code material copied from Wikipedia. A name is given to the reference material, a width (400px in this case) and at least one module should be selected. Click \'Save\' at the bottom when happy with the material. Using in Papers To associate, or link, the reference material with an actual paper, navigate firstly to a paper. Next, select \'Edit Properties\' from the sidebar menu. In the dialog box that appears (see below) click on the \'Reference Material\' tab. Here a list of reference materials that belong to the modules that the paper is on will appear. In this case there is only one but multiple reference materials can be used simultaneously on a paper. Select the checkbox next to \'Highway Code\' and click \'OK\' to save the settings. Now when \'Test &amp; Preview\' is selected the reference material will be displayed in a sidebar on the right hand side of the screen. The assessment questions part of the screen and the reference material part will scroll independently if there is too much text for the screen. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(297,'Objectives/Import from File','<p>Objectives can be imported from a .txt file by following this process:</p>\r\n<p>Create a .txt file in the following format with your required headings and Objectives:</p>\r\n<p>#Heading1<br />Objective1a<br />Objective1b<br />Objective1c<br />#Heading2<br />Objective2a<br />Objective2b<br />Objective2c</p>\r\n<p>From your module in Rogo, select Manage Objectives then Import from File and select your .txt file.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/import objectives.png\" alt=\"import objectives.png\" width=\"881\" height=\"293\" /></p>','Objectives can be imported from a .txt file by following this process: Create a .txt file in the following format with your required headings and Objectives: #Heading1Objective1aObjective1bObjective1c#Heading2Objective2aObjective2bObjective2c From your module in Rogo, select Manage Objectives then Import from File and select your .txt file. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(298,'Questions - About/Question Bank','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">All the questions used in Rogo are kept in Question Bank. Adding a question to a paper creates, in fact, a link to the Question Bank. The questions in the Question Bank can be duplicated to be independently used in different papers but also can be repeatedly linked to different papers. Multiple links&nbsp;of the same questions have this advantage that correcting or altering such a question in a question bank or in a paper results in an instant change of its every instance in every paper that incorporates it. Therefore there is important distinction&nbsp;between &lsquo;copying&rsquo; and &lsquo;linking&rsquo; questions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/question_bank.png\" alt=\"question_bank.png\" width=\"254\" height=\"251\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">There are also several ways to locate a specific question in a question bank and to add it to the paper.</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #c0c0c0; color: #c0c0c0; height: 1px; border: 0px;\" />\r\n<h2>Adding to paper</h2>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'questions_add.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Questions adding</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When the paper is opened, the basic method to add a question to it from the question bank paper is to select the \'Add Questions to Paper\' link from the \'Paper Tasks\' pane. This will display a popup window similar to the one below:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/question_add2.png\" alt=\"question_add2.png\" width=\"728\" height=\"372\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;This dialog has tabs allowing to show questions:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>created by the current user who are at the moment not assigned to any paper (unused),&nbsp;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>all the questions owned by the current user,</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>selected by Keywords,&nbsp;Status,&nbsp;Paper,&nbsp;or Team,</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>and to be search by combination of word/phrase, question type and/or question owner.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To add a question or questions from the list to the paper just click the relevant checkboxes, check the screen number is correct and then click on the \'Add Questions\' button. Questions will be added in the order displayed. It is therefore often useful to click on the \'Created\' heading to order the questions. Adding multiple questions in this order will appear on the paper in the same order as originally entered.</p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #c0c0c0; color: #c0c0c0; height: 1px; border: 0px;\" />\r\n<h2>Listing</h2>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'list_add_remove_mltp_training.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Questions linking and removing</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The other quick way of finding questions involves clicking on one of the first 3 links in the Question Bank Tasks: \'Questions by Type\', \'Questions by Team\', and \'Questions by Keyword\'.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\'Questions by Type\' displays popup menu of all available question types and after choosing one of them the list of all questions of that type from the question bank.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/questions_by_type2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"428\" height=\"149\" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\'Questions by Team\' displays popup menu of all the team that the user is part of and after choosing one of them the list of all questions from the question bank of that team.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/questions_by_team2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"428\" height=\"149\" /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\'Questions by Keyword\' displays popup menu of all the team and personal keywords and after choosing one of them the list of all questions from the question bank for that keyword.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/questions_by_keyword2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"428\" height=\"149\" /></p>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #c0c0c0; color: #c0c0c0; height: 1px; border: 0px;\" />\r\n<h2>Searching</h2>\r\n<div>\r\n<table onclick=\"openTutorial(\'questions_search.swf\')\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 70px;\" rowspan=\"2\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"large_play_icon.png\" alt=\"Demo Movie\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"color: blue; font-size: 125%;\">Questions searching and linking</div>\r\n<div style=\"color: #808080; font-size: 90%;\">Flash required</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Another method of locating questions involves performing a search for a question. Click on \'Search\' from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane and then select \'Questions\' from the popup menu.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/question_search.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"402\" height=\"206\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A special search pane will be displayed similar to the one shown below. Enter a word or phrase into the textbox and then click \'Search\'. If necessary you can limit the search to look for specific types of question and which section in the question to search. Dates when the question was modified and the Team or Owner can also be used in the search. The Blooms level and Keyword are also available to search on. Any matching question found in the bank will then be displayed in the main frame on the right hand side.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/question_search3.png\" alt=\"question_search3.png\" width=\"877\" height=\"373\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Assuming some questions have been found with the search term, the user may then single click on the lead-in of the question and the options in the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane will become active:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Edit Question - The current question can be opened and changes made unless a question has been used in an exam and is locked.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Information - Displays information (owner, creation date, modified date and papers used on) about the currently selected question.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Copy (create duplicate) - This will create a duplicate of the selected question in the question bank.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Link to Paper - This will display a dialog box allowing the user to link the currently selected question to an existing or new paper.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Delete Question - This will remove the currently selected question from the question bank. Deletions can only be performed by the question owner and only then if the question is not currently used on a paper.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; background-color: #c0c0c0; color: #c0c0c0; height: 1px; border: 0px;\" />\r\n<h2>Copying or Linking the Question from Bank</h2>\r\n<h3>Copying Questions</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To copy a question from the list directly into a paper, select the question that you want to copy and then select \'Copy onto Paper X...\'. A new window will open listing the papers that you have access to and a paper can be selected from the list. This adds a copy of the question to the selected paper and as there are now 2 versions of the question changes made to one of these does not affect the other.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When a question is copied the ownership of the copy is always set to the person performing the copy action regardless of the person owning the original.</p>\r\n<h3>Linking to Questions</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you don\'t want to make any changes to a question you can just select a paper that you want to link the question to. This is done by following the process described above but selecting \'Link to paper\' rather than the &lsquo;Copy&hellip;&rsquo; option. This would mean that any changes to the question would appear in both papers that are linked to it.</p>','Introduction\r\nAll the questions used in Rogo are kept in Question Bank. Adding a question to a paper creates, in fact, a link to the Question Bank. The questions in the Question Bank can be duplicated to be independently used in different papers but also can be repeatedly linked to different papers. Multiple links&nbsp;of the same questions have this advantage that correcting or altering such a question in a question bank or in a paper results in an instant change of its every instance in every paper that incorporates it. Therefore there is important distinction&nbsp;between &lsquo;copying&rsquo; and &lsquo;linking&rsquo; questions.\r\n\r\nThere are also several ways to locate a specific question in a question bank and to add it to the paper.\r\n\r\nAdding to paper\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nQuestions adding\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhen the paper is opened, the basic method to add a question to it from the question bank paper is to select the \'Add Questions to Paper\' link from the \'Paper Tasks\' pane. This will display a popup window similar to the one below:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;This dialog has tabs allowing to show questions:\r\n\r\n\r\ncreated by the current user who are at the moment not assigned to any paper (unused),&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\nall the questions owned by the current user,\r\n\r\n\r\nselected by Keywords,&nbsp;Status,&nbsp;Paper,&nbsp;or Team,\r\n\r\n\r\nand to be search by combination of word/phrase, question type and/or question owner.\r\n\r\n\r\nTo add a question or questions from the list to the paper just click the relevant checkboxes, check the screen number is correct and then click on the \'Add Questions\' button. Questions will be added in the order displayed. It is therefore often useful to click on the \'Created\' heading to order the questions. Adding multiple questions in this order will appear on the paper in the same order as originally entered.\r\n\r\nListing\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nQuestions linking and removing\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe other quick way of finding questions involves clicking on one of the first 3 links in the Question Bank Tasks: \'Questions by Type\', \'Questions by Team\', and \'Questions by Keyword\'.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\'Questions by Type\' displays popup menu of all available question types and after choosing one of them the list of all questions of that type from the question bank.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\'Questions by Team\' displays popup menu of all the team that the user is part of and after choosing one of them the list of all questions from the question bank of that team.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\'Questions by Keyword\' displays popup menu of all the team and personal keywords and after choosing one of them the list of all questions from the question bank for that keyword.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSearching\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nQuestions searching and linking\r\nFlash required\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAnother method of locating questions involves performing a search for a question. Click on \'Search\' from the \'Question Bank Tasks\' pane and then select \'Questions\' from the popup menu.\r\n\r\nA special search pane will be displayed similar to the one shown below. Enter a word or phrase into the textbox and then click \'Search\'. If necessary you can limit the search to look for specific types of question and which section in the question to search. Dates when the question was modified and the Team or Owner can also be used in the search. The Blooms level and Keyword are also available to search on. Any matching question found in the bank will then be displayed in the main frame on the right hand side.\r\n\r\nAssuming some questions have been found with the search term, the user may then single click on the lead-in of the question and the options in the \'Current Question Tasks\' pane will become active:\r\n\r\n\r\nEdit Question - The current question can be opened and changes made unless a question has been used in an exam and is locked.\r\n\r\n\r\nInformation - Displays information (owner, creation date, modified date and papers used on) about the currently selected question.\r\n\r\n\r\nCopy (create duplicate) - This will create a duplicate of the selected question in the question bank.\r\n\r\n\r\nLink to Paper - This will display a dialog box allowing the user to link the currently selected question to an existing or new paper.\r\n\r\n\r\nDelete Question - This will remove the currently selected question from the question bank. Deletions can only be performed by the question owner and only then if the question is not currently used on a paper.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCopying or Linking the Question from Bank\r\nCopying Questions\r\nTo copy a question from the list directly into a paper, select the question that you want to copy and then select \'Copy onto Paper X...\'. A new window will open listing the papers that you have access to and a paper can be selected from the list. This adds a copy of the question to the selected paper and as there are now 2 versions of the question changes made to one of these does not affect the other.\r\nWhen a question is copied the ownership of the copy is always set to the person performing the copy action regardless of the person owning the original.\r\nLinking to Questions\r\nIf you don\'t want to make any changes to a question you can just select a paper that you want to link the question to. This is done by following the process described above but selecting \'Link to paper\' rather than the &lsquo;Copy&hellip;&rsquo; option. This would mean that any changes to the question would appear in both papers that are linked to it.','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(306,'Questions - About/Performance','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note:</strong> It is first necessary to view the \'Frequency &amp; Discrimination (U-L) Analysis\' report which will save the performance data into the question bank.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To view the performance of a question first single click (1) on it in either a paper or from a search for questions, and then select \'Information\' (2) from the sidebar menu.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/q_perform_1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"771\" height=\"315\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A popup window will appear showing details of this question: date created, modified, author, etc. As the screenshot below shows it will also display details about any copies made. \'Copy of\' means that the current question has been copied from another question and \'Source for\' means that the current question has been used as a starting point for a new question. Below this can been seen a list of papers where the current question has been used. In this case the question has been used on a paper called \'A11MBM 2011/12\' with a cohort of 249 students. It has a difficulty (P) of 0.76 and a discrimination (D) of 0.27.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_no_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/q_perform_2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"720\" height=\"642\" /></p>','Note: It is first necessary to view the \'Frequency &amp; Discrimination (U-L) Analysis\' report which will save the performance data into the question bank. To view the performance of a question first single click (1) on it in either a paper or from a search for questions, and then select \'Information\' (2) from the sidebar menu. A popup window will appear showing details of this question: date created, modified, author, etc. As the screenshot below shows it will also display details about any copies made. \'Copy of\' means that the current question has been copied from another question and \'Source for\' means that the current question has been used as a starting point for a new question. Below this can been seen a list of papers where the current question has been used. In this case the question has been used on a paper called \'A11MBM 2011/12\' with a cohort of 249 students. It has a difficulty (P) of 0.76 and a discrimination (D) of 0.27. ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(304,'LTI Links','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To create a link in from an LTI tool consumer (e.g. Moodle) go into the VLE and into the relevant module you wish to put the Rogo paper into.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In Moodle turn editing on and select \'External Tool\' from the activity dropdown. Set a name for the activity (1), probably best to match the name to the paper in Rogo and select the correct external tool type (2). Now click \'Save and display\' (3).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/external_tool1b.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"532\" height=\"363\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rogo authorisation is required.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/external_tool2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"741\" height=\"156\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">With the LTI link now inserted into Moodle it can be clicked to go into Rogo. The first time a member of staff (i.e. module convenor) traverses the link Rogo will ask which assessment to associate with the link. This step is only done once.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/external_tool5.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"341\" height=\"226\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">After complete any students traversing the link from Moodle will go straight into the paper.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/external_tool4.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"589\" height=\"345\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>','To create a link in from an LTI tool consumer (e.g. Moodle) go into the VLE and into the relevant module you wish to put the Rogo paper into. In Moodle turn editing on and select \'External Tool\' from the activity dropdown. Set a name for the activity (1), probably best to match the name to the paper in Rogo and select the correct external tool type (2). Now click \'Save and display\' (3). Rogo authorisation is required. With the LTI link now inserted into Moodle it can be clicked to go into Rogo. The first time a member of staff (i.e. module convenor) traverses the link Rogo will ask which assessment to associate with the link. This step is only done once. After complete any students traversing the link from Moodle will go straight into the paper. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL),(305,'Question - Types/Area','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Area question requires students to trace around a particular part of an image.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Graphic to be uses shouldn\'t be&nbsp;bigger than 900 x 800 pixels and in one of these 3 format: JPG, GIF or PNG.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This technique allows to draw a polygon around an area by moving to corner points (vertices) and single-clicking the mouse while the system joins the dots up. The alternative move is to press and drag which will set node corners automaticaly. The area shape will be finished when user moves back to the starting position marked with the large green dot or when user double-clicks at any point.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To reshape the finished area the user is required to move the corner point (square handle) or add corner by moving circular handle. To erase corner it is required to select \'Delete point\' button and click on the square (or to click on the square with SHIFT pressed).</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/area_question.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"384\" height=\"506\" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\">Marking and Feedback</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marks can be given for correctly selected requested area of the graphic by question. Negative marks can also be given for incorrect responses. Depending on the feedback settings for the paper, ticks/crosses, user\'s area, correct area and the error area on the graphic can be displayed for each tab.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/area_feedback.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"383\" height=\"542\" /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\">Creating</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">A area&nbsp;question...</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/area_edit.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"539\" height=\"774\" /></div>','Presentation Area question requires students to trace around a particular part of an image. Graphic to be uses shouldn\'t be&nbsp;bigger than 900 x 800 pixels and in one of these 3 format: JPG, GIF or PNG. This technique allows to draw a polygon around an area by moving to corner points (vertices) and single-clicking the mouse while the system joins the dots up. The alternative move is to press and drag which will set node corners automaticaly. The area shape will be finished when user moves back to the starting position marked with the large green dot or when user double-clicks at any point. To reshape the finished area the user is required to move the corner point (square handle) or add corner by moving circular handle. To erase corner it is required to select \'Delete point\' button and click on the square (or to click on the square with SHIFT pressed).  &nbsp; Marking and Feedback Marks can be given for correctly selected requested area of the graphic by question. Negative marks can also be given for incorrect responses. Depending on the feedback settings for the paper, ticks/crosses, user\'s area, correct area and the error area on the graphic can be displayed for each tab. &nbsp;  Creating A area&nbsp;question... ','page',NULL,NULL,'Staff',NULL);
