INSERT INTO `student_help` VALUES (1,'About Rogo','<blockquote>\r\n<h2>System Design &amp; Programming</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Dr Simon Wilkinson</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Anthony Brown</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Dr Rob Ingram</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Flash</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Fay Cross</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Heather Rai</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>QTI</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Adam Clarke</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Logo</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Nuno Jorge</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>',' System Design &amp; Programming  Dr Simon Wilkinson  Anthony Brown  Dr Rob Ingram  Flash  Fay Cross  Heather Rai  QTI  Adam Clarke  Logo  Nuno Jorge  ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(2,'Types of Assessment','<p>Rogo currently supports four different types of assessment and survey papers:</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"8\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/formative icon.png\" alt=\"formative icon.png\" width=\"43\" height=\"46\" /></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<h2>Formative Assessment</h2>\r\nSelf-assessment quizzes, usually available for students to take throughout the semester. These quizzes allow the student to evaluate their own knowledge. It can be useful to complete a formative assessment at the start of a module and then repeat at the end of the module to evaluate change of knowledge and understanding. Completion of Formative Assessments also allows students to become familiar with the Rogo system which is good preparation for Summative Assessments. The marks generated from sitting formative assessments are never used to determine the final grading of a course or degree, they are practice for only.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/progress icon.png\" alt=\"progress icon.png\" width=\"44\" height=\"47\" /></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<h2>Progress Test</h2>\r\nA progress test is similar to a formative assessment but differs in that after completing it marks or feedback are not shown. The paper can only accessed during a specified time period and can only complete it once. Marks are released by the paper writer at a selected time. The writer may also change the format of the paper so that it can be accessed as a Formative paper showing the marks and feedback.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/summative icon.png\" alt=\"summative icon.png\" width=\"43\" height=\"46\" /></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<h2>Summative Assessment</h2>\r\nSummative assessments are any exams or tests where the marks are used to determine final course/module or degree grades. No immediate feedback or marks will be shown in the paper.</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/survey icon.png\" alt=\"survey icon.png\" width=\"42\" height=\"47\" /></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<h2>Survey</h2>\r\nSurveys, or questionnaires, are used to create papers to gather views and responses where there are no correct answers, for example, module evaluations. Typically, likert scales and open-ended textboxes are the most frequently used question types in a survey. Surveys can only be completed once.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','Rogo currently supports four different types of assessment and survey papers:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFormative Assessment\r\nSelf-assessment quizzes, usually available for students to take throughout the semester. These quizzes allow the student to evaluate their own knowledge. It can be useful to complete a formative assessment at the start of a module and then repeat at the end of the module to evaluate change of knowledge and understanding. Completion of Formative Assessments also allows students to become familiar with the Rogo system which is good preparation for Summative Assessments. The marks generated from sitting formative assessments are never used to determine the final grading of a course or degree, they are practice for only.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nProgress Test\r\nA progress test is similar to a formative assessment but differs in that after completing it marks or feedback are not shown. The paper can only accessed during a specified time period and can only complete it once. Marks are released by the paper writer at a selected time. The writer may also change the format of the paper so that it can be accessed as a Formative paper showing the marks and feedback.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSummative Assessment\r\nSummative assessments are any exams or tests where the marks are used to determine final course/module or degree grades. No immediate feedback or marks will be shown in the paper.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSurvey\r\nSurveys, or questionnaires, are used to create papers to gather views and responses where there are no correct answers, for example, module evaluations. Typically, likert scales and open-ended textboxes are the most frequently used question types in a survey. Surveys can only be completed once.\r\n\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(3,'Question Types/Dichotomous','<h2>Questions</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Textual Dichotomous question</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dichotomous questions present a lead-in question (i.e. \'Which of the following birds are extinct?\') together with a number of stems displayed below. The examinee must select either \'True\' or \'False\' for each stem, or \'Yes\' or \'No\' if these labels are used.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/dichotomous_question.gif\" alt=\"Textual\" width=\"356\" height=\"357\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Graphical Dichotomous question</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the example below graphics are used instead of textual stems. However, the principle is the same, each road symbol (stem) must be answered either \'True\' or \'False\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/dichotomous_question2.gif\" alt=\"Graphical\" width=\"523\" height=\"646\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Questions Textual Dichotomous question Dichotomous questions present a lead-in question (i.e. \'Which of the following birds are extinct?\') together with a number of stems displayed below. The examinee must select either \'True\' or \'False\' for each stem, or \'Yes\' or \'No\' if these labels are used. &nbsp; Graphical Dichotomous question In the example below graphics are used instead of textual stems. However, the principle is the same, each road symbol (stem) must be answered either \'True\' or \'False\'. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(4,'Question Types/Multiple Choice (MCQ)','<h2>Questions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the past a number of staff may have used the term \'MCQ\' to refer to what is termed here \'True/False\'. The definition of MCQ used here is a question that has a number of options of which only <strong>one</strong> is correct. The user interface uses option buttons so that as soon as one option is selected any previous options are unselected.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As the two examples below show, MCQs can be made up of textual options or graphical options. In both cases only one option is correct. All the other options are termed \'distractors\'.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Textual MCQs</strong></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mcq_question1.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"334\" /></div>\r\n<p><strong>Graphical MCQs</strong></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mcq_question2.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"340\" height=\"546\" /></div>\r\n<p><strong>Ruling out incorrect options</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A technique sometimes adopted by examinees in paper exams is to cross out with a pen any options which are known to be wrong in an attempt to narrow down the list of possibilities. Athough it is not possible to use a pen with online exams, it is possible to click on the text of any option in an MCQ and it will grey out (i.e. crossed out). Clicking again on a greyed-out option will reinstate it in black. This process of greying out options is simply a visual aid to answering the question; a candidate <em>must</em> still answer the question using the radio buttons.</p>','Questions In the past a number of staff may have used the term \'MCQ\' to refer to what is termed here \'True/False\'. The definition of MCQ used here is a question that has a number of options of which only one is correct. The user interface uses option buttons so that as soon as one option is selected any previous options are unselected. As the two examples below show, MCQs can be made up of textual options or graphical options. In both cases only one option is correct. All the other options are termed \'distractors\'. Textual MCQs Graphical MCQs Ruling out incorrect options A technique sometimes adopted by examinees in paper exams is to cross out with a pen any options which are known to be wrong in an attempt to narrow down the list of possibilities. Athough it is not possible to use a pen with online exams, it is possible to click on the text of any option in an MCQ and it will grey out (i.e. crossed out). Clicking again on a greyed-out option will reinstate it in black. This process of greying out options is simply a visual aid to answering the question; a candidate must still answer the question using the radio buttons.','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(5,'Question Types/Multiple Response','<h2>Questions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Multiple Response consist of questions which have multiple correct options. Unlike Multiple Choice Questions (MCQs), that can only have one of their options correct, Multiple Response allow each option to be selected or unselected. In the example below, 2 out of the 6 options correctly match the question \"Which two opponents did James Bond face in the film Moonraker?\".</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/mrq_question.gif\" alt=\"Question\" width=\"446\" height=\"628\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If more than two options are select a warning message will be displayed and after clicking \'OK\' the last option checked will be unchecked.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/mrq_warning.gif\" alt=\"Warning\" width=\"407\" height=\"126\" /></div>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Ruling out incorrect options</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A technique sometimes adopted by examinees in paper exams is to cross out with a pen any options which are known to be wrong in an attempt to narrow down the list of possibilities. Athough it is not possible to use a pen with online exams, it is possible to click on the text of any option in a Multiple Choice question and it will grey out (i.e. crossed out). Clicking again on a greyed-out option will reinstate it in black. This process of greying out options is simply a visual aid to answering the question; a candidate <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">must</span> still answer the question using the check boxes.</p>','Questions Multiple Response consist of questions which have multiple correct options. Unlike Multiple Choice Questions (MCQs), that can only have one of their options correct, Multiple Response allow each option to be selected or unselected. In the example below, 2 out of the 6 options correctly match the question \"Which two opponents did James Bond face in the film Moonraker?\". If more than two options are select a warning message will be displayed and after clicking \'OK\' the last option checked will be unchecked. Ruling out incorrect options A technique sometimes adopted by examinees in paper exams is to cross out with a pen any options which are known to be wrong in an attempt to narrow down the list of possibilities. Athough it is not possible to use a pen with online exams, it is possible to click on the text of any option in a Multiple Choice question and it will grey out (i.e. crossed out). Clicking again on a greyed-out option will reinstate it in black. This process of greying out options is simply a visual aid to answering the question; a candidate must still answer the question using the check boxes.','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(6,'Question Types/Extended Matching','<h1>Questions</h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Extended Matching questions are conceptually close to Multiple Response, but differ in that they present with multiple questions/scenarios based around a common theme. Each question has the same list of options (answers) to choose from. Often the number of options will be twice or three times the number of questions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the example below the theme is \'wine tasting\'. The same set of options is used throughout (i.e. Semillon, Gewuztraminer, Pinotage, Sauvignon Blanc, Shiraz, Chardonnay, Merlot, Riesling, Pinot Noir). The examinee should select (or match) one options per question using the dropdown lists.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/matching_question.gif\" alt=\"Questions\" width=\"472\" height=\"523\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"background-color: #f3d593; padding: 5px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Note:</span> If a dropdown list has focus the scroll-wheel on a mouse will alter the selected item. To stop this happening click on an empty part of the screen.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Another issue to check with dropdown menus on some systems is whether all the options are visible. When a large number of options are available some versions of Internet Explorer will employ a scrollbar on the dropdown list. If you see such a scrollbar, as shown below, use it to reveal all the possible options. The correct answer may be off the bottom of the list that is initially visible.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/dropdown_scrolling.png\" alt=\"Scrolling\" width=\"489\" height=\"342\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Questions Extended Matching questions are conceptually close to Multiple Response, but differ in that they present with multiple questions/scenarios based around a common theme. Each question has the same list of options (answers) to choose from. Often the number of options will be twice or three times the number of questions. In the example below the theme is \'wine tasting\'. The same set of options is used throughout (i.e. Semillon, Gewuztraminer, Pinotage, Sauvignon Blanc, Shiraz, Chardonnay, Merlot, Riesling, Pinot Noir). The examinee should select (or match) one options per question using the dropdown lists. Note: If a dropdown list has focus the scroll-wheel on a mouse will alter the selected item. To stop this happening click on an empty part of the screen. Another issue to check with dropdown menus on some systems is whether all the options are visible. When a large number of options are available some versions of Internet Explorer will employ a scrollbar on the dropdown list. If you see such a scrollbar, as shown below, use it to reveal all the possible options. The correct answer may be off the bottom of the list that is initially visible. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(7,'Question Types/Ranking','<h2>Questions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Unlike other question types such as True/False, multiple choice or multiple response, ranking questions do not test the user on which is the correct answer. Instead all the options are already correct; the task to be performed is to rank all the options in the correct order.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the example below the user is asked to rank the nine planets of the solar system by their position starting at one for the planet nearest the Sun.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/rank_question.gif\" alt=\"Question\" width=\"498\" height=\"550\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In some cases a question may only ask you to rank some of the options. In such circumstances always read the question carefully and only rank the number requested.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #800000;\"><strong>Note:</strong><br />When one of the dropdown menus of a ranking question has focus the scroll wheel on a mouse will change the selected answer. If wishing to scroll up and down the page with the mouse wheel always click on an empty area of the question paper before scrolling.</p>','Questions Unlike other question types such as True/False, multiple choice or multiple response, ranking questions do not test the user on which is the correct answer. Instead all the options are already correct; the task to be performed is to rank all the options in the correct order. In the example below the user is asked to rank the nine planets of the solar system by their position starting at one for the planet nearest the Sun. In some cases a question may only ask you to rank some of the options. In such circumstances always read the question carefully and only rank the number requested. Note:When one of the dropdown menus of a ranking question has focus the scroll wheel on a mouse will change the selected answer. If wishing to scroll up and down the page with the mouse wheel always click on an empty area of the question paper before scrolling.','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(8,'Question Types/Likert Scale','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Likert scales are used to elicit opinions on various topics in surveys. Each scale can use between 3 and 10 points. In the exam below each question has a 5 point Likert scale. The user is requested to select a point on the scales for each separate question. As shown below the example in this case has a range between \'Low\' and \'High\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/likert_scale.gif\" alt=\"Likert Scale\" width=\"609\" height=\"372\" /></div>','Likert scales are used to elicit opinions on various topics in surveys. Each scale can use between 3 and 10 points. In the exam below each question has a 5 point Likert scale. The user is requested to select a point on the scales for each separate question. As shown below the example in this case has a range between \'Low\' and \'High\'. ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(9,'Question Types/Fill-in-the-Blank','<h2>Questions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The screenshot below shows a typical Fill-in-the-Blank question example. A paragraph, or paragraphs, of text is displayed on screen with various selected key words removed. In their place drop-down menus are inserted showing the one correct answer and several false distractors. For each blank you must decide which word from the dropdown menu should be selected so that each sentence makes sense.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/blank_question.gif\" alt=\"Question\" width=\"626\" height=\"576\" /></div>','Questions The screenshot below shows a typical Fill-in-the-Blank question example. A paragraph, or paragraphs, of text is displayed on screen with various selected key words removed. In their place drop-down menus are inserted showing the one correct answer and several false distractors. For each blank you must decide which word from the dropdown menu should be selected so that each sentence makes sense. ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(11,'Terms of Use','<p>Usage in any way of Rogo is deemed as implicit acceptance of the terms of use outlined below.</p>\r\n<p>Failure to comply with the terms of use setforth on this page will be considered a disciplinary offence. Users breaking these terms may loose some or all of their rights to access Rogo and possible other e-Learning systems.</p>\r\n<h2>Regulations applicable to all forms of Assessment</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>All students must log in using their own username and password.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Usernames and passwords must not be disclosed to any other individual (this includes peers, family members and staff).</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><small>(Updated 04/11/2004)</small></p>','Usage in any way of Rogo is deemed as implicit acceptance of the terms of use outlined below. Failure to comply with the terms of use setforth on this page will be considered a disciplinary offence. Users breaking these terms may loose some or all of their rights to access Rogo and possible other e-Learning systems. Regulations applicable to all forms of Assessment  All students must log in using their own username and password.  Usernames and passwords must not be disclosed to any other individual (this includes peers, family members and staff).  &nbsp; (Updated 04/11/2004)','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(12,'Navigation','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Navigation is only an issue with exams and surveys consisting of multiple screens. Two forms are possible depending on how the invigilator wishes to conduct the exam: a) unidirectional and b) bidirectional.</p>\r\n<h2>Unidirectional</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In unidirectional mode all questions have to be completed on the current screen before submitting. There is no opportunity to complete previous questions once the user proceeds forwards.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The screenshot below was taken on screen&nbsp;4 of an assessment paper. It only shows a single button to continue to screen 5.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/linear navigation.png\" alt=\"linear navigation.png\" width=\"752\" height=\"242\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Once the \'Screen 3 &gt;\' button is clicked a warning dialog box is display similar to the one below. If the user has completed all questions and is happy with their answers then they should click \'OK\'. Otherwise selecting \'Cancel\' will dismiss the dialog box and keep the user on the current screen.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/continue_warning.gif\" alt=\"Warning Dialog Box\" width=\"485\" height=\"126\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Unidirectional navigation is used on assessment papers which use questions which could result in <em><a href=\"display_page.php?id=16\">consequential error</a></em> or <em><a href=\"display_page.php?id=15\">consequential help</a></em>.</p>\r\n<h2>Bidirectional</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In bidirectional mode the user is free to move around the paper one screen at a time forwards or backwards at the bottom of the screen (see buttons in screenshot below) or by clicking on the appropriate screen numbers in the top left of the screen. Answers are recorded in the database for the current screen whenever the user moves to a different one. No warning label is displayed neither is the warning dialog box which is used with the above unidirectional navigation. The only check that is made is when the user clicks on the \'Finish\' button on the final screen. Clicking \'OK\' on this final check will complete the paper and the user will no longer be able to navigate anymore.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/bidirectional navigation.png\" alt=\"bidirectional navigation.png\" width=\"753\" height=\"191\" /></div>\r\n<p><strong>WARNING!</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Always check to see if the scroll bar is active and there are more questions further down the current screen. A policy of only answering questions on the currently visible part of the screen and then clicking on the next available screen number at the top may inadvertently miss several questions and therefore not pass the examination.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"text-align: left; color: black; border: 0;\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"1\" width=\"40%\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=16\">Consequential Error</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=15\">Consequential Help</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Navigation is only an issue with exams and surveys consisting of multiple screens. Two forms are possible depending on how the invigilator wishes to conduct the exam: a) unidirectional and b) bidirectional. Unidirectional In unidirectional mode all questions have to be completed on the current screen before submitting. There is no opportunity to complete previous questions once the user proceeds forwards. The screenshot below was taken on screen&nbsp;4 of an assessment paper. It only shows a single button to continue to screen 5. &nbsp; Once the \'Screen 3 &gt;\' button is clicked a warning dialog box is display similar to the one below. If the user has completed all questions and is happy with their answers then they should click \'OK\'. Otherwise selecting \'Cancel\' will dismiss the dialog box and keep the user on the current screen. &nbsp; Unidirectional navigation is used on assessment papers which use questions which could result in consequential error or consequential help. Bidirectional In bidirectional mode the user is free to move around the paper one screen at a time forwards or backwards at the bottom of the screen (see buttons in screenshot below) or by clicking on the appropriate screen numbers in the top left of the screen. Answers are recorded in the database for the current screen whenever the user moves to a different one. No warning label is displayed neither is the warning dialog box which is used with the above unidirectional navigation. The only check that is made is when the user clicks on the \'Finish\' button on the final screen. Clicking \'OK\' on this final check will complete the paper and the user will no longer be able to navigate anymore. WARNING! Always check to see if the scroll bar is active and there are more questions further down the current screen. A policy of only answering questions on the currently visible part of the screen and then clicking on the next available screen number at the top may inadvertently miss several questions and therefore not pass the examination. &nbsp; See also: Consequential Error Consequential Help ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(13,'Random Mark','<h2>Purpose</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">With examinations using question types such as dichotomous, multiple choice, multiple response and extended matching, the user is asked to select the correct answer from the list of possible alternatives. However, given the fact that the correct answer is always one of the items in the list, as opposed to a short essay question where no answer is provided, there is always a statistically likelyhood or probability that a user might select the correct answer by chance.</p>\r\n<h2>How it is calculated</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The \'random mark\', the score one would expect is someone answered the questions on a paper at random, is generated by totally the individual random marks for each individual question. Different types of question have different probabilities. For example, with a 5 option multiple choice question there is a 1 in 5 chance that the user will select the right answer by accident. To calculate the random mark in this example the system will take a fifth of the marks for that question. So if the question is worth one mark then the random mark will be 0.2 marks. In another example a dichotomous (True/False) question with only 2 options will have a 1 in 2 chance which results in 0.5 random marks. The system goes through all the questions summing all the individual random marks to produce a final total which is displayed on-screen.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">When the random mark is generated it is used to scale, or factor out, the random element from the user\'s mark. This is done by calculating what is know as an <em>adjusted percentage</em>. To do this the random mark is subtracted from the user\'s <em>raw</em>mark. The same random mark is then subtracted from the total possible marks available for the paper and the two figures expressed as a percentage.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example</strong><br /> Student mark = 150<br /> Total possible marks = 200<br /> Calculated Random mark = 45</p>\r\n<p><strong>Adjusted Percentage:</strong><br /> 150 - 45 = 105<br /> 200 - 45 = 155<br /> (105 / 155) * 100 = 67.7% (adjusted)</p>','Purpose With examinations using question types such as dichotomous, multiple choice, multiple response and extended matching, the user is asked to select the correct answer from the list of possible alternatives. However, given the fact that the correct answer is always one of the items in the list, as opposed to a short essay question where no answer is provided, there is always a statistically likelyhood or probability that a user might select the correct answer by chance. How it is calculated The \'random mark\', the score one would expect is someone answered the questions on a paper at random, is generated by totally the individual random marks for each individual question. Different types of question have different probabilities. For example, with a 5 option multiple choice question there is a 1 in 5 chance that the user will select the right answer by accident. To calculate the random mark in this example the system will take a fifth of the marks for that question. So if the question is worth one mark then the random mark will be 0.2 marks. In another example a dichotomous (True/False) question with only 2 options will have a 1 in 2 chance which results in 0.5 random marks. The system goes through all the questions summing all the individual random marks to produce a final total which is displayed on-screen. When the random mark is generated it is used to scale, or factor out, the random element from the user\'s mark. This is done by calculating what is know as an adjusted percentage. To do this the random mark is subtracted from the user\'s rawmark. The same random mark is then subtracted from the total possible marks available for the paper and the two figures expressed as a percentage. Example Student mark = 150 Total possible marks = 200 Calculated Random mark = 45 Adjusted Percentage: 150 - 45 = 105 200 - 45 = 155 (105 / 155) * 100 = 67.7% (adjusted)','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(14,'Initial Screen','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/initial_screen2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"601\" height=\"309\" class=\"image_no_brd\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The name of the examination/survey paper is shown at the top of the screen.</li>\r\n<li>The <strong>Availability </strong>shows the date/time when the current paper can be completed.</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Candidates</strong> shows who is allowed to complete the paper, this is set by module&nbsp;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>The number of separate <strong>Screens</strong> used in the paper is shown where each screen will contain at least one question, usually several.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>Navigation </strong>will display either: a) unidirectional or b) bidirectional. In unidirectional mode the user will not be permitted to return to previous screens. All questions on the current screen should be attempted before clicking on the submit button. In bidirectional mode this does not matter as the user can move freely backwards and forwards between screens.</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Marks</strong> shows the total available marks for the paper. If the paper is scaled, as in the example above, then the marks will also include in brackets the calculated random mark.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div><strong>Current User </strong>shows the name of the currently logged in user.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>Help </strong>launches the online help system in a new window.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Start &gt;&gt;</strong>starts the exam or survey in a new window.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Previous&nbsp;Completions</strong>&nbsp;are listed below the blue line at the bottom of the screen. This is useful for formative assessment where users wish to monitor their improvement across a year or semester.</li>\r\n</ol>','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe name of the examination/survey paper is shown at the top of the screen.\r\nThe Availability shows the date/time when the current paper can be completed.\r\n\r\nCandidates shows who is allowed to complete the paper, this is set by module&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\nThe number of separate Screens used in the paper is shown where each screen will contain at least one question, usually several.\r\n\r\nNavigation will display either: a) unidirectional or b) bidirectional. In unidirectional mode the user will not be permitted to return to previous screens. All questions on the current screen should be attempted before clicking on the submit button. In bidirectional mode this does not matter as the user can move freely backwards and forwards between screens.\r\n\r\nMarks shows the total available marks for the paper. If the paper is scaled, as in the example above, then the marks will also include in brackets the calculated random mark.\r\n\r\n\r\nCurrent User shows the name of the currently logged in user.\r\n\r\nHelp launches the online help system in a new window.\r\nStart &gt;&gt;starts the exam or survey in a new window.\r\nPrevious&nbsp;Completions&nbsp;are listed below the blue line at the bottom of the screen. This is useful for formative assessment where users wish to monitor their improvement across a year or semester.\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(15,'Consequential Help','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Consequential help can occur in situations where two or more questions are related to each other. Take the following as an example: the user is asked what test to run for a woman who as fainted. This is a new sentence.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/consequential_help1.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"416\" height=\"190\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The user selects \'X-Ray\' as their answer. However, in question 2 they are told that Mrs Jones\' blood sugar level is low. This allows the user to scroll back up to question 1 and change their answer to \'Blood\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/consequential_help2.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"339\" height=\"186\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Two avoid such situations the exam writer should place these two questions on different screens and set the whole assessment paper to <em>unidirectional</em> mode.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"color: black; text-align: left; height: 1px; border: 0px;\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"1\" width=\"40%\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=12\">Navigation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=16\">Consequential Error</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Consequential help can occur in situations where two or more questions are related to each other. Take the following as an example: the user is asked what test to run for a woman who as fainted. This is a new sentence. &nbsp; The user selects \'X-Ray\' as their answer. However, in question 2 they are told that Mrs Jones\' blood sugar level is low. This allows the user to scroll back up to question 1 and change their answer to \'Blood\'. &nbsp; Two avoid such situations the exam writer should place these two questions on different screens and set the whole assessment paper to unidirectional mode. &nbsp; See also: Navigation Consequential Error ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(16,'Consequential Error','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Consequential error can occur in situations where two or more questions are related to each other. Take the following as an example: in the first question the user is asked which is the largest company. Unfortunately they incorrectly answer \'Marks and Spencer\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/consequential_error1.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"308\" height=\"202\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In question 2 they are asked what this company\'s primary line of business is. Here they answer \'Retail\' which matches \'Marks and Spencer\'. However, they score zero for both questions since \'Microsoft\' is the biggest company and its line of business is \'Software\'.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/consequential_error2.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"318\" height=\"196\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Two avoid such situations the exam writer should place these two questions on different screens and set the whole assessment paper to <em>unidirectional</em> mode. The second question on the following screen should be amended to read \'Microsoft is the largest company. What is its primary business?\' thus setting any erroneous students back on track.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr style=\"color: black; text-align: left; border: 0; height: 1px;\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"1\" width=\"40%\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=12\">Navigation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=15\">Consequential Help</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Consequential error can occur in situations where two or more questions are related to each other. Take the following as an example: in the first question the user is asked which is the largest company. Unfortunately they incorrectly answer \'Marks and Spencer\'. &nbsp; In question 2 they are asked what this company\'s primary line of business is. Here they answer \'Retail\' which matches \'Marks and Spencer\'. However, they score zero for both questions since \'Microsoft\' is the biggest company and its line of business is \'Software\'. &nbsp; Two avoid such situations the exam writer should place these two questions on different screens and set the whole assessment paper to unidirectional mode. The second question on the following screen should be amended to read \'Microsoft is the largest company. What is its primary business?\' thus setting any erroneous students back on track. &nbsp; See also: Navigation Consequential Help ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(17,'Data Protection','<h2>Right of Subject Access</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Data Protection Act provides that upon making a request in writing (which includes transmission by electronic means) and upon paying the appropriate fee to the University, an individual is entitled to be told by the University whether they, or someone else on the University\'s behalf, is processing that individuals\' personal data, and if so, to be given a description of:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>the personal data;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>the purposes for which they are being processed; and</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>those to whom they are or may be disclosed.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The University will not comply with a request where it has already complied with an identical or similar request by the same individual unless a reasonable interval has elapsed between compliance with the previous request and the making of the current request</p>\r\n<h2>Under the terms of the Act, you have to provide the University with the following before the subject access request can be processed:</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Your request in writing (which includes transmission by electronic means)</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">The information you require (which has to be sufficient to enable the University to locate the data which are sought).</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">The fee of &pound;10 is payable to&nbsp;cover administration costs.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">You should note that, by the terms of the Act, the University has to consider its duty of confidentiality to any other individual involved. This may involve obtaining the consent of other individuals to disclose the data. You will be informed if consent has not been given. You are also required to provide proof of your identity sufficient to satisfy the University before it will release any data. You will receive a response to your request within 40 days of receipt of a completed subject access request form, accompanying fee and proof of identification.</p>\r\n<h2>Rogo data</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The table belows shows the database table structure for information recorded for each user sitting an assessment or survey in Rogo. One database record is written per user per question so a single user may have as many as 150 records stored for a single examination paper. Data is recorded and stored for all paper types: formative, progess tests, summative exams and surveys.</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">id</td>\r\n<td>System administration only.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">username</td>\r\n<td>Username of the currently log in user. This can be cross referenced with the personal data (see below) to establish title, last name and email address of the user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">started</td>\r\n<td>The date/time when an assessment or survey was started by the current user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">q_paper</td>\r\n<td>The ID of the assessment/survey.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">q_id</td>\r\n<td>The numeric ID of the current question.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">mark</td>\r\n<td>The mark awarded to the user for the current question (not applicable to surveys).</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">totalpos</td>\r\n<td>The total possible marks available for the current question (not applicable to surveys).</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">user answer</td>\r\n<td>The answer provided by the user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">duration</td>\r\n<td>The duration, measured in seconds, that the user spent on the current screen.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">screen</td>\r\n<td>The number of the screen.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">ipaddress</td>\r\n<td>The IP address of the computer at which the assessment/survey was sat.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Personal data</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The table belows shows the database table structure for information stored for each user regarding authentication details. This data is used to verify that the user (staff or student) has a right to access Rogo and once given access which particular functions they are allowed to use within the system.</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">username</td>\r\n<td>The&nbsp;username of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">password</td>\r\n<td>The password of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">title</td>\r\n<td>The title (Mr, Mrs, Ms, etc) of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">initials</td>\r\n<td>The initials of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">forenames</td>\r\n<td>The forenames of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">last name</td>\r\n<td>The last name (family name) of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">degree programme</td>\r\n<td>The degree program (A100, A101, A300, etc) a user is registered for.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">year</td>\r\n<td>The year of study a user is registered for.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">roles</td>\r\n<td>The roles assigned to a user (usually \'Staff\' or \'Student\').</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">email address</td>\r\n<td>The email address of a user.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"background-color: #e5e5e5;\">modules</td>\r\n<td>A list of all the modules the user is registered on.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Right of Subject Access\r\nThe Data Protection Act provides that upon making a request in writing (which includes transmission by electronic means) and upon paying the appropriate fee to the University, an individual is entitled to be told by the University whether they, or someone else on the University\'s behalf, is processing that individuals\' personal data, and if so, to be given a description of:\r\n\r\n\r\nthe personal data;\r\n\r\n\r\nthe purposes for which they are being processed; and\r\n\r\n\r\nthose to whom they are or may be disclosed.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe University will not comply with a request where it has already complied with an identical or similar request by the same individual unless a reasonable interval has elapsed between compliance with the previous request and the making of the current request\r\nUnder the terms of the Act, you have to provide the University with the following before the subject access request can be processed:\r\n\r\nYour request in writing (which includes transmission by electronic means)\r\nThe information you require (which has to be sufficient to enable the University to locate the data which are sought).\r\nThe fee of &pound;10 is payable to&nbsp;cover administration costs.\r\n\r\nYou should note that, by the terms of the Act, the University has to consider its duty of confidentiality to any other individual involved. This may involve obtaining the consent of other individuals to disclose the data. You will be informed if consent has not been given. You are also required to provide proof of your identity sufficient to satisfy the University before it will release any data. You will receive a response to your request within 40 days of receipt of a completed subject access request form, accompanying fee and proof of identification.\r\nRogo data\r\nThe table belows shows the database table structure for information recorded for each user sitting an assessment or survey in Rogo. One database record is written per user per question so a single user may have as many as 150 records stored for a single examination paper. Data is recorded and stored for all paper types: formative, progess tests, summative exams and surveys.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nid\r\nSystem administration only.\r\n\r\n\r\nusername\r\nUsername of the currently log in user. This can be cross referenced with the personal data (see below) to establish title, last name and email address of the user.\r\n\r\n\r\nstarted\r\nThe date/time when an assessment or survey was started by the current user.\r\n\r\n\r\nq_paper\r\nThe ID of the assessment/survey.\r\n\r\n\r\nq_id\r\nThe numeric ID of the current question.\r\n\r\n\r\nmark\r\nThe mark awarded to the user for the current question (not applicable to surveys).\r\n\r\n\r\ntotalpos\r\nThe total possible marks available for the current question (not applicable to surveys).\r\n\r\n\r\nuser answer\r\nThe answer provided by the user.\r\n\r\n\r\nduration\r\nThe duration, measured in seconds, that the user spent on the current screen.\r\n\r\n\r\nscreen\r\nThe number of the screen.\r\n\r\n\r\nipaddress\r\nThe IP address of the computer at which the assessment/survey was sat.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nPersonal data\r\nThe table belows shows the database table structure for information stored for each user regarding authentication details. This data is used to verify that the user (staff or student) has a right to access Rogo and once given access which particular functions they are allowed to use within the system.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nusername\r\nThe&nbsp;username of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\npassword\r\nThe password of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\ntitle\r\nThe title (Mr, Mrs, Ms, etc) of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\ninitials\r\nThe initials of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\nforenames\r\nThe forenames of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\nlast name\r\nThe last name (family name) of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\ndegree programme\r\nThe degree program (A100, A101, A300, etc) a user is registered for.\r\n\r\n\r\nyear\r\nThe year of study a user is registered for.\r\n\r\n\r\nroles\r\nThe roles assigned to a user (usually \'Staff\' or \'Student\').\r\n\r\n\r\nemail address\r\nThe email address of a user.\r\n\r\n\r\nmodules\r\nA list of all the modules the user is registered on.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(18,'Types of Questions','<h2>Assessment Question Types</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=44\">Area</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=25\">Calculation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=3\">Dichotomous</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=6\">Extended Matching</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=9\">Fill-in-the-Blank</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=19\">Image Hotspot</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=24\">Labelling</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=4\">Multiple Choice</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=5\">Multiple Response</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=7\">Ranking</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Survey Question Types</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=8\">Likert Scale</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"display_page.php?id=20\">Textbox</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Assessment Question Types Area Calculation Dichotomous Extended Matching Fill-in-the-Blank Image Hotspot Labelling Multiple Choice Multiple Response Ranking Survey Question Types Likert Scale Textbox ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(19,'Question Types/Image Hotspot','<h2>Questions</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This question type displays a graphic with an instruction to click on a specific part of the graphic. The example shown below has two items that need to be identified (A and B).&nbsp;To answer part A, select part A from the options on the left then click on the area of the graphic that shows that item.&nbsp;The same process can then be completed for B.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you change your mind you can change your selection by clicking on a different part of the graphic.You can see from the screenshot below that markers show the areas that have been selected.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/image hotspot feedback.png\" alt=\"image hotspot feedback.png\" width=\"1023\" height=\"746\" /></p>','Questions This question type displays a graphic with an instruction to click on a specific part of the graphic. The example shown below has two items that need to be identified (A and B).&nbsp;To answer part A, select part A from the options on the left then click on the area of the graphic that shows that item.&nbsp;The same process can then be completed for B. If you change your mind you can change your selection by clicking on a different part of the graphic.You can see from the screenshot below that markers show the areas that have been selected. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(20,'Question Types/Textbox','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Textboxes are used to elicit open-ended feedback in surveys. Unless otherwise stated the comments made in a textbox will always be treated anonymously.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/textbox.gif\" alt=\"Textbox\" width=\"640\" height=\"274\" /></div>','Textboxes are used to elicit open-ended feedback in surveys. Unless otherwise stated the comments made in a textbox will always be treated anonymously. ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(22,'Fire Exits','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Fire Exit icons (one in each corner of the screen) will only be displayed for <span style=\"font-style: italic;\">summative</span> papers.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/fire_exit.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"548\" height=\"114\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the event of a real fire evacuation invigilators will instruct all examinees to click on any one of the four fire exit icons. This will do two things:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Examinees answers will be sent back to the server for recording. This allows a record of attempted questions in the event that there is a real fire and some of the client computers are destroyed.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">The second thing which will happen is the screen will be blanked with the following notice (see below). This is to stop examinees being able to look at peers answers while evacuating the room.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/fire_exit2.png\" alt=\"Fire Exit\" width=\"566\" height=\"90\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Fire Exit icons (one in each corner of the screen) will only be displayed for summative papers. &nbsp; &nbsp; In the event of a real fire evacuation invigilators will instruct all examinees to click on any one of the four fire exit icons. This will do two things: Examinees answers will be sent back to the server for recording. This allows a record of attempted questions in the event that there is a real fire and some of the client computers are destroyed. The second thing which will happen is the screen will be blanked with the following notice (see below). This is to stop examinees being able to look at peers answers while evacuating the room.  &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(23,'Calculator','<p>Certain papers may have a software calculator included for performing mathematical calculations. This facility is provided at the discretion of the exam writer. If a calculator is provided a small icon to launch it will be displayed just below each question number.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/calc_icon_on_paper.png\" alt=\"calc_icon_on_paper.png\" width=\"852\" height=\"229\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Clicking on this icon will popup in a new window a JavaScript calculator. It goes without saying that JavaScript must be enabled in your browser for this calculator to work. The default mode of the calculator can be seen below:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/calc_ui.png\" alt=\"calc_ui.png\" width=\"270\" height=\"433\" class=\"image_no_brd\" />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Keyboard Shortcuts</h2>\r\n<table style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Key</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>Calculator Function</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>0</td>\r\n<td>Zero</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>1</td>\r\n<td>One</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>2</td>\r\n<td>Two</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>3</td>\r\n<td>Three</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>4</td>\r\n<td>Four</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>5</td>\r\n<td>Five</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>6</td>\r\n<td>Six</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>7</td>\r\n<td>Seven</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>8</td>\r\n<td>Eight</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>9</td>\r\n<td>Nine</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>+</td>\r\n<td>Plus</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>-</td>\r\n<td>Minus</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>/</td>\r\n<td>Divide</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>*</td>\r\n<td>Multiply</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>=</td>\r\n<td>Equals</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>DELETE</td>\r\n<td>AC</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Certain papers may have a software calculator included for performing mathematical calculations. This facility is provided at the discretion of the exam writer. If a calculator is provided a small icon to launch it will be displayed just below each question number.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nClicking on this icon will popup in a new window a JavaScript calculator. It goes without saying that JavaScript must be enabled in your browser for this calculator to work. The default mode of the calculator can be seen below:\r\n&nbsp;\r\nKeyboard Shortcuts\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nKey\r\nCalculator Function\r\n\r\n\r\n0\r\nZero\r\n\r\n\r\n1\r\nOne\r\n\r\n\r\n2\r\nTwo\r\n\r\n\r\n3\r\nThree\r\n\r\n\r\n4\r\nFour\r\n\r\n\r\n5\r\nFive\r\n\r\n\r\n6\r\nSix\r\n\r\n\r\n7\r\nSeven\r\n\r\n\r\n8\r\nEight\r\n\r\n\r\n9\r\nNine\r\n\r\n\r\n+\r\nPlus\r\n\r\n\r\n-\r\nMinus\r\n\r\n\r\n/\r\nDivide\r\n\r\n\r\n*\r\nMultiply\r\n\r\n\r\n=\r\nEquals\r\n\r\n\r\nDELETE\r\nAC\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(43,'Marking','<h1>General marking features</h1>\r\n<p>Where questions have a number of parts that can be marked independently the Marking Method can be set to&nbsp;mark either by question or by option. The question types that is relevant to are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Dichotomous</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Extended Matching</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Fill-in-the-Blank</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Image Hotspot</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Labelling</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Matrix</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Multiple Response</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Ranking</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;Negative marking</h2>\r\n<p>If negative marking is being used, it will be stated under the question (see graphic below).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/neg marking.png\" alt=\"neg marking.png\" width=\"795\" height=\"271\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Question specific Marking Methods</h1>\r\n<h2>Ranking</h2>\r\n<p>The Ranking question type has two additional Marking Methods:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Allow partial Marks</strong> - Partial marks are awarded where options have been selected one&nbsp;place away from the correct place, e.g. 2nd rather than 3rd</p>\r\n<p><strong>Bonus Mark</strong> - A bonus mark is awarded when every option is in the correct place.</p>\r\n<h2>Calculation</h2>\r\n<p>Some calculation questions are set to give partial&nbsp;marks&nbsp;for answers that are within a selected tolerance of the correct answer.</p>','General marking features Where questions have a number of parts that can be marked independently the Marking Method can be set to&nbsp;mark either by question or by option. The question types that is relevant to are:  Dichotomous  Extended Matching  Fill-in-the-Blank  Image Hotspot  Labelling  Matrix  Multiple Response  Ranking  &nbsp; &nbsp;Negative marking If negative marking is being used, it will be stated under the question (see graphic below). &nbsp; &nbsp; Question specific Marking Methods Ranking The Ranking question type has two additional Marking Methods: Allow partial Marks - Partial marks are awarded where options have been selected one&nbsp;place away from the correct place, e.g. 2nd rather than 3rd Bonus Mark - A bonus mark is awarded when every option is in the correct place. Calculation Some calculation questions are set to give partial&nbsp;marks&nbsp;for answers that are within a selected tolerance of the correct answer.','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(24,'Question Types/Labelling (drag \'n drop)','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Labelling questions&nbsp;have a&nbsp;graphic with a number of empty rectangular \'placeholders\' over it. On the left hand side will be a number of similarly sized rectangular labels. In the example show below there are four labels that can be selected&nbsp;to be added to the two spaces on the graphic. The examinee must click on&nbsp;a label and drag it to&nbsp;the&nbsp;matching placeholder. When the label is dragged close enough to a&nbsp;placeholder it&nbsp;will snap into place. Always check that each answer has snapped correctly into its placeholder to be sure of getting a mark for that part of the question.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/labelling.png\" alt=\"labelling.png\" width=\"1004\" height=\"699\" /></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Presentation Labelling questions&nbsp;have a&nbsp;graphic with a number of empty rectangular \'placeholders\' over it. On the left hand side will be a number of similarly sized rectangular labels. In the example show below there are four labels that can be selected&nbsp;to be added to the two spaces on the graphic. The examinee must click on&nbsp;a label and drag it to&nbsp;the&nbsp;matching placeholder. When the label is dragged close enough to a&nbsp;placeholder it&nbsp;will snap into place. Always check that each answer has snapped correctly into its placeholder to be sure of getting a mark for that part of the question. &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(25,'Question Types/Calculation','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Calculation questions use one or more variables (calculated random values) to present numeric questions which change each time the paper is attempted. In the example below, concerning questionnaire response rates, two variables are used: the first is a random number between 300 and 800 (incrementing in 100 values), and the second variable is a random integer between 10 and the calculated value of the first variable.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/calculation_question1.png\" alt=\"Calculation question presentation\" width=\"556\" height=\"145\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br />There may be questions that use your answer to a previous calculation question as one of the values in the new question. If you answered the first calculation question incorrectly you will not be penalised in the second question. You will be awarded the marks set for the question if you have correclty answered the question based on the values given.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Note for very small or large number answers:</strong> Do <strong>not </strong>use exponential indication (e.g. 1e-5 or 1x10<sup>-5</sup>) for large or small numbers since this format does not register and you will be awarded zero. Note the units of each answer, where required, are stated next to the answer box.</p>','Presentation Calculation questions use one or more variables (calculated random values) to present numeric questions which change each time the paper is attempted. In the example below, concerning questionnaire response rates, two variables are used: the first is a random number between 300 and 800 (incrementing in 100 values), and the second variable is a random integer between 10 and the calculated value of the first variable. There may be questions that use your answer to a previous calculation question as one of the values in the new question. If you answered the first calculation question incorrectly you will not be penalised in the second question. You will be awarded the marks set for the question if you have correclty answered the question based on the values given. Note for very small or large number answers: Do not use exponential indication (e.g. 1e-5 or 1x10-5) for large or small numbers since this format does not register and you will be awarded zero. Note the units of each answer, where required, are stated next to the answer box.','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(26,'Clock','<p>A clock is available in the bottom status bar of each screen which shows the current tim (not the time remaining):</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"images/exam_clock.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"825\" height=\"235\" />&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The clock is created using JavaScript and as such takes its time from the client computer, not the server. Do not rely upon for split second accuracy.</p>','A clock is available in the bottom status bar of each screen which shows the current tim (not the time remaining): &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Note: The clock is created using JavaScript and as such takes its time from the client computer, not the server. Do not rely upon for split second accuracy.','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(27,'Health and Safety','<h1>VDUs</h1>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">VDUs have been blamed, usually wrongly, for a wide range of health problems. In fact, most problems occur because of the way the equipment is set up and used, rather than the equipment itself. A few simple guidelines can help to keep you comfortable when taking an online exam.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Sitting position</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Perform the following checks and make adjustments where necessary as soon as you are seated at a workstation. If you believe the setup of your workstation may adversely affect your performance please inform an invigilator before the exam begins.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Try to adjust the chair so that as you type and use the mouse your forearms are horizontal and your eyes are the same height as the top of the screen.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Place your feet flat on the floor and keep your legs uncrossed.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Position the mouse within easy reach and sit upright and close to the desk so that your mouse arm is not stretched. Support it on the desk so that it is relaxed.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Don\'t grip the mouse too tightly and rest your fingers lightly on the buttons.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Move the keyboard out of the way if it is not being used.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Adjust the brightness/contrast of the screen if ncessary.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Characters on the screen should be in focus and not flickering or moving. If you have a problem with your monitor, inform an invigilator - there are always spare screens.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/vdu_position.jpg\" alt=\"vdu seating position\" width=\"351\" height=\"345\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Can work with a VDU affect my eyesight?</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Extensive research has found no evidence that VDUs can cause disease or permanent damage to the eyes. However, long spells of VDU work can lead to tired eyes and discomfort. To reduce this:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Try to look away from the screen occasionally so that your eyes can change their focus.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Remember to bring glasses if you need them.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Get your eyes tested at least every two years.</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr style=\"color: black; text-align: left; border: 0;\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"1\" />\r\n<p><strong>See also:</strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href=\"images/indg36.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"image_no_brd\" src=\"images/pdf.gif\" alt=\"PDF\" width=\"32\" height=\"32\" /></a></td>\r\n<td><a href=\"images/indg36.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Working with VDUs</a><br />by the Health and Safety Executive</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','VDUs\r\nVDUs have been blamed, usually wrongly, for a wide range of health problems. In fact, most problems occur because of the way the equipment is set up and used, rather than the equipment itself. A few simple guidelines can help to keep you comfortable when taking an online exam.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSitting position\r\nPerform the following checks and make adjustments where necessary as soon as you are seated at a workstation. If you believe the setup of your workstation may adversely affect your performance please inform an invigilator before the exam begins.\r\n\r\n\r\nTry to adjust the chair so that as you type and use the mouse your forearms are horizontal and your eyes are the same height as the top of the screen.\r\n\r\n\r\nPlace your feet flat on the floor and keep your legs uncrossed.\r\n\r\n\r\nPosition the mouse within easy reach and sit upright and close to the desk so that your mouse arm is not stretched. Support it on the desk so that it is relaxed.\r\n\r\n\r\nDon\'t grip the mouse too tightly and rest your fingers lightly on the buttons.\r\n\r\n\r\nMove the keyboard out of the way if it is not being used.\r\n\r\n\r\nAdjust the brightness/contrast of the screen if ncessary.\r\n\r\n\r\nCharacters on the screen should be in focus and not flickering or moving. If you have a problem with your monitor, inform an invigilator - there are always spare screens.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCan work with a VDU affect my eyesight?\r\nExtensive research has found no evidence that VDUs can cause disease or permanent damage to the eyes. However, long spells of VDU work can lead to tired eyes and discomfort. To reduce this:\r\n\r\n\r\nTry to look away from the screen occasionally so that your eyes can change their focus.\r\n\r\n\r\nRemember to bring glasses if you need them.\r\n\r\n\r\nGet your eyes tested at least every two years.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSee also:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWorking with VDUsby the Health and Safety Executive\r\n\r\n\r\n','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(31,'About Rogo','<p>Rogo is the online assessment system created at the&nbsp;University of Nottingham.&nbsp; It is used to create Self-assessment quizzes&nbsp;and&nbsp;Summative exams&nbsp;(only available during the scheduled exam period).</p>','Rogo is the online assessment system created at the&nbsp;University of Nottingham.&nbsp; It is used to create Self-assessment quizzes&nbsp;and&nbsp;Summative exams&nbsp;(only available during the scheduled exam period).','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(32,'Summative Exam Guidelines','<h2>Before Exam</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Students that require adjustments to examination arrangements must arrange an appointment with academic support before examinations take place.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Formative self assessment papers&nbsp;allow students to:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Gain familiarity with question types</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>Gauge acquisition of subject matter</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>On the day of each exam ensure that you arrive 15 mins before the start of the exam.</p>\r\n<h2>During the&nbsp;Exam</h2>\r\n<div>Exams cannot be left under the following conditions:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>before 1 hour of the exam has passed</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>within the&nbsp;last 15 mins</div>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<div>if there are 2 sittings of the exam</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you are taking an exam where no calculators&nbsp;can be taken into the exam but they are required,&nbsp;an online calculator will&nbsp;be provided.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The screenshot below shows some of the features of Rogo exam papers.&nbsp; Q7 shows one greyed out option.&nbsp; Options that you want to \'rule out\' can be greyed out by clicking once.&nbsp; This feature is just to help you select the correct answer and is not assessed.&nbsp; Q8 is highlighted in red to show that the question has not yet been answered, the highlight only appears when you return to a screen that you have previously visited.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">There is clock on the bottom band of the screen and a fire exit icon at each corner of the screen.&nbsp; The fire exit is clicked on if there is a fire alarm and you have been instructed to leave the room.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/summ exam guide1.png\" alt=\"summ exam guide1.png\" /></div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If there is a problem at the workstation that you are working at, you will be moved to a different PC.&nbsp; Extra time will be given to address any time that you have lost.</p>\r\n<h2>Post Exam</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">If the questions in your exam have been mapped to objectives, feedback on your Learning objectives aquisition&nbsp;will be available. This feedback allows you to identify which areas you have not yet fully mastered and need to focus on.&nbsp; Exam marks will be available on the Portal.</span>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/student_feedback insight 2.png\" alt=\"student_feedback insight 2.png\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Before Exam Students that require adjustments to examination arrangements must arrange an appointment with academic support before examinations take place.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; Formative self assessment papers&nbsp;allow students to:  Gain familiarity with question types  Gauge acquisition of subject matter  On the day of each exam ensure that you arrive 15 mins before the start of the exam. During the&nbsp;Exam Exams cannot be left under the following conditions: &nbsp;  before 1 hour of the exam has passed  within the&nbsp;last 15 mins  if there are 2 sittings of the exam  &nbsp; If you are taking an exam where no calculators&nbsp;can be taken into the exam but they are required,&nbsp;an online calculator will&nbsp;be provided.&nbsp; &nbsp; The screenshot below shows some of the features of Rogo exam papers.&nbsp; Q7 shows one greyed out option.&nbsp; Options that you want to \'rule out\' can be greyed out by clicking once.&nbsp; This feature is just to help you select the correct answer and is not assessed.&nbsp; Q8 is highlighted in red to show that the question has not yet been answered, the highlight only appears when you return to a screen that you have previously visited. &nbsp; There is clock on the bottom band of the screen and a fire exit icon at each corner of the screen.&nbsp; The fire exit is clicked on if there is a fire alarm and you have been instructed to leave the room. &nbsp; If there is a problem at the workstation that you are working at, you will be moved to a different PC.&nbsp; Extra time will be given to address any time that you have lost. Post Exam If the questions in your exam have been mapped to objectives, feedback on your Learning objectives aquisition&nbsp;will be available. This feedback allows you to identify which areas you have not yet fully mastered and need to focus on.&nbsp; Exam marks will be available on the Portal.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(33,'Extenuating Circumstances','<p>If you believe your&nbsp;assessment performance may be, or has been, affected adversely by a significant factor then you should complete an extenuating circumstances form within 7 days of the circumstance arising.</p>\r\n<p>Additional guidance is available from:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/academicservices/qualitymanual/assessment/extenuatingcircumstances.aspx\" target=\"_new\">Extenuating Circumstances Procedures and Guidance</a></li>\r\n</ul>','If you believe your&nbsp;assessment performance may be, or has been, affected adversely by a significant factor then you should complete an extenuating circumstances form within 7 days of the circumstance arising. Additional guidance is available from: Extenuating Circumstances Procedures and Guidance ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(35,'Feedback/Summative Feedback','<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Learning objective-based feedback can be provided after online exams if the questions have been mapped to objectives. Instead of showing which questions you have got right and wrong specifically, it will show a little bit more generally which learning objectives you have achieved and which you have not. A rough traffic lights system is employed whereby green signifies wholly/mainly achieved, amber partially achieved and red mainly not achieved. You should use this objectives-based feedback as a guide to focusing on topics you may wish to study further. If there is a hyperlink at the end of the objective then this will link back to the VLE for further materials/information.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Icons</strong></div>\r\n<div>Green=wholly/mainly achieved, Amber=partially achieved, and Red=mainly not achieved.</div>\r\n<div><strong>Your Mark</strong></div>\r\n<div>Shows the number of marks of questions linked to each objective together with the number of marks you actually scored on these questions.</div>\r\n<div><strong>Relative</strong></div>\r\n<div>Show the average number of marks relative to the whole cohort. So, for example, a score of +0.1 means you scored 0.1 more marks than students in the cohort did on average for this learning objective.</div>\r\n<div><strong>Q no</strong></div>\r\n<div>The number of questions linked to a particular learning objective.</div>\r\n<div><strong>Objective</strong></div>\r\n<div>The text of the learning objective itself.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/exam_feedback.png\" alt=\"exam_feedback.png\" /></div>','Learning objective-based feedback can be provided after online exams if the questions have been mapped to objectives. Instead of showing which questions you have got right and wrong specifically, it will show a little bit more generally which learning objectives you have achieved and which you have not. A rough traffic lights system is employed whereby green signifies wholly/mainly achieved, amber partially achieved and red mainly not achieved. You should use this objectives-based feedback as a guide to focusing on topics you may wish to study further. If there is a hyperlink at the end of the objective then this will link back to the VLE for further materials/information. &nbsp; Icons Green=wholly/mainly achieved, Amber=partially achieved, and Red=mainly not achieved. Your Mark Shows the number of marks of questions linked to each objective together with the number of marks you actually scored on these questions. Relative Show the average number of marks relative to the whole cohort. So, for example, a score of +0.1 means you scored 0.1 more marks than students in the cohort did on average for this learning objective. Q no The number of questions linked to a particular learning objective. Objective The text of the learning objective itself. &nbsp; ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(37,'Tips for best use','<div>These are tips that will help you use Rogo in the most effective way, particularly during exams.</div>\r\n<h2>Greying out options</h2>\r\n<div>When you have questions with a number of options to select from it can be useful to grey out options that you are sure are incorrect. The candidate in the screenshot below has dismissed Lincoln and Leeds to narrow down the choice to three possible contenders. To grey out an option click on the text of the option. To bring it back to black simply click again on it.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/student tip greyout.png\" alt=\"student tip greyout.png\" width=\"631\" height=\"200\" /></p>\r\n<div><strong>Note:</strong> It is important to always answer the question by clicking on one of the radio buttons. Greying out four options and leaving one black will not answer the question.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Unanswered questions</h2>\r\n<div>When you move back to screens that contain unanswered questions, these questions are highlighted as a reminder.</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/unanswered questions.png\" alt=\"unanswered questions.png\" width=\"571\" height=\"326\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Use of the online calculator</h2>\r\n<div>You can use the mouse to select options in the online calculator but you may find it easier to use the numeric keypad on the right edge of the keyboard. You must make sure that the Num Lock is on.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Questions that require more than one option to be selected</h2>\r\n<div>Some questions require you to select more than one correct answer where you must hold down the Ctrl key as you click the second option. This instruction is shown on the screen, the text is underlined in the screenshot below.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/multi extend match.png\" alt=\"multi extend match.png\" width=\"766\" height=\"284\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','These are tips that will help you use Rogo in the most effective way, particularly during exams. Greying out options When you have questions with a number of options to select from it can be useful to grey out options that you are sure are incorrect. The candidate in the screenshot below has dismissed Lincoln and Leeds to narrow down the choice to three possible contenders. To grey out an option click on the text of the option. To bring it back to black simply click again on it. &nbsp; Note: It is important to always answer the question by clicking on one of the radio buttons. Greying out four options and leaving one black will not answer the question. &nbsp; Unanswered questions When you move back to screens that contain unanswered questions, these questions are highlighted as a reminder. Use of the online calculator You can use the mouse to select options in the online calculator but you may find it easier to use the numeric keypad on the right edge of the keyboard. You must make sure that the Num Lock is on. &nbsp; Questions that require more than one option to be selected Some questions require you to select more than one correct answer where you must hold down the Ctrl key as you click the second option. This instruction is shown on the screen, the text is underlined in the screenshot below. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(38,'Formative Assessment','<div align=\"left\">Links to Self Assessments&nbsp;can be made&nbsp;available through&nbsp;your VLE or directly from a URL. The questions in these tests are in the same format as those used in the Summative Exams. The difference between these 2 types of assessment are that the Formative Assessments include feedback.&nbsp; It is very useful for you to complete these self assessments to identify any gaps in your knowledge and also to become familiar with types of questions used in Formative exams.</div>\r\n<div align=\"left\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/student formative feedback2.png\" alt=\"student formative feedback2.png\" width=\"634\" height=\"352\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>In addition to the feedback shown in the graphic above, questions that have been standards set will show the rating as part of the feedback. This is shown in the graphic below where the Orange boxes show ratings, e.g EE is Easy Essential.</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/std_set_feedback.png\" alt=\"std_set_feedback.png\" width=\"728\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Standards Setting ratings</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; width: 720px; border-collapse: collapse;\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EE</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Easy-Essential</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">ME</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Medium-Essential</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HE</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Hard-Essential</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Easy-Important</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">MI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Medium-Important</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Hard-Important</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Easy-Nice to know</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">MN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Medium-Nice to know</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">&nbsp;Hard--Nice to know</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Links to Self Assessments&nbsp;can be made&nbsp;available through&nbsp;your VLE or directly from a URL. The questions in these tests are in the same format as those used in the Summative Exams. The difference between these 2 types of assessment are that the Formative Assessments include feedback.&nbsp; It is very useful for you to complete these self assessments to identify any gaps in your knowledge and also to become familiar with types of questions used in Formative exams. &nbsp; &nbsp; In addition to the feedback shown in the graphic above, questions that have been standards set will show the rating as part of the feedback. This is shown in the graphic below where the Orange boxes show ratings, e.g EE is Easy Essential. &nbsp; &nbsp; Standards Setting ratings &nbsp; &nbsp;   EE &nbsp;Easy-Essential ME &nbsp;Medium-Essential HE &nbsp;Hard-Essential  EI &nbsp;Easy-Important MI &nbsp;Medium-Important HI &nbsp;Hard-Important  EN &nbsp;Easy-Nice to know MN &nbsp;Medium-Nice to know HN &nbsp;Hard--Nice to know   &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(44,'Question Types/Area','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Area question requires students to trace around a particular part of an image using either freehand and/or series of individual points connected by straight lines.</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Answering</strong></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To answer move the mouse over the image and single click to create a starting point. Next either keep the mouse button depressed (freehand) or release mouse button and move to next point (straightline). When at the next&nbsp;location on the edge of the area&nbsp;click again with the mouse and another point will appear. Repeat this selection of points all the way around the area until back at the starting point (green dot). As a shortcut the user may double-click to insert a point at the current mouse location and automatically join up with the start point.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"images/area_question.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"384\" height=\"506\" /></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Adjusting&nbsp;Answer</strong></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are two main ways to adjust, or edit, an answer. The first is to click and drag&nbsp;the square points (in black). This will adjust the two connected lines with the current point\'s neighbours. The second type of adjustment that can be made is to click and drag one of the circle points (in white). This will break a line in two and insert a square point in the centre. This can be used to insert additional points for a more accurate overall shape. To remove a point (black square) first select \'Delete point\' from the toolbar and then click the point to be removed.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>','Presentation Area question requires students to trace around a particular part of an image using either freehand and/or series of individual points connected by straight lines. Answering To answer move the mouse over the image and single click to create a starting point. Next either keep the mouse button depressed (freehand) or release mouse button and move to next point (straightline). When at the next&nbsp;location on the edge of the area&nbsp;click again with the mouse and another point will appear. Repeat this selection of points all the way around the area until back at the starting point (green dot). As a shortcut the user may double-click to insert a point at the current mouse location and automatically join up with the start point. Adjusting&nbsp;Answer There are two main ways to adjust, or edit, an answer. The first is to click and drag&nbsp;the square points (in black). This will adjust the two connected lines with the current point\'s neighbours. The second type of adjustment that can be made is to click and drag one of the circle points (in white). This will break a line in two and insert a square point in the centre. This can be used to insert additional points for a more accurate overall shape. To remove a point (black square) first select \'Delete point\' from the toolbar and then click the point to be removed. &nbsp;&nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(39,'Feedback/Formative Feedback','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Feedback options are set for individual papers and may include the following:</p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\">Correct Answers/Text Feedback</h2>\r\n<div>The text feedback on the graphic below gives specific feedback for the options selected and the correct option that was missed by the student.</div>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/student formative feedback2.png\" alt=\"student formative feedback2.png\" width=\"634\" height=\"352\" /></p>\r\n<h2>Learning Objectives</h2>\r\n<p>If a paper has been mapped to learning objectives then these will appear beneath the question. They remind the student of the board topic area.</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/feedback_objectives.png\" alt=\"feedback_objectives.png\" width=\"700\" height=\"329\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Standards Setting</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is possible to standards set the questions in a paper and then to display this information to students on the feedback screen. The abbreviations are explained below, for example EE is Easy/Essential. Providing standards setting feedback in addition to the standard correct answer can provide an extra level of detail for students. For example most students should be getting Easy/Essential correct, but it is less important if some Hard/Nice to Know questions are answered incorrectly. Vice versa a student answering Hard/Nice to Know correctly may be on track for an honours degree award.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"image_brd\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"images/std_set_feedback.png\" alt=\"std_set_feedback.png\" width=\"728\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Standards Setting ratings</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; width: 600px; margin-left: 30px; border-collapse: collapse;\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EE</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Easy-Essential</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">ME</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Medium-Essential</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HE</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Hard-Essential</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Easy-Important</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">MI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Medium-Important</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HI</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Hard-Important</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">EN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Easy-Nice to know</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">MN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Medium-Nice to know</td>\r\n<td style=\"font-style: normal; background: #f27000; font-weight: bold; border: black 1px solid;\">\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">HN</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: black 1px solid;\">Hard--Nice to know</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>','Feedback options are set for individual papers and may include the following: Correct Answers/Text Feedback The text feedback on the graphic below gives specific feedback for the options selected and the correct option that was missed by the student. Learning Objectives If a paper has been mapped to learning objectives then these will appear beneath the question. They remind the student of the board topic area. Standards Setting It is possible to standards set the questions in a paper and then to display this information to students on the feedback screen. The abbreviations are explained below, for example EE is Easy/Essential. Providing standards setting feedback in addition to the standard correct answer can provide an extra level of detail for students. For example most students should be getting Easy/Essential correct, but it is less important if some Hard/Nice to Know questions are answered incorrectly. Vice versa a student answering Hard/Nice to Know correctly may be on track for an honours degree award. &nbsp; Standards Setting ratings &nbsp;   EE Easy-Essential ME Medium-Essential HE Hard-Essential  EI Easy-Important MI Medium-Important HI Hard-Important  EN Easy-Nice to know MN Medium-Nice to know HN Hard--Nice to know  &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(42,'Available assessments','<p>You can access all&nbsp;assessments that&nbsp;have been assigned to you from one screen. It includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Formative Self-Assessments</li>\r\n<li>Progress Tests</li>\r\n<li>Surveys</li>\r\n<li>Feedbacks</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>This includes those available in previous years of&nbsp;your study. Access is through the following URL: <a href=\"../../\">$local_server/students/</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #800000;\"><strong>Note:</strong> This <strong>does not </strong>include summative exam papers which can only be accessed on the scheduled exam day.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/available_assessments.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"778\" height=\"412\" /></p>','You can access all&nbsp;assessments that&nbsp;have been assigned to you from one screen. It includes: Formative Self-Assessments Progress Tests Surveys Feedbacks This includes those available in previous years of&nbsp;your study. Access is through the following URL: $local_server/students/ Note: This does not include summative exam papers which can only be accessed on the scheduled exam day. ','page',NULL,NULL,NULL),(41,'Question Types/Script Concordance Test (SCT)','<h2>Presentation</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This question shows a Vignette and a possible hypothesis based on the given data. There are then details of new information that was identified after the original hypothesis was made. The question then asks how this new information affects the hypothesis.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/script concordence preview v2.png\" alt=\"script concordence preview v2.png\" width=\"825\" height=\"338\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2>Marking</h2>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">There is not a correct answer for this question but a number of experts are asked what they think is correct. The option selected by the highest number of experts carries 1 mark. The other options carry a proportional mark depending on the number of experts that have selected it. If no experts have selected an option this will give a mark of 0.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><img class=\"image_brd\" src=\"images/script concordance feedback.png\" alt=\"script concordance feedback.png\" width=\"945\" height=\"231\" /></p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','Presentation This question shows a Vignette and a possible hypothesis based on the given data. There are then details of new information that was identified after the original hypothesis was made. The question then asks how this new information affects the hypothesis. &nbsp; &nbsp; Marking There is not a correct answer for this question but a number of experts are asked what they think is correct. The option selected by the highest number of experts carries 1 mark. The other options carry a proportional mark depending on the number of experts that have selected it. If no experts have selected an option this will give a mark of 0. &nbsp; &nbsp;','page',NULL,NULL,NULL);
